<LI><STRONG><A HREF="#qualitative">Qualitative Research: A Practical Guide</A></STRONG> by J.P. Rothe and D. McGregor (1994)

<LI><STRONG><A HREF="#target">Target Risk</A></STRONG> by Gerald J.S. Wilde

<LI><STRONG><A HREF="#dangerous">The Dangerous Edge</A></STRONG> by Michael J. Apter


<P> <HR><P>
<H3><A NAME="beyond">Beyond Traffic Safety</A><br>By J.P. Rothe</H3> 250 pages. $39.95 U.S., $53.95 Can. Plus $6.00 S & H.

<P> Sociologist J.P. Rothe asks readers to suspend all inherited beliefs 
about traffic safety problems and solutions. He takes readers into the rich 
and fertile terrain of traffic sociology and its implications for 
understanding the behaviour of road users. He examines the negotiation of 
physical risks to accommodate social expectations; the basic trust that 
establishes the relationships between road users; the driver's licence as a 
form of social control; the role of discretion and tolerance in police work; 
and the issue of speeding from the sociologist's point of view. The goal is 
to motivate the readers towards a new kind of thinking about traffic 
safety. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="car">Car Accident:</A> A practical recovery manual <BR>
by Jack Smith</H3>
178 pages. $12.95 U.S., $17.95 Can. Plus $6.00 S & H.<p>
Most people see driving as a relatively easy task and have little fear of it. But for a significant number of individuals, driving is fraught with risks and fears, especially if they have been subjected to the traumatic experience of a crash. Author Jack Smith has been working with people suffering from post-traumatic stress for 25 years. A veteran of Vietnam, he helped write the American Psychiatric Association's official diagnosis of posttraumatic stress disorder. He shows readers how to evaluate their stress reactions following the trauma of a crash and how to deal with them.<p>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>
 
<HR><H3><A NAME="challenges">Challenges</A> to Accident Prevention: <br>The Issue of Risk Compensation 
Behaviour<BR>Edited by Rudiger M. Trimpop and Gerald J.S. Wilde</H3>
$48.50 U.S., $67.50 Can. Plus $6.00 S & H. <P>


This collection of papers on risk behaviour/risk compensation was written by some of the leading experts in the field. This book highlights some of the underlying psychological processes involved in unwanted - and often unexpected - human reactions to system modifications aimed at improving safety on the roads and in industry. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="oldorder">Challenging</A> the Old Order: <br>Towards New Directions in Traffic Safety Theory<BR>Edited by J.P. Rothe</H3> 290 pages. $19.95 U.S., $26.25 Can. Plus $6.00 S & H. 

<P>A multidisciplinary look at road safety. Internationally renowned scholars look at the traffic safety problem from 
the standpoints of engineering, philosophy, economics, law, political 
science, education, communication and sociology. It's an exciting effort to 
establish a new theoretical launchpad from which to establish more effective 
initiatives in traffic safety. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="status">Driver</A> Education Status: A National Perspective <br>By Dr. James W. Crowe and Dr. Mohammad R. Torabi</H3>
42 pages. $16.95 U.S., $22.00 Can. plus $6.00 S & H. 
<P>A survey report on the status of the funding and delivery of driver education programs throughout the U.S. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="instructional">Instructional</A> support to drivers: The role of in-vehicle feedback in improving driving performance of qualified motorists<BR>
By  M. J. Kuiken (Ph.D. Thesis, 1996)</H3><p>
$19.95 U.S., $26.50 Can. plus $6.00 S & H, 68 pages. <p>

Given that the traffic environment does not give very good feedback on safety, would driving instructors be able to improve safe performance by providing better feedback about risks? What kind of feedback works best?<BR>
This thesis concludes that instructional support needs to be adapted to the individual driver and that, if it is properly suited to the traffic scenario in question, it can exert a positive influence on driver behavior. <P>

Research was conducted at the Traffic Research Centre, University of Groeningen, as part of the Generic Intelligent Driver Support project. Read more about this publication in the <A HREF="/ARTICLES/free/kuiken-96205-5961.html">Library</A>.<P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="david">New Driver Car Control:</A> <br>From Kamikaze to Competent<br>By David Thornhill Thompson</H3> $12.95 U.S., $17.95 Can. plus $6.00 S & H. 56 pages


<P>David Thompson's book is intended for the parent, family member or "coach" who provides the novice driver with the many hours of practice that are required in order to become accomplished behind the wheel. An attractive layout, combined with auto journalist Thompson's lively style and well researched content, make this a good book for any educator to have as a reference. It blends basic information about car control with insights into the psychology of driving. It also lays out a comprehensive program of exercises for co-drivers to follow during practice. These include braking techniques, collision avoidance, night maneuvers and vision tactics. Hints for both coaches and novices are included. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<HR><H3><A NAME="truckers">The Trucker's World: <br>Risk, Safety and Mobility <br>By J.P. Rothe</A></H3> $19.95 U.S., $26.25 Can. plus $6.00 S & H.  233 pages

<P>Why is the average trucker continuously placed in circumstances that, 
according to truckers, demand risky driving? Trucker safety interventions 
have traditionally been aimed at the truck driver. Traffic sociologist Rothe 
contends that intervention programs will work better if the focus is on the 
motivations and influences that govern drivers' behaviour. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<HR> <H3><A NAME="elderly">The Safety of Elderly Drivers: <br>Yesterday's Young in Today's Traffic
<br>By J.P. Rothe</A></H3> 435 pages. $24.95 U.S., $32.80 Can. plus $6.00 S & H.  
<P> A combination of statistical detail and sociological insight describes 
how the elderly perceive the problems of driving and cope with them. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P> 
<HR><H3><A NAME="rethinking">Rethinking Young Drivers <br>Edited by J.P. Rothe</A></H3> 291 pages. $19.95 U.S., $26.25 Can. plus $6.00 S & H. 

<P>Underlying the statistics about the crash problems experienced by young 
drivers are the social realities that motivate their thinking and behaviour. 
In this milestone book, researchers P.J. Cooper, J.P. Rothe and K. Stoddart 
probe these social realities in a search for solutions. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="motorcycle">Motorcyclists: Image and Reality <br>Edited by J.P. Rothe and P.J. 
Cooper</A></H3> 221 pages. $16.95 U.S., $22.50 Can. plus $6.00 S & H. 


<P> In similar vein as <STRONG><A HREF="#rethinking">Rethinking Young Drivers</A></STRONG>, this book explores 
the social reality of bikers against the background of the accident 
statistics of trained and untrained riders. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<p>

<HR><H3><A NAME="never">Never Say Always:<br>
Perspectives on Seatbelt Use <br>By J.P. Rothe and P.J. Cooper</A></H3> 192 pages. $19.95 U.S., $26.25 Can. plus $6.00 S & H. <p>
Rather than bombard people with a formal version of "What is" in terms of safety belt use, the authors focus on "What really is". What do people really think about safety belts? What are the real motivations that govern their use? Informative, easy to read and insightful. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="senior">Senior Drivers at Intersections: A Report<br>By J.P. Rothe and D. McGregor (1994)</A></H3> 226 pages. $26.50 U.S., $35.75 Can. plus $6.00 S & H. <p>
Why do seniors get into crashes at intersections? In this report, sociologists Rothe and McGregor focus on how seniors relate to intersections, how they feel about them, and what shapes their driving behaviour. It's an attempt "to uncover reasons, thought processes, and rationales as to why seniors drive through intersections the way they do." <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="qualitative">Qualitative Research: A Practical Guide<br>By J.P. Rothe and D. McGregor (1994)</A></H3> 180 pages. $19.95 U.S., $26.95 Can. plus $6.00 S & H<p>
While empirical, or quantative, research gathers facts and statistics, qualitative research zooms in on the human side of things and searches for the underlying causes of  human behaviour. It's a systematic form of the kind of inquiry most of us engage in regularly, whether we realize it or not. In this book, sociologist J.P. Rothe describes the methods of qualitative inquiry and the unique approach he used in researching his popular books on traffic sociology. <P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>
<p>
<HR><H3><A NAME="target">Target Risk <br>By Gerald J.S. Wilde</A></H3> 234 pages. $39.95 U.S., $53.95 Can. plus $6.00 S & H.

<P>
<STRONG><A HREF="excerpts.html">READ EXCERPTS</A></STRONG> from &quot;Target Risk&quot;.<P>
Antilock braking systems, airbags, seatbelt laws, traffic lights, speed 
regulations are all part of mammoth efforts to reduce traffic casualties. 
But do these measures and their counterparts in industry and public health 
have the effects intended? In his theory of risk homeostasis, Professor 
Gerald Wilde postulates that they don't because they fail to influence 
people's willingness to take risk. Now, for the first time, Wilde collects 
his controversial theory, along with its supporting arguments and data, into 
one fascinating document. <STRONG>Target Risk</STRONG> is a powerhouse of insights 
into human risk-taking behaviour. It's a book that everyone interested in 
safety and health promotion should have on the shelf. <P>
<P>
<HR><H3><A NAME="dangerous">The Dangerous Edge: The psychology of excitement <br>By Michael J. Apter</A></H3> 213 pages. $29.95 U.S., $39.95 Can. plus $6.00 S & H.
<P>
Give people a nice safe life and they'll seek out thrills and excitement - and sometimes real danger. In The Dangerous Edge,  Professor Michael J. Apter explores this phenomenon and enlightens us as to the conditions people typically set for themselves when they seek out sensations of excitement and danger. What Apter offers in this book is the first comprehensive and accessible guide to the psychology of excitement. He examines the complex relationship between excitement, anxiety, panic and euphoria. <P>

Apter explores the concept of excitement and what happens when excitement-seeking goes wrong. He discusses the mechanisms by which we allow ourselves to take risks and to reach higher arousal states. Healthy people, he says, seek excitement in ways that are constructive and led to learning, as opposed to antisocial and destructive modes of excitement-seeking such as "wilding", rape, vandalism and reckless driving. <P>

He offers us ways to manage our "protective frame" so that we can recognize what is genuinely threatening or risky and to control the risks we take so as to have more excitement and fun without courting disaster. <P>

This book is not available through bookstores or from the publisher. PDE Publications has a limited number of copies available. 
<P>
<STRONG><A HREF="form.html">ORDER FORM</A></STRONG> | <A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>
