<H2>ASSOCIATIONS &#38; ORGANIZATIONS</H2><P>

<HR><P>
<B>If you would like your association name and a brief description of its 
activities to appear in this section free of charge, please contact us at <a href="mailto:pde@drivers.com">pde@drivers.com</a></b>
<P>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3><A NAME="contents">CONTENTS</A></H3><P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#aamva">American Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators</A> (AAMVA)
<LI><A HREF="#aaa">American Automobile Association </A>(AAA)
<LI><A HREF="#aaasafe">AAA Foundation for  Traffic Safety</A>
<LI><A HREF="#adtsea">American Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association</A> (ADTSEA)
<LI><A HREF="#aded">Association of Driver Educators for the Disabled</A> (ADED)
<LI><A HREF="#csc">Canada Safety Council</A> (CSC)
<LI><A HREF="#ccmta">Canadian Council of Motor Transport Administrators</A> (CCMTA)
<LI><A HREF="#cpdea">The Canadian Professional Driver Education Association</A> (CPDEA)
<LI><A HREF="#umea">Department of Educational Measurement</A> (Ume&aring; University, Sweden)
<LI><A HREF="#dsaa">Driving School Association of the Americas</A> (DSAA)
<LI><A HREF="#dsao">Driving School Association of Ontario</A> (DSAO)
<LI><A HREF="#iihs">Insurance Institute for Highway Safety</A> (IIHS)
<LI><A HREF="#mvsa">Motor Vehicle Safety Association</A>
<LI><A HREF="#nhtsa">National Highway Traffic Safety Administration</A> (NHTSA)
<LI><A HREF="#nsc">National Safety Council</A> (NSC)
<LI><A HREF="#nets">Network of Employers for Traffic Safety </A> (NETS)
<LI><A HREF="#swedish">Swedish National Road Administration
</A><LI><A HREF="#tirf">Traffic Injury Research Foundation of Canada</A> (TIRF)
<LI><A HREF="#tsam">Traffic Safety Association of Michigan</A>
<LI><A HREF="#tsao">Transportation Safety Association of Ontario</A> (TSAO)

</UL>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="aamva">American Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators (AAMVA)</A></H3><P>


Founded in 1933, AAMVA represents the state and provincial officials in the 
U.S. and Canada who are responsible for the administration and enforcement 
of laws pertaining to the motor vehicle and its use. This includes driver 
licensing and training requirements. It's a &quot;voluntary, nonprofit, 
tax-exempt, educational organization.&quot;<P>
Activities include developing model programs in law enforcement and highway 
safety, and acting as an information clearinghouse for the various 
disciplines involved in this field. Active membership consists of the motor 
vehicle and traffic law enforcement administrators of member jurisdictions. 
Two categories of non-jurisdictional Associate membership are available:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Category I is for associations and business enterprises that are 
mutually compatible with AAMVA and its objectives. Fee: $1,500.
<li> Category II is for government entities not eligible for jurisdictional 
membership.  Fee: $750.<P>

</UL> 
<B>For information, contact:</B><BR>
Tel: (703) 522-4200, Fax: (703) 522-1553.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>



<P><HR><P>

<P><H3><A NAME="aaa">American Automobile Association (AAA)</A></H3><P>

The AAA has been involved in driver education since the 1930s. The 
Association offers a wide range of driver training accessories and teaching 
aids. Recently updated videos. Orders should be submitted through local 
clubs. Catalogue and list of local clubs available on request. Now playing a 
major role in training instructors.<P>

<B>For information, contact:</B><BR>
AAA Traffic Safety and Engineering<BR>
1000 AAA Drive<BR>
Heathrow, FL 32746-5063<BR>
Tel: (407) 444-7960.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>



<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="aaasafe">AAA Foundation for 
Traffic Safety</A></H3><P>


An independent, non-profit, public-charitable, education and research 
foundation. Provides research reports, videotapes, films, pamphlets.<P>

<B>Catalogue available from:</B><BR>
AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety<BR>
1440 New York Avenue NW, Suite 201<BR>
Washington D.C.  20036<BR>
Tel: (202) 638-5944. Fax: (202) 
638-5943.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>



<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="adtsea">American Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association (ADTSEA)</A></H3><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ADTSEA.drivers.com/ADTSEA/">Visit the ADTSEA 
home page</A><p>


Founded in 1956. Over 900 professional and corporate members. Annual and 
regional conferences.  resources include reports, brochures, videos, 
magazine. 
Membership is largely representative of public school driver education. 
University traffic safety centers and researchers also heavily represented. 
The commercial driving school sector is also represented and last year's 
annual conference had a special divisional meeting for the commercial 
sector.<P>

ADTSEA provides its members with a national office which represents the 
interests of members by keeping track of legislation on safety matters and 
lobbying for legislation to support driver and safety education. 
In 1970, ADTSEA took over the management of the National Student Safety 
Program (NSSP) from the National Education Association's Safety Commission 
(which was disbanded at that time) and has maintained this program ever 
since. The NSSP holds a national conference every year.<P>

<B>Membership fees:</B> Range from $10 (Student) to $400 (Corporate).<BR>
<B>Annual conference:</B> August.<BR>
<B>Publication:</B> &quot;The Chronicle&quot; (formerly &quot;The Journal of Driver and Traffic 
Safety Education&quot;)<BR>
<B>President:</B> Bob Sundermeier (CO)<BR> 
<B>President-Elect:</B> C. E. Welch (IL) <BR>
<B>Executive Director:</B> Dr. Allen Robinson (PA), Tel: (412) 357-4051<BR>
<B>Based at:</B><BR>
Indiana University of Pennsylvania<BR>
Highway Safety Center<BR>
Indiana, PA 15705<BR>
Tel: (412) 357-4051<p>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="aded">Association of Driver Educators for the Disabled (ADED)

</A></H3><P>

Founded in 1977. Represents about 450 professionals (from U.S., Canada, and 
some other countries) in the fields of driver education, occupational 
therapy, physical therapy, equipment manufacture, medicine, social work, 
rehabilitation, and rehabilitation technology. Annual conference and 
pre-conference seminars. Services include professional development programs, 
research support, certification of driver rehab specialists.<P>

<B>Membership fees:</B> Individuals $40, Associate member $20, Corporate $100, 
Vendor $50.<BR>
<B>Publications:</B> ADED Newsletter (quarterly).<BR>
<B>Secretariat:</B><BR>
Ricardo G. Cerna<BR>
P.O. Box 49<BR>
Edgerton, WI 53534<BR>
Tel: (608) 884-8833.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>



<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="csc">Canada Safety Council (CSC)</A></H3><P>

The Canada Safety Council is Canada's not-for-profit safety organization. It 
has three sections: Public Safety; Occupational Safety; and Traffic Safety. 
One of its missions is to promote safe driving through the provision of the 
Defensive Driving Course (DDC). The CSC offers packaged programs for 
experienced drivers, professional drivers (school bus, trucks, etc.), and 
drivers of specialized vehicles (utility vehicles, tow trucks). Catalogue 
available on request.<P>

<B>Membership fees:</B> Individual, $50 (Can).<BR>
<B>Annual conference:</B> May.<BR>
<B>Publications:</B> &quot;Safety Canada&quot; (Newsletter) and &quot;Living Safety&quot; (Magazine)<BR>
<B>Information from:</B><BR>
Canada Safety Council<BR>
6-2750 Stevenage Drive<BR>
Ottawa, Ontario, Canada K1G 3N2<BR>
Tel: (613) 739-1535 Fax: (613) 739-1566<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>



<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="ccmta">Canadian Council of Motor Transport Administrators (CCMTA)</A></H3>

The CCMTA is a non-profit organization set up by the provincial, territorial 
and federal ministries of transportation to act as a coordinating body for 
motor transport administrators. This includes driver licensing 
administrations. It is the Canadian equivalent of the AAMVA. In a recent 
move to open up lines of communication with non-government groups, the 
Association initiated two levels of associate membership. Level A membership costs $300 (Can.), and includes a free comprehensive directory, copies of all records of decisions of standing committee meetings, discounts on Annual Meeting registration, publications and other products and services. Level B is free and includes copies of the newsletter, <STRONG>CCMTA News.</STRONG><P>

<STRONG>Annual Meeting and Exhibition:</STRONG> May<P>

<STRONG>For information, contact:</STRONG><BR>

Audrey Henderson, Director of Programs<BR>
2323 St. Laurent Blvd, Ottawa, Ontario, K1G 4K6, Canada<BR>
Tel: (613) 736-1003  Fax: (613) 736-1395<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:secretariat@ccmta.ca">secretariat@ccmta.ca
</A><BR>
Internet homepage: <A HREF="http://www.ccmta.ca">www.ccmta.ca</A><P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<P><HR><P>
<H3><A NAME="cpdea">The Canadian Professional Driver Education Association (CPDEA)</A></H3><P>
<A HREF="http://www.CPDEA.drivers.com/CPDEA/">Visit the CPDEA 
home page</A><p>

The CPDEA was established in 1968 to foster and advance the interests of driving schools and instructors with the government, the insurance industry and the public.   <p>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<P><HR><P>
<H3><A NAME="umea">Department of Educational Measurement<br>(Ume&aring; University, Sweden)</A></H3>
<A HREF="http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/UMEA/">Visit Ume&aring;'s Village Web Site</A><P>

Founded in 1992. A number of measurement-related research and development 
projects are carried out within the department's research program. The 
largest and currently oldest is the Swedish Scholastic Aptitude Test 
(SweSAT). Another project, commissioned by the Swedish National Road 
Administration, is working on developing the driving licence examination as 
far as reliability and validity. One area of interest is to map out the 
complexity of this subject through an international perspective.<p>

<B>For information, contact:</B><BR>
Department of Educational Measurement<BR>
Ume&aring; University<BR>
S-901 87 UME&Aring;, SWEDEN.<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:anna.zolland@edmeas.umu.se">anna.zolland@edmeas.umu.se</A><p>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="dsaa">Driving School Association of the Americas (DSAA)</A></H3>
<A HREF="http://www.DSAA.drivers.com/dsaa/">Visit DSAA's Village Web Site</A><P>


Founded in 1973. Represents commercial driving schools throughout the U.S. 
and Canada. Lobbies for legislation and regulation to support more effective 
driver training/education. Currently lobbying for the High Risk Drivers Act 
put before Congress by Senator John C. Danforth. DSAA carries a range of 
instructional aids and accessories, including textbooks, workbooks and 
videos. Catalogue available. Operates professional upgrading programs for 
instructors and driving school owners.<P>

<B>Membership fees:</B> 1-5 cars, $100; 6-12 cars, $150; 13 or more cars, $200.<BR> 
<B>Annual conference:</B> November<BR>
<B>Publication:</B> &quot;Dual News&quot; (Quarterly)<BR>
<B>President:</B> Jack Sousa, Tel: (203) 574-3158<BR>

<B>Executive Director:</B> Robert Maximo, Tel: (301) 929-7918<BR>
<B>Communications Director:</B> Kathy Pavlo, Tel: 1-800-270-DSAA.<BR>
<B>Based at:</B><BR>
23 Woodtick Rd.<BR>
Waterbury, CT 06705<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="dsao">Driving School Association of Ontario (DSAO)</A></H3><P>
<A HREF="http://www.DSAO.drivers.com/DSAO/">Visit DSAO's Village Web Site</A><P>

Founded in 1975 to represent commercial driving schools in dialogue with government, and to raise standards of instruction and education.  <P>
 
<B>Annual conference:</B> May<BR>
<B>Publication:</B> &quot;Driving School Press&quot; (Quarterly)<BR>
<B>President:</B> Gera Gutenberg<BR> 
<B>Based at:</B><BR>
557 Dixon Rd., Unit 110<BR>
Etobicoke, Ontario M9W 1H8<BR>
Tel: (416) 247-2278 Fax: (416) 247-4883<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="iihs">Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS)</A></H3><P>


An independent, nonprofit, scientific scientific and educational 
organization supported by the insurance industry.<P>

<B>Publication:</B> Status Reports (Quarterly). Free.<BR>
<B>For information or to receive copies contact:</B><BR>
The IIHS Communications Department<BR>
1005, North Glebe Rd.<BR>
Arlington, VA 22501<BR>
Tel: (703) 247-1500 Fax: (703) 247-1588.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="mvsa">Motor Vehicle Safety Association</A></H3><p>

The aims of the MVSA are to promote safety training and to encourage the 
safe operations of motor vehicle fleets on our streets and highways. 
To cooperate with all existing Safety organizations in developing a healthly 
national attitude which will reduce accidents.<p>

Membership is available to those whose work involves an interest in safety 
and who are associated with road Safety training methods.<p>

<B>For information, contact:</B><BR>
David Sheepway, Tel. (905) 838-2918 or E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:rgram@idirect.com">rgram@idirect.com</A>
<p>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="nhtsa">National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA)</A></H3><P>


Established by the Highway Safety Act of 1970, the NHTSA has a congressional 
mandate to reduce deaths, injuries, and economic losses resulting from 
traffic accidents on the nation's highways. Its activities range from 
establishing safeguards for the protection of purchasers of motor vehicles 
and developing fuel economy standards, to establishing research and 
development priorities and overseeing traffic safety programs. The law 
provides for federal matching funds to assist states with their driver, 
pedestrian, and motor vehicle safety programs. <P>
The NHTSA issues standards as guidelines and provides technical assistance 
to state and local community safety programs. Countermeasure emphasis is on 
reducing impaired driving, increasing occupant restraint usage, improving 
emergency medical systems, and controlling the aberant driver. The 
Administration maintains a register of persons who have had their operators' 
license withdrawn or revoked for more than 6 months.<P>

<B>For further information, contact:</B><BR>
The Office of Public and Consumer Affairs<BR>
NHTSA<BR>
Department of Transportation<BR>
400 Seventh St., SW<BR>
Washington DC 20590<BR>
Tel: (202) 366-9550.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>


<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="nsc">National Safety Council (NSC)</A></H3><P>


Founded in 1913. The mission of the U.S. National Safety Council is to 
educate and influence society to adopt safety, health and environmental 
policies, practices and procedures that prevent loss and suffering from 
preventable causes. Broad spectrum of activities (ranging from swimming and 
first aid to driver education) include the development of the widely known 
Defensive Driving Course (DDC), which is used throughout North America and 
in a number of countries around the world. A version for personal computers 
is now available. The NSC produces a wide range of videos and other teaching 
accessories for a variety of road users and specialized drivers. Catalogue 
available on request. 
<P>
<B>Membership fees:</B><BR>
1-99 employees: $150<BR>
Ranging up to 500,000+ employees: $9,700<BR>
<B>Publications:</B> Wide range of publications, of which the bimonthly &quot;Traffic 
Safety&quot; is the most relevant for driver educators. Subscription $18.98, with 
discounts for group subscriptions.<BR>

<B>Based at:</B><BR>
1121 Spring Lake Drive<BR>
Itasca, IL 60143-3201<BR>
Tel: 1-800-621-6244, (708) 285-1121.<P>

<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>




<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="nets">Network of Employers for Traffic Safety (NETS)</A></H3><P>

NETS is a public/private partnership and non-profit 
organization working to help employers develop and 
implement comprehensive workplace highway safety 
programs. It was the brainchild of James Kemper, Jr., 
former CEO of Kemper National Insurance Companies; 
Samuel Skinner, former US Secretary of Transportation; 
and other business leaders.<BR>

Mission:<BR>

NETS is dedicated to reducing the human and economic 
costs associated with the primary cause of employee 
fatalities and lost work time -- highway crashes.<BR>

<STRONG>For information, contact:</STRONG><BR>

The Network of Employers for Traffic Safety<BR>
1900 L Street, N.W., Suite 705<BR>
Washington, DC 20036<BR>
VOX: 202-452-6005<BR>
FAX: 202-223-7012<BR> 
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:joe.vidanes@hsn.org">joe.vidanes@hsn.org</A><BR>
Web: <A HREF="http://wildhack.com/nets">http://wildhack.com/nets</A><p>

<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P>
<H3><A NAME="swedish">Swedish National Road Administration</A></h3>
<P>
The Licensing, Testing and Development division of the Drivers License Department of the Swedish National Road Administration is responsible for the development and evaluation of examination procedures for the Drivers License Department, and for the quality and organization of education. It is also responsible for teacher education and curriculum.<P>

<STRONG>STAFF:</STRONG><BR>
Christer Drangel (Head)<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:christer.drangel@vv.se">christer.drangel@vv.se</A><BR>
Hans Mattsson<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:hans.mattsson@vv.se">hans.mattsson@vv.se</A><BR>
Per-Olov Grummas Granstrom<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:per-olov.grummas@vv.se">per-olov.grummas@vv.se</A><P>

<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="tirf">Traffic Injury Research Foundation of Canada (TIRF)</A></H3><P>


TIRF is a national charitable road safety institute. Founded in 1964, it has 
become a world leader in research and program development in many areas, 
from driver licensing to motorcycle safety, from elderly drivers to bicycle 
safety. It has received international acclaim for work in the area of young 
novice drivers as well as alcohol, drugs and traffic safety. Director: Dr. 
Herb Simpson.<P>

<B>Publication:</B> &quot;Impact&quot; (A project of Canada's Drug Strategy). Free dist.<BR>
<B>For information, contact:</B><BR>
Tel: (613) 238-5235 Fax: (613) 238-5292.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="tsam">Traffic Safety Association of Michigan</A></H3><P>

The Traffic Safety Association of Michigan (TSA) is a non-profit, statewide organization which provides a range of services to businesses and government agencies, including driver training and education,  free or low-cost printed materials, a free-loan video library and a periodic newsletter.  Membership is open to any business or organization interested in promoting traffic safety.  The TSA is a member of the National Safety Council and offers several types of defensive driving courses.<P>
<B>For information, contact:</B><BR>
Traffic Safety Association of Michigan<br>
124 W. Allegan Street, Suite 602<BR> 
Michigan National Tower<br>
Lansing, MI 48933<br>
Tel: (517) 487-8811 Fax: (517) 487-6358<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

<P><HR><P><H3><A NAME="tsao">Transportation Safety Association of Ontario (TSAO)</A></H3><P>

The Transportation Safety Association of Ontario is a not-for-profit organization incorporated in 1942. Our purpose is to work with Labour and Management to ensure that the workplace parties are effectively trained to avoid injuries and accidents in the workplace. We offer a wide range of training programs, safety literature, videos, as well as In-cab Evaluations, Facility Audits, Safe Driver and Safe Worker Award Programs. We also sponsor the Transportation Safety Association of Ontario Council of Driver Trainers with eight chapters located throughout the province.<p>

<B>Membership Fees: </B><br>
TSAO: None<br>	 
Council of Driver Trainers: call for details<p>

<B>Publications: </B>&quot;Safety Bulletin&quot;  and &quot;Drivers Newsletter&quot;&#42; published quarterly. Various other publications also available.<BR>
&#42; &quot;Drivers Newsletter&quot; only issued to companies enrolled in our Driver Award Program.<p>

<B>For information contact: </B><br>
Transportation Safety Association of Ontario<br>
555 Dixon Road, Suite 101<BR>
Etobicoke, Ontario M9W 1H8<br>
Tel: (416) 242-4771 or 1-800-263-5016<br>
Fax: (416) 242-4714 or E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:tsao@echo-on.net">tsao@echo-on.net</A><p>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A><P>

