<H2>Guide to the Information Highway</H2>

Here are some sites that may be of interest to Village visitors. If you know of any others that should be included in this section, please <A HREF="mailto:pde@drivers.com">send us</A> the addresses, along with brief descriptions of the sites.<P>

Note: Soon we will be reorganizing this section into categories.<P>
<HR><P>

<blockquote>

<IMG SRC="new.gif" ALT="New sites:"><P>


<A HREF="http://www.aracnet.com/~pdxkevin/memorial.html">The Victims of Drunken Driving Memorial Wall</A>. This site describes a project to build a memorial wall for the victims of drunk driving. <P>

<A HREF="http://www.driving.co.uk">Successfull Driving</A>, Bill Lavender's new site in the UK. Driving issues, testing, licensing.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.webplus.net/ncutlo/">National Traffic Law Information Clearing House</A>: Page from the National Committee on Uniform Traffic Laws and Ordinances.<BR>
107 S. West, #110<BR>
Alexandria, VA 22314<BR>
Tel: 1-800-807-5290 Fax: 703-441-1144<p>




<A HREF="http://www.webplus.net/ncutlo/gradlaw.html">Graduated Driver Licensing Model Law</A>, Ninth Draft, Sept. 11, 1996.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.fctpa.coedu.usf.edu/org/fahperd/fall95j/gradDriv.html#top">Richard Stryker article</A> on Graduated Driver License system&#59; references provided. Page by Florida Center for Technology in Physical Activity.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.azleg.state.az.us/legtext/42leg/1r/bills/hb2190p.htm 
">Text of legislation</A> concerning violations and driver improvement and driver education in Arizona.<P>

<HR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.aamva.org">The American Association of Motor Vehicles Administrators</A> represents vehicle and licensing administrators in jurisdictions through out the U.S. Site has links to agencies in jurisdictions throughout the U.S. and Canada.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.state.fl.us/hsmv">The Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles.</A><P>

<A HREF="http://www.trucking.org/safety/quiz.html">ATA Safety Net -- Test Your Traffic Skills!</A> An online traffic safety quiz about cars and trucks.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.engr.usask.ca/tc/skhwy/tsn/tsndec95.html">Traffic Safety News -- Saskatchewan Highways and Transportation

</A> Newsletter Dec. 1995. For those interested in traffic safety issues in Saskatchewan.<P>

<A HREF="http://calvin.cc.ndsu.nodak.edu/ugpti/ugpti.htm">Upper Great Plains Transportation Institute - North Dakota State University</A>: Interesting research papers on transportion safety.<P>

<A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/rdu/home2.html">Reasonable Drivers Unanimous</A>: A part of Kevin Atkinson's home page. Some interesting articles on driving issues, and links to interesting articles on other parts of the web.<P>

<A HREF="http://home.ican.net/~rpcole/index.html">Canadian Association of Technical Accident Investigators &#38; Reconstructionists</A> (CATAIR): Catair was founded in 1984 and is a professional organization of accident investigators, reconstructionists and others involved in all aspects of road safety.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.goodnet.com/~teenvue/">Teenvue:</A> A teenage driver safety program. System offered throughout the U.S. for reporting teens' bad (or good) driving through the anonymity of the Teenvue program.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.veta.se/">Driver support by VETA.</A> VETA is a Swedish acronym for Science and Experience in Traffic Safety Work. Good articles on ABS, risk compensation.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.hwysafety.org/">Insurance Institute for Highway Safety.</A> Excellent articles on safety issues such as drugs and driving, laws and regulations, pedestrians, speed limits, vehicle safety features, crash reports.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.carsafety.org/">Highway Loss Data Institute.</A> Related to the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety. Articles about losses through collisions, injuries, theft of autos.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.taro.com/">The Traffic Accident Reconstruction Origin.</A> Articles, reports, discussions concerning accident reconstruction.<P>

<STRONG>TRUCKS and TRUCKING:
</STRONG><blockquote>
<A HREF="http://www.e-z.net/~ts/ts/ts.html">
The Truck Safety Page</A>, presented by Technical Services, Vancouver, WA.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.truck.net/">Net of information</a> re: truck publications, associations, truck law, GPS, trucker links, truckers store, radio, TV programs, directories, trucks for sale, etc.<P>



<A HREF="http://www.netside.com/~bmeyer/index.html">
&quot;18 Wheels On The Web:</A> What they never teach us in Drivers' Education (but should!)&quot;. Trucking/Automobile Driver Safety topics, and &quot;fun stuff&quot;.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.truckers.com/">
A page</a> for the truck driver. Information re: truckers' resources, NAFTA, jobs, education, events, etc. <P>

<A HREF="http://www.saferoads.org/policy/truck.html">Truck Safety Page: Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety</A> -- Truck safety information from a U.S. group called <STRONG>Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety.</STRONG><P>
<A HREF="http://www.sendit.com/c-design/page2.html">Trucking Resources</A>: A wide variety of links and phone numbers pertaining to commercial trucking. Very complete and very comprehensive.<P>
<A HREF="http://www.sendit.com/c-design/page2.html">
A listing</a> of events and resources related to trucking safety. Headings: Computer software, Office of Motor Carrier addresses&#59; Books/manuals/manuscripts&#59; Journals/directories&#59; Catalogues&#59; Associations&#59; Consultants&#59; Services. Compiled by custom design and consultation. <P>

<STRONG>American Trucking Associations</STRONG><BR>
2200 Mill Road<BR>
Alexandria, Virginia  22314-4677<BR>
USA<BR>
Telephone: 703-838-1721 Fax: 703-836-0751&lt;BR&gt;<BR>
Email: <A HREF="mailto:4903329@MCIMAIL.COM">4903329@MCIMAIL.COM</A><P>
</blockquote>

<A HREF="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/usr/rahuls/www/sapient.html">
Situational Awareness Planner</A> for Implementing Effective Navigation in Traffic.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.aaafts.org/aaa/index.html">
AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety.</A><P>

<A HREF="http://www.dot.gov/internet/states.html">
Listing</A> of State Departments of Transportation Internet site WWW links.<P>

<A HREF="http://itre.uncecs.edu/index.html">
The Institute for Transportation Research and Education</A> (ITRE), recognized by state and local government agencies as a leading resource in transportation research and technical assistance.  As a unit of North Carolina State University, ITRE provides research assistance and project administration for the 16-campus UNC system and Duke University, as well as for state government agencies. ITRE assists local government and state government agencies in meeting a wide range of transportation challenges through the application of research.<P>

<A HREF="http://ftp.std.com/NE/bosdrivers.html">
Basic rules</a> for driving in Boston (part of Boston Online page).<P>

<A HREF="http://www.ccad.uiowa.edu:80/~smaddhi/">
Srinivas Maddhi's Home Page</A> (works at The Center for Computer-Aided Design at Iowa with Driving Simulator project).<P>

<A HREF="http://www.ccad.uiowa.edu:80/~smaddhi/ids.gif">
Photo</A> of the University of Iowa driving simulator (courtesy of Srinivas Maddhi)<P>

<A HREF="http://www.ucm.es/OTROS/Psyap/congresos/trafico.htm">
Details of conference</A> on traffic psychology at Valencia, Spain, call for papers, IAAP Traffic and Transport Division, information about topics, organizers, e-mail address for information.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.biols.susx.ac.uk/home/trevs/motorcycles/home.html">
University of Sussex, Trev's Motorcycle Home Page</a>. Inlcludes links to related pages re: legislation, equipment, rights, schools, training, etc. Also the IAM Home Page.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.soc.hawaii.edu/~leonj/leonj/leonpsy/leon.html">The Traffic Psychology</a> Page of Dr Leon James, Professor of Psychology at the University of Hawaii. Web site contains principles of Traffic Psychology, definitions, methodologies, student projects. 
<P>

<A HREF="http://dragon.princeton.edu/~dhb/">
A comprehensive guide</a> to transportation resources on the Net. Maintained by the Intelligent Transportation Systems Program at Princeton University. Has its own search tool. Deals with everything from airline schedules to transportation information systems. Not much related to training/education issues.<P>


<A HREF="http://www.motorists.com/">
National Motorists Association.</a> This organization has been around since 1982. Describes itself as &quot;the only organization in North America striving to stop the exploitation of motorists&quot;. Big issue is speed limits. Membership fees range from $29/yr for individuals to $1,000/yr for a business. You can read about the history of the NMA, its goals, and articles promoting its views.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.ADTSEA.drivers.com/ADTSEA/">
The American Driver &#38;Traffic Safety Safety Education Association</a> was founded in 1956 under the auspices of the National Education Association. It represents professional driver and traffic safety educators at a national level by offering a national office, monitoring events at a national level, liaising with the media, providing informational resources, hosting a national conference and regional meetings, and providing administrative services for the National Student Safety Program.<P>

<A HREF="http://users.feldspar.com/~mtrenout/photo2.html">
The photo radar home page</a>. Prepared and maintained by Mark Trenouth. He says it's NOT a political page but it takes a firm stand against photo-radar enforcement of speed limits. Provides some interesting information and statistics.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~karl/govt/driver.html">
This site</a> presents a long document, put up on the net by Karl Kleinpaste. The document argues (with lots of legal-looking references) that states do not have the right to demand that individuals obtain a license in order to drive on public roadways. <P>

<A HREF="http://www.nwu.edu/traffic/ti1.htm">
The Traffic Institute</a> is a national non-profit organization which serves public agencies responsible for law enforcement, criminal justice, public safety, traffic management, and highway transportation systems. Local, county, state and federal government agencies, as well as agencies from foreign countries, are served through programs of specialized training, continuing education, research and development, publications, and direct assistance.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.mrtraffic.com">
&quot;Ask Mr. Traffic with Kenny Morse&quot;.</a> Kenny Morse is Los Angeles's &quot;Mr. Traffic&quot; and he's &quot;the only television and radio talk-show host who talks about driving issues in America.&quot; He's also a California Comedy Traffic School teacher. A local type of page that offer tips and information on various aspects of driving, from drowsiness to fighting tickets and insurance.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.homeless.com/homepages/jimbo@midland.co.nz.html">
New Zealand -- Master Drive Services</a> Home page. Master Drive Services Ltd. was formed in 1992 when staff members of the former Driver Education Unit of the NZ MOT's Land Transport Division decided on a management buy-out of the unit. The Company, with some employees as shareholders, operates Driver Training and Consulting services nationwide, with 
the Managing Director and Registered Office in Hamilton. The company provides training programmes, courses, seminars, practical instruction, one-on-one tuition. This Home Page offers a listing of company services and an e-mail address to contact them. <P></blockquote><HR>
