<html><head>
<title>INFORMAL VS. FORMAL TRAFFIC LAWS</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>INFORMAL VS. FORMAL TRAFFIC LAWS</h2>
<p>
<b></b>
<p>
A traffic ticket and a criminal record for driving at the speed limit? With a sign protesting the 100 km/h limit fixed to their cars, two men drove side by side at exactly the limit on Ontario's highway 401 last summer, creating a moving roadblock. They were charged with obstructing the highway and public mischief. The real issue was their challenge to what traffic sociologist J. Peter Rothe calls "the moral order of the roadway." The men engaged in a conspiracy to disrupt the delicate balance between the written law and the moral order.
<p><img align="middle" src="/icons/view-full.gif">
<a href="/pde/ARTICLES/free/informal-96166-27187.html"> VIEW FULL TEXT</a><p>
