<html><head>
<title>RISK TAKING, HEALTH AND SAFETY</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>RISK TAKING, HEALTH AND SAFETY</h2>
<p>
<b></b>
<p>In 1977, British Columbia undertook a massive campaign against drunk driving. 
The program reduced drinking and driving fatalities by an estimated 18%, but overall traffic deaths were up 19%.
Professor Gerald Wilde, a Canadian psychologist, argues 
that safety campaigns 
tend to move accidents around rather than reduce them 
because traditional approaches do not motivate individuals 
to change their "target level" of risk.
<p><img align="middle" src="/icons/view-full.gif">
<a href="/pde/ARTICLES/free/rht-96166-27183.html"> VIEW FULL TEXT</a><p>
