<html><head><title>The Vision Place</title></head><body bgcolor="ffffff" text="000044" link="0000ff" vlink="660099">

<A HREF="http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/index.html">
<img hspace=5 align="middle" src="/pde/home_btn.gif" alt=""> VILLAGE Home Page</A>
<a href="/pde/homepage.html"><IMG  hspace=5 align="middle" SRC="back.gif" alt=""> VILLAGE Web Sites</a><P><HR><P><IMG SRC="vision.GIF" ALT=""Welcome to The Vision Place at the Information Village"">
<p>

<hr>



<H3>The Center for Unlimited Vision<br>

80 Fifth Ave., Suite 1105<br>

New York, NY 10011</font></H3><p>


<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Center is dedicated to educating people about vision, especially as it

relates to driving. Our instructional materials include the acclaimed

20-minute video "Save a Second. Save a Life."<p>



"Eyes don't tell people what they see. People tell eyes what to look for."

That's the theme of our video, which comes with a short guide for the

instructor and vision charts for testing.<p>

It uses "sports vision" concepts to instruct the use of the eyes in

traffic. Starting with an explanation of central vision and the importance

of visual acuity, it goes on to show how the eyes gather information and

how they can be trained to gather it more effectively.<p>



The emphasis is on how visual skills can be used to get early warning of

potential problems and provide the driver with that extra second of

reaction time that, research tells us, could prevent as many as 80% of

crashes.<p>



Appropriately, the video ends with a quotation from the French philosopher

Voltaire: "There is no such thing as an accident. What we call by that name

is the effect of some cause which we do not see."<p>



<b>"An outstanding training video for instructors and students"<br></b>

Bob Maximo, Past President, DSAA<p>



<b>"An information-packed overview of visual techniques for drivers."<br></b>

Burton H. Brooks, School Library Journal<p>



<b>"It's the best video I have come across on the topic."<br></b>

Dan Miller, American Driver Education Resource Center<p>

<p>

Dr. Shapiro of the Center for Unlimited Vision is available to help companies set up on-site visual safety screening programs. These programs would be designed to test drivers for: usable visual acuity, contrast sensitivity, depth perception, color vision, eye-muscle balance, and peripheral vision. In addition to the testing program, Dr. Shapiro could design and set up a visual skills training and enhancement program. <p>



<b>For more information, contact us at:<br>

Tel: (212) 255-2240  Fax: Same</b><p>
<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<hr>
<TABLE BORDER><TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD></TD><TD><B> <A HREF="http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/">A Traffic Safety Information Village Web Site</A> </B></TD><TD></TD></TR></TABLE></body></html>









