<p><HR>


</A><H2><A NAME="positive">Positive Influences Ahead</A></H2>
<STRONG>BY Allen Robinson, Ph.D.<BR>
ADTSEA Chief Executive Officer</STRONG><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Each quarter I have the opportunity to share with our members the continued growth and improvement of driver education. As spring approaches we see many positive signs of a brighter tomorrow.
<P>

The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), in cooperation with the American Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators (AAMVA), has just released new guidelines on graduated driver licensing. This document clearly describes the importance of driver education in the licensing process. All driver education teachers should have this document. For those attending the ADTSEA conference in Grand Junction, Colorado, the publication entitled, &quot;Graduated Driver Licensing System for Young Drivers,&quot; produced by NHTSA in cooperation with AAMVA will be available at the registration desk.<P>

Speaking of the ADTSEA conference, Barbara Brody has planned an excellent conference. Two credit workshops for driver education teachers are offered the week prior to the conference. Information on these courses was provided in a previous mailing. I encourage you to participate in these course offerings and be ready for the future in graduated licensing. The conference program has national leaders at each general session preparing us for the future. To be current and ready for tomorrow, you need to be in Grand Junction, Colorado.<P>

Our president, Bob Sundermeier, and his wife have planned great activities. Get your reservations in early so you can join the exciting festivities planned.<P>

The changes we are experiencing in driver education are tremendous. Combining driver education with driver licensing has had a positive impact on our driver education programs. Several states will be reporting on success stories at our conference. I personally believe this is the single most important change we can make in our programs. You can't sell a steak without sizzle. It is hard to sell driver education without some sizzle--a driver license. I encourage you to become involved in driver education/licensing.<P>

Driver educators have been aware of the value of parent involvement for some time. Several of our corporate members are developing excellent programs to assist us. They are AAA, Champion, Allstate, and General Motors. Each of these programs will be discussed at our conference.<P>

The National Student Safety Program (NSSP) continues to be a great success. The July conference in Honolulu, Hawaii will have 500 students and advisors present for a five day program. Jan Meeker of the Hawaii Department of Education has done an excellent job in planning and hosting this conference. I wish more driver education teachers would become involved in NSSP activities.<P>

We continue to get good press in major newspapers. The Chicago Tribune recently published a significant article on driver education in Illinois. I was personally interviewed for the article and was quoted correctly.<P>

I recently attended the Southeast Region ADTSEA meeting in Atlanta, Georgia. David Donaldson, Maynard Bridges, and Charles McDaniel planned an excellent conference. The conference was both enjoyable and professionally beneficial for me. Thanks, Southeast, for the invitation to participate. By the way, the only way you can attend the Southeast ADTSEA meeting is to be a member of ADTSEA.<P>

Travel plans this spring include  Arizona, Wisconsin, North Dakota, Illinois, and Michigan to talk about graduated licensing, driver education/driver licensing, restructuring driver education, teacher training and certification, parent involvement in driver education, and the enhanced driver education program in Pennsylvania. All these topics have many common threads. The most significant is that of changing the way we do business.<P>

You need to be the leader in your community who directs this change in driver education. Be willing to accept change and provide improved opportunities for young people to drive safely. Convince those who teach with you that driver education is our profession. It provides us with a good job and income to support our families. Teachers need to support ADTSEA so we can make sure the future is bright for our members.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="colorado">A Warm Welcome to Colorado</A></H2>
<STRONG>BY Robert L. Sundermeier<BR>
ADTSEA President</STRONG><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>It is unbelievable that Spring is just around the corner! Where does the time go? We are nearing completion and planning of our 40th ADTSEA Conference program thanks to the hard work and dedication of some special individuals. Your host outing, along with the many fun activities being planned for your stay here in western Colorado, has been finalized. We hope to meet your expectations for both the conference program and many activities.<P>
Special thanks go to Barbara Brody for the many hours of planning our conference program. She has put together one of the most informative and exciting programs to be offered to the ADTSEA membership in some time. Most areas of traffic safety have been included. You should have received a draft of the 40th Conference Program, so there is time for any suggestions you may care to make relative to our program planning.  <P>
To my spouse, Barbara, the other half of our conference hosts, a special thank you for a job well done in planning our Tuesday night outing and the many fun activities you can experience. For those of you who never visited this part of Colorado, it will be a once in a lifetime experience. Plan to arrive early and leave late in order to vacation and enjoy our beautiful state. <P>
My appreciation goes to Allen Robinson and the staff at IUP for their assistance and mailing the preconference information. Conference and workshop registrations, bylaw amendments, and voting ballots arrived for our membership in a timely fashion. Please take notice of deadline requirements for each planned activity. Make your reservations early, preferably by the June 1, 1996 deadline. Should you need assistance or have questions about the conference or planned activities, please write or call my wife, Barbara, or me.  <P>
An ambitious spring travel schedule is being planned. I will attend state and regional traffic safety meetings in Kansas, Texas, Utah, and Montana. My purpose is to promote new membership in those states and to personally invite all traffic safety educators to attend our 1996 ADTSEA Conference from August 3-8, 1996 in Colorado.  <P>
I strongly encourage our present ADTSEA members to renew their memberships early and get one new member to join. We all need to contribute in order to realize our goal of 200 new members this year. To quote our friends in the Northwest, &quot;Your ADTSEA membership proves your belief that traffic safety education needs a unified voice to speak at the national level. Your ADTSEA membership strengthens the national association of traffic safety professionals which in turn strengthens and complements our state and regional associations. Your ADTSEA membership entitles you to a subscription to <STRONG>The Chronicle,</STRONG> ADTSEA's journal which keeps you informed about new research, curriculum development, and coming events in the various state, regional, and national association programs.&quot;<P>
With winter behind us, we look forward to new challenges ahead. By working together we can make a difference in meeting those challenges and look forward to a brighter future. <P><A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="impact">IMPACT Is Dead On</A></H2>
<STRONG>by Alisa Vald&eacute;s, Boston GLOBE Staff<P>

This video on the dangers of reckless driving won as Best Documentary at the New England Children's Film and Video Festival. The win generated national exposure for the issue of drinking and driving, including a full-length televised broadcast of IMPACT and discussion with Jason Murray--one of the student filmmakers--as well as a prominent story in the Boston Globe. Here are excerpts from that article.<P>

</STRONG><BLOCKQUOTE>MIDDLEBURY, Vt. -- Charles Smith's name is never mentioned in the documentary, IMPACT, but his ghost circles every word. &quot;As the medical crew was putting the C-collar on you they started suctioning your airway,&quot; says the ambulance driver. He looks right at the camera. &quot;There was nothing left of the driver's side door,&quot; says the state trooper, her eyes narrowing with the memory. &quot;You weren't breathing.&quot;<P>
&quot;I took your heart in my hand and I began squeezing,&quot; says the emergency room doctor. She is crying. <P>
Shortly after Smith's death in November 1989, his peers at a technical high school in Middlebury got together to make IMPACT, a film about auto safety and teenagers. Five car crashes involving young people from that high school took place that year. The teenagers asked everyone involved in Smith's accident--doctor, trooper, EMT, tow truck driver--to look right into the camera and explain to Smith how he died. <P>
Now, six years later, this 17-minute film made by hard-luck, working-class kids in rural Vermont has been voted the best documentary at the New England Children's Film and Video Festival. <P>
&quot;IMPACT was the one that stuck with kid judges the longest after they left,&quot; said Cheryl Hirshman, the coordinator of the festival. &quot;I think the format of having the viewer as the victim is very effective. For most of the kids who judged it, this was something none of them had really thought much about.&quot;<P>
Auto accidents are a common topic of discussion for high school students. There's a saying among them: &quot;Summer's here, three a year,&quot; pointing out how many teenagers are expected to get hurt, if not killed, in auto accidents. <P>
In IMPACT, the footage of people talking to Charles Smith is interspliced with footage of teenage boys talking about accidents they have been involved in themselves. <P>
According to Vermont State Trooper Melody Perkins, who has investigated more than 300 auto accidents in five years, including Charles Smith's, they usually involve males. &quot;I'm so tired of telling mothers their sons are dead,&quot; she said. <P>

<STRONG>Chronicle</STRONG> readers may purchase the IMPACT video and presentation guide at a discounted price of $29.95 + $4.75 S&amp;H. Send shipping address and check or P.O. to :<P>

The NoodleHead Network<BR>
107-D Intervale Avenue Burlington, VT 05401<BR>
1-800-493-4323.<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:noodlhed@together.net">noodlhed@together.net</A><P><A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="alcohol">The Influence of 
Legislation on the Driving</A><BR>
and Alcohol Consumption of College Students</H2><HR>
<p><STRONG>BY Robyn Hagler, Carolyn Miller, John Burling, and Cheri Smith</STRONG><BR>University of Montevallo<p><HR>
<p>
<strong>A number of factors impact drinking and driving. These factors include 
peer pressure, risk taking, knowledge, and legislation. This descriptive study 
utilized a questionnaire approach to sample 159 college students with regard to 
peer pressure, risk taking, knowledge, and legislation. The results support the 
efficacy of strengthened legislation and increased educational programs as 
deterrents to drinking and driving.</strong>
<P><HR><BLOCKQUOTE>
Driving an automobile is a challenge that is accompanied by a 
variety of choices. The choices made by drivers can have a tremendous impact on 
the individual and society. One such choice is that of combining drinking and 
driving, a combination that can be deadly to everyone involved. Alcohol 
impairment is a major problem involving not only drivers, but also pedestrians 
and other roadway users. Approximately 500,000 persons per year are injured in 
alcohol-related crashes. On average, one person is injured every minute and one 
person is killed every twenty-three minutes in an alcohol related crash (MADD, 
1993). <p>
When these numbers are broken down there is some room for optimism. The 
proportion of fatally injured drivers of passenger vehicles with blood alcohol 
concentration of 0.10&#37; or more has declined by at least 5&#37; from 1985 to 1994 
(Fatality Facts: Alcohol, 1995). The factors responsible for this decline may 
also be the same factors that influence a driver's decision to combine drinking 
and driving knowledge, risk taking behaviors, peer pressure, and legislation.<p>
Although students know that alcohol-related automobile accidents are the 
leading cause of death among young people, they also indicate a need for an 
increase in  related information (Wechsler &amp; Isaac, 1993 and Mazon, 1987). 
At the same time, the effectiveness of education approaches such as designated 
drivers may seem to be small when evaluated in terms of reduction of accident 
rates (Eigen, 1991; DeJong &amp; Winsten, 1992; and Giller, 1985). The 
responsibility and liability involved in operating a motor vehicle should be 
stressed in any educational program (Valois, 1983).<p>
Balancing responsibility with the factors of risk-taking behavior and peer 
pressure is a challenge that confronts many young drivers. Giller (1985) states 
that most of the time students believe they make their own decisions and deny 
any pressure from peers. However, many students cite peer pressure as the 
reason for drinking more than they want to (Wechsler &amp; Isaac, 1993; Shore 
&amp; River, 1985 ; Mason, 1987; and Poteat &amp; Moltern, 1982). Combining 
peer pressure with an adolescent sense of immortality and invulnerability can 
result in risk-taking behaviors (Nicholson, Minqi and Mahoney, 1994; Giller, 
1985). High-risk drinking attitude and behavior is often developed and 
reinforced during the college years (Hunnicutt, Davis, Perry-Hunnicutt, and 
Newman, 1992).<p>
While peer pressure and risk-taking are important, it appears that major 
deterrents for drinking and driving among college-age youth involve legislation 
and education.<p>
Drinking alcohol during the college years continues to gain social acceptance, 
yet the trend toward drinking and then driving continues to decline. This 
paradox leaves many safety experts pleasantly surprised and puzzled. Much of 
the reduction in alcohol-related crashes is a result of prevention initiatives 
and stronger drunk driving legislation at the federal and state levels. Driving 
while intoxicated (DWI) laws have steadily grown in strength over the last two 
decades, thanks to the emergence of groups such as Mothers Against Drunk 
Drivers (MADD)  and Students Against Driving Drunk (SADD) (Nicholson, Wang, and 
Mahoney, 1994). Furthermore, a variety of legislative mandates, such as the 
recent Drug Free Schools and Communities Act of 1989, have provided additional 
motivation for the increasing concern about the consumption of alcohol on 
college and university campuses (Gehring &amp; Geraci, 1989).<p>
In 1995, the U.S. Congress repealed the national speed limit, leaving highway 
speed decisions up to the individual states. Congress then followed suit by 
repealing mandatory helmet laws, also leaving that decision up to the 
individual states. However, the decision was made to leave mandatory safety 
belt laws in place. Congress has called for states to strengthen their driving 
under the influence (DUI) legislation. States failing to heed this mandate will 
lose  federal highway funds (Nicholson, Wang, and Mahoney, 1994).
<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Method</H3>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This study focuses on the impact of peer pressure, risk-taking 
behaviors, knowledge, and legislative efforts have had on the drinking and 
driving habits of college-aged students.<p>
<strong>Subjects</strong>: The subjects in this study consisted of 159 college 
student volunteers enrolled in  core curriculum health classes in a public 
liberal arts university in the southeast. Of the 159, 60 were male and 99 
female. Eighty-eight  of the students were 18-20 years of age, which is below 
the national drinking age. There were 52  students aged 21-24 years and 19 were 
age 25 and over. Approximately 40&#37; of the sample population classified 
themselves as sophomores, 26&#37; as juniors, 25&#37; as seniors and 9&#37; as freshmen. Of 
those sampled 98&#37; reported to be licensed drivers.<p>
<strong>Survey:</strong> The measurement instrument was a 31 item questionnaire 
with responses on a nine-item scale ranging from never to very often.  Nine of 
the questions related to demographic information such as class status, license 
status, and drinking status. Of the remaining 22 questions, a number focused on 
the effect legislation has on the subject's decision to drink and then operate 
a motor vehicle. Questions relating to legislation included: <p>

<UL><LI>The prospect of spending up to one year in jail for a DUI conviction 
influences my decision not to operate a motor vehicle after drinking alcohol.
<LI>The prospect of being stopped by a police officer for DUI influences my 
decision not to operate a motor vehicle after drinking alcohol. 
</UL><P>
Several questions related to other factors including time, religion, peer 
pressure, knowledge, and risk-taking behavior. Examples of these questions 
included:

<UL><LI>I drink alcohol and drive even though I know it is unsafe.
<LI>My friends influence my decision to drink alcohol.</UL>

<P>
<STRONG>Procedure: </STRONG>The subjects were given the questionnaire following 
a one-hour presentation on alcohol awareness and the most recent legislative 
changes in their state. Each of the subjects was asked to fill out the survey 
and was informed that the results would remain anonymous.<p>
<p></blockquote>
<H3>Results</H3>
<p><blockquote>
Sixty-three percent of the respondents reported that they 
drank on a routine basis, and 21&#37; stated that either they or a member of their 
family had been involved in an alcohol-related crash. Only 27&#37; had ever had any 
association with a group such as MADD or SADD. More than half of the students 
(52&#37;) reported alcoholism within their immediate family.<p>
Sixty-two percent of the respondents  reported  that they drank on a routine 
basis. Twenty percent of the females said they or a member of their family had 
ever been involved in an alcohol-related crash. Thirty percent reported to have 
been involved with an organization such as MADD or SADD. Ninety-six percent of 
the female respondents were licensed drivers. Sixty percent of the females 
surveyed were 18-20 years of age, which is below the legal drinking age in this 
state.<p>
The study included five items designed to measure risk-taking behavior related 
to alcohol. Thirty percent of the males admitted they operated a vehicle on a 
routine basis after consuming alcohol, while 19&#37; of the females reported to 
drive a vehicle after consuming alcohol. When asked if they would get in the 
car with a friend who had been drinking, 25&#37; of the males and 11&#37; of the 
females indicated they would take this risk. Assuming that it is unsafe to 
drink and then operate an automobile, 24&#37; of the males and 16&#37; of the females 
reported that they do so on a routine basis.<p>
The survey also looked at the role peer pressure plays in the decision to drink 
and drive.  Of those surveyed, 30&#37; of males and 19&#37; of the females indicated 
their friends influenced their decision to drink alcohol. Seventy-nine percent 
of the females indicated they would get into the car with a drinking driver 
because their friends do, while 77&#37; of the males would do so based on what 
their friends encourage. The survey showed 12&#37; of the female respondents would 
intervene to keep a friend from driving after drinking, while 22&#37; of the male 
respondents would intervene.<p>
Six items focused on the effect of legislation on a college student's decision 
to operate a motor vehicle after drinking alcohol.  Studies indicate that males 
continue to outnumber females two to one in alcohol-related collisions and 
three to one among subjects aged 16-25. <p>
Legislation appears to be a deterrent to the majority of both male and female 
students. A slightly higher percentage was recorded for females in every 
category. The fact that drinking and driving is illegal was a deterrent to 17&#37; 
of the female respondents and 30&#37; of the male respondents. This was the single 
item in which male respondents were closer to the desired response than the 
female respondents. This may indicate that female respondents were more 
responsive to the material penalties than the moral issues.<p>
The prospect of being stopped by a police officer for the suspicion of DUI was 
found to be a deterrent to 80&#37; of the female respondents and 76&#37; of the male 
respondents. The prospect of spending time in jail was a deterrent for 81&#37; of 
the females and 74&#37; of the males. Payment of a fine was reported as a deterrent 
by 79&#37; of the female respondents and 73&#37; of the male respondents. <p>
Two other areas of legislation surveyed were license suspension and license 
revocation.  All respondents reported a suspended and revoked license as a 
deterrent. Females reported 76&#37; and 78&#37; respectively, compared to 69&#37; and 72&#37; 
for the male respondents. Curfew enforcement did not serve as a significant 
deterrent to drinking and driving. Twenty-two percent of the female respondents 
and 24&#37; of the males reported that curfews serve as a deterrent to drinking.
<p>
</blockquote>
<H3>Discussion</h3><p>
<p>
<blockquote>Study results may indicate that some young drivers are prone 
to take alcohol-related risks when operating a motor vehicle. While the 
percentages were relatively low, many students did engage in risk-taking 
behavior involving alcohol use and driving. This has the potential to 
dramatically increase the risk of collision. The results may indicate that 
females remain less aggressive drivers. Female respondents are more likely to 
be affected by the material penalties when dealing with sanctions, fines, jail 
sentences, license suspension, or license revocation. Present data supports 
strengthening legislation to act as a deterrent to drinking and driving.<p>
The intention of a college-level alcohol education program is to inform 
students about the effects of alcohol and encourage responsible drinking. These 
programs should encompass prevention, identification, and the development of 
long-term support for alternative methods. Thirty percent of the female 
respondents have ever been involved with socially conscious groups or the 
designated driver program. Perhaps, improvement of accessibility to such 
programs could lower the percentage of drinking and driving among college 
students.<p>
The issue of deterring drinking and driving for college-age youth appears to 
focus on legislation and education. To separate the effect of education from 
the effects of legislation would be difficult. To obtain desired results, the 
elements of education and legislation should be applied to all aspects of this 
critical issue.<p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p><HR>

<H3>References</H3>
<blockquote>
DeJong, W. and Winsten, J.A. 1992. &quot;The role of the designated driver program in 
the prevention of alcohol impaired driving: A critical reassessment.&quot;
 <strong>Health Education Quarterly, 19</strong>, 429 - 442.<p>
Eigen, L.D. 1991. &quot;Alcohol practices, policies and potentials of American 
