<BODY>
<H4>The Chronicle: Fall Issue, 1996<BR>
<HR></H4>
<H1>Beyond the horizon</H1>
<H3><I>By Allen Robinson, Ph.D.</I></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This summer has seen proof that our previous discussions have
led to completed products. Four different sets of materials will be available
to drastically improve your ability for implementing parent involvement
programs. The American Automobile Association (AAA), Allstate Insurance
Company, Champion Education, and General Motors have each completed materials
which support parent involvement in driver education. Each program differs
and complements the others. It is exciting to have so many good products
become available at the same time. <BR>
<BR>
We continue to be a society that expects simple solutions to our problems.
We expect our cars to protect us rather than take responsibility for ourselves.
We naively believe that laws are supposed to control others who do not know
how to take care of themselves. We believe that engineering should remove
all hazards associated with driving. <BR>
<BR>
The federal government, the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, and
most state agencies take the above approach to highway safety. Rather than
deal with the single most important element, the driver, they tie bells
and whistles on these quick and easy solutions. While these temporary solutions
do result in some progress, they also create additional problems. We continue
to have unacceptable accident, injury, and fatality rates in this country.
<BR>
<BR>
Recent efforts by major automobile safety stakeholders are beginning to
yield results. ADTSEA member participation at the National Summit in Crystal
City was greatly appreciated. Each of you made significant contributions
during the sessions, and I know that your efforts will be helpful in finalizing
a strategic plan that is beneficial to ADTSEA goals for driver education.<BR>
<BR>
Members do need to understand that organization development takes many forms
and appearances through its developmental phases. Initial indications and
insights did not support using ADTSEA as a parent agency for this new coalition.
Indications were that a separate agency may need to be developed to avoid
conflicts with goals and efforts of existing agencies. ADTSEA would benefit
from the formation of a separate or joint agency to improve youthful driver
performance. <BR>
<BR>
As ADTSEA CEO, my position on creating a new agency is being reconsidered.
Perhaps this foundling organization can grow within the support of ADTSEA
efforts and goals. During the next few weeks, I will be meeting and discussing
with several different groups concerning the concept of the Summit organizers
forming a coalition or partnership with ADTSEA to achieve the goals discussed
in Crystal City, Virginia. <BR>
<BR>
Decisions have not been made on how we can collectively support efforts
to improve youthful driver performance through education. The Summit was
fruitful in regard to encouraging efforts to move forward with the plans
and develop a strategic plan for implementation. As plans become more clear,
I will share them with the membership through The Chronicle, ADTSEA News
and Views, or a personal communique. This is an exciting time for developing
the opportunities that exist. Education has long been ignored as a component
of highway safety countermeasures. It is very encouraging to feel the support
and energy of major stakeholders supporting efforts to improve youthful
driver performance through education. ADTSEA support and contributions to
this effort are being noticed and are well received.<BR>
<BR>
I encourage everyone to support this effort as we go through the process
of determining how ADTSEA and this newly formed coalition can work together
to improve youthful driver performance. ADTSEA will be called upon to make
extra efforts to develop national education program goals and provide professional
certification recommendations. I encourage every member to lend support
as required during this formative period and wish to thank all who have
given of their time and efforts to this point. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="toc.html">Return to Table of contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
