<H4>The Chronicle: Fall issue 1996</H4>
<HR>
<H1>Future ADTSEA activities</H1>
<H3>by C.E. Welch<BR>
President</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
It is an honor and privilege to serve as your president. Efforts to support
traffic safety initiatives throughout North America are beginning to take
shape. My plans include the development and maintenance of programs that
enhance membership growth and provide communication and tools to keep traffic
safety instructors on the cutting edge. <BR>
<BR>
We plan to increase membership by 200 through having a promotional membership
drive. ADTSEA needs to be visible at affiliated state and regional conferences
and at the National Safety Council. The board of directors, executive committee,
corporate community, and the ADTSEA CEO will strive to bring in four new
corporate memberships and develop an advisory council that will work with
states facing serious traffic safety education problems such as budget cuts.
<BR>
<BR>
ADTSEA will continue to restructure our organization to support the highest
level of quality and performance. The Standards Committee will continue
to work on establishing professional standards and performance outcomes
to be presented to the Board of Directors in 1996 and 1997. The Evaluations
and Goals Committee will define the duties and responsibilities of the executive
board and the board of directors more clearly by looking carefully at the
Constitution and Bylaws. They will present changes to the membership for
passage. <BR>
<BR>
ADTSEA will clarify the restructuring of driver education to assist states
in the implementation of the graduated licensing programs. ADTSEA will continue
to create partnerships to support driver and traffic safety education by
networking with other organizations, agencies, businesses, communities,
and institutions that promote traffic safety awareness. <BR>
<BR>
We will continue working to secure passage of the Congressional High Risk
Users Act while networking with those support organizations and associations
that represent individuals with special needs. Our goals are to continue
to work with national organizations such as National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration (NHTSA) and the American Automobile Association (AAA) to
promote graduated driver licensing bills in all states. <BR>
<BR>
The ADTSEA Board will continue working to establish criteria and award a
National Driver Education Teacher of the Year. Plans include continuing
to expand the National Student Safety Program (NSSP) by finding and securing
a funding grant to offset the cost of the NSSP program with attempts to
maintain the registration cost for the conference at $200. ADTSEA will request
the NSSP Executive Board to revise the NSSP Constitution with the advice
of the NSSP liaison committee. <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="toc.html">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
