<TITLE>The road from Dearborn to Chrystal City</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H4>The Chronicle: Fall issue 1996<BR>
<HR></H4>
<H1>The Road from Dearborn to Crystal City</H1>
<H3>By <I>Terry L. Kline, Ed.D.</I></H3>
<H4><i>Texas A&amp;M University</i></H4>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Major stakeholders in driver and traffic safety have recognized a need to improve youthful driver performance through educational efforts. Major insurance companies and automobile manufacturers are seeking ways to improve the educational practices for developing a graduated driver education program consistent with the current efforts for graduated licensing. <BR>
<BR>
State Farm Insurance and Ford Motor Company initiated efforts in Dearborn,
Michigan leading to a Summit on Youthful Driver Performance in Crystal City, Virginia (Planning Committee Report, 1996). The plans to develop a mechanism for improving youthful driver performance were unveiled to public, private, and governmental agencies. Strategic plans and funding efforts will be developed prior to January 1, 1997 which may include ADTSEA efforts to support graduated education programs to coincide with graduated licensing programs.<BR>
<BR>
The planning committee attendees received a supportive letter from Mr. Ron
Blue of State Farm Insurance. The contents of his letter appear throughout
this article. Ron explained that for the last several months, a small group
of concerned volunteers from many different sources have been working to
form a coalition to dramatically reduce the number of teenage traffic deaths.
Our approach has been to identify ways to significantly improve driver education, driver skills and driver experience under an organizational format that could be either a national coalition, a foundation, or both. As part of
that group, Ron would invite representatives to attend the National Summit
on Driver Education at the Crystal City Hyatt in Washington, DC on September 16 and 17, 1996. He encouraged attendees to continue their role as a member of the coalition for change in driver education and performance. <BR>
<BR>
Planning committee members are calling our effort A Coalition for Improved
Driver Education (CIDE), and Ron has accepted the challenge to serve as
interim chairman. Permanent leadership will be identified as quickly as
feasible. <BR>
<BR>
The coalition continues to attract the interest and attention of a growing
of important individuals who agree that our current systems for training
young people to drive are grossly inadequate. To a person, they agree that
we are on the right track in our efforts to promote national attention among
a group of leading problem solvers who will work in concert to change youthful driver behavior. Never have so many important people been so interested in a grass roots effort to create change in our system for driver education and training. By the same token, as realists, we are all aware of the tremendous effort that will be required and the commitment so many in our society will be asked to make. <BR>
<BR>
Interested coalition members agree, however, that the results and the goals
of our coalition, to reduce the number of teenage deaths by 1,000 or more
by the year 2000, are clearly worth the effort needed to address the issue.
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Defining the Need</H3>

Meeting participants defined and redefined the needs for a unified national
effort because it was believed that only by creating this need could hope
exist to achieve the enrollment needed to move this effort forward. Participants defined the following needs: <p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Li> Define the customer(s) and create awareness and demand
for the programs we develop. <BR>
<Li>  Get youthful buy-in supported by society, customer, parent, peer,
passenger, etc. <BR>
<Li>  Define the content of a program or process that can work. <BR>
<Li>  Reinforce youthful or novice driver responsibility for safety, experience,
and consequence at an attitudinal, knowledge, skill, and behavioral levels.
<BR>
<Li>  Develop and promote a tough graduated license scheme (based upon
skill or age or both). <BR>
<Li>  Develop tougher programs that include consistent driver evaluation
and measurable outcomes. <BR>
<Li>  Define the role of the schools in implementing driver education programs
and do so within the context of other school (societal) needs. <BR>
<Li>  Provide a stronger leadership community for driver education and
for the programmatic efforts we are undertaking. <BR>
<Li>  Place accent on driver road skills and behind-the-wheel experience
in a wide range of conditions. <BR>
<Li>  Create partnership and alliance at all levels.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
The planning committee agreed that the improvement of youthful driver performance
and attitude can be accomplished through:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE><Li>  Awareness<BR>
<Li>  Education<BR>
<Li>  Regulation<BR>
<Li>  Industry and Government <BR>
Partnerships<BR>
<Li>  Research </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Concept discussions were held in June at State Farm's Bloomington, Illinois
offices between representatives from auto manufacturers, glazing suppliers,
and State Farm personnel. It was concluded at these discussions that a joint
industry and government coalition effort, aimed at developing and deploying
improvements in driver education programs and curriculum, could be very
beneficial to society in general. It was also concluded that a focused planning
pre-meeting session made up of a few key and interested persons would be
a necessary step prior to hosting a larger group meeting with all interested
parties. It was thus decided to hold the pre-meeting planning session on
July 26 at Ford Motor Company in Dearborn, Michigan and to hold the larger
group meeting on September 16-17 in Washington D.C. The pre-meeting planning
session was used to establish an agenda and to develop a set of strawman
strategic goals at the September meeting in Washington D.C. The pre-meeting
planning session and the group meeting was facilitated by Dudley Davis,
Davis Consulting Group from Baltimore, MD. It was hoped that the meeting
will result in the following outcomes:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE><Li>  A list of the invitees to the September 16-17 group meeting
in Washington D.C.<BR>
<Li>  Development of an agenda for the September 16-17 meeting in Washington
D.C. <BR>
<Li>  Determine the probability of success of a joint driver education
coalition effort. <BR>
<Li>  Identify the current initiatives and needs in the driver education
field (gap analysis). This task to be refined and completed at the September
meeting. <BR>
<Li> Development of major strawman strategic goals needed to direct a coalition effort. This task to be refined and completed at the September meeting.
<BR>
<Li> Agreement on individual roles prior to and during Washington meeting. </BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Mission Statement</H3>

To significantly reduce the number of youthful driver crashes, injuries,
and fatalities as a result of the improved quality of education, awareness,
research, and regulation in North America through an alliance of powerful,
private, public, and nonprofit partnerships committed to increasing the
competence, experience, performance, and attitudes of teenage drivers. This
will be accomplished through an organization which will develop, promote,
and support a wide variety of initiatives and strategic partnerships. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Goals of a National Summit </H3>

The planning committee supported the following goals of a national summit:<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Li>  To identify the need for an initiative for improved youthful
driver performance and attitudes in North America. <BR>
<Li>  To identify what has been happening in North America as a foundation
for the initiatives developed at the Summit. <BR>
<Li>  To identify the important research and to determine what future scientific
discovery will help in the development of youthful driver initiatives. <BR>
<Li>  To develop goals and tactics that could be used if an alliance is
developed that will underwrite, partner with, or otherwise create technology,
awareness, regulations, research, and strategic partnerships which will
significantly improve teenage driver performance and attitude. <BR>
<Li>  To consider an organization or strategic alliance that can serve
as a source for the certification or accreditation of materials, curricula,
methods, and equipment developed by others, and thereby promote teaching
and learning excellence in schools or wherever youthful driver performance
and attitudes are developed. <BR>
<Li>  To develop, recommend, and provide initial funding for a new initiative to achieve these goals. </BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Traffic Safety Education Trends </H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Li>  The public's attitude toward driver education will decline
unless a national campaign is launched on the seriousness of the magnitude
of the motor vehicle crash problem for youth under 25. <BR>
<Li>  More states will be issuing provisional, probational, or restricted
licenses to teenagers. <BR>
<Li>  States will be imposing stiffer licensing penalties for teenagers
than on older drivers for drinking and driving violations. <BR>
<Li>  More states will be considering imposing night driving curfews for
newly licensed teenagers. <BR>
<Li>  Agencies responsible for road testing and driver licensing will eliminate
road testing and give the responsibility of evaluation to the local certified
driver education teacher. <Li>  Driver and traffic safety education programs
need to strive for a more relevant and measurable curriculum that is student
centered, has performance objectives, has criterion reference tests, and
has instructional materials that have been validated. <BR>
<Li>  Fewer universities will be producing driver education teachers. The
driver education teacher shortage is real. <BR>
<Li>  The most critical concern will be the lack of adequate teacher preparation
standards and certification.<BR>
<Li>  Driver education must, in theory, reflect current knowledge in the
fields of social psychology, mass communication, and organization change.
For example, when discussing drunk driving, use alcohol-impaired driving
because a person does not have to be drunk to be impaired. Do not use &quot;accidents,&quot;
use &quot;crashes&quot; since the term accident suggests the event could
not have been avoided. <BR>
<Li>  Higher standards need to be established by state licensing agencies
if driver education programs improve their effectiveness. <BR>
<Li>  Effective driver education programs will establish partnerships with
parents and businesses in the community to support teaching and learning
in area of driver and traffic safety education. <BR>
<Li>  Parents and good public relations are the key to maintaining a driver
and traffic safety education program. </BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Planning Committee Members </H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
