<td><A HREF="index.html">ADTSEA page</A><P></TR>


<HR>
<H4>The Chronicle: Fall Issue 1996</H4>
<HR>
<H1>The Zone Control System Provides Blueprint for Risk Reduction Habits
</H1>
<H3><I>By Frederik R. Mottola</I></H3>
<H4><I>Professor, Southern Connecticut State University</I></H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The curriculum for the Zone Control Driving System accomplishes
many of the concepts Carney (1996) suggests as necessary for risk reduction
behavior. Eugene Carney is strongly commended for his The Chronicle 44 (3)
article entitled, &quot;Driver Education Curriculum&shyp;A Critique and
A Proposal,&quot; in which he addresses several shortcomings of current
driver education curricula. <BR>
<BR>
If there is a value to offering a driver education program, as well there
should be, the major goal should be to help novice drivers acquire the capabilities
to reduce the risks associated with driving. We never drive without exposure
and risk. Most of the risk is manageable, and the consequences of taking
risky actions are very predictable. <BR>
<BR>
An effective driver education curriculum should serve as a blueprint that
can provide a teen with the precise steps necessary for the development
of safe, comfortable, low-risk, and convenient driving habits that will
last a lifetime. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Blueprint to Develop Habits </H3>

If, as educators, rather than teach teens to drive, we were asked to help
them build a house that would provide shelter, security, safety, comfort,
and convenience for the rest of their lives, we would want a design to show
what the finished product should look like. We would also need a detailed
blueprint to efficiently direct the construction. <BR>
<BR>
To build a house, we would need a solid footing to support the foundation.
The foundation must be structured to support the exterior walls of the house,
while the the walls must be able to support the roof of the house. Each
component must be constructed at the proper time and with a perspective
of how it fits into the total plan. It would be of little value to begin
building the walls before the foundation was built. To build a foundation
for a three room house, when our plan is to build a six room house, would
not allow us to achieve our goal. The blueprint would provide us with a
precise plan to guide the construction of the house and to have each stage
of the building process take place in a proper and timely sequence. <BR>
<BR>
Teaching a teen how to use a hammer to drive nails into a two-by-four and
how to use a saw to cut the two-by-four is not the same as teaching the
teen to build the house. Yet, for someone without a blueprint, the driving
of nails may seem the same as building a house. For some, the concept of
what a teen needs to learn to drive a car is focused only upon the immediate
task of &quot;safely&quot; maneuvering the car, with little concern for
what kind of habits are being built that will serve the individual for a
lifetime of driving. Our driver education programs must help students construct
a sturdy shelter of low-risk habits that will provide a lifetime of protection
from the incalculable number of ways that a crash can occur. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>The Zone Control System </H3>

During 1971-72, thousands of motor vehicle crashes were analyzed in an attempt
to discover which driver behavioral patterns were necessary to avoid crashes.
The results of my studies led to the formation of the Zone Control Driving
System. It has been used effectively for teaching novice as well as licensed
drivers risk avoidance behavioral patterns. The millions of ways that crashes
occur involve two common factors. Most crashes occur when there is a reduction
in the driver's line of sight (LOS) and/or a change to the driver's intended
path of travel (POT). Someone or something changes the control which the
driver has over his/her LOS-POT before driving into the deteriorated situation.
<p>
Our mind tells our eyes what to look for. To see effectively, drivers need
to know where to look and what to look for. With the Zone Control System,
instructors are able to teach drivers to look for situations that affect
their LOS-POT. Carney states, &quot;A common practice of treating each traffic
scene as an independent situation to be analyzed independently does not
provide the learner with the transferable guidelines which insure consistent
risk management performances.&quot; This is an important point Carney makes
and a significant reason why the Zone Control System is needed. Although
there are an astronomical number of ways to lose control while driving,
there are only a few principles a driver must learn and practice into habit
to minimize the risk. <BR>
<BR>
The Zone Control System is like having a picture of what our house should
look like when properly constructed. With a clear picture of what the educational
intervention should achieve, we can then formulate the blueprint to direct
the efficient use of our resources to that end. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Two Powerful Tools </H3>

A hammer and hand saw are no longer the most efficient and effective tools
to use for the construction of our house. If we learn how to use a few power
tools, we can build a larger and sturdier house in less time than it would
take with the use of the old hand tools. <BR>
<BR>
Two powerful tools we can use in the construction of our students' shelter
of low-risk habits are targeting and vehicle reference points. By using
the tool of targeting, the student is able to learn how to use searching
skill to gain a mental picture of the space the car is to occupy, which
aids in maintaining a safe path-of-travel. Targeting can give the driver
information more than 12-15 seconds ahead of the car. It can also increase
steering accuracy and help the student develop skid avoidance skills. <BR>
<BR>
The use of reference points allows the driver to get accurate information
as to how the car is positioned in relation to the roadway. Because the
driver's view of the road is blocked by the dashboard and by the hood of
the car, optical illusions make the car appear somewhere other than where
it is. With the use of reference points, the driver is able to see some
part of the vehicle as it relates to some part of the roadway, knowing exactly
where the vehicle is positioned. A driver gains many advantages from the
use of reference points. To list a few: <P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Li>The ability to gain consistent success by receiving accurate
feedback of where the vehicle is positioned on the roadway before performing
a turn and other maneuvers and knowing how to easily correct failures. <BR>
<BR>
<Li> Once the method of reference points is learned for one vehicle, the
techniques can be applied to any vehicle. There is rapid transfer of learning
to new situations. <BR>
<BR>
<Li> Even a novice driver can get into a larger vehicle than accustomed
to, such as a sport utility vehicle, van, truck, or motor home, and within
five minutes be comfortable and confident maneuvering it in tight spaces
and in traffic situations. <BR>
<br>

<I>Ed. Note: There will be detailed information on the use of reference
points in the next issue of The Chronicle.</I> </BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Concurrent Classroom and In-Car </H3>
Carney states, &quot;...decision making guidelines mandate a concurrent
classroom and laboratory instruction program. A single component of risk
can be introduced in class and simultaneously pursued in any laboratory
setting, environment, or situation.&quot; Classroom activities must give
students an opportunity to learn and apply concepts that they will be expected
to perform during the next in-car session. <BR>
<BR>
For example, students learn how to use targeting in the classroom before
applying it to an in-car session. The classroom activities are able to give
the student physical, equivalent, mental, and/or rehearsal opportunities
to prove that they are able to use the &quot;tool.&quot; Once successful
usage is demonstrated in the classroom, then the student should apply that
same process during an in-car session as soon as possible. In-car practice
activities can take place while the student is in the backseat as well as
while driving. <BR>
<BR>
There are four stages of skill development for learning to use targeting.
The first stage is learning how to locate a target. A target is a stationary
object that appears in the center of where you intend to drive the car.
For example, if you look as far down the road as possible to the space that
you expect the car to occupy, you'll see some fixed object, such as part
of a house, a tree, a pole, a sign, a bush, etc. <BR>
<BR>
How to locate a target can be practiced in the classroom or the whole class
can be taken outside and practice selecting targets. It is a good learning
environment. Ten minutes can be spent in the parking lot performing physical, mental, and/or rehearsal of targeting skills by having the students
hold a cardboard pizza round (which can be obtained free from a vendor)
to simulate a steering wheel, while directing them to walk toward various
targets. <BR>
<BR>
Everyone has a good time. The students love it. And you, as the administrator
of the program, will save money. A class of 30 students uses 10 instructor
minutes to prepare all of the students with skills that would have taken
10 minutes for each student to accomplish in-car. That would have cost 300
instructor minutes, saving 290 minutes of valuable in-car instruction time,
benefiting all students. Imagine the savings if this same ratio is applied
to many of the other skills and behavioral patterns the students must learn.
It surely can improve the quality of in-car activities when the student
has already demonstrated some success at the expected performance. <BR>
<BR>
The second stage of targeting is for the student to learn how to evaluate
the target area. The target area is the driving environment to the left
and right of where the target is located. Searching the target area for
driving related information is more important than merely identifying a
target. <BR>
<BR>
The third stage of targeting is to evaluate the targeting path. The targeting
path is the actual space the car is expected to travel on the roadway, from
the present location point when the target is first visible to the destination
point in the target area. <BR>
<BR>
The fourth stage of targeting is to search from one target area to another
for LOS-POT changes. Now the students are ready to begin applying the principles
of Zone Control. <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Six Zones We Must Control </H3>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="zones.gif" WIDTH="212" HEIGHT="73" 
ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Introduction to Zone Control </H3>

Zones are either Open, Closed, or Changed. An Open Zone is when there is
space to operate without an LOS-POT restriction. A Closed Zone is a zone
not available as a POT and/or there is a restriction to the LOS. A Changed
Zone is a worsening zone condition. It is an open zone changed to a closed
LOS-POT or a zone that was already closed and has an additional change.
<BR>
<BR>
Examples of LOS-POT Zone Changes <BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Li>A red traffic light is a closed front zone POT. <BR>
<Li>A hill crest is a closed front zone LOS. <BR>
<Li>A parked car to your right is a closed right zone LOS-POT. <BR>
<Li>A bicyclist to your right is a closed right zone POT. <BR>
<Li>Oncoming traffic is a closed left zone POT. <BR>
<Li>A truck following closely is a closed rear zone LOS-POT. </BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<H3>First Step of Zone Control </H3>

The first step of Zone Control takes place upon seeing an LOS-POT zone change.
Carney states, &quot;Benign experiences such as...parked vehicles remaining
stationary...encourage drivers to erroneously assign little or no risk to
potential events having considerable risk.&quot; When a driver is taught
to &quot;be careful&amp;quot; because the parked car may pull in front,
or a door may pop open, or someone may be concealed by the parked car, and
none of these events occur, the driver develops an okay expectancy which
leads him/her to believe the danger is no longer there. Or to describe it
in another way, the driver feels comfortable. The internal value of risk
perception is void. There appears to be nothing wrong. <BR>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>The ABC's of Zone Control </H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE><B>A</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><B>Alert switched on<BR>
</B>See an LOS-POT change</BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>
B</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><B>Before acting: </B><BR>
Check The Other Zones </BLOCKQUOTE>

<B>C</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><B>Create time/space management: </B><BR>
Get the Best Speed Control, Lane Position, Communication </BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
With the Zone Control System, the parked car is a right-front zone change.
The right-front zone change requires the driver to check other zones to
determine options, then get the best selection of speed, lane position,
and communication. It doesn't matter if the car remains parked. It still
changes the right-front zone, which requires the driver to &quot;create&quot;
control over the situation. The actions required by the driver for the right-front
zone change caused by the parked car are exactly the same as what the driver
would need to do if any right-front zone change occurs, such as: a car backing
out of a driveway, a hitchhiker, an ice cream vendor, construction, a jogger,
a car stopped at an intersection, or a snow bank. <BR>
<BR>
Because the process is the same, and only the elements of the situation
change, we have many opportunities for conscious performance of the routine
to be practiced into habit. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Second Step of Zone Control </H3>

The second step of Zone Control begins after the driver's alert switch is
turned on by detecting a closed zone. Before taking an action, all necessary
information should be obtained by &quot;Checking The Other Zones.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
To make consistently low-risk decisions, a driver needs to gather all available
information in a timely manner. When a deteriorated zone condition is detected
at least 12-15 seconds ahead in the target area, there is ample time to
get complete information. <BR>
<BR>
Example: After seeing a closed front zone, a check of the rear zone should
take place each and every time before or as the foot goes onto the brake
pedal. Such conscious performance during the learning process will help
the driver develop a proper habitual searching pattern. At some time, perhaps
many years after the driver receives his/her license, the driver is confronted
with a quick and unexpected braking action while traveling at 60 mph on
a highway as traffic comes to a sudden stop. A timely, instinctive glance
in the rear view mirror can give the driver options to avoid a devastating
rear end crash. It would be unlikely that a driver education teacher would
ever experience that high risk situation during in-car performance. However,
there can be hundreds of opportunities to practice control of the rear zone,
beginning with checking the rear view mirror during routine stop situations.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Third Step of Zone Control </H3>

The third step of Zone Control takes place after all available information
has been processed. It results in the driver taking the appropriate actions
that will result in the best speed control, lane position, and communication.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Speed Control Options </H3>

After making an evaluation of the zone conditions, you have five options
for speed control. One of these five choices is the best option. 
<BLOCKQUOTE>Same Speed <BR>
Decelerate <BR>
Off Gas - Cover Brake <BR>
Off Gas - Apply Brake <BR>
Increase Speed </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
At any given moment one of the speed control options is best. Which is &quot;best&quot;
is determined by the principles of Zone Control. For example, one of the
principles states &quot;When the front zone is closed, adjust speed to arrive
into an open zone.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Therefore, while approaching a red traffic light, our expectation of correct
performance goes beyond merely stopping for the red light. There is an opportunity
to put the three steps of Zone Control into action culminating with an effective
selection of speed control. <BR>
<BR>
When students take their foot off the accelerator, check the rear view mirror,
and begin applying the brake, positive feedback can be given to reinforce
correct behavior. When the foot stays on the accelerator too long, a cue
can be given to generate a correct response. Effective speed control is
achieved on a conscious level and can be applied in the same manner to numerous
other situations until correct habitual behavior occurs. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Lane Position Options </H3>
<IMG SRC="lanepos.gif" WIDTH="401" HEIGHT="104"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
There are five possible lane positions a driver can select from to gain
&quot;best&quot; lane positioning. Lane <B>position one</B> is in the center
of the lane. Lane <B>position two</B> is to the left edge of the lane. Lane
<B>position three</B> is to the right edge of the lane. Lane <B>positions
four and five</B> are straddle positions used for special situations. <BR>
<BR>
One of the principles of Zone Control for determining correct lane usage
says, &quot;Keep the most open space away from the worst problem.&quot;
While most travel lanes are twelve feet wide, cars are less than six feet
wide. When a driver moves away from a right front zone change by going into
lane position two, there becomes six feet of empty space. Such empty space
can give you more time to recognize when a vehicle is entering your intended
travel path, and it will give other drivers an escape path to minimize or
to avoid a crash. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Students Need to Learn How to Acquire Accurate Feedback </H3>

From the use of the Zone Control System and its principles, drivers are
able to acquire a feedback system to know when successful low-risk behavior
and wrongful higher-risk behavior occur. <BR>
<BR>
The major objective of the Zone Control System is to create control of all
six zones surrounding the vehicle. Drivers are taught not to enter closed
zones and to create adjustments in time and space to arrive into open zones.
They are expected to create improvements in speed and positioning to other
vehicles and to LOS restrictions to gain the best control. <BR>
<BR>
When a zone change is present, and the driver uses the Zone Control System
to create control, the standard for success is several steps removed from
a crash. For example, while approaching an intersection, a truck is stopped
in the left turn lane, resulting in an LOS restriction of the left-front
zone. The driver creates control over the LOS restriction by checking the
rear zone, evaluating lane choice and positioning within the lane, covering
the brake, selecting an appropriate speed choice, and searching to the left-front
of the stopped truck to evaluate POT conditions. <BR>
<BR>
The student can receive positive feedback for any or all of these action.
At first the feedback comes from the instruction, then positive self-feedback
can occur. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Go Beyond Defensive Driving: Be A Creative Driver! </H3>

The Zone Control System, quite simply, teaches drivers how to create control
of the driving environment they are operating in. To be in control means
applying the principles of Zone Control to situations when there is the
best opportunity to neutralize a zone change from becoming a high risk situation
that could result in a dramatic, and often traumatic, reaction. Zone Control
is a proactive system that teaches drivers to make small adjustments to
take control of a situation before the trap is sprung. <BR>
<BR>
Perhaps it is time to stop teaching slogans such a &quot;drive defensively&quot;
and begin teaching drivers how to create control over a situation. When
a driver is in control of a situation, there are fewer surprises from others'
actions. That allows the elimination of stressful, if not dangerous situations.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>The Science of Driving </H3>

There are cause and effect relationships that can give the driver predictable
feedback when a particular condition takes place. For example, when a driver
turns the steering wheel fully in a given direction, and a certain speed
is obtained, the turning radius of the vehicle will be consistent under
those same conditions. When speed is increased the turning radius of the
vehicle will increase. If a driver is approaching a small radius curve and
speed is not reduced, the car is going to use a large steering radius which
makes the car travel beyond the radius of the road. The results are very
predictable. The car goes off the road surface and crashes into the trees
bordering the road's edge. <BR>
<BR>
Carney stated, &quot;Speed selection is not an independent issue. It is
a complex accommodation of a variety of factors.&quot; There are many factors
which can compound the risk a driver is exposed to, and there are always
risk-generating factors not known to the driver. <BR>
<BR>
While approaching a small radius curve, some of the risk factors having
a scientific effect upon the steering radius of the vehicle are direction
of the curve, left or right; camber of the road surface, grade elevation,
up, down, or level; loose sand, water, ice, snow, dew on the road surface;
composition of the pavement; suspension system of the vehicle; tire pressure;
application of acceleration or braking forces; number of occupants in the
vehicle; seating location of occupants; weight of occupants; drive line
entry into the curve; apex positioning; an exiting point of the drive line.
<BR>
<BR>
The presence of any one of these risk factors can result in the car going
out of control when the driver is operating close to the edge of the traction
envelope. <BR>
<BR>
It would be beyond human capabilities to expect a driver to know all the
risk factors that may be working against him/her at any given moment. But
we can teach a system of habit formation that will give the driver an opportunity
to make a low-risk, timely response to compensate for the unknown and unknown
risk factors. <BR>
<BR>
Using the Zone Control System, a driver would identify the curve in the
target area as a front zone change. Check the other zones to see what options
are available for best lane positioning on the approach to the curve. Evaluate
tire/surface traction to aid in the selection of the &quot;best&quot; speed
control. Search into the curve for the condition of the POT before and during
entry. <BR>
<BR>
For each situation, whether it is a curve ahead, a red traffic light, a
parked car, a construction site, stopped traffic, or any of the other countless
different situations, the Zone Control process is the same. The student
need learn only a few principles and apply them over and over in a variety
of situations until it becomes an internalized value. Summary Most good
building contractors are not architects, but they are able to build a solid
structure when provided with a proper blueprint. Spending the past few years
traveling around the country sharing ideas with a great many driver educators,
I have found eager and highly motivated driver educators who welcome effective
curriculum materials. <BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Ed. Note: </I></B><I>To obtain a copy of <B>Partnership for Driver
Excellence: Student, Parent, Teacher, an in-car curriculum guide,</B> please
contact: Professor Fred R. Mottola, 390 Maple Avenue Cheshire, CT 06410
</I><P>

