<H1>THE DRIVER LICENSING Eagle Eye </H1>
<P><HR><P>

<STRONG><A HREF="eagle24.html">VIEW A SAMPLE</A> of THE DRIVER LICENSING Eagle Eye</strong><P>
<HR><P>

<STRONG>FOR SUBSCRIBERS ONLY:</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/pde/ARTICLES/restricted/eagle2.html">Volume 2, Issue 1</A> (Jan. 1996)
<LI><A HREF="/pde/ARTICLES/restricted/eagle3.html">Volume 2, Issue 2</A> (March 1996)
<LI><A HREF="/pde/ARTICLES/restricted/eagle4.html">Volume 2, Issue 3</A> (May 1996)
</UL><P>
<HR><P>
Issued every two months, <B>Eagle Eye</B> newletter reports the 
latest news and developments in U.S. driver licensing. For a one-year 
subscription please send cheque for $25 U.S. ($35 U.S. for Canadian 
residents) to Eagle Vision Consultants, PO Box 34, Williamston, ML 48895. 
Please include your full name and address, organization, title and phone and 
fax numbers. <P>
<HR><P>
<B>Here are the conclusions from a recent &quot;Eagle Eye&quot; report on 
Commercial Driver Licensing (CDL):</B><P>
<blockquote>
The CDL licensing program is and has been a very effective federal and state 
partnership program. While loopholes and weaknesses do exist, the strength 
and integrity level of the overall system is high.<P>
The recommendations from the AAMVA (American Association of Motor Vehicle 
Administrators) report seem to be reasonable in strengthening the system in 
the short term; however, the long-term solution to achieve a 99% integrity 
level will require numerous additional resources and mandated program. To 
achieve a one-person/one-license/one-record system would require a biometric 
identifier. In addition, an all-driver information system, not just CDLIS, 
would need to be developed (a true national driver register).<P>
Major weaknesses still exist in the information system. The first being a 
licensing jurisdiction's inability to check a license status or record using 
their own network called "AAMVAnet". If a state motor vehicle agency wants 
to check a license, it must go through the National Law Enforcement 
Telecommunication Syhstem (NLETS). The other major weakness is the lack of a 
uniform management information subsystem. Many states do not even know 
passing rates on CDL knowledge tests - let alone information Congress and 
FHWA (Federal Highway Administration)want. In hindsight, the FHWA should 
have required this type of data as part of their rulemaking.<P>
There is still a need for uniformity in U.S. jurisdictions base licensing 
systems. For example, stand alone basic uniform class, type endorsements, 
and restriction codes on the driver license itself are needed. This would 
allow driver licensing personnel and the law enforcement community almost 
total recognition of license information.<P>
FWHA has allowed certain states to use tests that are substandard to the 
model tests, therefore, full uniformity will not be achieved. States using 
the model tests require CDL holders transferring to their state to take the 
model CDL tests. Only a few states have skills test reciprocity.<P>
AAMVA did not conduct, nor has the FHWA required, an investigation into 
fatal crashes similar to the 1980 NTSB previously mentioned. The AAMVA 
report recognizes that CDL holders are using non-CDL licenses to avoid 
convictions, points, etc. The scope of this p;ractice has not been 
determined, nor is it one of the FHWA contract objectives.<P>
Finally, citation tracking research needs to be conducted to determine the 
integrity of the whole traffic records system and if we truly are to 
identify problem drivers.<P></blockquote><HR><P>

For authoritative comment and analysis on driver licensing in the United 
States, <BR>subscribe to <B>THE DRIVER LICENSING Eagle Eye.</B><P>
<HR>
RETURN to <A HREF="newsleta.html">Sample Newsletters</A>.<P>
<p>
<img src="/icons/line_sun.gif" alt="----------">
