<img src="/icons/line_sun.gif" alt="----------">
<p>

<H1>
Proposed definitions of safe driving</H1>
<H3>An attempt to clear the road for more effective driver education</H3>
<p>

<i>Abstract from a paper by Pierro Hirsch, of Montreal, Quebec</i><p>
<blockquote>
A survey of traffic accident literature reveals a marked lack of agreement on what constitutes a valid measure of safe driving. Nor does there appear to be any strong support for a single coherent theoretical model to explain or to account for the occurrance of driving collisions. <p>The only consensus shared by researchers seems to be that involvement in an automobile collision is not, by itself, considered to be a reliable indicator of "unsafe" driving. This discussion paper suggests that one of the reasons for this overall lack of clarity may be a general tendency to confuse the interrelated but distinctly different concepts of "legal" and "safe" driving. <p>A definition of "safe" driving is proposed and contrasted with "legal" driving and a basis for a cognitive approach to collision-prevention training and driver licence evaluation is suggested. <p>
<i>PROCEEDINGS of the Canadian Multidisciplinary Road Safety Conference IX; May 28-31, 1995; Montreal, Quebec.</i><p></blockquote><HR>
<STRONG>Copyright PDE Publications. No reproduction of any kind without permission.</STRONG></BODY></HTML> 


