<HEAD>
<TITLE>Some predictions on driver ed</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<A HREF="http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/index.html">
<img src="/pde/home_btn.gif" 
     hspace=5
     align="middle" 
     alt="HOME">

VILLAGE Home Page
</A>
	<A HREF="/pde/infodbase.html">
	<img src="/pde/info.gif" 
hspace=5
		align="middle"
		alt="INFODATA">
	Library
	</A> <A HREF="/cgi-bin/pde-search.pl?heading=training">
	<img src="/pde/back.gif" 
hspace=5
		align="middle"
		alt="Training">
	Training &#38; Education
	</A>


 <p>
<img src="/icons/line_sun.gif" alt="----------">
<p>

<H1>Some predictions on driver ed</H1><P><blockquote>Several years ago, as president of the American Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association, John Harvey identified some trends in driver training and education that would characterize the decade of the nineties.<P>
  
A national campaign would be necessary to keep the public's attention focused on traffic deaths, he predicted, otherwise the problem would fade into the background as more sensational problems such as AIDS and crime took the spotlight. That observation proved to be on target.<P>
 
Harvey, who is Regional Traffic Safety Education Coordinator for Service District 101 in Washington State, also predicted that governments would toughen up license requirements and impose harsher penalties for driving infractions. These predictions, too, seem to be right on track.<P>

<H4>Graduated licensing</H4><P>

The province of Ontario has just introduced a two-phase system of graduated licensing which will involve a second driving test for license applicants, and a number of jurisdictions are considering similar initiatives. <P>
The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration supports the trend to graduated licensing and also a two-phase system of training/education for drivers. Legislation to support states in developing tougher licensing standards and tougher penalties for violators is before Congress.<P> 

<H4>Shortage of instructors</H4><P>

Fewer universities are involved in training driver education teachers these days, Harvey says, and he sees a critical shortage of adequately-trained instructors ahead as an aging populaton of teachers reaches retirement. This concern is also expressed by the American Automobile Association, which has stepped up its efforts to provide instructor training.<P>
 
"Validation" will be the theme for curriculum development over the next few years, Harvey feels. He predicts an increasing emphasis on student-centered performance objectives, criterion reference tests, and instructional materials that have been tested for effectiveness.<P>

Harvey also sees a trend towards qualitative changes in the way programs operate. Curriculum will be connected to other social and educational issues, he says, and there will be an increase in partnerships with communities through Community Traffic Safety Programs.  These partnerships, he predicts, will be the key to maintaining strong driver ed.<P>

</blockquote><HR>
<STRONG>Copyright PDE Publications. No reproduction of any kind without permission.</STRONG></BODY></HTML> 

 



