<H1>International driver's license invaluable</H1><P><H4>By Dan Keegan</H4>
<P><blockquote>
<P>For the small cost involved, an International Driving Permit is a wise investment if you're thinking of driving while abroad. And even if you're not actually planning to drive, who knows? Your plans might change so why not be prepared.<P>
Essentially, an International Driving Permit (IDP) is proof that you hold a valid driver's licence in your own country.<P>
It may not be absolutely necessary to have it, since most countries recognize each other's licenses. but possessing an IDP has many advantages.<P>
The permit is intended to overcome the difficulties drivers might have while travelling by car in other countries that may have widely varying license requirements.<P>
The authorization for the IDP has its basis in international conventions on road safety. There were conventions in 1923, 1943, 1949 and 1968 which established rules for IDPs.<P>
One of the main advantages of the IDP, which is easy to apply for and doesn't involve taking a driving test, is that it is printed in 10 languages - the five United Nations official languages (English, French, Spanish, Russian and Chinese) plus German Arabic, Italian, the Scandinavian languages and Portuguese.<P>
It's easy to imagine how this might solve problems. If you're stopped by the police for some reason, or you need identification, you can present a document that may be in the local language, or at least can be understood.<P>
There are other advantages, too.<P>
If you're in an accident, or need to rent a car, it can be invaluable. In fact, in more than 40 countries you can't rent a car at all unless you have an IDP. For driving in Europe, travel officials say the IDP is more necessary in some countries than others, but it's advised for most.<P></blockquote><HR>
<STRONG>Copyright PDE Publications. No reproduction of any kind without permission.</STRONG>
</BODY></HTML>
