<TITLE>Ontario moves to graduated licensing</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<A HREF="http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/index.html">
<img src="/pde/home_btn.gif" 
     hspace=5
     align="middle" 
     alt="HOME">

VILLAGE Home Page
</A>
	<A HREF="/pde/infodbase.html">
	<img src="/pde/info.gif" 
hspace=5
		align="middle"
		alt="INFODATA">
	Library
	</A> <A HREF="/cgi-bin/pde-search.pl?heading=licensing">
	<img src="/pde/back.gif" 
hspace=5
		align="middle"
		alt="Licensing">
	Driver Licensing
	</A>


 <p>
<img src="/icons/line_sun.gif" alt="----------">
<p>


<H1>Ontario moves to graduated licensing</H1><P>
<P>
<P>
<I> (Driver/Education, June. 1994)</I><P>
<blockquote>
Ontario moved very quickly, during the past year, to become the first jurisdiction in North America to adopt a full-fledged graduated driver licensing (GDL) system for all new drivers. 
<P>
Following cabinet endorsement in June 1993, the legislation for GDL moved quickly through the system and by December it had passed into law. This was record-breaking speed, according to Assistant Deputy Minister and Registrar for Motor Vehicles Kim Devooght. And it reflects the extent of government commitment to the initiative and a level of public support that's been estimated as high as 87%. 
<P>
The system was initiated on April 1, 1994, and will be fully implemented as of June 6. It's a two-level system with provision for a road test in each level and restrictions that are gradually lifted as drivers move through.<P>
Drivers coming from jurisdictions outside the province that have driver licensing exchange agreements with Ontario (all Canadian provinces and territories, the United States and Japan) are exempt from the conditions of GDL provided they have at least two years' driving experience. <P>
These drivers will receive an Ontario driver's license without having to complete a knowledge test or road test, provided they meet all the medical requirements. 
<P>
Licensed drivers from these jurisdictions with less than two years driving experience will be allowed to enter Level Two of the GDL system, and they can take a Level Two road test to become fully licensed after they have accumulated two years' driving experience under the system. 
<P>
Drivers from jurisdictions without a licensing agreement with Ontario must meet all medical requirements and pass a vision and knowledge test on the rules of the road. If they don't have proof of more than two years' driving experience they will be treated as new drivers. If they do have such proof, they will be allowed to take a Level Two road test and become fully licensed drivers if they pass it.If they fail, they can schedule a Level One road test.<P>
 
All drivers holding a class `L'(Car) or Class `R'(Motorcycle) learner's license before April 1, 1994, were allowed to continue under the existing system. However, they must pass their road test before June 6, 1994 to avoid the graduated system. If they don't pass this test before June 6, they enter Level Two of the graduated system. 
<P>

<H4>Anxious new drivers</H4><P>

Prior to the initial implementation date of April 1, 1994, aspiring new drivers almost literally invaded driver examination centers in an attempt to squeeze through before being caught in the GDL mesh. One center in downtown Toronto reported that, for a two-week period in March, applications for learner permits soared from the normal rate of about 150-200 per day to more than 700 per day. <P>
At some centers police had to be called in to maintain order in the line-ups and even that, said one examiner, didn't prevent friction between impatient applicants.<P>


<H4>License costs go up</H4><P>
 

The cost of an Ontario driver's license will increase considerably under the new system. The previous charge of $31 covered the knowledge test, vision test, road test, and a charge for the license itself. New rates were announced recently: $10 for the knowledge test; $40 for the Level One road test; $75 for the Level Two road test. Novice drivers exiting the graduated system will pay an additional $50 for a five-year driver's license, bringing the total to $175.<P>
 

<H4>The second road test</H4><P>


A prototype of the Level Two road test has been developed by consultants Engel and Townsend under contract to the Ontario Ministry of Transportation. Data analysis from field tests conducted over the summer will be used to finalise test procedures, set examiner training, and set passing scores based on norms provided by the field test data. A final version should be ready by early 1995. The same prototype is being used for the development of a Level Two motorcycle test.  
<P>
The prototype is based on a similar test (also developed by Engel and Townsend) now being used for commercial drivers throughout the U.S. The U.S. Commercial Driver License test is the first research-based driver license test to be developed and used in North America. <P>
It cost over $1,000,000 to develop and it emphasised three key factors: what behaviours are involved in safe driving; what the examiner has to do to see the driver performing these behaviours; and what criteria the examiner can use to decide whether the driver performed these behaviours correctly. The test relies on a high standard of examiner training and consistency in scoring license applicants. 
<P>
An interim Level Two test, which is an extended version of the pre-GDL road test, will be used until the prototype is finalised.<P><H3>FROM THE OLD TO THE NEW IN ONTARIO</H3><P>
<P>
<P>
<I> (Driver/Education, June. 1994)</I><P>

Under the old licensing system, new drivers in Ontario had to pass a vision test and a written test (40 questions) to obtain an `L' or learner's license. Then they were required to wait a minimum of three days before taking a road test. Successful completion of the road test gave them a two-year probationary licence. 
<P>
Graduated licensing began on April 1, 1994 and was fully implemented on June 6.<P>
<P>
 
<H4>Conditions for GDL</H4>

<H5>LEVEL ONE</H5> (entry, minimum of 8 months)<P>


<UL>
<LI>Minimum age 16.
<LI>Pass vision and knowledge test.
<LI>Can now drive on public roads, provided a fully licensed driver with at least four years' experience is in the front passenger seat. 
<LI>No driving between midnight and 5 a.m.
<LI>No blood alcohol content (BAC) allowed for driver. Licensed co-drivers must have BAC less than 0.05%.
<LI>Passengers limited to number of seatbelts available. 
<li>Not allowed to drive on high-speed expressways. (Ontario highways have a general 80kph/50mph speed limit. Expressways and freeways may have 100kph/60 mph limits.)
</UL>
At the end of level One (12 months, or 8 months with driver ed. certificate) the license applicant must pass a road test to enter Level Two.<P>


<H5>LEVEL TWO</H5> (lasts 12 months)<P>
 

Novice drivers in Level Two are allowed to drive any time of the day or night, without an accompanying driver. They may also drive on any Ontario road. 
There are two restrictions:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Zero BAC.
<li>Every passenger must wear a seatbelt.
</UL><P>

 
At the end of level Two, the novice driver must pass an advanced driving test in order to obtain a full license.<P><H3>CHANGING OVER TO GDL IN ONTARIO</H3><P>
<P>
<P>
<I> (Driver/Education, June. 1994)</I><P>

Summarized below are the contents of a circular issued to Ontario's new drivers by the Province's Ministry of Transportation:<P><P>
 

1.	If you received your Learner License before April 1, 1994, and you pass your road test before June 6:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Graduated Licensing does not apply to you.
<LI>You are only subject to the Learner License conditions until you pass your road test.
<li>When you pass the road test, you are subject to the standard two-year probationary period.
</UL><P>


2.	If you received your Learner License before April 1, 1994, and you pass your road test after June 5:<P>

<UL>
<LI>The Learner License conditions apply to you until you pass the road test.
<LI>When you pass the road test, you enter Level 2 and must drive under Level 2 conditions.
<LI>You must remain in Level 2 for 12 months, plus any time remaining on your Learner License,* before you can take the Level 2 road test.
<li>When you pass the Level 2 test, you are fully licensed.
</UL><P>


3.	If you received your Learner License between April 1 and June 5, 1994, and you take the Level 1 road test after June 5:<P>

<UL>
<LI>The Learner License conditions apply to you until June 5, 1994.
<LI>As of June 6, 1994, the Level 1 conditions apply to you.
<LI>You must remain in Level 1 for 12 months* before you can take the Level 1 road test.
<LI>When you pass the Level 1 test, you enter Level 2 and must drive under the Level 2 conditions.
<LI>You must remain in Level 2 for 12 months before you can take the Level 2 road test.
<LI>When you pass the Level 2 test, you are fully licensed.
</UL><P>

4.	If you apply for your license after June 6, 1994:<P>

<UL>
<LI>You are subject to both levels of Graduated Licensing from the 			beginning.
<LI>You must remain in Level 1, and drive under Level 1 conditions, for 12 months.* You graduate from this level when you pass the Level 1 road test.
<LI>You must drive in Level 2, and abide by its conditions, for 12 months before you can take the Level 2 road test.
<li>When you pass the Level 2 test, you are fully licensed.
</UL><P>


<H4>*	DRIVER'S EDUCATION COURSE:</H4><P>

Remember that passing a driver's education course will reduce your 		mandatory time periods.<P>

<UL>
<LI>In Example 2, the "remaining time" on the Learner's License can be reduced by up to 4 months.
<li>In Examples 3 and 4, the 12-month Level 1 period can be reduced to only 8 months.
</UL><P>


<H4>MOTORCYCLE DRIVERS:</H4><P>

The above examples also apply to motorcycle licenses, with the 
following exceptions:<P>

	a.	The Level 1 mandatory time period is 60 days, not 12 months.
	b.	The Level 2 mandatory time period is 22 months, not 12 months.
	c.	The Motorcycle Safety Course time reduction can only be 
		applied to Level 2, not Level 1.<P>
</blockquote><HR>
