<HTML><head><TITLE>Front-wheel handbrake an anomaly</TITLE></head>
<BODY>
<A HREF="http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/index.html">
<img src="/pde/home_btn.gif" 
     hspace=5
     align="middle" 
     alt="HOME">

VILLAGE Home Page
</A>
	<A HREF="/pde/infodbase.html">
	<img src="/pde/info.gif" 
hspace=5
		align="middle"
		alt="INFODATA">
	Library
	</A> <A HREF="/cgi-bin/pde-search.pl?heading=general">
	<img src="/pde/back.gif" 
hspace=5
		align="middle"
		alt="General">
General Subjects
	</A>


 <p>
<img src="/icons/line_sun.gif" alt="----------">
<p>



<H1>Front-wheel handbrake an anomaly</H1><P>
Driver/Ed, 1994<P>
<blockquote>


Everyone knows that a car's handbrake is connected to the rear wheels, right? 
In most cases the answer is yes, unless you happen to own a Subaru Loyale or one of Subaru's sporty XT series. These cars represent a bit of an anomaly because their handbrake is linked to the front wheels.<P>
 
Explains Richard Marsan, Technical Services Manager with Subaru Canada Ltd. in Montreal: "The handbrake is basically an emergency brake. And looking at things from an engineering standpoint, Subaru manufacturer Fuji decided to install it on the front disks, which are larger and provide more stopping power.<P>
"Stopping a car with only one set of brakes, front or rear, is never too satisfactory because the vehicle tends to slip all over the place, especially in bad weather," Marsan adds. "This skidding effect is really very evident where the handbrake is connected to the rear wheels, as in most cars."<P>
There's little chance of inducing a front wheel skid with the Loyale or XT handbrake, Marsan says. "The Loyale weighs around 2,800 pounds and you'd need the strength of an Arnold Schwarzenegger to lock up the front end," he adds. <P>The handbrake, of course, requires more strength to apply because it is cable-activated rather than hydraulic or power-assisted. Also, there are always trade-offs and the front wheel emergency brake is less efficient when used as a parking brake. <P>If a parked car's disks are hot from driving, for instance, the handbrake shoes will squeeze the expanded disks, possibly causing damage. In addition, when the disk cools and the metal contracts, there's a danger of the car rolling downhill if the brake hasn't been applied firmly in the first place.<P> 
As a result, Fuji has switched back on its newer Legacy, SVX and Impreza models, all of which have disks all round. The handbrake has been connected to a combined drum and disk on the rear wheels.<P> 
"It's not a new idea," says Marsan. "In fact, I think it first appeared on the '66 Porsche. Basically, it consists of a small drum containing the handbrake shoes and surrounded by the disk. In this configuration, the disk provides reinforcement for the drum, preventing any distortion during heavy use."<P>
Why not install a disk/drum combination on the front end? "Firstly, it takes up a lot of room," says Marsan, "and also the front-end handbrake is extremely expensive because it must be engineered to let the wheels turn. Putting it on the rear wheels is really a cost-saving measure."<P>
If you've just got to have a front-wheel handbrake model, better look for a used car. Subaru has already replaced its XT series with the SVX, and the best-selling Loyale has also been phased out.<P>

<H4>Winter handbrake tip</H4><P> 

A car that doesn't have traction control can be stuck if just one wheel is on a slippery surface, even though all the others have excellent traction. Since the differential gear allows the engine to turn the drive wheels of the car at different rates (essential for going around corners), a patch of ice that offers little or no resistance to one of the drive wheels can cause all the power to go to that wheel, leaving the other drive wheel stopped. <P>If the spinning wheel can be slowed down, then power has to transfer to the stopped wheel. 
If the parking brake works on the drivewheels, which it does on pretty well all rear-wheel-drive cars, and also on the front-wheel-drive Subaru described on this page, a trick that may work is to slow the spinning wheel using a slight pressure from the parking brake. <P>If the parking brake slows the spinning wheel, then power has to shift to the stopped wheel. This trick doesn't always work, but it may save a tow if you're stuck sometime.<P>

</blockquote><HR>
<STRONG>Copyright PDE Publications. No reproduction of any kind without permission.</STRONG></BODY></HTML>

