<P>
<H2><A NAME="safety">Is safety killing driver ed?</A></H2><P>
<blockquote>&quot;Your teenager will still think he's immortal. But we'll have improved his life expectancy.&quot;<P>

That statement appeared in a Kingston, Ontario, newspaper advertisement last 
month. It was an ad for a novice driver training program run by Young 
Drivers of Canada (YD), an internationally franchised chain of driving 
schools that has branches in the U.S. and Europe. It angered psychology 
professor Gerald Wilde, an expert on driving and risk-taking behaviour based 
at the local Queen's University. He feels it's misleading advertising.<P>

The ad's statement, Wilde feels, conflicts with evidence about the 
effectiveness of driver education. It also conflicts with Wilde's theory of 
risk homeostasis, which tries to explain why it is that safety measures 
developed by industry and government often don't yield the intended 
results.<P>
Risk homeostasis theory (RHT) has been the subject of hot debate in safety 
and health circles for almost two decades now. It states that unless a 
safety measure motivates drivers to reduce their &quot;target level of risk,&quot; it 
will have no effect on their chances of having an accident and no effect on 
their life expectancy prospects. Wilde has just put his theory, along with 
all of its supporting arguments and data, into a book titled <STRONG><A HREF="target.html">Target Risk</A></STRONG>.<P>

Wilde's theory is debated because it brings into question the effectiveness 
of any safety measure -- whether it be engineering, enforcement or education -- in reducing crashes, unless it can change safety motivation. The recent 
revelation from the Highway Loss Data Institute that antilock braking 
systems have not reduced deaths, injuries or repair bills, is a case in 
point. <P>
It bolsters Wilde's theory that drivers tend to use up the safety value of 
such interventions by adjusting their behaviour so that their perceived 
level of risk remains the same. In the case of ABS, the evidence shows that 
drivers of cars equipped with it tend to drive faster, take more chances, 
and use their brakes more heavily.<P>

With regard to driver training as a safety intervention, Wilde writes: 
&quot;There are two opposing views, the prevailing one that driver training is 
productive towards safety, and the view held by RHT that it is not. &quot;<P>  
Professor Wilde defines training as &quot;the instilling of practical perceptual, 
decisional and motor skills,&quot; and education as &quot;the effort to enlighten, to 
civilize, and thus to impart more mature views, beliefs and values.&quot; He 
points out that the evidence does not support beliefs that current driver 
training/education programs for novice drivers reduce crashes. In fact, he 
goes further to argue that the same applies to post-licensure defensive 
driving courses.<P> 
Risk homeostasis theory has been described as &quot;a frontal attack&quot; on the 
basic premises underlying most of today's government and industry safety 
practices by internationally renowned risk analysis experts Paul Slovic and 
Baruch Fischhoff, and as &quot;the devil's idea to some in the safety community&quot; 
by  economics professor Glenn Blomquist of the University of Kentucky.<P>

It's of particular importance to the driver education community right now. 
Concerns about the safety value of driver education programs have been 
undermining driver ed efforts for more than a decade and there is an obvious 
dissonance between what the driver training/education community feels it's 
doing, and what the research and policymaking communities believe about the 
achievements of training/education. It's also of particular interest in that 
Professor Wilde is part of the Northport Associates team that is developing 
a model for a new kind of driver training/education curriculum.<P>
<H3>Outdated curriculum</H3><P>

In recent years, educators have been shifting their emphasis strongly in 
favour of safety as the primary outcome of training and education. Driver 
education textbooks that became packed with details various interest groups 
felt were important are now seen as a problem in terms of safety 
effectiveness. &quot;We have a 90-hour textbook and a 30-hour classroom,&quot; says 
former Oregon Driver Education Supervisor Del Freeman. &quot;They're trying to 
cover uphill park, downhill park, how to change a flat tire, but there's no 
injury rate involved in those things&quot; (see <STRONG>Driver/Education</STRONG>, September 
1994).<P>

The new emphasis is on teaching risk perception and decisionmaking. But if 
driver training doesn't produce a safety effect, do we need it? Might we be 
faced, at some time in the future, with the rather bizarre prospect of zero 
training requirements for the operation of expensive, and potentially 
dangerous automobiles on overcrowded roadways?<P>

In recent years, lack of support for driver training and education has 
devastated the quality of services in many jurisdictions. Tough competition 
for business has meant that standards have slipped and many of the better 
operators have been forced out. &quot;Bad operators have a tendency to drive out 
good,&quot; says AAA Foundation Executive Director David K. Willis.  In tough 
economic times, school owners who cut corners, pay low rates to instructors, 
and provide minimal service can survive better, while owners who obey the 
rules, pay their taxes, and maintain high standards fall by the wayside.<P>

Most participants in the training industry seem to feel that safety has to 
be their product. It's difficult to get instructors to talk about other 
kinds of outcomes without quoting safety as a benefit.  Most instructors 
want to feel that their students will learn good driving habits from them, 
maintain those habits after getting a licence, and be less likely to have a 
crash as a result. However, the practical reality for instructors is that 
their students would like to pass their driving test and get a licence, and 
that has to be the instructor's immediate priority. For the most part, the 
driving test drives training priorities and determines the quality of 
training.<P>

Does this basic necessity preclude making driver's safer? It doesn't have 
to, according to Young Drivers of Canada (YD) president Peter Christianson. 
Christianson takes issue with Wilde's view of training effectiveness. &quot;We're 
brave enough to say we can keep somebody alive,&quot; he says. &quot;Wilde wants to 
challenge ... he hasn't taken our course. He hasn't driven down a gravel 
shoulder at 80 km/h with two wheels on the gravel ... done threshold braking 
from 80 km/h ... done brake and avoid...hasn't taken a defensive driving 
course so he knows how to move his eyes properly.&quot;<P>

&quot;If you design your course with the specific objectives of reducing crashes 
and saving lives you will see something totally different from what most 
driving schools are teaching, that is, to pass the road test.&quot; 
Christianson sees a big challenge for driver trainers in Ontario's new &quot;G2&quot; 
road test. This is a longer, and more thorough, test of defensive driving 
ability that will be given to driver licence applicants in Ontario at the 
end of the second phase of graduated licensing. It will likely be 
implemented in the spring of 1995. Currently, G2 licence applicants are 
being tested with an enhanced version of the pre-graduated licence road 
test.<P>

You can't pass the G2 test, Christianson says, unless you drive defensively. 
And YD Graduates will find it easy, he feels, because YD has always trained 
students to meet these kinds of demands. However, the trend away from 
driving basics is not something Christianson favours. The YD strategy, he 
says, is &quot;to give people the basic skills quickly, so that the remaining 
60-70&#37; of course time can be spent on teaching defensive driving or 
safety.&quot;<P>

Studies that have indicated driver education courses as being ineffective in 
producing safety gains don't impress Christianson. Researchers, he feels, 
haven't studied the best programs. &quot;I can't give you any studies that 
validate driver training,&quot; he says, &quot;but they (researchers) can't validate 
what they're saying either.&quot; The DeKalb study, often quoted as the largest 
and most controlled study of driver education effectiveness ever, and as 
definitive evidence of driver ed's failure, was flawed, he points out, in 
that there was very little actual on-road driving time included. &quot;Any 
educator will tell you that you remember 10&#37; of what you hear, 20&#37; of what 
you hear and see, up to 80&#37; of what you hear see and do...it's the doing 
that creates the change.&quot;<P>

Can training programs change the attitudes and behaviour that lead to 
crashes? &quot;Change of attitude is cemented,&quot; Christianson says, &quot;when students 
can see the results of a different type of driving behaviour -- they see what 
they can do...but they don't tend to become risk takers unless you do the 
training badly.<P>

<H3>Training paradox</H3><P>

The DeKalb study mentioned above compared three large groups of about 5,500 
high school students. One group got a specially developed &quot;Safe Performance 
curriculum&quot; (SPC), which included 32 hours of classroom instruction, about 
16 hours of simulator training, about 16 hours on a driving range, and about 
four hours of on-road training. A second group got a minimal training 
program with only 20 hours classroom, simulator and range combined, and just 
one hour of actual on-road training. The third group were not allocated to 
any formal training at all and were left to parental instruction, although 
some might have taken formal training on their own initiative.<P>

While Christianson is critical of the small amount of time spent in on-road 
training with the SPC DeKalb group, Professor Wilde is more interested in 
the fact that the group that got the most training had the worst driving 
record in the years following, a result that's been echoed in similar 
studies in the UK and Norway.  &quot;Since it's difficult to accept that training 
could make people worse,&quot; he writes in <STRONG><A HREF="target.html">Target Risk</A></STRONG>, &quot;one could reason as 
follows. Suppose that beginner drivers as a group more often overestimate 
risk than underestimate it. All else being equal, they will incur fewer 
accidents.&quot; <P>
The highly trained DeKalb group, Wilde surmises, were likely overconfident 
due to their increased level of skill. The less trained were likely to 
overestimate their risk in driving situations and, as a consequence, to 
drive with greater caution.<P>

This, according to Wilde's risk theory, leads to the paradoxical situation 
in which &quot;additional training should lead to an increase in accident rate 
precisely because the graduates have become more competent -- more competent 
risk takers, that is. Better driving skill -- risk perception included -- does 
not necessarily mean fewer accidents,&quot; he concludes.<P>

Christianson agrees that the accident chances of risk overestimators could 
be increased through training -- if that training has the wrong approach. 
Skid control training is an example, he feels. &quot;Skid training has been done 
incorrectly for the past 25 years; (many) programs have removed the fear, 
the respect for danger, by giving students a skid baptism, spinning them 
out.&quot; Emergency techniques training on YD courses does not include 
situations in which the student driver loses control over the car.<P>

A skid that doesn't go past the limits of recovery is OK, but spinning out 
just serves to overcome the student's natural fear of losing control. &quot;We 
should leave students with a fear of unknown. Once it becomes fun, every off 
ramp becomes a place to skid,&quot; says Christianson.<P>

While Wilde's homeostasis theory is threatening to driver training/education 
it is not necessarily incompatible with it. &quot;The notion that people could be 
educated to lower their acceptance of accident risk is not incompatible with 
the postulates of risk homeostasis theory,&quot; he writes, pointing to 
reductions in accidents and violations achieved in a preliminary study of a 
form of psychotherapy applied to repeated offenders as an example.<P>

Driver educators will get a clearer look at the future of training/education 
when the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety releases its model for curriculum 
development. One of the critical questions to be decided in framing the 
model, says project leader Lawrence Lonero, is the question of how 
priorities will be balanced between attempting to develop methods that are 
more effective in producing safety benefits and the furthering of other 
potential outcomes such as greater mobility, more efficient drivers, and the 
production more sophisticated traffic citizens. 
 <P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>
<H2><A NAME="happening">What's happening...</A></H2>
<blockquote>
<h3><A NAME="aaa">AAA curriculum on track</A></h3><P>
The AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety's project to develop a model for a new kind of driver education is on schedule for completion at the end of January 1995, according to the Foundation's Executive Director, David K. Willis. <P>
The model curriculum will be in the public domain once completed, and anyone can take it and continue the work, Willis says. It will be a signpost for further development and Willis hopes that some organization or group will carry on the work once the report on the project is released. <p>
Under project leader Lawrence P. Lonero of Northport Associates, the process of developing a model curriculum guideline includes an extensive review of the literature, discussions with selected key people in the field, and a weighing and balancing of key issues. One of these issues, says Lonero, is the question of whether safety should be the sole priority of driver training/education or whether other objectives such as mobility, efficiency, and economy in using the automobile in the traffic system should receive prominent emphasis. <P>

