<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="street">Street driving and the gas pedal</A></H2>
<blockquote>
Today's auto advertisers know that speed and power sell. And they also know that they're selling to a largely unsophisticated market in which most of the &quot;targets&quot; of the advertising are not particularly knowledgeable about what power and speed mean, or how to use them. <P>
Car advertising consistently depicts speed and maneuverability as selling points, and when it comes to speed the most commonly cited statistic is acceleration from 0-60 mph (0-100 km/h). And that, according to auto technology journalist Gerry Malloy, is a particularly useless statistic to offer in relation to a car's acceleration needs for common traffic situations.<P>
Since drivers rarely, if ever, need to accelerate from 0-60 mph (0-100 km/h) in one burst, what should interest them more are the kinds of acceleration needed for traffic situations such as merging into a traffic flow, changing into faster lanes of traffic, or getting onto freeways. In other words, acceleration from 30-50 mph (50-80km/h) or from 50-70 mph (80-120 km/h) is much more significant for the driver, suggests Malloy. <P>
But even these statistics may not be as important as how the car actually responds to the accelerator pedal. Acceleration figures are measured at full throttle. What is more relevant to the street driver, Malloy says, is how the engine responds to pressure on the pedal. If the response is too slow, the driver may regard the engine as underpowered, even though it may, in fact, be more powerful than the engines of comparable cars. And if the response is too quick it may be difficult, or even impossible, to get smooth starts or smooth transitions to higher speeds. Also, the car may be difficult to control, particularly in slippery conditions, because it's all-too-easy to overdo things with the gas pedal at the wrong moment.  <P>
There may be a number of reasons for poor throttle response, Malloy points out. The car may be underpowered, but it could also be due to poor throttle linkage geometry, &quot;or its low-speed, part-throttle performance may be compromised to generate a high peak power output that will look good in advertising comparisons with the competition.&quot;<P>
Some manufacturers are beginning to see the light and are beginning to favour better feel over big horsepower numbers, according to Malloy. One 1995 car, he says, is getting a reduction in power to increase its performance in the more critical street-driving responses. <P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="cars">Cars are getting smarter</A></H2>
<blockquote>
By 1996, the Atlanta, Georgia area will be a showcase for the Intelligent Vehicle Highway System (IVHS). The area has been selected to be one of the first large-scale tests of IVHS technology, and visitors to the Olympic Games will find cars, taxis and buses that are equipped with onboard computers giving them information about locations, traffic problems and routes. These technologies have already been tried out in a number of areas around the world, including a test in the Orlando, Florida area that was completed this year. The Orlando system is reported to have saved about 20% in driving time for cars equipped with the devices. <P>
Electronic wizardry is also saving money, and crashes, at toll areas on some highways. The Oklahoma Turnpike Authority reports that before installing electronic toll collection at its 10 toll plazas, 13% of fatalities occurred in their vicinity. Since then, there have been no fatalities and only two crashes. <P>
Vehicles equipped with the electronic toll recorders don't have to stop as they pass the booths. It's estimated that about 500,000 American cars already have these devices installed. <P>
Even smarter vehicles have radar that warns drivers about obstacles in their path and slows their vehicle if it's getting too close to the one ahead. One such vehicle has been driven from Detroit to Chicago and back without the driver having to assume control over speed. <P>

<h3>... And licenses too...</h3><P>
Soon, the European Union will adopt a &quot;smart card&quot; driver's license as the standard for the new unified European license. The card will store information about the driver, for example, about convictions, medical information, and so on. And it can be re-programmed.<P>
In Sweden, Fred Goldberg is taking this idea a step further. Goldberg's daughter was killed by a driver who was driving at high speed while under the influence of alcohol, and whose licence had already been suspended for another drunk driving conviction. Goldberg's idea is a smart-card license that is recognized by a reader installed in the vehicle. The reader would be programmed to recognize whether a license is valid, or even to recognize just certain licenses, such as those of family members. It could also be programmed to recognize whether an alcohol breath test is required before a driver is allowed to start the car. <P>
There are potential problems with the card. For example, you'd have to lend your license to someone who wanted to borrow your car, or to the auto dealer for servicing. But the prospects for implementation look good. The Swedish National Road Administration has given a grant to Goldberg to develop his idea and he also has the support of businesses, including SAAB and Volvo. <P>

So what about drivers? Keep reading <STRONG>Driver/Education</STRONG> for ideas on how to make drivers smarter.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="skid">Skid training results difficult to figure</A></H2>
<blockquote>
&quot; Driving in snow is democracy&#59; money and power don't count.&quot; <br>
-- From the Internet<P>

A skid training program offered to high school students in the Portland, Oregon area who had completed a driver training course the year before, showed some interesting differences between trained and untrained drivers and between subsequent male and female accident and violation rates. <P>
The training program was the subject of a study carried out under the direction of Dr. Barnie Jones, Office of the Manager, Oregon Driver and Motor Vehicle Services. <P>
The training was carried out at a Portland area commercial driving school. It consisted of a short classroom session followed by behind-the-wheel training on a large, flat, asphalt parking lot with a serpentine course marked off with pylons.<P>
 The practical training was carried out in a car equipped with a special hydraulically-operated outrigger system that lifts the weight of the vehicle off the wheels, thereby simulating reduced traction conditions. The outrigger system is mounted on castoring wheels that allow the car to drift in any direction if traction is sufficiently reduced. The weight can be lifted off any of the four wheels independently, so that oversteer can be simulated as well as very low friction conditions such as snow or ice. <P>

There were three phases to the practical training:<P>

<UL><LI>The first phase consisted of instruction in driver position, hand position and eye placement, first-hand experience of loss of traction under various conditions, and the application of various techniques for maintaining traction and control.<LI>
The second phase consisted of timed trials over the serpentine course.<LI>
In the third phase, students were asked to drive over the course without brakes.</UL> <P>

Throughout the course, the instructor emphasized skills for anticipating hazards and avoiding loss of traction. <P>
About 1000 students participated in the study. One group of 300 students actually completed the training. A second group of 322 students consisted of those who had asked to be on the course but did not complete the training. A third group of 396 students did not volunteer.<P>
In a summary of the results of this and other studies of the effectiveness of skid training, Jones concluded that &quot;available research on skid training is highly equivocal.&quot;  Studies in Norway, Sweden, and the U.S. generally show increases in accident rates among course graduates, rather than decreases. However, some interesting differences revealed by Jones's findings may point up important areas of development for advanced training providers to explore.<P>

<H3>The results</h3><P>
<UL><LI>Males and females appear to respond differently to advanced skills training. For example, trained males had slightly more violations than untrained, and trained females slightly less than untrained females. <LI>
Students who completed the training were slightly more likely to have an accident rather than less. <LI>
The trained group had significantly less accidents in reduced-traction conditions than the untrained group. This training effect was clear for both sexes, although females tended to have relatively more slick-surface accidents.<LI>
Interestingly, there was virtually no difference between trained and untrained groups in culpability for accidents. <LI>
Drivers with skid car training were involved in a lower proportion of rear-end collisions.</UL> <P>

Jones suggests that several competing explanations for the results should be explored. First, those with skid car training may drive more and, independent of the quality of their driving, have more accidents. Second, trained drivers may be more confident of their ability on slick roads and drive more in these situations. Third, skid training may promote overconfidence which is manifested in more risky driving in all kinds of driving situations. <P>
&quot;On the surface,&quot; Jones says, &quot;the findings seem contradictory. A higher overall accident rate suggests that skid car training is detrimental, but the relative absence of slick surface accidents and rear-end collisions indicates that skid car training is having the desired effect, to the extent that these are the types of accidents that the training should be expected to prevent.&quot; <P>

<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="tailgate">Why drivers tailgate</A></H2>
<blockquote>
Alison Smiley  (Human factors expert):  &quot;It's a sociological question.&quot;<P>

Tom Prescott (Forensic services/accident investigator): &quot;Drivers are close to one another and feel as if they're walking...there's a lack of speed differential.&quot;<P>

John Sawatsky (Former police psychologist): &quot;It's aggression.&quot;<P>

Roadworthy (Driver education textbook): &quot;It often indicates that the driver is half asleep and is following the moves of other traffic like a robot.&quot;<P>

Leonard Evans (Author of <STRONG>Traffic Safety and the Driver</STRONG>): &quot;Drivers learn, from repeated experience, that it is safe to do so...the dominant cue when following is the relative speeds of the cars...as long as the vehicles are moving at the same speed there is no feeling of danger...People from different countries have different perceptions of risk in the following distance behind other vehicles...it's a 'collective' learning experience.&quot;<P>

Peter Marsh and Peter Collett (Authors, The Driving Passion). &quot;It's territorial...To prevent overtaking cars getting into the frontal territory, drivers will frequently close up the gap between themselves and the car in front.&quot;<P>
<blockquote><HR></blockquote>


As the preceding items indicate, there are lots of opinions on why drivers tailgate. But there doesn't seem to be much in the line of hard research that would cast some light on this particular kind of driving behaviour. <P>
Several experts queried in preparation for this article admitted that, while they know of research dealing with tailgating behaviour in general, they could not bring to mind any  specific research into why individual drivers do it. Even GM Senior Researcher Leonard Evans, author of <strong>Traffic Safety and the Driver,</strong> a book that has been referred to as the bible of traffic safety research, seems to have little more than opinion to offer on the topic of why drivers adopt a tactic in traffic that is not only dangerous, but also has several tactical disadvantages. <P>
&quot;Why do drivers choose to follow so closely? It seems to me that it becomes largely a driving habit, rather than a reasoned conscious behaviour,&quot; Evans writes. &quot;Drivers appear to do many things for their own benefit rather than for any utility benefit.&quot; He goes on to suggest that, in some cases, it may be done as criminal behaviour that's indulged in for its own sake. <P>
Evans also suggests that the lack of speed difference between vehicles allows drivers to feel safe. This, and the fact that crashes are rare events and that drivers can get away with tailgating, makes drivers complacent about the danger. &quot;They have learned from repeated experience that it is safe to do so, in the sense that they have been doing it for years without adverse consequences,&quot; he writes. <P>

<h3>Challenge for educators</h3><P>
If these views hold true, driver educators have an almost impossible challenge in dealing with the problem. The 2-second rule is taught as a rule of thumb for minimum safe following distance. Many educators now suggest 3-4 seconds as a minimum. But selling this driving technique on the basis of safety may be difficult if penalties for tailgating (in the form of accidents) are rare and drivers feel no sense of danger. <P>
On the other hand, more utilitarian penalties for tailgating are quite common. Tailgaters get blocked in more often because they are unable to anticipate problems ahead and select the best lane. &quot;They feel more stress because they can't use their vision properly and do long-range traffic planning,&quot; says driver training consultant David Baker. &quot;Drivers are often more concentrated on defending the indefensible, the space between them and the car in front, rather than on the cooperative aspect of driving in traffic,&quot; says Baker. &quot;When they're shown how, they can see and feel the benefits of staying back and having more control. They feel more confident about their control over the situation.&quot;<P>
However, it might be a lot easier to find ways to sell these benefits if a great deal more were known about why tailgaters tailgate. <P>

<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="commercial">Commercial driver training standards under scrutiny</A></H2>
<blockquote>
A report from the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) on the effectiveness of private sector commercial-driver training is expected to be released this month. <P>
Congress asked the FHWA for the report to help it decide on whether the training should be subjected to mandatory or voluntary standards. Trucking interests are divided in their opinions. Owner-operators feel that there should be mandatory standards, but an alliance of trucking interests has been formed to lobby for voluntary standards. <P>
One reason the American Association of Trucking Associations is in favour of voluntary standards is because of the difficulty government might have in adapting standards to the great variety of training needed for drivers in different jobs. &quot;The government is likely to take a one-size-fits-all approach, which is not necessarily appropriate,&quot; ATA senior vice president John Collins told the Highway &#38; Vehicle Safety Report recently. Collins believes the government should set standards based on outcomes, or what the driver can do, rather than on hours spent in class or on a particular topic. The owner-operators maintain that drivers are not being properly trained and that mandatory standards are required to change this.<P>
The Driver Training Alliance is sponsoring a forum in March 1995 to search for solutions. <p>


<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="life">Life under graduated licensing</A></H2>
<blockquote>
After only nine months, it's too soon to offer a diagnosis on how North America's first comprehensive graduated driver licensing system is panning out -- but there are a few snapshot images that can help set the scene. <P>
Government is quite likely doing very well out of it. Before graduated driver licensing (GDL) the cost of getting a license was $31. That included $10 for the knowledge test, $14 for the road test, and $7 for the license itself -- a bargain by any measure. After GDL, the total licence cost is $175, including the second road test at the end of Level Two. With over 200,000 licence applicants each year that means a lot of extra dollars in government coffers. <P>
In the driver training world the picture is dramatically different. It's a disaster area. Business has been down about 50&#37;, by all accounts,  in some areas perhaps as much as 75&#37;. Times are worse than any of the old hands in the business can remember. Intense competition, price cutting, and even sharp practices are the order of the day. <P>
Government is selling the public a product they want and will pay extra to get -- the right to drive.  <P>
In contrast, the driver training industry is facing a dilemma that was neatly demonstrated by a sting operation shown on national television on December 13. A TV reporter is filmed, with a hidden camera, through the window of a driving school. He's bargaining with a driving school owner about taking a course and he wants to know if he really has to sit in class for the whole 25 hours required to get a valid certificate that will give him insurance rebates and a reduction of four months in Level One of GDL. The school owner assures him that they can work something out.<P>
It's a unique situation. The customer wants to cheat by taking less service than he is paying for! But that's the driving school business. If it weren't for incentives it's very unlikely that Ontario driving schools would sell anything like the more than 100,000 approved driving courses (25 hours class, 10-12 hours in-car) now sold each year. <P>
The drop in driving school business was anticipated by the industry. It was a repeat of what happened in New Zealand when a similar licensing system started there in 1987. <P>


<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="update">Update on Ontario</A></H2>
<blockquote>
The Ministry of Transportation has launched a review of the content and delivery of driver education programs throughout the province. Aston Mutiisa, manager of the ministry's Strategic Issues Office, has invited individuals and organizations to participate by joining an advisory committee. <P>

<H3>New tests</H3><P>

A report on the government's new Level Two road test has been presented to an advisory committee which represents the various road safety stakeholders, including driving school owners. Details of the test will likely be released early in the new year. In the meantime, the Road Safety Educators Association (RSEA), which represents driving instructors, has its own test -- the Driver Competency Assessment. This evaluation procedure was developed under the aegis of Transport Canada. It concentrates on a driver's information gathering skills and defensive driving tactics, in addition to basic operational skills. Extensive use of extra interior mirrors by the tester to monitor the eye movement of subjects is a feature of the test.<P>

<H3>Unity prevails</H3><P>

The September issue of <STRONG>Driver/Education</STRONG> included a lengthy account of a well-planned campaign by the Ontario commercial driver training industry to gain a measure of self-regulation and to upgrade standards for schools and instructors.  <P>
The account ended with discord between the long-established Driving School Association of Ontario (DSAO) and a group of dissident driving schools that was attempting to form a breakaway association. At the heart of the discord was a detailed scheme put forward by the Road Safety Educators Association (RSEA) whereby driving schools conducting approved driver education courses would only use RSEA members as instructors and would require instructors to upgrade. Many driving school owners and instructors felt threatened by these proposals. <P>
Just as the September issue was going to print, there was talk of reconciliation between the breakaway group and the DSAO. For a while, it was difficult to determine how things were progressing. The DSAO initiated legal proceedings against the principals of the breakaway group and no one would talk about it. <P>
As the December issue goes to press, the matter seems to have been resolved. The breakaway group has dissolved and two of its members have taken  newly-created seats on the DSAO's board of directors. A primary financial concern for the smaller school owners has been cleared up in that the RSEA will not require instructors to take courses but will offer them as options.<P>


<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="reviews">REVIEWS</A></H2>
<blockquote>
<STRONG>DON'T LET UP: ANTILOCK BRAKING SYSTEMS</STRONG><BR>
AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety. 1994, 11 minutes<BR>
For a FREE copy of this video, fax your request to the Foundation at (202) 638-5943. Extra copies are available at $4.95 U.S.<P>&quot;We've done a great job over the years of teaching people how to pump the brakes to maintain control,&quot; says Foundation Executive Director David K. Willis. &quot;You can't do that with ABS.&quot; Many people don't have the foggiest notion how ABS works or how it affects driving techniques, Willis says. The video, made with generous support from General Motors,  brought an actual driver ed class to the GM proving grounds at Milford, Michigan to demonstrate the dos and don'ts of ABS. The class is shown how ABS works and the correct way to use it to maintain control over a car in brake-and-avoid situations. The advantages of ABS are demonstrated and it is emphasized that ABS's main advantage is in enabling the driver to maintain control. A 12-page Teacher's Guide booklet accompanies the video. <P>

<STRONG>AVOIDING COLLISIONS: <BR>HOW TO SURVIVE THE TEENAGE DRIVING YEARS</STRONG><BR>
Liberty Mutual Insurance Group, 1992
<BR>Kit, includes 16-minute video
<BR>For free loan call Modern Talking Pictures at 1-800-243-6877 (US). In Canada call your local Liberty Mutual office (there are offices in Ontario, Quebec, and Alberta). <P>
This program is aimed at generating discussion between teacher, parent and teenager about four major areas of concern for teenage drivers: speeding, night driving, safety belt use, and drinking and driving. The kit includes the videotape, and instructor's materials consisting of four reproducible activity mastersheets, a master copy of the SADD Contract for Life, a sample letter to parents, a fact sheet about teen  driving, a response card, and a four-page viewer's guide. The video features dialogue between teens and their parents about their differing views on teen driving and the risks associated with the four areas of concern. Inserted at intervals are prompts for discussion, and facts about teen driving casualties. The plan is for teachers to preview the video before showing it to students, and it is suggested that it be viewed in segments. The materials are designed to help teenagers identify the consequences of driving at excessive speeds, realize that night driving is hazardous, recognize the importance of seatbelt use, and establish guidelines of responsibility for both drivers and passengers. <P>

<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>




