<H2><A NAME="penn">Pennsylvania's Enhanced</A><BR>
Driver Education Curriculum Part II</H2>
<STRONG>BY Richard Hornfeck, Ph.D.</STRONG><BR>
Indiana University of Pennsylvania <P>

This is the second of three articles dealing with Pennsylvania's attempt to produce a lower-risk, entry-level driver into the highway transportation system. The first article in <STRONG>The Chronicle,</STRONG> Vol. 44 (1), discussed the development of the curriculum and the selection of the pilot and control schools. This article will discuss the implementation process, difficulties encountered, and the evaluation process.  <P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The driver education teacher was the key person in selecting the schools to implement the enhanced curriculum. We found that the respective administrators readily approved their school to participate in the study when the driver education teacher enthusiastically endorsed the four components of the enhanced curriculum (decision making, parent involvement, visual training, and night driving). A great deal of responsibility was placed on the teacher because of the following commitments.  <P>
<UL><LI>The teacher would be required to attend a one-week workshop, at which time he/she would be given the material and shown how to incorporate it into his/her current curriculum. <LI>
The teacher would revise his/her current curriculum to reflect the components of the enhanced curriculum. <LI>
 The teacher would develop a parental involvement plan. This would include activities such as the initial meeting with the parents, planned learning experiences, establishing lines of communication, etc. <LI>
 The teacher would schedule night driving experiences for the beginning driver. <LI>
 The teacher would be responsible for the completion of the survey instruments by both students and parents. <LI>
 The teacher would continue the curriculum for a minimum of three years. </UL>
Without the dedication and commitment of the driver education teacher, we would not have been able to implement the enhanced curriculum in selected high school programs throughout the state.<P>
</blockquote>
<H3>Difficulties Encountered</H3>
<blockquote>
The greatest difficulties encountered when implementing the enhanced curriculum involved the night driving experience. As mentioned in the first article, more schools would have participated had it not been for the night driving requirement. Even with the eighteen schools that were committed to teaching the enhanced curriculum, most of the difficulties encountered evolved around the night driving requirement. <P>
Initially, the teachers were asked to have two night driving experiences with each of their students. The idea was to first work with the student in an environment that placed fewer demands upon the student.  With the second experience, the student would face greater risk in relation to seeing hazards and controlling the car . The teacher would usually schedule two or three students for a block of time. With the two driving experiences, the student could get as much as sixty minutes of driving time and the same or greater observation time. Teachers encountered some problems with this when students failed to show for their scheduled times. This created a dilemma when only two students were scheduled and one was absent. Some teachers felt the best way to address the problem was to involve the parents in this phase of learning by having them ride along with the teacher. This activity enhanced the parent involvement and developed a greater awareness on the parent's part in relation to the risks associated with night driving and how to respond to these risks. <P>
Another problem related to night driving was the longer daylight hours during late spring, summer, and early fall. It does not start to become dark until 8:30 p.m., and this was shortening the available time in which to work with students at night. This meant that the teacher might be working as late as 10:00 p.m. in attempting to meet the night driving requirement. <P>
Another problem encountered with night driving involved those schools that had large student enrollments and only one teacher. Attempting to take each student out for two driving experiences with the limited time available created a major scheduling problem. <P>
To address these problems associated with the night driving experience, we recommended or investigated these solutions.<P>
<UL><LI>  The teacher should be the judge of whether or not the beginning driver needs more than one night driving experience. If the student demonstrates less than desirable skills, he/she should be schedule at least one more time. <LI>
  Parents need to assume a greater role in this part of the instruction. They need to be shown what the risks are, how to safely manage them, and how to plan a night driving route. Parents planned routes from simple environments to the more complex. The parents need to maintain a driving log for their beginning drivers and share it with the teacher.</UL><p>
It is important for the teacher to work with the beginning driver in this low-light environment that is extremely difficult for both the beginning and experienced driver. Even when the teacher is able to take a student out a total of two times in this high risk environment, the beginning driver still needs a great deal more supervised practice with a parent or guardian. Involving the parents in this phase of training would not only address the identified problems, but would also enhance the overall learning experiences for the beginning driver. <P>
Another difficulty encountered with the pilot schools is getting the parents/guardians to participate in the program. This participation begins with the initial meeting that the teacher plans with the parents. Attendance varies between the schools. It also varies in relation to the time of year. Planned meetings for the fall semester usually have a greater turnout than those for the spring semester. Only one of the pilot schools has achieved 100% attendance with the parents/guardians. That school requires the meeting if the novice driver is going to take the laboratory phase of driver education. A meeting time for a week night, an alternate time on Saturday, and an individual appointment is scheduled as needed. This is the only school that makes the initial meeting with the parents mandatory. All the other pilot schools arrange for meeting times, but do not make the meeting mandatory. <P>
</blockquote>
<H3>Program Evaluation</H3>
<blockquote>
As mentioned in the first article, there are eighteen pilot/treatment schools and eighteen control schools going into the third year of the study. All of the schools are state-approved programs. The only thing that is significantly different between the two groups is the enhanced curriculum. The four methods of evaluation occurring with this project are:<P>
<STRONG>State Driving Records.</STRONG> After a student has completed both the classroom and behind-the-wheel phases of driver education, the teacher enters the student's name and permit/license number on a roster and sends it to the State. The student should have a minimum of six months driving experience before the driving record is examined for moving violations and reportable accidents. Comparisons will be made between the pilot/treatment group and the control group. <P>
<STRONG>Self-Reporting Survey.</STRONG> To supplement the state records, an extensive self-reporting survey is administered to the students a minimum of six months after completion of both phases of the driver education program. The survey is referred to as Driver Education Survey II. Students remain completely anonymous when completing the survey and are only identifying their high school, grade, and gender. The self-reporting survey is a supplement to the state records because it is providing a great deal more information than would be available with only the state records. Van Fleet (1979) reported that self-reporting surveys have proven to be a valid means of evaluating the risk and exposure of a young driver.<P>
The five major categories of information being sought with the survey are:<P>
<STRONG>Demographics. </STRONG> General information pertaining to the new driver, including gender, grade, age when receiving a learner's permit, number of months on the learner's permit before being licensed, number of licensing attempts, and whose car is usually driven. <P>
<STRONG>Exposures. </STRONG>Type and amount of driving, including location where most of the driving occurs, types of highways or streets where majority of driving occurs, number of times they drive to school, who accompanies them most of the time, day and time when driving occurs, and safety belt usage. <P>
<STRONG>Violations.</STRONG> Violation information, including number of violations, accumulation of points, and types of violations. <P>
<STRONG>Collisions.</STRONG> Collision experience, including numbers of collisions, when they occurred, and types of collisions.<P>
<STRONG>Cause/Effect. </STRONG>Specifics of collisions experienced by drivers are requested.<P>
Overall, this survey instrument will provide a great deal of information on the beginning driver and will supplement the state records. <P>
<STRONG>Student Program Evaluation. </STRONG> This survey instrument is given to the students immediately after completion of both phases of the driver education program. The thirty questions enable measurement of the student perceptions of the driving task. We also request the student to evaluate the driver education program and driver education in general. The information is also shared with the respective high school program (treatment or control). <P>
<STRONG>Parent Program Evaluation. </STRONG> Once the high school students have completed both phases of the driver education program, they are asked to take a survey instrument home and have their parents complete the respective survey. As with the survey instrument completed by the students, parents are asked identical or similar questions. Examples of the questions are: difficulty, if any, the beginning driver had with certain driving tasks&#59; their evaluation of the driver education program&#59; and their evaluation of driver education in general. Once again, the information is shared with the respective high school (treatment or control). <P>
Data has been collected from both treatment and control schools, since the 1993-1994 school year. The number of schools in both groups has progressively grown since the first school year. In 1993-1994, seven treatment and nine control schools were selected to participate in the project. During 1994-1995, seven treatment and five control schools volunteered to participate, while four treatment and four control schools were added in 1995-1996. Presently, a total of 36 schools (18 treatment and 18 control) are providing data for the four evaluation areas. Initial data analysis is planned for the summer of 1996. Preliminary findings should be available in the fall of 1996 for a future <STRONG>Chronicle</STRONG> article. <P>

<STRONG>REFERENCES</STRONG><P>
Hornfeck, R.J. 1996.<STRONG> Pennsylvania's Enhanced Driver Education Project.</STRONG> The Chronicle of the American Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association. <P>
Van Fleet, E.L. 1979. <STRONG>&quot;An Evaluation of the Effectiveness of the Illinois Demonstration - Satellite Performance Curriculum as Measured by Student Self-Report Accident Involvement.&quot; </STRONG>Ph.D. Dissertation. Michigan State University. <P><A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="vote">Exploring Highway Safety Responsibility</A><BR>
Through Values Voting</H2>
<STRONG>BY Martin J. Spellicy, Director </STRONG><BR>
Alabama Traffic Safety Center, University of Montevallo<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Too often our senses are exposed to motor vehicle tragedy. Radio, television, and newspaper accounts transmit glimpses of lives and families forever altered. Far too often the young seize these headlines, for novice drivers are overrepresented in highway crashes both on a per mile and per capita basis (Wilde, 1994). Wilde (1994) states this overrepresentation is a result of immaturity and experience. Passenger deaths account for 48% of all teenage passenger car occupant deaths, compared with 27% for those older (Williams and Wells, 1995). It behooves driver education instructors to present learning experiences within a low-risk milieu, allowing students to process personal values as they simultaneously assimilate highway safety content. Facilitation of learning experiences which foster student analytical decision making skills, within the current knowledge base of driver education, may better equip students to perceive and confront high risk situations, both as drivers and passengers. <P>
The media reports convey recurrent themes--16-year-old, late at night, weekend, peer pressure, recently licensed, limited experience, speed too fast for conditions, alcohol involvement, multiple passengers, and lack of occupant protection. Unless one is personally acquainted with the victims, the stories soon fade from the conscious memory&#173;only to resurface on subsequent days with different names. How state and federal legislative bodies fulfill their respective highway safety roles can add another causal factor to the youth road safety dialogue. All the while, teachable moments are being squandered. <P>
The following article presents two scenarios, easily incorporated into the curriculum, allowing for the group process to materialize. With the disproportionate losses youth bear as a direct consequence of irresponsible behavior in motor vehicles, the following lesson can nurture the process of shared group values toward individual, publicly acclaimed, self-protective behavior in motor vehicles. <P>
<STRONG>Topic. </STRONG> Responsible decision making related to highway safety issues. <P>
<STRONG>Lesson Objective. </STRONG>Student will interpret and analyze two highway crashes and determine a rank ordering of responsibility for characters in the scenario. Students summarize the influence of peer pressure and the multifaceted issues that can result from irresponsible motor vehicle operation and faulty decision making process. <P>
<STRONG>Assessment Criteria. </STRONG>Students demonstrate analysis in determining and defending rankings of characters in the scenarios. <P>
<STRONG>Activities and Strategies.</STRONG> This teaching activity can be geared either toward pickup truck occupant safety or seat belt safety, and can be presented as either one or two lessons. <P>
<STRONG>Resources and Materials.</STRONG> News stories, cast of characters, scale of characters, rank order of characters, and obituary assignment. <P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Teaching Activity One </H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>This activity is geared toward pickup truck safety.<P>
<STRONG>Teacher Instructions. </STRONG>Distribute news story and cast of characters sheets. Students read these items, then rank the cast of characters as to degree of responsibility for the outcome. <P>
Students then list the seven characters from most to least responsible. Students (as time allows) come to a small group and/or class consensus. Teacher participates in discussion by pointing out need for individual responsibility and the role peer pressure played in the tragic outcome.<P>

<STRONG>2 Killed, 5 Critically Injured In 11 PM Crash<BR>
</STRONG>(Middleton) Two Middleton 9th graders were killed last night when they were apparently ejected from a pickup truck bed onto the pavement of Highway 13 shortly after 11 pm. A pickup truck, driven by 16-year-old Jim Bond, collided with a sedan operated by 82-year-old Gus Padden. Bond had five occupants riding in the truck bed when the crash occurred. Two of the truck bed occupants were killed and the remaining three occupants riding in the bed of the Bond vehicle were critically injured. Pronounced dead at the scene from massive head injuries were Tom Hart and Conner Belden, ages 15 and 16, respectively. Hart and Belden were ejected from the bed of the Bond pickup and thrown onto the pavement. The drivers, Bond and Padden, were taken to Middleton General Hospital, where each was diagnosed with head trauma and spinal cord injuries. Bond's three additional truck bed passengers, George and Doris Black (brother and sister) aged 16, and Ann Shaw, 17, suffered broken bones and complained of back and neck pain. These three are currently undergoing medical tests at Middleton General. <P>
Police investigators state that Bond was travelling north on Highway 13 when Padden, travelling south, apparently drifted into the northbound lane resulting in the two vehicles colliding head on. Further investigation revealed neither Bond nor Padden were wearing safety belts at the time of the collision. Padden was ticketed for failure to wear prescriptive lenses and failure to maintain lane position. Investigation into the crash is continuing. A bill filed in the state legislature earlier this year that would have prohibited persons from riding in truck beds, along with additional highway safety countermeasures, died in committee.  <P>
Funeral arrangements for Tom Hart and Conner Belden are listed in the Obituary section on page 5. <P>

<STRONG>CAST OF CHARACTERS</STRONG><P>

<STRONG>Jim Bond.</STRONG> 16-year-old, had license two weeks and was told to drive safely by parents but was not provided limits on use of the pickup nor any set time to be home. <P>
<STRONG>Father (Jim Bond).</STRONG> Gives Jim set of keys to pickup and takes Jim to get his license the day he is of age. <P>
<STRONG>Mother (Jim Bond).</STRONG> Allows Jim to leave driveway with five friends in the bed of the pickup. <P>
<STRONG>Five Friends. </STRONG>All rode in the bed of pickup even though they knew of the danger. <P>
<STRONG>State Legislature.</STRONG>  Legislature killed bill in committee that would have made it illegal to have passengers in the bed of pickups and enacted safety belt law with secondary enforcement provisions an a maximum $5.00 penalty, while killing bills that would have instituted a graduated license for persons under 21 years of age.  <P>
<STRONG>Police Officers.</STRONG> Observed Jim and the group drive by and did not stop them. <P>
<STRONG>Gus Padden. </STRONG>Driver, 82 years of age, whose license stipulated he was to wear glasses while driving. <P>
<STRONG>Additional information. </STRONG>The graduated licensing provision would have included stipulations that would not allow a novice driver to operate a vehicle without someone over 21 in the vehicle during the first year of operation&#59; those drivers under 17 would not be allowed to drive with more than two other persons under 18 in the vehicle unless accompanied by a licensed driver over 21 years of age. <P>
A bill that would have limited drivers under 18 to daylight hours of vehicle operation was also not passed.<P>
<STRONG>Scenario 1, Activity 1.</STRONG> For each of the listed characters, circle the letter corresponding to the degree of responsibility you place on the person(s) for the deaths and injuries reported in the news story:<BR>
a. extremely responsible&#59;<BR>
b. somewhat responsible&#59;<BR>
c. not responsible.<P>

<table border><TR><TD>Father (Jim Bond)</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Mother (Jim Bond)</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Five Friends</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Jim Bond</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR>
<TR><TD>State Legislature</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Police Officers</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Gus Padden</td><td>a</td><td>b</td><td>c</td></tR></table><P>

<STRONG>Scenario 1, Activity 2.</STRONG> Rank in order the characters, from those you believe to be most responsible to least responsible for outcome. Be prepared to defend your ranking. <P>

<table border><TR><TD>Father (Jim Bond)</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Mother (Jim Bond)</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Five Friends</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Jim Bond</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR>
<TR><TD>State Legislature</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Police Officers</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR>
<TR><TD>Gus Padden</td><td>&#91; &#93;</td></tR></table><P>

<STRONG>Scenario 1, Activity 3.</STRONG> Write an obituary for either Tom Hart or Conner Belden in a form that may convince others not to make the same mistake that resulted in Tom and Conner's deaths. (In class or homework assignment.)<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Teaching Activity Two</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>This teaching activity is using values voting geared toward safety belt safety.<P>
<STRONG>Teacher Instructions.</STRONG> Distribute news story and cast of characters sheets. Students read these items and then rank the cast of characters as to degree of responsibility for the outcome. Students then list the seven characters, from most to least responsible. Students (as time allows) come to a small group and/or class consensus. Teacher participates in discussion by pointing out need for individual responsibility and the role peer pressure played in the tragic outcome.<P>
 <P>
<STRONG>1 Killed, 2 Escape Injury in 11 PM Crash</STRONG><BR>

(Middleton) One Middleton 9th grader was killed last night when he was apparently ejected onto the pavement of Highway 13 shortly after 11 pm. The driver of the pickup truck, 16-year-old Jim Bond, collided with a 2 door sedan operated by 82-year-old Gus Padden. Bond was pronounced dead at the scene from massive head injuries. A passenger in the Bond vehicle, Meg Shine, was buckled up and reported no injury. Gus Padden, the operator of the sedan, was also buckled up at the time of the collision and was not injured. <P>
Police investigators stated Bond was travelling north on Highway 13 when Padden, who was travelling south, apparently drifted into his lane resulting in the two vehicles colliding head on. It is estimated that each vehicle was travelling within the 30 mph posted speed limit. Bond was ejected from his vehicle and sustained fatal injuries from collision with the he pavement. Padden was ticketed for failure to wear prescriptive lenses and for failure to maintain lane position. A bill filed in the state legislature earlier this year that would have added several provisional safeguards for young drivers died in committee. Investigation into this crash is continuing. <P>
Funeral arrangements for Jim Bond are listed in the Obituary section on page 5. <P>

<STRONG>CAST OF CHARACTERS</STRONG><P>

<STRONG>Jim Bond.</STRONG> 16-year-old, licensed two weeks, has been told to drive safely by parents but has not been provided any limits on use of vehicle or time to be home&#59; believed wearing a safety belt would make him appear uncool and was not buckled up at time of crash. <P>
<STRONG>Father (Jim Bond).</STRONG> Bought and gave Jim car when Jim turned 16&#59; did not stress safety when he presented Jim with the car&#59; gave Jim set of keys to pickup and took Jim to get his license the day Jim was of age. <P>
<STRONG>Mother (Jim Bond).</STRONG> Sees Jim leave driveway without safety belt fastened&#59; says nothing to him as she waved good-bye.<P>
<STRONG>Meg Shine (Bond friend).</STRONG> Reminded Jim to buckle up but didn't insist on it&#59; she buckled up and was not injured in the crash. <P>
<STRONG>State Legislature.</STRONG> Enacted safety belt law with secondary enforcement provision and a maximum $5.00 penalty.<P>
<STRONG>Local Police. </STRONG> In the five years the safety belt law has been on the books, the department has not issued a ticket for noncompliance&#59; observed Jim drive by not buckled up and did not stop the pickup.<P>
<STRONG>Gus Padden.</STRONG> 82-year-old driver whose license stipulated he was to wear glasses at all times of vehicle operation&#59; Padden was not wearing them at the time of the collision. Padden was buckled up at the time of the crash and was not injured. <P>
<STRONG>Additional Information.</STRONG>  Legislature killed bills to institute a graduated license for persons under 21 years of age. The provision would have included stipulations that would not allow a driver to drive without someone over 21 in the vehicle during the first year of operation&#59; those drivers under 17 would not be allowed to drive with more than two other persons under 18 in the vehicle unless accompanied by a licensed driver over 21. Killed a bill that would have limited drivers under 18 to daylight hours of vehicle operation. <P>

<STRONG>Scenario 1, Activity 1.</strong> For each of the listed characters, circle the letter corresponding to the degree of responsibility you place on the person(s) for the deaths of Jim Bond.<BR>
a. extremely responsible&#59;<BR>
b. somewhat responsible&#59;<BR>
c. not responsible.<P>

