<STRONG>Scenario 1, Activity 3.</STRONG> Write an obituary for Jim Bond in a format that may prevent others from dying in a similar manner. (In class or homework assignment.)<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Conclusions</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Driver education instructors need to present learning experiences within a low-risk milieu, allowing students to process personal values as they simultaneously assimilate highway safety content. Learning experiences which foster student analytical decision making skills, within the current knowledge base of driver education, may better equip students to perceive and confront high risk situations, both as drivers and passengers. Based on Wilde (1994) models, this technique may provide better student decision-making behavior.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>References</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Wilde, G.J.S. 1994. <STRONG>Risk homeostasis theory and its premise for improved safety.</STRONG> In R.M. Trimpop &amp; G.J.S. Wilde (Eds.), <A HREF="/pde/books.html#challenges">Challenges to accident prevention: The issue of risk compensation behaviour</A> (pp. 9-24). Groningen, The Netherlands: Styx Publications. <P>
Williams, A.F., Wells., J.K. 1995. <STRONG>Deaths of Teenagers as Motor-Vehicle Passengers.</STRONG> Journal of Safety Research, 14(1), 161-167.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
