<H2><A NAME="sahler">ADTSEA loses founding father</A></H2>
<STRONG>FROM Vernon P. Gainey, </STRONG>Retired (Jackson, MS)
<BLOCKQUOTE>David H. Sahler died January 15, 1996, at the age of 64 years. David was one of the founders of ADTSEA in 1956. He supported and promoted Driver and Safety Education wherever he went. David had served on the Board of Directors of ADTSEA, served as president of the Southeast Region, and president of Mississippi Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association. David had attended nearly all of the ADTSEA Conferences and the Southeast Regional Conferences. <P>
He was one of the founders of the Mississippi Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association and had attended all the state conferences.  <P>
David encouraged student participation in the safety programs and annually carried students to the Southern Youth Safety Conferences and to the National Safety Council. <P>
He was one of the organizers and supporters of the Mississippi Youth Safety Conference, as well as the annual Teenage Driving Road-e-o.<P>
David was a native of Pekin, Illinois and was a graduate of State University of Oswego, New York and Mississippi College. He had also taken advanced driver and safety education courses. <P>
He served two years in the United States Army and after his discharge came to Mississippi. He had served as Supervisor of Driver Education of the Hinds County Public Schools and for the Jackson Public Schools. David also taught driver education and safety courses at the local parochial schools and several colleges/universities in the state. <P>
David had recently retired after nearly forty years of teaching, supervising and promoting driver and safety education.  Driver and safety education and ADTSEA have indeed lost a hard working, dedicated, loyal friend who will be greatly missed.  <P><A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="kaywood">Richard Kaywood Memorial Award</A></H2>
<STRONG>BY Allen Robinson, Ph.D.</STRONG><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Each year at the annual ADTSEA conference an award is presented to an individual for outstanding contributions to traffic safety in memory of Dr. Richard Kaywood, who served the Association and traffic safety education for many years. This award is sponsored cooperatively with the ScottForesman Publishing Company which presents the recipient an honorarium of $500.<P>
The selection from among nominees is made by the ADTSEA Executive Committee and is announced at the annual conference banquet. <P>
To better assure that deserving individuals are given consideration, ADTSEA members are encouraged to submit names of persons they feel made substantial contributions to the field. Each submission must be accompanied by a summary of the candidate's professional background and contributions to traffic safety education. Following is a list of criteria for determining eligibility. <P>
<UL><LI>The person must have made a significant contribution to traffic safety education on the national and/or international level. <LI>
The person must have served the traffic safety education profession for not less than 20 years. <LI>
The person must have been an active member of ADTSEA for not less than 20 years. <LI>
The summary of the nominee's contributions to the field of traffic safety education should include but are not limited to the following.<P>

<UL><LI>Scholarship - Masters or Doctorate degree<LI>
Leadership - Served ADTSEA in an elected or appointed position<LI>
Author or contributing author of a textbook(s)<LI>
Speaker/Presenter/Panel member at state/national conferences<LI>
Regional/local workshop leader/presenter<LI>
Researcher<LI>
Teacher</UL></UL><P>

Nominations must be submitted to ADTSEA prior to March 31 of any given calendar year and addressed to:<BR>
	Allen Robinson, CEO<BR>
	American Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association<BR>
	IUP Highway Safety Center<BR>
	Indiana, PA 15705<P><A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>


<H2><A NAME="grad">Graduate Study Assistantships Available</A></H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>A broad interdisciplinary approach to safety at the graduate degree level is offered in Texas A&amp;M University's Safety Education Program. Superior physical facilities and a well-qualified faculty help prepare students for a variety of career opportunities. The program is part of the Health and Safety Division of the Department of Health and Kinesiology. Interdisciplinary ties with the Department of Educational Human Resources Development also provide expanded career options. <P>

A safety education emphasis may be incorporated into the master of science, master of education, and doctor of philosophy degree programs offered through the Department of Health and Kinesiology. The program is structured so that students may pursue individual interests and develop abilities in a variety of safety areas. Career opportunities in higher education, state agencies, and the private sector are available to graduates who have degrees with an emphasis in safety education. <P>
For information on current research assistantships and graduate assistantships, contact:<BR>

Maurice E. Dennis, Ph.D.<BR>
Coordinator, Safety Education Program<BR>
Department of Health and Kinesiology<BR>
Texas A&amp;M University<BR>
College Station, Texas 77843-4243<BR>
(409) 845-3019<BR>
FAX (409) 845-0155<P>

