<H2><A NAME="wa">Washington State Teenagers</A><BR>
Compared to National Averages</H2>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Washington teenage drivers from 16 to 20 had a collision rate 22.2% lower than the national collision rate for the same age group. Fatal collision rates compared even more favorably. Washington's rate was 30.4 percent lower than the national fatal collision rate in 1994 based on FARS records. <P>

<STRONG>Traffic Records Data Center</STRONG><BR>
Washington Traffic Safety Commission <BR>
1000 S. Cherry Street<BR>
P.O. Box 40944<BR>
Olympia, WA 98504-0944<BR>
(360) 753-6197<P><A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents
</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><P>

<h2><A NAME="five">Five-year Teenage Trends in Washington State</A></h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Over the past five years, the fatal collision rate for drivers 19 and younger has fallen significantly, from 6.6 fatal collisions per 100,000 licensed drivers in 1990, to 4.5 fatal collisions per 100,000 in 1994. The rate for total collisions has shown a moderate improvement, from a rate of 1,521 in 1990 to 1,324 in 1994.

<P>
