<h1>THE DRIVER LICENSING Eagle Eye</h1>

<H3>Volume 1, No. 4, July 1995</H3><hr><p>
 
 
<STRONG>SUBSCRIPTION INFORMATION</STRONG><p>



<strong>The Driver Licensing Eagle Eye</strong> is a bi-monthly newsletter reporting the latest news and developments in driver licensing. The Eagle Eye is published by Eagle Vision Consultants and is available by subscription only for $25 ($35 if Canadian address).
<BR>Send to: Eagle Vision Consultants, P.O. Box 34, Williamston, MI 48895.<p>
<HR><P>
<H2><A NAME="contents">CONTENTS</A></H2>
<A HREF="#aaam"><UL><LI>AAAM proposes sweeping changes in the CDL medical fitness program</A><LI>
<A HREF="#states">News from the states</A><LI>
<A HREF="#feds">News from the Feds</A><LI>
<A HREF="#misc">Miscellaneous</A><LI>
<A HREF="#courts">News from the courts</A></UL>



<hr><p><h2><A NAME="aaam">AAAM PROPOSES SWEEPING CHANGES</A><br>IN THE 
CDL MEDICAL FITNESS PROGRAM</h2><p>
<blockquote>
The Association for the Advancement of Automotive Medicine, in a report to the Federal Highway Administration, has made numerous recommendations regarding the medical fitness program for drivers engaged in interstate commerce. The recommendations include:<p>

<STRONG>REGULATORY CHANGES</STRONG><p>

<ol><li>The commercial driver medical certification process should be integrated with the 
licensing process at the state level.<p>
Part 391 and Part 383 of the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Regulations (FMCSR) 
should be merged, thus giving the states the responsibility for issuing CDLs in 
compliance with current national standards. Possession of a valid CDL should be 
prima facie evidence that a driver meets all the requirements for a CDL. The 
need for a separate medical certificate should be eliminated.<P>

<li>The license renewal cycle and the medical fitness examination period, currently 
biennial, should be harmonized.<P>

<li>Exemptions from the medical fitness requirements should be eliminated.<P>

<li>The definitions of what constitutes a &quot;commercial motor vehicle&quot; must be
 resolved.<p>

Part 391 of the FMCSRs applies to interstate operators of vehicles weighing more 
than 10,000 pounds; however, Part 383 (CDL) applies to drivers of vehicles 
weighing more than 26,000 pounds. There should be consistency in the weight 
threshold if the medical fitness requirements are incorporated into the licensing 
process.<P>

<li>The definition of an interstate driver should be revised to reflect the driving risk 
rather than the cargo lading.<p>

The relative risk of driving a large commercial vehicle, the on-the-job 
responsibilities of the driver, distances and time traveled, and overall driving 
environment should determine the level of functional capacity necessary to drive 
safely, rather than the type of cargo the driver carries or the way in which the 
vehicle he or she drives has been designated for purposes or commerce. There 
should be no fundamental difference between inter- and intrastate driving for 
safety purposes.</ol>

<STRONG>DRIVER LICENSE AGENCY</STRONG><p>

<ol><li>Driver examiners and medical review specialists should be trained to administer 
the fitness evaluation program.<P>

<li>A state-administered fitness certification program must ensure confidentiality.<p>

Medical reporting procedures and documents must be tamper-resistant. Drivers 
must be assured that their privacy regarding medical conditions is protected. 
Access to medical information within the driver licensing agency should be strictly 
controlled and the use of such information clearly defined so that drivers are fully 
informed of their rights and responsibilities in this regard.<P>

<li>State driver license agencies must have the authority to cancel CDLs if drivers do 
not meet current medical standards.<p>

Appropriate authority vested in the driver licensing agency is fundamental.</ol>

<STRONG>MEDICAL COMMUNITY</STRONG><p>

<ol><li>A national pool of medical examiners should be trained and certified to perform commercial driver physical examinations.<p>

At the present time, the quality of medical examiners varies enormously. A 
national system would establish standards of excellence to ensure more effective 
physical examiners would afford drivers the opportunity to have an examination 
anywhere in the country and would establish a system to monitor the quality of 
physical examinations.<P>

<li>Physicians who choose to report drivers with medically disqualifying conditions 
should have immunity from legal action.<P>

<li>A functioning Medical Advisory Board is a fundamental component of an effective 
commercial driver fitness certification program.<p>

The availability of a case by case review process would address some of the 
current issues raised in the Americans with Disabilities Act.</ol>

<STRONG>MOTOR CARRIER INDUSTRY</STRONG><p>

The support of the motor carrier industry is fundamental to a state-administered 
fitness certification process.<p>

Motor carriers must be assured that the issuance of a CDL means that a 
commercial driver is medically fit to drive.<p>

<STRONG>RESEARCH ISSUES</STRONG><p>

<ol><li>Current medical standards should be evaluated.<p>

There is no question that uniform national standards are needed for commercial 
drivers. States should have the right to set high standards for drivers they 
license. Criteria should be based on functional capability rather than be disease 
specific.<P>

<li>The relationship between current medical standards and crash risk should be 
investigated.</ol><P>


<A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents<P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>
<H2><A NAME="states">NEWS FROM THE STATES</A></H2><p>
<blockquote>
<ul><li>The Bureau of Motor Vehicles in Ohio began issuance of a new plastic, credit card-type license that are specifically designed to be more secure and tamper-proof. The 
new licenses also have bar codes and magnetic stripes.<p>




<li>The Oregon legislature gave final approval and sent to the governor a bill that would 
allow school officials to suspend students' driver licenses for bringing weapons to 
school. Students' licenses could be suspended until they turn 21 years of age.<p>



 
 
<li>Oregon Department of Motor Vehicles offices are back open after a seven-day strike by the Oregon Public Employees Union. <p> 

The Union had sought a 6.5% pay raise to offset a ballot measure passed last fall that requires employees to pay 6% of their salaries into their pension funds. The state offered a 3% raise on 7/1/95 and 11/1/96. Later, the offer was increased by proposing more benefits.


<li>A bill moving through the Louisiana legislature will allow 14-year-olds to obtain driver permits and enroll in driver education courses.<p>




<li>Because of the Oklahoma City bombing, lawmakers who have introduced bills in New York and Pennsylvania legislatures want rental vehicles to have photographic identification of renters.<p>

The bills would require photographs to be taken of customers at the time a vehicle is rented. The New York bill only applies to truck rental while the Pennsylvania bill includes truck and passenger vehicle rental.<p>




<li>Roger David, who is legally blind as well as 55% deaf, surrendered his driver license after admitting that a Arkansas state employee helped him with test answers when he applied for and received his license.<p>




<li>This fall, Virginia will join 40 other states that use a different I.D. system on driver licenses other than social security numbers.<p>




<li>Newton, Massachusetts police raided the American Family Thrift Store and seized more than 200 applications for false driver licenses, as well as the computer and video imaging to make them. Police stated the equipment was used to reproduce driver licenses from all 50 states right down to holograms and driver license restrictions. <p>




<li>A bill passed by the Rhode Island house would add a one-year prison term to motorists convicted of drunk driving when a child is in the car. An additional term of up to ten years would be imposed if the child is injured or killed.<p>


 

<li>The Alabama legislature, under the leadership of Lt. Governor Don Siegelman, is working on drunk driving legislation that would lower the BAC level to .08% for drivers 21 and over, lower the BAC to .02% for under 21 drivers, set a .02% BAC level for drivers of school buses, day-care vans, and commuter buses as well as permit the seizure and sale upon the third conviction for drunk driving. <p>




<li>About 200 employees of New Jersey Department of Motor Vehicles walked off their jobs to attend a protest against plans to privatize their offices. A judge has given approval to an injunction barring future job actions.<p>




<li>The look of Arizona's driver license is about to change for the better. <p> 

The Arizona Motor Vehicle Division unveiled a driver license that promises to be more convenient and useful than the one most motorists are carrying with them today. MVD will begin issuing the licenses through a pilot program that started in June in Glendale and Prescott. It will be available statewide on July 1.<p>

This card is made of more durable plastic and features an easy-to-read format. It has a colorful Arizona scene, an embedded driver photo, a hologram film coating, and a bar code/magnetic stripe. The license is produced on equipment that will allow people to leave most MVD offices with the license in hand, rather than waiting for it to come in the mail.<p>

The new design has many features intended to help cut down on fraud. The hologram film will reveal any attempt to tamper with information printed on the face of the card. That same printed information is duplicated in the bar code and magnetic stripe. Twenty-eight states currently issue driver licenses using bar codes and/or magnetic stripe technology as a means of reducing fraud.<p>

The cost of the driver license remains the same. People with a valid license may wait until the license expires or their first photo update to get the new license. For those wishing to get the new license before that time, the cost is $4.<p>

A new &quot;Under 21&quot; license will be issued. It features the driver's photo on the left side of the card and includes the date the cardholder turns 21.<p>




<li>Despite support from the American Association of Retired Persons, the Maine House of Representatives has rejected a bill that would have required drivers over the age of 40 to be vision tested every six years. Foes said teen drivers are more of a threat.</ul><P>

<A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents<P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>
<H2><A NAME="feds">NEWS FROM THE FEDS</A></h2><p>
<blockquote>
<STRONG>FHWA Proposes CDL Waiver for Fireworks Industry</STRONG><p>

The American Pyrotechnics Association (APA), a non-profit group representing the pyrotechnics industry, has petitioned the FHWA to reconsider its previous determinations and grant a CDL waiver to part-time drivers involved in fireworks displays.<p>

APA argues that the waiver is necessary because, since implementation of the CDL rule in 1992, the fireworks industry has faced serious problems in delivering small fireworks displays to customers located in remote areas. In order to respond to thousands of requests by Fourth of July celebrants, such as small townships, the companies must rely on part-time drivers who not only drive to the display sites, but also handle and discharge the fireworks. The FHWA is requesting public comments on a petition submitted by the pyrotechnics industry on March 6, 1995, for relief from the requirements of the commercial driver license regulations (CDL) 49 CFR Part 383. The FHWA is proposing to authorize waivers for certain drivers transporting fireworks to displays during the period of Independence Day celebrations from the CDL testing and licensing standards The drivers to be covered by these waivers are part-time drivers who have an otherwise valid driver license, as well as licenses or permits issued by applicable state or local agencies certifying that they are approved pyrotechnic operators. A waiver issued by a state under this proposal would only authorize the transportation of less than 500 pounds of fireworks classified as DOT Class 1.3G explosives, from June 30 through July 6 of each year, 
provided that the vehicles operated have gross vehicle weight ratings (GVWR) of less than 
10,001 pounds and are operated within 300 miles of the sites of origin. The FHWA requests public comments on whether, if granted, the proposed grant of waiver authority would be contrary to the public interest or diminish the safe operation of commercial motor vehicles.<p>

 
Comments to the docket were due June 9, 1995.<p>



<STRONG>NTSB Critical of Texas's CDL Issuance Program</STRONG><p>
 
The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), in a report regarding an August 8, 1994, crash on Interstate 30 near Hanks, Texas, was quite critical of the State of Texas.<p>



The commercial truck driver and his passenger were killed after the driver fell asleep and ran into a bridge column. An autopsy of the driver showed marijuana residual and other drugs in his bloodstream and was slightly below the limit for legal intoxication.<p>



NTSB board chair, Jim Hall, states, &quot;Somebody was asleep at the switch there, weren't they?&quot; <p>


Hall was referring to the fact that the truck driver had three DWI convictions as well as an 
extensive criminal record that included sale of amphetamines and unlawful distribution of a controlled substance, Vice Chairman, Robert T. Francos II added, &quot;Two people are asleep at the switch, one is the licensing authority, the other is the employer.&quot;<p>



The Texas Department of Public Safety stated that nothing on the driver's record would have disqualified him from being issued a CDL under Texas law.<p>

<A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents<P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>


<h2><A NAME="misc">MISCELLANEOUS</A></h2><p>

<blockquote>

<STRONG>Keep Your CDL Clean</STRONG><p>


 
Mark D. Sutherland of Santa Ana, has authored a new book that he says no trucker should be without titled, &quot;Traffic Ticket Defense for Truckers.&quot;<p>



He claims that this new and unique book by the premier traffic ticket attorney in America 
instructs drivers with strategies, options, and procedures to fight and win your traffic tickets. He adds that &quot;remember you can't outrun the radar, but you sure can beat it.&quot;<p>



<STRONG>Motorcycle Fatal Crash Study</STRONG><p>



A motorcycle fatal crash study completed by the Michigan Department of State reveals that almost half of all motorcycle operators involved in fatal crashes did not have a motorcycle endorsement. The study profiles the motorcyclist involved in a crash as 31 years old, male, riding alone, and not likely to posses a motorcycle endorsement. In addition, a large sub-population of motorcyclists killed during the five years of study were hard-core scofflaw drivers meaning no motorcycle endorsement, license suspended at the time of the crash, multiple previous crashes, suspensions, and convictions.<p>



A copy of the study is available by writing the Office of Traffic Safety, Michigan Department of State, 208 N. Capitol Avenue, Lansing, MI 48918.<p>


<A HREF="#contents">RETURN</A> to Table of Contents<P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="courts">NEWS FROM THE COURTS</A></H2><p>

<blockquote>

<STRONG>Is Administrative License Revocation <br>Constitutional?</STRONG><p>



<ul><li>A Fremont County Colorado judge has ruled that the state ALR drunken driving law violates the constitutional prohibition against double jeopardy. Judge Walter Fox ordered that drunken driving charges against Paul Gallardo be dismissed because a second prosecution would have violated the 5th and 14th amendments. Fox noted that the United States Supreme Court, in several decisions, has ruled that &quot;jeopardy attaches at a beginning of a civil proceeding to bar a subsequent criminal prosecution in which a defendant may be punished for the same conduct.&quot;<p>
Courts in Arizona, Florida, Idaho, Kansas, Minnesota, Ohio, Virginia, and Washington have dismissed charges for the same reason.<p>





<li>A Virginia judge has given Virginia police the go ahead to resume suspending the driver license of motorists arrested for drunk driving. Judge William Broadhurst wrote that suspending the license of a DUI suspect before his or her trial does not amount to double jeopardy because the suspension and subsequent DUI prosecution are part of the same proceeding. It is expected that a definition ruling won't come until months from now by the Virginia Supreme Court.<p>



<li>Prosecutors in Minnesota in arguments before the State Court of Appeals, say the decision to suspend licenses at the time of arrest is remedial and is done not to punish but to protect the public. The Minnesota Court of Appeals is expected to rule by September, 1995 on what is punishment and what is public protection.<p>



<li>The Nebraska Court of Appeals has ruled that when a prosecutor dismisses a drunken driving case, the Department of Motor Vehicles cannot refuse to reinstate the license of the driver. This ruling comes after a previous ruling rejecting arguments that Nebraska's ALR law constitutes double jeopardy.<p>



<li>Ohio Court of Appeals for the Third Appellate District becomes the most recent state appellate court to reject the double jeopardy defense raised by a DWI defendant. In reaching this conclusion, the Court relied upon language from prior Ohio and other state appellate court decisions in holding that &quot;an administrative license suspension is remedial in nature and does not constitute punishment under the Double Jeopardy Clause.&quot;</ul><p>


 
<STRONG>Illegal Immigrants Not Eligible <br>for CA Driver Licenses</STRONG><p>


 
A California state appeals court has ruled that illegal immigrants are ineligible for California driver licenses. Opponents argued that licenses could be renewed despite a separate 1994 law that bars &quot;original&quot; licenses to illegal immigrants. But the court said a 1992 state law requires all applicants to give their Social Security numbers. &quot;Persons whose presence in the United States is not authorized by law are not entitled to such documents,&quot; the court said. The case is unrelated to Proposition 187, which would deny many state services to people illegally in the country.<p>



<STRONG>WI Appeals Court Upholds Driver License<br>Suspension for Drug Possession</STRONG><p>



The 2nd Wisconsin District Court of Appeals has upheld the constitutionality of a Wisconsin law requiring the suspension of a driver's license for possessing drugs. The Court said the law is constitutional as it promotes a proper public purpose, such as deterring drug crimes.<p>




<STRONG>U.S. Supreme Court Agrees to Rule<br>
on Property Seizure</STRONG><p>


 
The U.S. Supreme Court has agreed to rule on a Michigan property seizure case that could have an effect on repeat offenders and DUIL impoundment laws.<p>



The Michigan case involved a woman who was a joint owner of an automobile which was 
confiscated because of her husband's using the automobile in conjunction with illegal sex.<p>



<STRONG>New York State's Court of Appeals<br>
Rules Out Scarlet Letter</STRONG><p>



New York State's Court of Appeals has ruled that a Nassau County Court judge lacked the 
authority to require a six-time drunk driving offender to stick a fluorescent sign on the license plates of his car reading &quot;convicted DWI.&quot;<p>



The court stated, &quot;A sentencing court cannot impose forms of punishment not authorized by statute for a particular crime.&quot;<p>

