<TD>
<Table Width=410
>
<TR><TD>
<center><h2>Water Management</h2><hr></center><Font Size=-1>
<CENTER><I><B><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">All the water that
will ever be is right now.</FONT></B></I></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Garamond">National Geographic<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Garamond">W</font>ater <FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">is one of the most important
substances found on earth.  Yet in much of the world,  because
of contamination, excessive demand, and other factors, supplies
of clean water are becoming scarce.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">The EERC is an expert in water management.
 Through its acclaimed Water Management Group, the EERC has the
ability to assess water resources, conduct analysis, clean contaminated
water, and develop ways to prevent water from becoming polluted.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">Its comprehensive approach to water
management enables the EERC to pinpoint, solve, and even prevent
problems involving water resources - something few others in the
field can do.   This capability has earned the EERC the trust
of clients throughout the world. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=2 COLOR=#808080 FACE="GeographicSymbols">
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">In the United States alone, there
are 3.5 million miles of rivers and streams; 41 million acres
of lakes, ponds, and reservoirs; and 278 million acres of wetlands.
  As vast as this supply is, an even greater amount of water exists
underground in the United States.   There are more than 33,000
trillion gallons of groundwater in the nation. Groundwater is
a source of drinking water for more than half of all Americans.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">An adequate supply of clean water
is necessary not only for humans to survive but to thrive.  Without
it, economic expansion and population growth cannot occur.   It
takes, for instance, almost 1000 gallons of water to grow the
wheat needed to make a 2-pound loaf of bread.  Almost 39,000 gallons
of water are needed to produce the average automobile.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">During the latter half of the 20th
century, the amount of water used each day in the United States
more than doubled. For industries, communities, and other water
users, it has become increasingly important that water supplies
be managed properly today and into the future.  With its experience
and expertise in water management, the EERC is helping.</FONT>


</Table>
</TD>
