<head>
<title>Wind turbines</title>

</head>
<BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/windback.gif">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=220>
<TR><TD><img src="/gif/wind5i.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>The first of two wind turbines erected with the EERC's assistance was west of Belcourt, N.D.,
on the Turtle Mountain Chippewa Reservation.</font></TD></TR><p><p>
<TR><TD><img src="/gif/wind3i.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>Workers prepare the turbine generator for lifting to the top of the tower.</font></TD></TR><p><p>
<TR><TD><img src="/gif/wind6i.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>Jay Haley, an EERC senior research engineer, assists in guiding the turbine generator into
place as it's lifted by crane to the top of the tower.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=380
>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h1>Wind turbines installed on two North Dakota reservations</h1><hr></center>
    With assistance from the EERC, two North Dakota American Indian tribes are producing electricity
from wind turbines to help power reservation facilities.<p>
    On Aug. 9, a 100 kilowatt wind turbine began generating electricity for the Spirit Lake Casino, which
is owned and operated by the Spirit Lake Nation and located south of Devils Lake, N.D.  An identical wind
turbine west of Belcourt, N.D., began generating electricity Sept. 10 for a water treatment plant that serves
the Turtle Mountain Chippewa Reservation and neighboring communities.  Formal dedication ceremonies are
planned at each site during October.<p>

    The Spirit Lake wind turbine is expected to provide about one-quarter of the casino's electricity needs. 
The Turtle Mountain wind turbine should provide about 30 percent of the water treatment plant's electricity
needs.  The utility-scale wind turbines, previously owned and operated by the Foras Company, Palm Springs,
Calif., are 80 feet tall with blades 65 feet in diameter.  Each wind turbine can generate enough electricity to
serve at least 50 homes. Both turbines were erected between July 22 and Aug. 9 under the supervision of Joe
Kolbach, operations manager for Micon Wind Turbines Inc.<p>
    Jay Haley, an EERC senior research engineer and technical manager for the projects, says the wind
turbines will provide both tribes with experience in operating and maintaining the technology.  Tribal
windsmiths, who received training at a Foras wind farm in California earlier this year, will be responsible for
operating and maintaining the turbines and gathering research data.<p>
    Haley says that data collected from the turbines will be used to determine the economic feasibility of
building wind farms to produce electricity for the reservations.  With 36 percent of America's potential wind
energy, North Dakota is sometimes referred to as "the Saudi Arabia of wind energy."<p>
    The EERC is also involved in the assessment of wind energy resources on the Standing Rock
Reservation, located in south central North Dakota and north central South Dakota.  The Center is a
subcontractor to Xenergy, Burlington, Mass., which is conducting an integrated evaluation of the
reservation's energy resources aimed at improving energy efficiency and evaluating potential new energy
sources.<p>
    All three projects are being funded by the <a href="http://www.doe.gov">U.S. Department of Energy (DOE)
</a> under the 1992 EnergyPolicy Act.  They are part of a DOE program coordinated by the 
<a href="http://www.nrel.gov">National Renewable Energy Laboratory
(NREL)</a>, Golden, Colo., to develop Native American energy resources.  <p>
    <h3>For more information, contact:</h3>
  Jay Haley/<a href=mailto:jhaley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhaley@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
 EERC research engineer<br>
 (701) 777-5260<p>
Burl McCaslin, windsmith<br>
Little Hoop College<br>
 (701) 766-1318<p>
Anita Blue, tribal planner<br>
Turtle Mountain Reservation<br>
(701) 477-6451<p>
Mark White Bull, tribal planner<br>
Standing Rock Sioux Reservation<br>
(701)854-7214<p>


