<head>
<title>Partnership Opportunities</title>

</head>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=200>
<TR><TD><a href="part.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="emtech.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=400>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Partnership Opportunities</h2><hr></center>
 
The EERC has enjoyed extraordinary growth during the past decade. Its list of clients includes hundreds of domestic and international companies as well as scores of national and international academic institutions and government agencies.  Today, the number of contracts at the EERC is approaching 200 per year.  Annual contract revenue exceeds $22 million. The EERC maintains a highly flexible business approach, tailoring contractual agreements to individual client needs.   More than 70 percent of its contracts are with private industrial partners.
<p>
<h2>EERC-DOE Jointly Sponsored Research Program</h2>
<ul plain>
The EERC is an agent for the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) Jointly Sponsored Research Program (JSRP).   Through this program, commercial entities can team with the EERC and DOE to demonstrate and commercialize innovative energy and environmental technologies. The JSRP provides up to 40 percent cofunding for nonfederally matched projects that address a broad range of national energy and environmental priorities.
</ul><p>
<h2>EERC Consortium-Sponsored Research</h2>
<ul plain>
The EERC's consortium-sponsored research is a proven approach to addressing similar needs of multiple clients. Through this program, research and financial risks are spread over a larger base, enabling members to obtain a greater product than would have been possible with the same amount of funding invested individually.
</ul><p>
<h2>EERC-DOE Environmental Management Program</h2>
<ul plain>
The EERC has a partnership with DOE's Morgantown Energy Technology Center to assist in the development and implementation of innovative technologies to clean up environmental contamination at U.S. nuclear weapons facilities.  The EERC-DOE Cooperative Agreement focuses special attention on involving U.S. small businesses and their cleanup technologies.  The EERC's role is to work with small businesses on final development and demonstration of these technologies.
</ul><p>
<h2>EERC-EPA Center for Air Toxic Metals</h2>
<ul plain>
The EERC's Center for Air Toxic Metals (CATM) is a partnership with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, industry, and research organizations that is involved in the prevention and control of air toxic metal emissions.  CATM has an Affiliates Program that allows organizations to participate as partners in its assorted technical program areas.  Affiliate members provide direction to ensure CATM program areas are focused on issues relevant to industry and government. The cost of becoming a member of the Affiliates Program is $20,000 per year.
 </ul><p>
<h2>EERC Memoranda of Understanding</h2>
<ul plain>
The EERC has executed several short-term, renewable memoranda of understanding with private sector companies.  These memoranda are "agreements" to pursue specific technology applications or other opportunities and serve as the basis for subsequent formal contractual relationships.
</ul><p>
<h2>EERC Foundation</h2>
<ul plain>
The EERC has established the EERC Foundation to house intellectual property developed at the EERC and to foster the development, demonstration, and commercialization of energy and environmental technologies.
</ul><p>
<h2>EERC Confidentiality</h2>
<ul plain>
Confidentiality is often a concern for industrial clients seeking to maintain a competitive edge.  North Dakota law provides for practical confidentiality agreements between the EERC and its partners.
</ul><p>

<hr>
</Table>
</TD>
