<html>
<head>
<title>Environmental Management</title>

</head><body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=235>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/earl01.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="partop.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" Border=0></a><a href="catm.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" Border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" Border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=380>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Environmental Management Technology
Demonstration and Commercialization</h2><hr></center>

The U.S. Department of Energy is facing the monumental task of cleaning up environmental contamination at nuclear weapons facilities and other sites across the nation.  The EERC has entered into a Cooperative Agreement with the DOE Morgantown Energy Technology Center to develop, demonstrate, and commercialize environmental management technologies to clean up these sites.  The EERC's Environmental Management (EM) Program is working to accomplish this in two ways:  1) by providing the private sector, especially small businesses, with the expertise and technical resources needed to take their technologies to the marketplace and 2) through research, development, and demonstration of its own technologies, leading to commercialization partnerships with the private sector.
<p>
<h2>Key Environmental Management Activities</h2>
<ul plain>
<li>Extraction and Analysis of Pollutant Organics from Contaminated Solids Using Off-Line Supercritical Fluid Extraction and On-Line SFE/IR - The EERC is evaluating and demonstrating simple-to-operate field instrumentation and extraction methods capable of providing rapid analysis of organic contaminants.
<p>
<li>Thermal Decomposition of High-Organic-Content Radioactive Wastes - In partnership with the American Plastics Council, DOE, and other U.S. companies, the EERC has developed a low-temperature process for thermal decomposition of mixed-waste plastics, automotive shredder wastes, and chemical spill residuals.  The process will form the basis of a commercially viable recycling process able to accommodate a variety of plastics and high-organic-content materials from laboratory and production facilities that handle low-level nuclear materials.
<p>
<li>Fluid-Bed Calcination for Liquid Wastes - The EERC is evaluating denitrification strategies that can be applied to bed-sintering problems experienced in the fluid-bed processing of liquid wastes at EM sites.
<p>
<li>Centrifugal Membrane Filtration - Large volumes of water contaminated with heavy metals and radionuclides exist at DOE and Department of Defense sites. SpinTek Membrane Systems Inc. of Huntington Beach, California, has developed a uniquely configured centrifugal membrane filtration process to produce a clean, filtered water stream and a low-volume concentrate stream.  The EERC is evaluating the process and conducting several other tasks to optimize the application of the technology to EM cleanup needs.
<p>
<li>Laser Cleaning of Contaminated Painted Surfaces - Radionuclide-contaminated paint is an obstacle to the economical decommissioning of structures and equipment at EM sites.  F2 Associates of Albuquerque, New Mexico, has developed an innovative laser cleaning unit that removes contaminated paint from surfaces without releasing hazardous contaminants into the atmosphere.  The EERC is providing technical support in the development of the technology.
<p>
<li>Systems Analysis of Environmental Technologies - Many technologies are being developed to clean up EM sites. The EERC, in cooperation with the Waste Policy Institute and DOE's Morgantown Energy Technology Center, is evaluating the technical viability and economic competitiveness of these technologies.  Results from the evaluations will be used to enhance current research programs and to advance the timing of site cleanup.</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>Contact People</h3>
