<head>
<title>Center for Air Toxic Metals</title>

</head>
<BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<nobr>
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=235>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/catm1.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="emtech.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" Border=0></a><a href="aii.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" Border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" Border=0></a></TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=380>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Center for Air Toxic Metals</h2><hr></center>

Air toxic metals pose a significant challenge to the preservation of the global environment.  To meet this challenge, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency in 1993 designated the EERC as the Center for Air Toxic Metals (CATM).  CATM is focused on minimizing the effects of air toxic metal pollutants on the environment.  The Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 require regulatory actions addressing 189 substances, including air toxic metals.  In order to devise regulations, CATM is working with industry and government to develop sufficient information on air toxic metals to provide a theoretical basis for preventing and controlling the emissions and evaluating the fate and impacts of air toxic metals on plants and animals, including humans.  Developing, demonstrating, and commercializing technologies and processes that reduce the release of air toxic metals is a major part of CATM's mission.  The EERC's internationally recognized research on fuels characterization, combustion, ash behavior, ash utilization, ash disposal, and groundwater and its experience in developing partnerships and training programs uniquely qualify CATM to be the world leader in air toxics research.  CATM invites international participation in the program.
<p>
<h2>Key CATM Activities</h2><ul plain>
<li>Identifying sources of toxic metals in the oil, gas, utility, and waste-to-energy industries.<p>
<li>Examining all options to prevent the release of air toxic metals.<p>
<li>Determining the partitioning of metals in process streams and their amount, form, and ultimate fate.<p>
<li>Developing, demonstrating, and commercializing technologies and processes that mitigate the release or toxicity of potentially toxic metals.<p>
<li>Developing techniques to effectively sample and measure air toxic metals in feedstocks and process streams.<p>
<li>Developing computer-based technologies to compile the vast quantities of data and predict the fate of air toxic metals.<p>
<li>Developing educational programs to foster environmental literacy in students.<p>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>Contact People</h3>

