<html>
<head>
<title>American Indian Initiative</title>

</head>
<body>
<BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=250>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/lakeview.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="catm.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="watman.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=360
>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>American Indian Initiative</h2><hr></center>


The University of North Dakota has a long-standing commitment to American Indians.  The EERC is continuing this tradition through a program focused on responding to energy and environmental needs on Indian lands.  The EERC is developing partnerships with a growing network of American Indian organizations, including tribal governments, tribal colleges, American Indian-owned businesses, and the Council of Energy Resource Tribes (CERT).  The EERC also is working to increase American Indian university enrollments in energy and environmental disciplines to broaden American Indian employment opportunities.
<p>

<h3>Key American Indian Initiative Activities</h3>
<ul plain>
<li>A considerable percentage of the Alaska Native population is located in remote villages. Because of the long distance that fuel must be shipped and other factors, the cost of energy in these communities is among the highest in the United States.  The EERC and DOE's Morgantown Energy Technology Center are working in partnership with Alaska Native and state officials to introduce small, economical, environmentally friendly, easy-to-operate-and-maintain technologies that use indigenous fuels and waste materials to produce electricity and heat.  The lessons being learned in Alaska are transferable to Native Hawaiian and American Indian communities throughout the United States and to the world.<p>

<li>The Devils Lake Sioux Tribe in Fort Totten, North Dakota, has contracted with the EERC to evaluate the environmental impact of the tribal municipal landfill, wastewater treatment lagoons, and nitrate contamination on groundwater near tribal water supply wells.<p>

<li>The Turtle Mountain Chippewa Tribe (TMCT), in partnership with the EERC, has been awarded $248,000 from DOE's National Renewable Energy Laboratory to demonstrate the production of electricity from wind on the Turtle Mountain Reservation in North Dakota.  The TMCT-EERC team will conduct an environmental impact assessment, identify the optimal wind energy sites, and install and operate a wind turbine to produce power for tribal industries.<p>

<li>Universal Technologies Corporation (UTC), a 100% American Indian-owned and 
-controlled environmental consulting firm in Powell, Wyoming, and the EERC have signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) under which both parties offer a broad range of services, including resource characterization, energy conversion, site assessment, groundwater geology, waste utilization, and contaminant remediation.<p>

<li>Council of Energy Resource Tribes, an organization of 53 federally recognized Indian tribes and four Canadian Indian nations, and the EERC have developed an MOU under which CERT, members of CERT, and the EERC will work together on specific research, development, demonstration, and commercialization projects focused on resource assessment, energy conversion technology, reclamation of disturbed lands, waste utilization, site cleanup, contaminant remediation technology, and training.</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>Contact People</h3>

Michael Jones/<a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Associate Director<br>
Telephone:  (701) 777-5130 <p>

Gerald Groenewold/<a href=mailto:ghg@eerc.und.nodak.edu>ghg@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Director<br>
