<head>
<title>Water Management</title>

</head>
<body>
<BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=235>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/harju.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="aii.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="educat.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=370>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Water Management</h2><hr></center>

Water is the world's most precious resource.  In order to ensure sufficient quantities of quality water for public use and future development of industry and agriculture, intelligent use and management of water resources are required.  The EERC has a long history of water management research.  Today, it is a recognized expert on a host of water conservation and contamination issues and has an expanding number of water management initiatives.
<p>
<h2>Key Water Management Activities</h2>
<ul plain>
<li>Red River Basin Water Management Consortium - The EERC and AGVISE Laboratories Inc., a Northwood, North Dakota, private laboratory specializing in environmental and agricultural testing and research, have teamed to develop a water management program for the Red River of the North Basin.  The program will establish a consortium of industry, municipalities, and other entities in partnership with state and federal governments to develop a long-term watershed management strategy for the basin.  The program is expected to become a model for watershed management in other areas of the United States and the world.
<p>
<li>Freeze-Thaw/Evaporation - The EERC has developed a process in partnership with B.C. Technologies in Laramie, Wyoming, to remove salts, organic material, and other contaminants from brackish water.  The freeze-thaw/evaporation process relies on ice crystallization in below-freezing temperatures and evaporation in warm weather to purify contaminated water.  Brackish water is produced during oil and gas industry operations.  Current disposal methods are costly.  The process also has the potential to turn naturally salty groundwater and surface water into high-quality, potable water.
<p>
<li>Red River Basin Riparian Demonstration Project - The establishment of riparian zones-areas of trees, shrubs, and vegetation that line the banks of streams and rivers-is one of the best methods for preventing surface water and groundwater pollution.  The EERC is spearheading a project aimed at restoring riparian areas and improving surface water and groundwater in eastern North Dakota.
<p>
<li>Impacts of Agricultural Chemicals on Groundwater Quality - The EERC is conducting a research program to determine the potential for groundwater contamination from agricultural chemicals.  Through long-term, comprehensive studies of multiple field sites in the northern Great Plains, the program will provide a scientific basis for effectively managing agricultural chemicals and a model to resolve specific problems. 
</ul><p>
<hr>
<h3>Contact People</h3>

Edward Steadman/<a href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Deputy Associate Director<br>
Telephone:  (701) 777-5157<p>

Gale Mayer/<a href=mailto:gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Senior Research Manager<br>
Telephone:  (701) 777-5108<p>

John Harju/<a href=mailto:jharju@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jharju@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Senior Research Manager<br>
Telephone:  (701) 777-5208<p>

Gerald Groenewold/<a href=mailto:ghg@eerc.und.nodak.edu>ghg@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
