<head>
<title>Education and Training</title>

</head>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=215>
<TR><TD><a href="watman.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" Border=0></a><a href="grnd.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" Border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" Border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=400>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h1>Education and Training</h1><hr></center>

Education and training are a key part of the EERC's mission. EERC education and training activities include conferences, short courses, 
workshops, participation in academic programs, and practically oriented field experiences.  The EERC's education and training program 
strives to disseminate critical scientific and engineering knowledge in a timely manner to a wide range of audiences. The goal is to 
facilitate communication between research entities, industry, government, academia, and the public.
<p>
<h2>Key Education and Training Activities</h2>		
With its expertise and industrial network, the EERC is capable of providing state-of-the-art education and 
training on such internationally critical topics as:
<ul plain>
<li>Wind Energy
<li>Air Pollution Control
<li>Gas Industry Environmental Issues
<li>Oil Industry Environmental Issues
<li>Waste to Energy
<li>Contaminant Cleanup and Site Remediation
<li>Energy Policy
<li>Clean and Efficient Power Production from Coal
<li>Mined Land Reclamation
<li>Groundwater
<li>Wetlands
<li>Plastics Recycling
<li>Waste Utilization and Disposal
<li>Coal Gasification
<li>Water and Wastewater Treatment
<li>Pollution Prevention
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Conferences</h2>

The EERC sponsors, organizes, and participates in energy and environmental conferences worldwide. Examples include the following:		
<p>	<ul plain>
<li>International Conference on Energy & Environment, Shanghai, China, 1995
<li>Midwest Groundwater Conference, 1994
<li>Energy and Environment:  Transitions in East Central Europe, Prague, Czech Republic, 	1992 and 1994
<li>International Engineering Foundation conferences on ash behavior in power systems, 	1991 and 1993
<li>SynOps - Opportunities in the Synthetic Fuels Industry, 1988, 1990, and 1992
<li>Seventeen Biennial Low-Rank Fuels Symposia, 1961-1993  
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Short Courses</h2>	
<ul plain>
<li>The EERC offers a one-day ash deposition short course, "Recent Advances in Research on Ash Deposition in Utility Boilers:  Practical Applications for the Electric Power and Coal Industries."
<p>
<li>The EERC provides training in scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and supercritical fluid extraction (SFE) techniques to visiting scientists from government, industrial, and academic laboratories.
<p>
<li>The EERC has provided training for foreign energy industry leaders for the Institute of International Education under the sponsorship of the U.S. Agency for International Development.
<p></ul>
<h2>Workshops</h2>
<ul plain>
<li>The EERC is delivering a series of workshops around the United States focused on understanding and managing mercury-related issues facing the gas industry. These workshops are sponsored by the Gas Research Institute and the U.S. DOE.
<p>
<li>The EERC hosted an Advanced Recycling Technologies Workshop in May 1995 for industry and academia and federal, state, and local government agencies. The workshop included an overview of advanced recycling technologies and discussions on the status of recycling in the United States, Canada, Europe, and Japan.
<p>
<li>In 1995, the EERC coordinated and cosponsored the Alaska Native, American Indian, and Native Hawaiian Remote-Site Power Generation Workshop:  Transferring the Alaskan Experience, a follow-up to a Small Alternative Power Generation Workshop held in Anchorage, Alaska, in 1994. The 1995 workshop explored activities undertaken to meet the energy needs of remote villages in Alaska and the opportunities to commercialize technologies and transfer relevant information to other indigenous communities.  
<p>
<li>The EERC presented two workshops under DOE sponsorship in Prague, Czech Republic, focused on Least-Cost Economic Power Generation in East Central Europe and Production and Utilization of Ecological Fuels from East Central European Coals.
<p>
<li>The EERC held a workshop, Trace Element Transformations in Coal-Fired Power Systems, sponsored by the Electric Power Research Institute and DOE. 
<p>
<li>The EERC has organized and presented ash reuse workshops for a variety of industrial audiences.
<p>
<li>The EERC cosponsored riparian workshops focused on management and restoration of river bottom ecosystems and management of forested riparian areas and bioengineering for streambank stabilization.
<p></ul>
<h2>Academic Programs</h2>
<ul plain>
<li>More than 100 students each year, from undergraduates to postdoctorates, are involved in EERC projects that often provide practical thesis and dissertation topic opportunities for advanced degrees.  
<p>
<li>Key EERC researchers hold faculty appointments and adjunct faculty appointments at universities across the United States. The EERC is a key participant in the UND School of Engineering and Mines Ph.D. program in  energy engineering.
<p>
<li>EERC researchers have taught a university course, "Inorganic Transformations and Ash Deposition During Combustion."  </ul>
<p><hr>
<h3>Contact Person</h3>

Deb Haley/<a href=mailto:dhaley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dhaley@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Assistant to the Director<br>
Telephone:  (701) 777-3120<br>
