<head>
<title>Renewable Energy</title>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=190>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/windmill.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="oil.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="nonc.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=430
>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Renewable Energy</h2><hr></center>

Technological advances, increased energy demand, and environmental regulation will heighten the use of renewable energy resources in the 21st century.  Renewable energy resources include solar, wind, tide, running water, geothermal, and biomass. The EERC is committed to increased utilization of these renewable energy resources, which are more environmentally friendly and can offer favorable economic advantages.  EERC renewable energy research is based on the philosophy that understanding the resource is a prerequisite to technological development.  The EERC has a multidisciplinary team of scientists and engineers who understand the pathways along which energy flows through the environment and apply that understanding to the development and commercialization of renewable energy technologies.
<P>
<h2>Key Renewable Energy Activities</h2>
<ul plain>
<li><a href="../wind/webwind.htm">Wind Energy</a>
<li><a href="../nafl/nafl.htm">National Alternative Fuels Laboratory</a>
<li>Vegetable Oil Diesel Fuel
<li>Liquefaction of Carbon Compounds
<li>Waste Utilization and Disposal
<li>Refuse-Derived Fuels
<li>Combustion and Environmental Issues
<li>Effects of Biomass on Combustion System Performance
<li>Advanced Combustion Systems
</ul>
<hr>

<h3>Contact People</h3>

Michael Jones/<a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
Associate Director<br>
