<title>Reclamation of Disturbed Lands</title></head>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=230>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/reclam.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="ams.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="aec.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>

</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=370
>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Reclamation of Disturbed Lands</h2><hr></center>

Reclamation of lands disturbed by mining, energy extraction, wetlands alteration, waste disposal, agriculture, military operations, and other activities is the final step in the use of the earth's resources. Understanding the geology and water resources of a site is key to successful reclamation.  The EERC has more than two decades of applied research focused on understanding different landscapes prior to disturbance, enabling it to tailor reclamation that is cost-effective and compatible with the surrounding environment.
<p>
<h2>Key Reclamation of Disturbed Lands Activities</h2>
<ul plain>

<li>National Mine Land Reclamation Center - Western Region
<li>Analytical Methods Development
<li>Advanced Leaching Protocols
<li>Coal Evaluation and Characterization
<li>Groundwater Research Program for the North American Gas and Oil Industry
<li>Impacts of Agricultural Chemicals on Groundwater Quality
<li>Waste Utilization and Disposal
<li>Coal, Uranium, and Metal Mine Reclamation
<li>Applied Geology
</ul>
<p>
