<head>
<title>Atmospheric Emission Control</title>

</head>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=220>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/ptcunit.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="rdl.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="wud.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=380
>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Atmospheric Emission Control</h2><hr></center>

Atmospheric emission control of pollutants at power plants and other facilities is critical to maintaining a healthy level of air quality in the world.   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has designated the EERC the Center for Air Toxic Metals.  EERC atmospheric emission control research has led to retrofit acid gas and particulate removal technologies for existing energy facilities. It also is providing understanding critical to the design of the next generation of equipment needed to control particulate as well as gaseous organic and inorganic emissions from utilities, incinerators, refineries, and other industrial sources.  By-products produced by power plant emission control systems are a resource that can be used for a variety of purposes.  The EERC has extensive experience in the utilization of these by-products.
<p>
<h2>Key Atmospheric Emission Control Activities</h2>
<ul plain>
<li>Air Toxics
<li>Flue Gas Conditioning for Enhanced Particulate Control
<li>Fine Particulate Control
<li>Hot-Gas Cleaning
<li>Acid Gas Emission Control
<li>Fuel and Sorbent Characterization
<li>Repowering
<li>Advanced Power Systems
<li>Waste Utilization and Disposal
<li>Fuel Conditioning
<li>Sampling and Analytical Methods Development
</ul><p>
