<head>
<title>Waste Utilization and Disposal</title>

</head>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=230>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/lab06.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="aec.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" border=0></a><a href="ccsr.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=380>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Waste Utilization and Disposal</h2><hr></center>

Cost-effective, environmentally sound utilization of wastes continues to be a volatile issue. The EERC's approach begins with understanding the physical, chemical, mineralogical, leaching, and biological character of different wastes. This understanding enables the EERC to predict what is in a material, how much is there, how it may leach into surrounding soil and groundwater, and how it ultimately will behave in the environment--information critical to its successful use or disposal.  The knowledge gained in waste research is valuable in the cleanup of contaminated sites. Waste utilization is the preferred option. Disposal is the option of last resort.   Solutions must integrate science, technology, individual responsibility, and policy.
<p>
<h2>Key Waste Utilization and Disposal Activities</h2>
<ul plain>
<li>Materials Characterization Focused on Process Residuals
<li>Coal Ash Resources Research Consortium
<li>Advanced and Conventional Power Systems Research
<li>Waste Utilization Options
<li>Groundwater Research Program for the North American Gas and Oil Industry
<li>Impacts of Agricultural Chemicals on Groundwater Quality
<li>Contaminant Cleanup and Site Remediation
<li>Advanced Leaching Procedures
<li>Atmospheric Emission Control
<li>Analytical Methods Development
<li>Coal, Uranium, and Metal Mine Reclamation
<li>Applied Geology
</ul><p>
<h3>Contact People</h3>

