<html>
<head>
<title>Experimental Design and Analytical Methods Development</title>

</head>
<BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="/gif/bkgrnd.jpg">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=250>
<TR><TD><Img Src="/gif/sem_anal.gif" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="ccsr.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" Border=0></a><a href="rfe.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" Border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" Border=0></a></TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=370>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<h2>Experimental Design and Analytical Methods Development</h2><hr></center>

Experimental design and analytical methods development are necessary to identify, quantify, and understand increasingly complex materials and processes in ever greater detail. Standard methods of analysis for measuring the results of experiments are often inadequate for research needs, making it necessary to develop appropriate protocols, which, in turn, typically become tomorrow's standard methods. The EERC is committed to practical experimental design and the development of new analytical methods to identify and quantify natural and synthetic materials. Helping clients understand critical questions regarding their problems so that cost-effective answers can be obtained in a timely manner is the primary goal.
<p>
<h3>Key Experimental Design and Analytical Methods Development Activities</h3>
<ul plain>
<li>Supercritical Fluid Extraction
<li>Capillary Zone Electrophoresis
<li>Atomic Fluorescence
<li>Metal Speciation
<li>Fiber-Optic-Coupled Laser Fluorescence
<li>Computer-Controlled Scanning Electron Microscopy
<li>Automated Trace Element Wavelength-Dispersive X-Ray Fluorescence Spectrometry
<li>Particle-by-Particle Scanning Electron Microscopy
<li>Conceptual Modeling
<li>Numerical Modeling
<li>Database Management
<li>Geographic Information Systems
<li>On-Line Particle-Size Analysis
<li>Cohesive Properties of Fly Ash
</ul><p>
<h3>Contact People</h3>

