<TD>
<Table Width=395
>
<TR><TD><Font Size=-1>
<H2>Director's
Message<BR>Dr. Gerald
H. Groenewold</h2>

</TD> </TR> </TABLE> </BR>
One of my most enjoyable activities is sharing the culture, personality, and accomplishments of
the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center (EERC) with the numerous individuals who
visit
our Center each year.  The vast majority of our first-time visitors seem quite surprised at the
practically oriented, problem-solving, business approach to research, development,
demonstration,
and technology commercialization that has become the cornerstone of our organization.  <p>

<p>

Since 1983, the EERC has evolved from an almost strictly coal-oriented, federal R&amp;D
facility to
a
broadly focused, global energy and environmental technology center.  During FY95 alone, the
EERC developed 139 contracts with U.S. industrial clients in 34 states.  During the same period
of time, we received contracts for projects in eight foreign countries as well as a variety of
federal
contracts.  <p>

<p>

Partnership building is a key element of EERC program development efforts.  The EERC has a
multiyear Cooperative Agreement with the Department of Energy which provides select     
funding
for applied basic research and for joint venture projects with nonfederal partners.  During fiscal
year 1995, the Jointly Sponsored Research Program funding available from the Department of
Energy was used to cofund 19 partnership projects.  Eleven new Jointly Sponsored Research
Program projects were initiated during the year, while eight existing projects received additional
funding.  The nonfederal funding brought to this program by the Energy &amp; Environmental
Research Center represents 61% of the total dollars for the program.  With the current focus to
reduce or eliminate the federal deficit, Congress must seek to identify and fund technically
superior, cost-effective programs.  The EERC's Cooperative Agreements for fundamental
research and jointly sponsored research combine to form just such a program.  Nonfederal
entities
are voting for this program with their hard-earned research, development, demonstration, and
commercialization dollars, as evidenced by the 61% funding share they provided during the past
year.  <p>

<p>

   Technology commercialization and global technology export opportunities are currently
generating a great deal of discussion in our country.  Fundamental to maximizing the success of
these efforts is the development of industry, government, and research organization partnerships. 
The EERC is a successful practicing model for partnership building.  In addition, during the past
few years, the EERC has spun off eight technology companies; others are anticipated in the near
future.  <p>

<p>

   As you read through this report, you will gain a sense of the problem-solving,
business-oriented, partnership-building culture of the EERC.  All organizations reflect the
people
who work there.  We are blessed with an extremely talented technical and support staff. 
Moreover, at least as important as their technical talents are the dedication, decency, and high
level of integrity of our staff.  <p>

<p>

<p>   We look forward to another successful and gratifying year in 1996.  Please call us if we
may be able to provide assistance to you or your organization.</p>
<p>

<hr>
Gerald Groenewold/<a href=mailto:ghg@eerc.und.nodak.edu>ghg@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5295<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
