<title>EERC Highlights: July-December 1993</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>EERC Highlights: July-December 1993</h2>

<hr>
<h3>Eastern European Initiative Results in Two Projects for
the EERC</h3>

     As part of its ongoing Eastern European initiative, the EERC was involved in two
projects
totaling $500,000 to study opportunities for coal technology commercialization in the
Czech Republic and clean coal technology uses in Bulgaria.<p>


<hr>
<h3>Ethanol Study Focuses on Effects of Denaturant and
Water </h3>

     The EERC conducted a research project for the National Corn Growers Association to
determine whether controlling the amount of denaturant and water in ethanol could make
it a more environmentally friendly fuel additive.  The research was important in light of the
Environmental Protection Agency's fall 1994 deadline to issue final rules regulating
reformulated gasoline.  <p>

<hr>
<h3>EERC Director Appointed to North Dakota 2000
Committee </h3>

     EERC Director Gerald Groenewold was one of nine North Dakotans appointed to the
29-member North Dakota 2000 Committee.  The committee was begun in 1988 by the
Greater North Dakota Association to develop a vision for the future of the state.  It held a
series of town meetings in 40 communities to create a consensus on North Dakota's
direction into the next century.  Groenewold chaired the Greater North Dakota Association
Futures Committee prior to being appointed to the North Dakota 2000 Committee.<p>
<hr>
<h3> Works on Canadian Oil and Gas Industry Project
</h3>

     The EERC worked with the Canadian oil and gas industry on a $500,000 field
demonstration project to identify the most effective and economical ways to clean up
subsurface contamination at plants processing high-sulfur natural gas (sour gas).  The
EERC joined the Alberta Sour Gas Plant Subsurface Remedial Technologies Project,
initiated several years ago under the joint sponsorship of the Canadian Association of
Petroleum Producers and Environment Canada.  Sour gas-producing plants are found
worldwide, and the large number of them in Alberta cause varying levels of subsurface
contamination.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Scientist Participates in National Science Foundation
Madagascar Project</h3>

     EERC paleontologist Joseph Hartman spent six weeks during the summer of 1993 in
Madagascar, an island nation off the east coast of Africa, conducting paleontologic and
geologic research as part of the National Science Foundation's Grants for Exploratory
Research Program.  He was part of a group of paleontologists looking for vertebrates
(mammals and dinosaurs) and invertebrates from the Late Cretaceous period.  Hartman
specializes in nonmarine mollusks, such as clams and snails, that lived in freshwater or
terrestrial environments.<p>
<hr>
<h3> Fluid-Bed Combustion Project Good Example of
Research, Industry, and Government Partnership </h3>
     State and federal governments and utilities worked with the EERC on a 3-year, $1.2
million jointly sponsored research project to study ash-related problems in fluid-bed combustion
boilers.  Fluid-bed combustors can burn a wide variety of fuels, including coal, almond shells,
wood chips,
orchard prunings, and waste sludge and can be retrofitted to older power plants, helping to
improve
efficiency and reduce air pollution. <p>

<hr>
<h3>  EERC Researcher Honored with International Award
</h3>

     EERC researcher Steven Hawthorne, known worldwide for his work in the field of
supercritical fluid extraction, was honored with the Award of Excellence at the 5th
International Symposium on Supercritical Fluid Chromatography and Extraction in
Baltimore.<p>

<hr>
<h3>  Research Could Help Farmers Avoid Agricultural
Chemical Contamination of Groundwater </h3>

     The EERC began the fourth year of a 7-year, $3.5 million groundwater research project
funded by the U.S. Department of Agriculture to develop an understanding of the
occurrence, transport, and fate of agricultural chemicals.  This research will  help conserve
and protect irrigation and drinking water resources, increase agricultural efficiency, improve
chemical management practices, and provide a scientific basis for the regulation of
agricultural chemicals.<p>

<hr>
<h3>  Center Receives Funding for Aircraft Deicing Research
</h3>

     The North Dakota Department of Economic Development and Finance's Technology
Transfer, Inc., financed a 6-month, $100,000 research project at the EERC to develop and
demonstrate an environmentally friendly technology to deice aircraft at airports.  The
approach will result in more effective aircraft deicing, leading to greater air traffic safety.<p>

<hr>
<h3> EERC Promotes Environmental Awareness Through
Center for Air Toxic Metals </h3>

     In conjunction with being named the Center for Air Toxic Metals by the Environmental
Protection Agency,  the EERC formed an Environmental Education Committee to promote
environmental awareness within the Center and the University of North Dakota, as well as
throughout surrounding communities.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Patents Economical Coal Liquefaction Process
</h3>

     The elusive goal of economically converting coal into synthetic petroleum products is
one
step closer because of a coal liquefaction process patented by the EERC.  Preliminary
economic evaluations show that the EERC's coal liquefaction process, which is designed to
use lignitic and subbituminous coals (low-rank coals), can produce synthetic petroleum
30% to 40% below the cost of existing coal liquefaction technologies using bituminous coal. 

<hr>
<h3>  Research Shows Promise of New Technology to Recycle
Plastics </h3>

     Research showing that most plastics can be converted into useful liquids to serve as
manufacturing feedstocks provides new options for recycling postconsumer plastics,
diverting waste from landfills, and helping to conserve natural resources.  A research project
on advanced technology to recycle plastics was conducted by the EERC for the American
Plastics Council, a consortium of 25 major U.S. plastics manufacturers.<p>


<hr>
<h3>  EERC Matches State Lignite Research Program Dollars
5 to 1 </h3>

     State dollars awarded to the EERC through the North Dakota Lignite Research,
Development and Marketing Program were matched at a ratio of better than 5 to 1. 
According to the Lignite Energy Council, the EERC received $387,000 in contract funding
through the state program, which was leveraged into projects totaling nearly $2 million. <p>

<hr>
<h3>  Research Probes Airborne Contamination of
Groundwater by Pesticides </h3>

     Scientists at the EERC turned up some interesting findings in their efforts to determine
how pesticides and fertilizers used in agriculture reach groundwater.  Analyses of wind-blown
soil particles from the Grand Forks region show that these particles contain a
number of commonly used pesticides.  Airborne particles are eventually deposited over the
landscape, falling in surface water and on the ground.  In certain situations, chemicals may
leach downward and enter shallow groundwater aquifers.<p>
<hr>


