<html>
<head>
<title>EERC Highlights: January-December 1994</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>EERC Highlights: January-December 1994</h2>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Expansion Project Finished, Move into New
Facilities Completed</h3> 

     Completion of two new facilities gave the EERC an opportunity to further expand in
order to meet the
worldwide demand for its services and expertise.  The EERC completed its new Environmental
Research Laboratory Addition in January 1994, and nearly all staff and equipment were moved
into it
before the end of February.  Funding for the $7.6 million project was provided from the
following
sources:  $3.5 million from a U.S. Department of Energy grant, $2.5 million from a state bond
issue
guaranteed by the University of North Dakota Alumni Association Foundation (to be paid back
by the
EERC over a 10-year period), and a $1 million grant from the Grand Forks Growth Fund.  The
EERC
provided $600,000 in funding from its revenues.  The expansion project was completed in two
phases. 
The first phase was the four-level, 50,000-ft<SUP>2</SUP> Environmental
Research Laboratory
Addition.  The
second phase was a three-level, 7400-ft<SUP>2</SUP> Pilot Plant Addition.  <p>

<hr>
<h3>Enertech, EERC, and DOE Team Up on Municipal Solid
Waste Project</h3>

     The EERC, EnerTech Environmental, Inc., of Atlanta, and the U.S. Department of
Energy are
working together on a joint venture project investigating the use of municipal solid waste and
lignite
coal slurries to cofire power plants.<p>

<hr>
<h3>  Clay Soils Provide Natural Channels for Groundwater
Contamination</h3> 

     As natural filters, clay soils can help prevent agricultural chemicals from reaching
shallow
groundwater, but they probably are not providing nearly as much protection as once thought. 
Researchers at the EERC are finding that clay soils form relatively imperfect barriers between
agricultural chemicals and groundwater aquifers.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Center for Air Toxic Metals Officially Kicks Off
Program</b><p> </font> 

     An EERC research program aimed at controlling emissions of air toxic metals from
power plants and
waste incinerators officially began in May 1994.  In conjunction with this program, the EERC
started
a project with North Dakota's State Industrial Commission and the lignite industry to reduce air
toxic
emissions from lignite-fired power plants. <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Patented EERC Process Makes High-Value Char from
Low-Value Leonardite</b><p> </font> 

     A process patented by the EERC converts leonardite, a low-value, naturally occurring
material, into a
high-value char that sells for $400 to $1000 a ton. The Center's technology uses leonardite and a
mild
gasification process to produce a char that can replace expensive activated carbon used for air
and
water filtration.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  American Foundrymen's Society Supports EERC Form
Coke Project</b><p> </font> 

     The EERC is using the mild gasification process it developed to produce a form coke
briquette from
subbituminous coal for use as a furnace fuel and carbon source in hot metal production.  The
Center is
working with the American Foundrymen's Society of Chicago on a 4-year, $420,751 project
aimed at
producing a coke product that costs less and is equal to or better than conventional foundry coke
made
from high-quality bituminous coal.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Coal-Cleaning Process Offers Potential for Low-Rank
Lignite</b><p> </font> 

     Preliminary results of EERC research show that low-rank lignite coal can be cleaned to
produce a fuel
that complies with national clean air standards.  The research was conducted under North
Dakota's
Lignite Research, Development and Marketing Program using coal from Knife River Coal
Mining
Company's Beulah (North Dakota) mine. <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Waste-to-Energy Options Discussed with Grand Forks
Officials</b><p> </font> 

     EERC Director Gerald Groenewold and Associate Director Michael Jones met with
Grand Forks city
and county officials in June 1994 to discuss an innovative waste-to-energy technology that may
offer a
potential solution to the city's future landfill concerns.  The officials heard about a process the
EERC
is developing with EnerTech Environmental, Inc., Atlanta, Georgia, and the U.S. Department of
Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Indonesian Delegation Discusses Partnership
Opportunities with the EERC</b><p> </font> 

     A delegation of six high-level Indonesian government officials visited the EERC in
September 1994 to
discuss the possibility of establishing a cooperative research and development training program
in
clean coal technologies. <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Receives Environmental and Beautification
Awards</h3> 

     The EERC received an environmental award from the University of North Dakota and a
beautification
award from the Grand Forks Chamber of Commerce.  The University of North Dakota presented
the
EERC with the John Meagher Ecology Award in recognition of the EERC's recycling efforts and
its
environmental research program.  The Grand Forks Chamber of Commerce presented the EERC
with
its 1994 Beautification Award in recognition of the Center's efforts to improve and maintain the
beauty of its property.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Studies Effects of Fly Ash Used to Stabilize
Underground Mines</b><p> </font> 

     The EERC worked with the North Dakota Public Service Commission, which regulates
mining and
reclamation in the state, and the North Dakota State Department of Health and Consolidated
Laboratories, the state agency that enforces environmental regulations, to provide objective
scientific
information to answer questions about using fly ash for mine stabilization.  <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Electric Power Research Institute Brings International
Hot-Gas Filter Project to the EERC</b><p> </font> 

     An international consortium formed by the Electric Power Research Institute is working
with the
EERC to study ash problems associated with the cleaning of hot gases in advanced energy
systems. 
The 3-year, $1.8 million project is funded by the Electric Power Research Institute, the U.S.
Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center, and nine energy-related
businesses in
Germany, the Netherlands, France, the United Kingdom, and the United States.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Energy Secretary O'Leary Dedicates Two New EERC
Additions</b><p> </font> 

     U.S. Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary spoke during a ceremony August 26, 1994, to
dedicate the new
Environmental Research Laboratory and Pilot Plant Additions at the EERC.  O'Leary, a former
vice
president with Northern States Power Company in Minneapolis, was appointed to her post by
President Bill Clinton in 1993.  Also attending and speaking at the event were Senator Jocelyn
Burdick, Senator Kent Conrad, Senator Byron Dorgan, Congressman Earl Pomeroy, Grand Forks
Mayor Michael Polovitz, and Earl Strinden, executive director of the University of North Dakota
Alumni Association and Foundation.  University of North Dakota President Kendall Baker
presided. 
Construction on the $7.6 million expansion project began in 1992 and was completed in early
1994. 
The EERC's growing environmental research and development programs required a significant
expansion of laboratory facilities.  The new additions enabled the Center to consolidate labs that
were
located across the University of North Dakota campus and provide office space for the
researchers and
technicians who work in the labs.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Two UND Environmental Education Proposals Approved
for Funding</b><p> </font> 

     Two environmental education courses funded with grants from the EERC's Center for
Air Toxic
Metals were offered at the University of North Dakota fall 1994.  The courses were selected
from
among seven proposals submitted to the EERC by University of North Dakota faculty.  <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Process Sponsored Through Gas Research Institute,
EERC Project Wins R&amp;D Award</b><p> </font> 

     A mercury removal and recovery process that the EERC evaluated and helped refine was
selected as
one of the top 100 international research and development projects in 1994 by <i>R&amp;D
Magazine</i>. 
Mercury Recovery Services Inc. and Pittsburgh Mineral &amp; Environmental Technology Inc.
received
the award in September 1994 for their process, sponsored as part of a Gas Research Institute and
EERC project studying mercury contamination at gas industry metering and processing sites.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  1994 Prague Conference Builds Long-Term
Relationships for the EERC</b><p> </font> 

     The EERC's initiative in East Central Europe took a big step forward in November 1994
with the
successful completion of the Center's second energy and environmental conference in Prague,
Czech
Republic. The conference and its associated workshops attracted more than 300 industry
representatives, government officials, and researchers from 20 countries.  Entitled "The Second
International Conference on Energy and Environment:  Transitions in East Central Europe," the
conference was organized by the EERC and the Power Research Institute of Prague.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Coal-Water Fuel Technology Attracts Russian and
German Interest</b><p> </font> 

     Technology pioneered by the EERC to produce coal-water fuel from low-rank coals
attracted the
attention of a German company and a Russian research institute during the energy and
environmental
conference in Prague. The EERC's coal-water fuel process produces a liquid fuel from low-rank
coal
that upgrades the coal's energy value and environmental performance and can be used as a
replacement for heavy oil in industrial and utility boilers.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Workshops Focus on Low-Cost Power Generation, Clean
Fuels for East Central Europe</b><p> </font> 

     Two 2-day workshops preceding the November Prague conference examined the best
technologies for
generating power using the low-rank brown coal found in East Central Europe and how to deal
with
air pollution caused by domestic use of low-rank brown coal.  The workshops were sponsored by
the
U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center and organized by the
EERC.  <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Czech Coal Industry Seeks EERC Assistance to Remain
Competitive</b><p> </font> 

     Facing stiff competition from imported Russian natural gas, Czech coal industry officials
met in
Prague with representatives of the EERC to discuss how their industry can become more
competitive
in the energy marketplace.<p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Assisting with Cleanup of U.S. Department of
Energy Nuclear Weapons Sites and Facilities</b><p> </font> 

     The EERC is assisting the U.S. Department of Energy with the cleanup of its nuclear
weapons
complex and other contaminated sites throughout the country.  The Center began work on a
5-year,
$2.5 million cooperative agreement with the U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy
Technology Center.  The Center is supporting the U.S. Department of Energy Environmental
Restoration and Waste Management Program, which is aimed at cleaning up soil and water
contamination at the agency's sites.  <p>

<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Meets with Environmental Protection Agency, U.S.
Department of Energy, and Industry on Air Toxic Metals</h3> </font> 

     Measuring and controlling emissions of mercury, selenium, lead, and other air toxic
metals from
energy generation systems was the focus of a December 1994 meeting between government
officials,
industry representatives, and researchers.  Held at the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's
combustion and environmental laboratory research facilities in Research Triangle Park, North
Carolina, the meeting provided a forum for the exchange of information on the measurement and
control of air toxic metals.  Participants were also updated on the activities of the Center for Air
Toxic Metals, a nationally coordinated research program funded by the Environmental
Protection
Agency and industry and operated by the EERC at Grand Forks, North Dakota.<p>
<hr>
<A href="../index.html"> EERC Home Page</a> |
