<html>
<head>
<title>EERC Highlights: January-June 1995</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>EERC Highlights: January-June 1995</h2> 
<hr>
<h3> EERC Environmental Education Program Fosters
<font color="#00ff00">"Greening of UND"</h3> </font> 

     The EERC actively promoted the "greening of UND" to encourage environmental awareness
and
pollution prevention within the Center and on the University of North Dakota campus.  The
EERC's
greening program also aims at reducing waste and increasing energy efficiency both locally and
globally, with efforts ranging from the Center's own recycling program to its research on
developing
new recycling technology for the plastics industry.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Helps Venezuelan Refinery Recover Valuable
Element</h3> 

     The EERC assisted a Venezuelan oil refinery in recovering vanadium, a valuable element
found in
unusually high concentrations in the crude petroleum of northern South America.  The Center
worked
with the Lagoven Amuay Refinery in Judibana, Venezuela, one of the world's largest refineries. 
The
refinery plans to recover the vanadium from ash and market it worldwide.  Vanadium is used in
rust-resistant
high-speed tools, as a steel alloy, as a commercial catalyst, and in power plant air pollution
control systems.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Provides Examples of How University Research
Benefits Communities</h3> 

     Practical, market-driven university research can be a springboard for creating jobs and
economic
growth within North Dakota communities.  University research can also help these communities
deal
effectively with the energy and environmental issues they face.  Those messages were conveyed
by
Michael Jones, EERC associate director, during two workshops he conducted at Marketplace '95
in
January at Bismarck, North Dakota.<p>

<hr>
<h3>  U.S. Department of Energy Official Recognizes EERC for
Work on Coal Ash Report</h3> 

     The EERC received recognition in January 1995 at the American Coal Ash Association's 11th
International Symposium on Use and Management of Coal Combustion By-Products in Orlando,
Florida.  Robert Bedick of  the U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology
Center
accepted an award from the association, which was presented to the U.S. Department of Energy
for
its effort in submitting a report to Congress on the barriers to increased coal by-product
utilization.  In
his acceptance speech, Bedick acknowledged the EERC's efforts in assembling the background
information for the report.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Out-of-State Dollars Create Regional Jobs at the
EERC</h3> 

     North Dakotans and Minnesotans benefit the most from research dollars brought into the
northern
plains region from across the country and around the world by the EERC.  More than two-thirds
of
the EERC's 260 employees are from North Dakota and Minnesota, with 112 from 45
communities in
North Dakota and 62 from 40 communities in Minnesota.  Forty-four of the Center's North
Dakota
employees are from Grand Forks; 90 are graduates of the University of North Dakota; and 44
people
from the North Dakota-Minnesota region are nondegreed employees holding technical and
support
positions. <p>
<hr>

<h3>  EERC Surfs the "Information Superhighway"</h3>
</font> 

     Cruisers of the information superhighway can learn about the EERC's programs, facilities, and
capabilities through its World-Wide Web home page on the Internet.  With an Internet connection
and
Web-browsing software such as Mosaic and Netscape, the Center's home page can be accessed at
http://www.eerc.und.nodak.edu.  The EERC's home page, which first went on-line in July 1994,
was
accessed more than 30,000 times by people around the world in a 6-month period.  In 1995 the
home page
was accessed over 150,000 times.  <p>
<hr>
<h3>  Center Cosponsors International Conference in
China</h3> 

     The EERC was one of three U.S. university research centers cosponsoring the 1995
International
Conference on Energy and Environment in Shanghai, China.  Held in May 1995, the conference's
primary sponsors are the National Natural Science Foundation of China and the Shanghai
Association
for Science and Technology.<p>

<hr>
<h3>  EERC Technology, Expertise Create Spin-Off
Businesses</h3> 

     Although the EERC is known internationally for its energy and environmental research, it also
contributes to economic development in Grand Forks and the surrounding region.  Seven
companies
have been formed by EERC staff that are based on the technology and expertise developed at the
Center.  These companies have either commercialized processes, techniques, and scientific
research
developed at the EERC or are moving them closer to commercialization.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Joint Venture Program with U.S. Department of Energy
Assists Industry Research</h3> 

     Using federal dollars made available through a jointly sponsored research program with the
Department of Energy, the EERC has helped industry deal with energy and environmental issues. 
From the beginning of the joint venture program through fiscal year 1994, the U.S. Department of
Energy contributed $12.9 million in 72 EERC projects, totaling $28.5 million in confunded
research. 
In FY94, the $2.6 million Department of Energy investment resulted in $6.1 million in joint
projects
(57% nonfederal match).  In FY95, the EERC achieved a 61% private to 39% federal match.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Coal Ash Behavior and Deposition Short Course
Taught Nationwide</h3> 

     The EERC sponsors a one-day short course, available throughout the United States, offering a
practical overview of the physical and chemical processes related to ash behavior in coal-fired
boilers. 
The goal of this course is to provide an overview of recent research that is increasing the
understanding of mineral behavior in coal utilization and leading to the advancement of methods
to
predict ash behavior.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Senior Research Manager Receives Keene P. Dimick
Award</h3> 

     Steve Hawthorne, EERC senior research manager, was honored with the Keene P. Dimick
Award at
the Pittsburgh Conference (Pittcon '95), held in March 1995 in New Orleans, Louisiana. 
Hawthorne
received the award for his contributions to the development of supercritical fluid extraction as an
analytical technique.  The Pittsburgh Conference showcases the latest innovations in science and
technology and honors outstanding contributions to spectroscopy and analytical chemistry.<p>
<hr>
<h3>     EERC Environmental Education Committee Sponsors
Earth Day Poster Contest</h3> 

     An Earth Day poster contest for Grand Forks fifth-grade classes in honor of Earth Day's 25th
anniversary (April 22, 1995) was sponsored by the EERC's Environmental Education Committee. 
Nineteen students from a class at Lewis and Clark Elementary School in Grand Forks won the
contest.  They toured the EERC and participated in the Center's Earth Day party.  Posters created
as
a class project were based on the theme "Clean Energy for a Clean Environment."  EERC
researchers
helped students learn how energy can be produced cleanly and efficiently and provided
demonstrations
of how Center work helps prevent pollution and clean up environmental contamination.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Mercury Contamination Workshops Offered to Oil and
Gas Industry</h3> 

     Workshops focused on mercury soil contamination at oil and gas industry metering sites are
held at
cities throughout the United States.  The workshops are organized by the EERC with the support
of
Gas Research Institute, Chicago, and the U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy
Technology
Center.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Assists North Dakota Tribe in Conducting Wind
Energy Research</h3> 

     In an effort to harness some of the enormous energy potential of North Dakota's windswept
prairies,
the Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa is working to develop its wind energy resources in
partnership
with the EERC.  The project began in May 1995 and will be conducted in three phases on the
36-square-mile
Turtle Mountain Reservation in north central North Dakota. The goals are to develop a
model wind program for the Chippewa Tribe and determine the feasibility of building a
larger-scale
wind power plant to produce the reservation's electricity.<p>
<hr>
<h3>  Girl Scouts Explore Career Opportunities in Science at
the EERC</h3> 

     About 50 Girl Scouts from eastern North Dakota and western Minnesota gathered at the
EERC in
June.  They "shadowed" EERC researchers to learn more about career opportunities in science
and
participated in other activities to earn the Girl Scout "eco action" badge.  The activities at the
EERC
were part of a 2-day event sponsored by the Pine-to-Prairie Girl Scout Council, headquartered in
Grand Forks. <p>
<hr>
<h3>  EERC Hosts Project Learning Tree Environmental
Education Workshops</h3>

     More than 60 teachers, youth group leaders, and natural resource professionals from North
Dakota
attended workshops in January and June at the EERC as part of Project Learning Tree, a
nationwide
environmental education program.  The workshops provided an opportunity for the EERC to
become
more active in community outreach programs involving environmental education.  Project
Learning
Tree is a grassroots volunteer program that works in conjunction with local schools, state
agencies,
and natural resource organizations.
<hr>

