<html>
<head>
<title>Resource Assessment</title>

</head>
<body><BODY Bgcolor=ffffff Background="../gif/backgr.gif">
<Img Src="/gif/eerc_hd.gif">

<Table Width=600 CellPadding=0>
<TR>
<TD Valign=Top>
<Table Width=200>
<TR><TD><Img Src="../gif/earl.jpg" Border=0></A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><a href="water1.htm"><img src="../gif/back.gif" Border=0></a><a href="water3.htm"><img src="../gif/next.gif" Border=0></a><a href="../index.html"><img src="../gif/home.gif" Border=0></a>
</TD></TR>
</Table>
</TD>

<TD>
<Table Width=410
>
<TR><TD>
<center><H2>Resource Assessment</H2><hr></center><Font Size=-1>
<CENTER><I><B><FONT SIZE=2 COLOR=#000000 FACE="Garamond">When
the well's dry, we know the worth of water.</FONT></B></I></CENTER>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Garamond">Benjamin Franklin</FONT></CENTER>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Garamond">1706-1790<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">More than 400 billion gallons of
water are used in the United States each day.  For businesses,
landowners, communities, and regions to use water wisely, they
first must know how much water they have, where it is, how it
gets there, where it goes, and more.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">The EERC specializes in water assessment.
 It has experts in groundwater geochemistry, environmental geology,
contaminant hydrogeology, wetlands hydrology, and hydrogeological
and hydrogeochemical data collection and processing, modeling,
and interpretation.  Through its Information and Computing Technologies
Group, the EERC has the capability to develop predictive models
and relational database management systems, including geographic
information systems, to assess current and historical data on
water quality, quantity, and usage.<BR>
<BR>

</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">The EERC has handled an assortment
of water assessment projects.  Its recent experience includes
the formation and oversight of a consortium of private industry,
state and federal government, and municipal groups to study water
quality and quantity issues and develop a long-term watershed
management strategy for the Red River of the North watershed.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">This northern Great Plains region
is one of the most fertile and productive agricultural areas in
the world.  The goals of the Red River Water Management Consortium
include inventorying surface and groundwater data in the watershed;
determining the occurrence, transport, and fate of agricultural
chemicals; assessing water quality and quantity requirements of
municipalities and industries; and determining the environmental
impacts of municipal and industrial discharges.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Garamond">With this information, inhabitants
of the watershed will be better able to protect vital irrigation
and drinking water sources, increase agricultural efficiency,
improve chemical and water management practices, and provide a
scientifically valid basis for meaningful regulation of the region's
water resources.  The program is expected to become a model for
watershed management in other areas of the United States and the
world.</FONT>
</Table>
</TD>
</TR>
</Table>
</BODY>
</HTML>









</DOC>
