<html>
<head>
<title>EERC Partneship Opportunities in Research,
Development, Demonstration, and Commercialization</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>EERC Partneship Opportunities in Research,
Development, Demonstration, and Commercialization</h2>

<ul plain>
<h3> The Challenge and the Opportunity</h3>

     The EERC extends an invitation for partnership ventures to anyone seeking
research, development, demonstration, and commercialization opportunities
focused on energy and environmental technologies.  The greatest challenges of
the twenty-first century will include conversion of energy resources to
appropriate and environmentally acceptable forms, cost-effective remediation
of past environmental contamination, and prevention of future environmental
contamination.  The high quality of life we seek depends upon a thriving
environment and sufficient energy to meet our needs and wants.  As our need
for energy increases, so does the potential for adverse environmental impacts. 
Therefore, efficient energy production combined with pollution prevention
and/or pollution control is essential to maintain a high quality of life.  Our
future depends upon our ability to extract energy and other resources from our
environment in a manner that does not jeopardize the integrity and stability of
our environment.  These challenges present great business opportunities.<p>

<ul plain>
<h3>  EERC Philosophy and Team Approach</h3>

     The EERC is a self-supporting entity within the University of North Dakota.  The EERC's
staff of more than 260 scientists, engineers, and support personnel is dedicated to practical
problem-solving research, development, and demonstration activities leading to
commercial opportunities.<p>

     The EERC is committed to a team approach to commercializing energy and environmental
technologies through partnerships with industry.  Only effective partnerships poised to
solve the complex energy and environmental problems of today will develop the
opportunities vital for the thriving, dynamic society of tomorrow.  A single entity cannot
master and apply the wide range of skills needed to compete successfully in our emerging
world marketplace.  A synergistic team of distinctive talents, disciplines, and
organizational philosophies is needed to bring an idea through the multifaceted stages of
research, development, demonstration, and commercialization.<p>

     The EERC research team embraces a practical cradle-to-grave philosophy.  Because
energy and environment are intimately related and are cornerstones of our society, they
must be considered in a total context.  However, the magnitude of many energy and
environmental issues demands that they be treated as distinct components to facilitate
understanding.  EERC research areas are interrelated through commonalities in issues,
objectives, people, and facilities.  These commonalities provide an interconnecting web
that strengthens EERC multidisciplinary research programs.<p>


     The EERC philosophy for team building is to engage the best possible expertise.  If that
expertise is not available at the Center, it is obtained elsewhere.  The result is a large and
growing group of EERC research associates in the United States and abroad.<p>


     By the time an idea is commercialized, the project team will have grown to encompass a
wide variety of talent that may include government and private research organizations,
scientists, research managers, laboratory technicians, engineers, engineering technicians,
venture capitalists, investors, market analysts, entrepreneurs, marketers, business
managers, accountants, patent and copyright counsel, legal counsel, elected officials, and
regulatory agencies.  Even so, the technology must still be championed by a leader who
can bring the team together to produce the desired outcome, while keeping individual
members informed and focused on their specific roles in the overall plan.  <p>

 
<h3> Long-Term Investment and Risk</h3>

     The commercialization of energy and environmental technologies commonly requires
long-term investments with the potential for significant return.  Successful entrepreneurs
ignore today's societal aversion to risk by making calculated, long-term business decisions,
knowing that progress in any arena requires the willingness to take risks.  The EERC is
committed to taking advantage of long-term investment opportunities and is prepared to
take calculated business risks.<p>


<h3> Confidentiality</h3>

     Confidentiality is commonly a concern for industrial clients seeking to maintain a
competitive edge.  North Dakota law provides for practical and highly flexible
confidentiality agreements between the EERC and its partners.<p>

<h3> Education and Training Opportunities</h3>

     The rapid expansion of technology coupled with the competitive nature of the energy and
environmental industries has resulted in the need for very efficient ways to transfer
technology.  The EERC has developed a series of practically oriented short courses for
industry.  The short courses are designed not only to educate, but also to develop
relationships between the researchers in the energy and environmental industries who
actually apply technologies in commercial settings.  This cross-flow of information is
critical to the technology supplier and user alike. The industrial technology users cannot
afford to be ignorant of the latest advances that increase their ability to compete, while
those involved in research and development, as suppliers of new technologies, cannot
afford to be unaware of the changing needs in industry.  <p>

     Additionally, the EERC annually employs more than 125 highly motivated students from
the undergraduate to postdoctorate levels.  As these students graduate and move into the
private sector, they bring with them state-of-the-art understanding of a wide range of
energy and environmental issues and technologies.  EERC industrial partners have a
unique opportunity to attract new employees from this student group.<p>
</ul>

<h3> EERC Partnership Opportunities</h3>
     The EERC currently has more than 150 unique contractual agreements with a wide range
of domestic and foreign partners.  At present, over 70% of those contracts are with
industrial partners.  The period of performance for an individual contract can vary from
one week to over a decade in length.  The EERC maintains a very flexible business
approach that facilitates tailoring contractual agreements to the individual needs of clients. 
From this experience, a variety of very attractive and productive types of business
relationships have evolved.<p>

<ul>
<h3>  EERC-DOE Jointly Sponsored Research
Program</h3>

     The EERC is an agent for the U.S. Department of Energy's (DOE) Jointly Sponsored
Research Program. Through this program, the EERC provides up to 50% cofunding for
nonfederally matched projects that address a broad range of national energy and
environmental priorities.  Since 1990, the EERC has committed more than $9.5 million of
matching funds to over 90 projects.<p>

     The Jointly Sponsored Research Program provides a model funding vehicle that
encourages commercial entities to team with the EERC and DOE to demonstrate and
commercialize innovative energy and environmental technologies.  The Jointly Sponsored
Research Program has been a primary catalyst for the development of strategic U.S.
government, industry, and research-sector partnerships.  <p>

<h3>  EERC Consortium-Sponsored Research</h3>

     The EERC's consortium-sponsored research is a proven approach to addressing similar
needs of multiple clients.  In these programs, each member of the consortium obtains a
greater product than would have been possible with the same amount of funding invested
individually.  In many cases, consortium membership provides access to facilities that
would be prohibitively expensive for individual members to build, operate, and maintain.<p>

     Additionally, consortium-sponsored research is attractive to many sponsors because it
spreads research and financial risks over a larger base.  To date, the EERC has established
15 research consortia involving more than 120 sponsors to address a variety of energy and
environmental issues.<p>

<h3>  EERC-DOE Environmental Management
Program</h3>

     The EERC has a partnership with the DOE's Morgantown Energy Technology Center to
assist in the development and implementation of innovative new technology options to
clean up environmental legacies remaining from the U.S. nuclear weapons program.  The
EERC-DOE Cooperative Agreement focuses special attention on involving U.S. small
businesses and their technologies in solving the environmental problems at the U.S.
weapons sites.  The EERC's role is to work with small businesses on final development 
and demonstration of these technologies.<p>

<h3> EERC Memoranda of Understanding</h3>

     The EERC has executed several short-term, renewable memoranda of understanding
(MOU) with private- sector companies.  These memoranda are "agreements" to pursue
specific technology applications or other opportunities and serve as the basis for
subsequent formal contractual relationships.  For example, the EERC and firms in New
Zealand and Australia have an MOU to promote an underground coal gasification
demonstration project in the southwestern Pacific region.  Similarly, the EERC and an
American Indian-owned company have an MOU to pursue energy and environmental
technology applications on Indian lands in the American West.  In addition, the EERC has
developed an MOU with the Council of Energy Resource Tribes (CERT) focused on
addressing energy and environmental management needs on Indian lands.  An official
signing ceremony is being scheduled for the near future.<p>


<h3> EERC Foundation</h3>

     The EERC has established the EERC Foundation to aid in the development,
demonstration, and commercialization of energy and environmental technologies.  The
Foundation's role is to house and license technologies for which the EERC holds a unique
position by virtue of expertise, patents, or copyrights and to facilitate the formation of
spin-off technology companies that will commercialize EERC-derived technologies.<p>
</ul></ul>
<hr>
