<html>
<head>
<title>Energy Champion Award</title>
</head>
<body>
<center> <img src ="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><h2>Energy Champion Award</h2> </center> 


<font color="#990066"> <h3>Award History</h3> </font>
     The EERC created the Energy Champion Award to honor individuals who have demonstrated
extraordinary personal commitment to energy and environmental research and development
programs.  The Energy Champion Award has been awarded to the following people:<p>

<p>


<ul plain>
 <IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Sixth Energy Champion - Dr. Everett A. Sondreal, Principal
Research Advisor, Energy Environmental Research Center, 1995<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Fifth Energy Champion - Thomas J. Clifford, President
Emeritus,
University of North Dakota, 1993</li>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Fourth Energy Champion - The Honorable Kent Conrad, U.S.
Senator, Democrat-North Dakota, 1992</li>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Third Energy Champion - John MacFarlane, President and Chief
Executive Officer, Otter Tail Power Company, 1990</li>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Second Energy Champion - Con Aas, Assistant Manager of
Research, Northern States Power Company, 1986</li>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> First Energy Champion - The Honorable Mark Andrews, U.S.
Senator, Republican-North Dakota, 1986</li>
</ul>
<p>

<font color="#990066"> <h3><b>6th Champion - Dr. Everett A. Sondreal</b></h3>
</font> <p>

<p>

     Dr. Everett A. Sondreal was honored as the sixth recipient of the Energy &amp; Environmental
Research Center (EERC) Energy Champion Award.  Over the past 40 years, his commitment
to excellence and his dedication to providing practical solutions to critical energy and
environmental problems have come to embody the EERC's philosophy and approach.  His
research on coal and clean coal technologies, as well as his leadership during the EERC's
transition from federal to state ownership, make him a worthy candidate for this award.<p>

<p>

Currently serving as principal research advisor at the EERC, Dr. Sondreal was the primary
architect of the Cooperative Agreement between the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and
the University of North Dakota (UND) when the Center was defederalized in 1983.  His
efforts helped smooth the  transition to state ownership while avoiding harmful impacts on
the Center's staff.  The Center also retained its mission capability as the leading authority
on low-rank coal technology, enabling it to develop a more diversified program of scientific
and engineering research, testing, and evaluation.<p>

<p>

More recently, Dr. Sondreal played a key role in the EERC's international outreach activities,
including two energy and environmental conferences in Prague and a training program with the
U.S. State Department's Agency for International Development conducted by the EERC for
high-level energy managers from East Central Europe.  In the research area, Dr. Sondreal's
principal interests and expertise are in coal properties and clean coal technology.  <p>

<p>

He has authored or coauthored more than 60 publications, and he holds a U.S. patent for
continuous liquefaction of coal. <p>

<p>

A native of Grand Forks, North Dakota, Dr. Sondreal first worked at the Center in 1955 as an
undergraduate student at UND.  After graduating with a degree in chemical engineering, he
served in the U.S. Air Force as a nuclear research officer from 1957 to 1959 and then was
hired as a development engineer for DuPont.  He came back to UND in 1960 and worked at
the EERC as a graduate student while earning his master's degree in chemical engineering. 
Dr. Sondreal joined the Center's full-time staff as a research engineer in 1962 and was later
promoted to research supervisor.<p>

<p>

After receiving a Department of Interior training award, he attended the University of
Michigan from 1969 to 1972, where he earned his Ph.D.  There, he applied his work on the
computer modeling of combustion to the afterburning of auto emissions.  His models were
used by Ford and General Motors in designing emission control systems for their cars and
trucks.  Upon returning to the Center in 1972, Dr. Sondreal assumed a greater leadership role
in its programs.  <p>

<p>

The 1973 Arab Oil Embargo created one of the most exciting and interesting periods in the
Center's history as America attempted to capitalize on coal, its most abundant energy resource. 
Dr. Sondreal spearheaded efforts to expand the Center's programs in the areas of gasification,
liquefaction, and emissions control.  These opportunities brought significant growth in the
Center's staff and budget.  In addition, the Center was also assigned DOE responsibility for
oversight of environmental processes during the design and construction of the Great Plains
Gasification Plant near Beulah, North Dakota, which remains the nation's only
commercial-scale coal gasification facility.<p>

<p>

Dr. Sondreal served as the Center's deputy director from 1978 to 1980 and as its director from
1980 to 1983.  He received DOE's Exceptional Service and Super Achievement Award in
1982 and 1983.  Following the defederalization of the Center in 1983, Dr. Sondreal served as
president of Coal Energy Technology Consultants, Inc., Grand Forks, from 1984 to 1991.  He
returned to work for the EERC on a part-time basis as a senior research advisor in 1987 and
was recently named principal research advisor.  He and his wife, Grace, live on the Sondreal
family farm south of Grand Forks.<p>

<p>

In great appreciation for Dr. Sondreal's dedication to making the EERC one of the world's
leading energy and environmental research facilities and for his pragmatic approach to
conducting focused, practical research, he is honored with the 1995 Energy Champion.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"> <h3><b>5th Champion - Thomas J. Clifford</b></h3>
</font> <p>

<p>

For his long-term commitment to North Dakota, for understanding that higher education must
evolve toward being more sensitive to the marketplace, for his vision, for his political savvy,
and for consistently demonstrating the courage of his convictions, the EERC awarded Thomas
J. Clifford, President Emeritus, University of North Dakota (UND), the Fifth Energy
Champion Award.<p>

<p>

President of UND from 1971 to 1992, his visionary leadership and recognition of the potential
for commercial development of energy and environmental technologies set the stage for a
brighter economic future for North Dakota.  His association with UND spanned more than 50
years, and he served more years at the University than any other full-time employee.  In 1983,
the EERC became part of UND under then-President Clifford's tenure.  He is credited with
having the wisdom and foresight to understand what the EERC meant to the University and its
potential for economic development and jobs creation.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"> <h3><b>4th Champion - Senator Kent Conrad</b></h3>
</font> <p>

<p>

To show our appreciation for Senator Kent Conrad's dedication, determination, and
support for the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center and the state of North Dakota,
the EERC recognized him as the fourth recipient of the Energy Champion Award.  The
EERC greatly values its close working relationship with Senator Conrad and his efforts to
base national energy and environmental policy on sound scientific information.<p>

<p>

Senator Conrad is among our nation's leaders in shaping American energy policy, serving
as a member of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee and as vice chairman
of the committee's subcommittee on Water and Power.  Recognizing the enormous
potential of markets in East Central Europe and the Pacific Rim, he has worked relentlessly
and tirelessly to create opportunities for the export of North Dakota's energy and
environmental technologies to those markets.  Senator Conrad has been a speaker and a
participant in such important EERC events as the biennial SynOps Conferences, the Low-Rank Fuels
Symposium,
and the April 1992 East Central European energy and
environment conference in Prague, Czech Republic.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"> <h3><b>3rd Champion - John MacFarlane</b></h3> </font>
<p>

<p>

For exceptional personal and corporate dedication and commitment, the Energy &amp;
Environmental Research Center proclaimed Mr. John MacFarlane, President and Chief
Executive Officer of Otter Tail Power Company, as the third Energy Champion Award
recipient.  Through an ongoing commitment of personal time, financial gifts, and genuine
involvement, MacFarlane has demonstrated his support for the Center, the School of
Engineering and Mines, and the University of North Dakota.  <p>

<p>

MacFarlane demonstrates extraordinary personal commitment to energy and
environmental research and development programs.  Under his leadership, Otter Tail
Power Company has been among the most progressive industrial sponsors of the Center's
research programs, including Project Sodium, the Coal Ash Resources Research
Consortium, the groundwater-monitoring program, the circulating fluidized-bed
combustion program, and others.  These research efforts will potentially lead to lower
operating costs for utilities, thus helping hold down electrical energy costs to residents of
the upper Plains states.  In addition to coal-related research, MacFarlane has demonstrated
a commitment to renewable energy technologies and regional economic development.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"> <h3><b>2nd Champion - Conrad Aas</b></h3> </font>
<p>

<p>

Mr. Con Aas, formerly Assistant Manager of Research at Northern States Power Company
(NSP) in Minneapolis, Minnesota, made outstanding contributions to the advancement of
energy technology and to the energy industry in North Dakota.  He actively initiated
sponsorship of a variety of energy-related research projects at the University of North
Dakota, including ground-coupled heat pump systems and monitoring background solar
and wind energy, as well as supporting Project Sodium and the Coal Ash Resources
Research Consortium, projects involving enhanced efficiency in coal combustion and ash
management studies.  These projects provided excellent research opportunities for UND
faculty, staff, and students, while helping to put NSP at the forefront of technology
development in the electric utility industry.<p>

<p>

Aas continually demonstrated the unique ability to shape a research concept to fit the
goals and interests  of  not  only  NSP,  but  also  of the electric utility industry as a whole. 
This perception and foresight, as well as the level of personal dedication to research
programs, distinguished Aas as the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center's second
Energy Champion Award.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"> <h3><b>1st Champion - U.S. Senator Mark Andrews</b></h3>
</font> <p>

<p>

Former U.S. Senator Mark Andrews, a member of the Appropriations Committee and a
strong supporter of fossil energy programs and the federal coal research program, was an
extremely deserving recipient of the first Energy <p>

<p>

Champion Award.  Former Senator Andrews was very involved with several areas at the
EERC, including the jet fuel study and the chemcoal project, and he provided generous
support for transitional funding during the Center's defederalization process through his work
on the Appropriations Committee.<p>

<p>

The Senator's strong belief that the federal coal research program would provide long-term
benefits to the American consumer as the result of more efficient utilization of coal, reduced
environmental impacts, and availability of substitutes for expensive oil and gas was very
apparent in his ongoing support, and the EERC recognized his achievements and foresight as
setting outstanding precedents for the first Energy Champion.
<hr>
