<head>
<title>Environmental Management Program</title>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center>
<h1>Environmental Management Program</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>  Background</h2>
<p>
     At numerous locations across the nation, the <a href="http://www.doe.gov">U.S. Department of Energy</a> (DOE) is
facing the monumental task of cleaning up environmental contamination at nuclear
weapons facilities and other sites, a process that has been estimated to take 30 years and
cost hundreds of billions of dollars.  The <a href="http://www.eerc.und.nodak.edu">EERC</a> is an active partner in DOE's
Environmental Restoration and Waste Management Program, which is aimed at
demonstrating and commercializing new technologies to characterize and clean up these
sites.  The EERC's Environmental Management (EM) program is working to
commercialize new cleanup technologies in two ways: 1) through research,
development, and demonstration of our own technologies, leading to partnerships with
the private sector in commercialization and 2) by providing the private sector
(especially small businesses) with the expertise and technical resources needed to take
their technologies to the marketplace.<p>
<p>
     Critical to this effort is the need to accelerate the commercial development of new
technologies.  The EM Program at the EERC is designed to assist the private sector in
advancing faster, safer, and cheaper analytical techniques and environmental cleanup
technologies toward demonstration and full commercial application.  Working in
cooperation with DOE's Morgantown Energy Technology Center (METC), the EERC
provides technical support and serves as a broker in arranging and implementing jointly
sponsored research projects.  With capabilities in waste characterization, processing,
containment, site remediation, extraction, vitrification, pyrolysis, and plasma
remediation, as well as access to field sites where applicable cleanup technologies can
be demonstrated, the EERC is particularly well equipped to assist small business with
technical and logistical support in the development and commercialization of their
innovative environmental management technologies.<p>
<p>
<h2> Program Goals</h2>
<p>
<ul plain> 
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Commercializing innovative, cost-effective analytical and cleanup technologies in
a timely manner.<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Establishing partnerships with small businesses to provide coordination and
technical support in the smooth transition from research to commercialization.<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Seeking guidance from clients and other EM stakeholders to merge science and
technology development.  
</ul><p>
<h2> Activities</h2
<p>
<ul >
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Inventory existing environmental management technologies<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Identify promising new processes and products<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Build teams to leverage scientific and technological assets<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Perform research, development, and demonstration leading to new cleanup
technologies<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Establish partnerships to serve small businesses<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Coordinate the arrangement of demonstration sites<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Negotiate patent and data rights to encourage commercialization<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Team with the private sector to commercially implement promising
technologies<p>
</ul>
<p>
<h2> Current Contract Activities</H2>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Extraction and Analysis of Pollutant Organics from Contaminated Solids Using
Off-Line Supercritical Fluid Extraction and On-Line SFE/IR - The EERC is evaluating and demonstrating
simple-to-operate field instrumentation and extraction methods capable of rapidly extracting organic
contaminants at parts per million  to parts per billion levels. 
<p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Pyrolysis of Plastic Waste - The EERC is developing a commercial process to
reduce the volume of low-level radioactive mixed-plastics/paper/resin waste that will depolymerize a variety of
bulk plastic materials to produce crude oil-type liquids and separable solid wastes.
<p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Stabilization of Vitrified Waste by Enhanced Crystallization and Development of a
Protocol to Predict Long-Term Stability - The EERC is developing enhanced vitrification methods based on the
incorporation of toxic metals and radionuclides into crystallized phases that are environmentally stable under
disposal conditions over long periods of time.  Stability will be established based on the known geochemical
properties of mineral phases in nature and the EERC-developed synthetic groundwater leaching procedure  
(SGLP) and long-term leaching (LTL) procedure.
<p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Extraction of Hazardous Metals from Mixed Solid Wastes by Chelation and
Supercritical Fluid Extraction - The EERC is proposing to use chelation of hazardous metals and extraction by
supercritical CO<sub>2</sub> in suitable combinations to separate various hazardous metals sequentially
from mixed wastes.
<p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Subcritical Water Extraction of Organic Pollutants - The EERC is proposing to
demonstrate subcritical water extraction at low pressure and moderate temperatures of 200&#176; to
300&#176; C to be a rapid, low-cost method for selectively separating organic pollutants from wastes.  <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Demonstration of a Low-Temperature Plasma Remediation Technology - The
EERC's patent-pending plasma remediation technology will be demonstrated as a field-transportable,
low-temperature alternative to incineration for oxidative destruction of organic contaminants in soil without
producing problematic volatile by-products.  <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Centrifugal Membrane Filtration - The EERC is involved in a partnership with
Spintek, a small business with anovel centrifugal membrane filtration technology.  This project will demonstrate
the application of the Spintek technology in the remediation of liquid mixed-waste streams at DOE facilities. 
The technology is a uniquely configured process that combines ultrafiltration and centrifugal force to separate
suspended and dissolved solids from liquid waste streams, producing a filtered water stream and a
low-volume concentrate stream. Potential applications for the technology include remediation of groundwater
contaminant plumes and treatment of contaminated process waters from decontamination and
decommissioning activities.  </ul>
<p>
<h2>Future Direction</h2>
<p>
     The EERC will continue to advance joint initiatives with small business entities under
the EM program, with the objective of developing high-payoff technologies to manage
DOE-generated wastes faster, safer, and cheaper than currently available environmental
cleanup technologies.  The development of technologies for the safe and efficient
cleanup of mixed wastes will have a broad application worldwide.  New cleanup
technologies are a critical component of our expanding international opportunities.
<br>
<hr><a href="title.htm">Back to Home Page</a>

