<head>
<title>American Indian Initiative</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center>
<h1>Native American Initiative</h1></center>
<hr>
<p>
   The EERC is enhancing a longstanding University of North Dakota (UND) commitment to American Indians
through a program focused on responding to energy and environmental needs on Indian lands. Traditional
UND efforts include a nationally acclaimed "Indians into Medicine" (INMED) program, which has matriculated
20% of all Native American physicians practicing in our nation today.  UND's Center for Teaching and Learning
has prepared teachers and educational administrators for schools on reservations throughout the nation for
more than two decades.  Other established UND programs focus on recruiting and graduating Indians in the
fields of communications, psychology, nursing, and law.  The EERC recognizes the need to increase Native American
 enrollments in energy and environmental disciplines to broaden their employment opportunities.  The
EERC is responding to newly emerging energy and environmental needs in partnership with a growing
network, including tribal governments, American Indian-owned businesses, the Council of Energy Resource
Tribes (CERT), tribal colleges, and the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE).  Specific relationships include the
following:<p> 
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> <b>Alaskan Remote-Site Initiative</b> A
considerable percentage of Alaska's Native population is located in remote villages.  Heat and electricity for
residential and commercial energy needs in remote villages are often supplied by diesel engines powered by
diesel oil imported from the lower 48 states.  Because of the long distances that the fuel must be shipped, the
means of transport, the fuel storage requirements in harsh environments and the cost of installing power
equipment in these remote environments, the cost of energy in these communities is among the highest in the
United States.  In addition, the use and storage of diesel fuel creates environmental problems that Alaskan
residents would like to mitigate.  DOE's Morgantown Energy Technology Center (METC) and the EERC have
been working in partnership with Alaskan Native and state officials for several years to introduce technology
concepts to Alaska and create the atmosphere for the introduction of new technologies in the villages. 
Projects have progressed to demonstrate these small, easy-to-operate-and-maintain, environmentally friendly,
economically acceptable technologies using indigenous fuels and waste materials to produce electricity and
heat.  The lessons learned to date in Alaska are transferable to Hawaiian Native and Native American
communities throughout the United States and into international markets. <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"><b>The Devils Lake Sioux Tribe </b> , Fort
Totten, North Dakota, has contracted with the EERC to evaluate the environmental impact of the tribal
municipal landfill, wastewater treatment lagoons, and groundwater in the area of tribal water supply wells.
This project is providing information regarding potential environmental problems with respect to short- and
long-term tribal environmental goals. <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"><b> The Turtle Mountain Chippewa Tribe </b>
(TMCT) in partnership with the EERC has been awarded $248,000 from DOE's National Renewable Energy
Laboratory to demonstrate the production of electricity from wind on the Turtle Mountain Reservation. The
TMCT-EERC team will conduct an environmental impact assessment, identify the optimal wind energy sites, and
install and operate a Zond System wind turbine to produce power for tribal industry. <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"><b> Universal Technologies Corporation</b> 
(UTC), a 100% Native American-owned and - controlled environmental consulting firm located in Powell,
Wyoming, and the EERC have signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) under which both parties offer
services relevant to a wide range of Native American issues, including resource characterization, energy
conversion, site assessment, groundwater geology, waste management, contaminant remediation, education,
training, environmental justice, and environmental enforcement.  <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> <b>Council of Energy Resource Tribes  </b>, an
organization of 53 federally recognized Indian tribes and four Canadian Indian nations, and the EERC have
developed an MOU focused on addressing energy and environmental management needs on Indian lands.  An
official signing ceremony is being scheduled for the near future.  This MOU enables CERT, members of CERT,
and the EERC to work together on specific research, development, demonstration, and commercialization
projects focused on resource assessment, energy conversion technology, reclamation of disturbed lands,
waste management, site cleanup, contaminant remediation technology, and training. <p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"><b>Standing Rock College, </b> Fort Yates,
North Dakota, CERT, and the EERC have signed an MOU under which the team has submitted a proposal to the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Environmental Justice Community/University Partnership Grants
Program. The proposed program is designed to articulate the Indian principles of environmental justice and to
translate those principles into education and training curricula that can guide Native Americans in the
planning, development, and implementation of environmental protection programs that comport with those
principles.<p>

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"><b> Little Hoop Community College </b>, located
on the Fort Totten Indian Reservation, in partnership with the EERC, has submitted a proposal to the EPA
Environmental Justice program that focuses on identifying environmental justice issues on the Fort Totten
Indian Reservation, identifying a community action team, training the community action team in waste
management and water resource issues, and conducting community workshops on the reservation. <p> 

<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The EERC, in cooperation with the UND Foundation,
UND Office of Native American Programs, UND Office of Enrollment Services, Turtle
Mountain Community College, Little Hoop Community College, and UTC, has designed
an education and training program focused on energy and environmental needs on Indian
lands. The intended product is to recruit Native American professionals at the associate
and bachelor levels to participate in a specially tailored curriculum combined with
on-the-job training and field experience relevant to problems on Indian lands.
</ul>
<hr>
<a href="title.htm">Back to Home Page</a>

