<head>
<title>Energy and Environmental Issues Assessment</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Energy and Environmental Issues Assessment</h2>
<hr><h3>Background</h3> 
Energy industry decisions on resources, utilization technologies, and emission prevention and
control measures are made in reference to changing patterns of fuel cost and availability,
emerging technological choices, externality impacts, and government policies, statutes, and
regulations.  Research related to energy and the environment must be performed with an
awareness of the forces that shape these future trends and should anticipate needs in order to
compensate for developmental lead time.  <p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

The purpose of this activity was to understand the potentialities, limitations, and status of
competing energy technologies in terms of scientific basis, state of development, technical
barriers, cost, efficiency, policy treatment, and environmental performance in order to support
research program development.  Activities included critical literature surveys, surveys and
assessments of active research programs and information sources, comparative data
compilation, interpretive calculations, and tracking of regulatory, policy, and technical issues.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
<ul plain>
<img src="gifs/bl_dot.gif"> A report entitled "Energy and Environmental Profile for Selected
East-Central
European Nations" was prepared which provides an overview of energy and the
environment issues in the Czech and Slovak Republics, Hungary, Poland, and Bulgaria. 
The report features a table, organized by subject and country and current through 1992,
that presents summary information on economics, energy consumption, environmental
priorities, energy resources, production and utilization, electrical generation and
transmission, district heating, briquettes, and environmental regulations.  The report
will be available in the summer of 1995 in the proceedings of the "Energy and
Environment:  Transitions in East Central Europe" conference held in the fall of 1994
in Prague, Czech Republic.
<p>

<img src="gifs/bl_dot.gif"> A review of North Dakota energy issues was presented at the State of
the State
Economic Conference on January 25, 1995, in Bismarck, North Dakota.
<p>

<img src="gifs/bl_dot.gif"> A review was prepared of process design and cost projections for an
Alaskan
Low-
Rank Coal-Water Fuel  demonstration project with regard to possible use of the slurry
fuel in integrated gasification combined-cycle (IGCC) and coal-fired diesel facilities
under the U.S. Department of Energy Clean Coal Technology Demonstration program.
<p>

<img src="gifs/bl_dot.gif"> Updating and testing of a generalized iterative spreadsheet were
performed in
order to evaluate changes in IGCC and pressurized fluidized-bed combustion  performance in
reference to variations in coal moisture, ash, and sulfur contents.  The spreadsheet was originally
developed
for performing heat and material balances based on enthalpy correlations for coal, ash, and twenty
reactant
and product species.
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Daniel J. Daly<br>
<b>E-mail Address:</b> <a href=mailto:ddaly@eerc.und.nodak.edu>ddaly@eerc.und.nodak.edu
</a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>   (701) 777-2822<br>
<b> Sponsor: </b>U.S. Department of Energy  Morgantown Energy
Technology  Center<br>
 <b> Duration of Project </b> :  March 1994 to March 1995<br>
