<html>
<head>
<title>Bulgarian Clean Coal </title>
</head>

<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Bulgarian Clean Coal Utilization Technology Assessment </h2>
<hr>
<h3>Background </h3>
     The nations of East Central Europe regained their political and economic freedom in 1989,
ending nearly half a century of centrally planned economies under the hegemony of the
former Soviet Union.  These nations are now emerging from economic conditions marked
by price distortions, a focus on heavy industry, isolation from world markets, and a lack of
occupational health and environmental safeguards.  Economic recovery, environmental
restoration, and political stability, as well as eventual entrance into the European
Community, require a reordering of policies and priorities, including those bearing on
energy and environment.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>

     Focusing on these needs, the EERC led a project funded by the U.S. Department of
Energy (DOE).  The primary goal of this project was to introduce the Bulgarian energy
sector to technologies required to make better use of their indigenous lignite for least-cost
electric power generation and briquette production, while reducing emissions.  Specific
objectives were to help evaluate the clean coal technology options for Bobov Dol, Sofia,
and Maritsa East lignite-based power generation and domestic heating fuel production and
to facilitate the transfer of U.S. technologies to meet Bulgaria's needs for power
generation, domestic solid fuel, and reduced emissions at minimum cost.  The emphasis of
this work was on identifying opportunities for integrating near-term options into the long-term
development of
Bulgaria's lignite resources.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The EERC worked in close cooperation with the Bulgarian energy firms Energoproekt
and TOTEMA.  Their assistance was essential in identifying the needs of the Bulgarian
power industry, assessing the current conditions of equipment and fuel in Bulgaria, and
selecting and prioritizing the final technological areas for the investigations.  The most
urgent problems facing the Bulgarian energy sector are the low reliability and availability
of their thermal power plants, stemming from age, poor boiler maintenance, low-quality
coal, and interruption of coal supply.  Other major issues are high emissions of SO<sub>2</sub>,
NO<sub>x</sub>, and particulates and how to bring plants into compliance with environmental
standards at
reasonable costs.<p>

     The steps taken in evaluating these problems and formulating recommendations included
1) reviewing the current condition of power plant equipment and characteristics of the
fuels, 2) evaluating potential remedial options, 3) selecting and contacting vendors, 4)
developing a technology options handbook, and 5) hosting a workshop to introduce
representatives of the Bulgarian power sector to U.S. vendors.  The technological areas
considered, listed in the priority order determined by the Bulgarian energy firms, are as
follows:<p>


<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Particulate control<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Rehabilitation and life extension of existing units<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Fuel switching<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Advanced power systems<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Retrofit with circulating fluidized-bed combustors<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Flue gas desulfurization<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Coal beneficiation<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> NO<sub>x</sub> control<br>
</ul>
<p>

     The project culminated in a "Technology Options Handbook," which provides a matrix of
methods and problems relating to each of the technical areas studied.  Each method is
specifically discussed as it relates to Bulgarian lignites, with the focus being the Maritsa East
mine, which is the only low-cost source of indigenous Bulgarian coal.  Those clean coal
technologies that best meet the needs of the Bulgarians were identified.  Additionally, the
investigation deliberately avoided all-or-nothing approaches to meeting environmental
regulations, which reject technologies offering less than the approximately 98% sulfur removal
efficiency required to meet international standards.  Cost-benefit analysis was performed using
ICECAP, an integrated coal evaluation, cost, and performance model developed by DOE.<p>

     In addition to the technical evaluation provided by the EERC in the handbook, appendices
containing vendor qualifications, technical information, and points of contact are supplied.  The
intent of these appendices is to provide the Bulgarians with a "buyer's guide" to U.S.
technologies.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>  Michael L. Jones<br>
<b> E-mail Address: </b>  <a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>
mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>  Phone: </b>  (701) 777-5130<br>
<b> Sponsor: </b>   U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b> Duration of Project: </b>  October 1993 to June 1995<br>
