<html>
<head>
<title>Polish Power Industry Least-Cost Analysis for Power
Plant Upgrade</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Polish Power Industry Least-Cost Analysis for Power
Plant Upgrade</h2><hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     Ninety-five percent of Polish electricity production is from coal--hard coal and brown
coal.  Seventy-five percent of all energy consumption is from coal.  Unfortunately,
very few plants have desulfurization and NOx reduction technology, which contributes
to make Poland one of the most polluted countries in Europe.  A major contributor to
the pollution is the 32 GW of inefficient, aging power plants typically found in the
major population centers of Poland.  About 135 TWh of electricity was produced in
1991, along with 248 PJ of heat. <p>

     Recently, the Polish Ministry of Environmental Protection issued a set of national
emission standards that will be effective January 1, 1998.  Plants that exceed the
standards will have fines levied against them.  Consequently, Polish power stations
need extensive upgrading to meet these forthcoming standards.  Such upgrading
includes life extension of existing plants, improved availability of power, increased
efficiency, and pollution control.<p>

     Poland is currently evaluating the process it uses to produce, deliver, and set prices for
electricity.  A critical step in the evaluation process is the development and adoption of
analytical tools to conduct a "multivariant feasibility investigation" of Polish power
plants to provide a common basis for estimating the technical, environmental, and
economic performance or modifications needed to extend the life of aging power
plants, increase efficiency, and control emissions.  This is especially necessary so that
the Polish power plant industry can become an informed customer by establishing its
own requirements and deal effectively with the multitude of vendors of plant-upgrading
services and air pollution control equipment.<p>

<h3>Objective</h3>

     The objective of this work was to assist the government of Poland by undertaking a
cost-shared project to select, test, and adopt personal computer (PC)-based analytical
tools that can be used by Polish power plants to conduct the multivariant feasibility
studies needed to define cost-effective approaches to upgrade power plants and bring
them into compliance with 1988 emission standards.<p>
 <h3>Results</h3>

     The EERC participated in a one-day briefing of Polish power station personnel in
Warsaw, Poland.  Based on feedback from this visit, a site-specific feasibility study on
upgrade options was performed on a power plant selected by the Polish Power Institute
(PPI).  The EERC worked with PPI to make the final selection of technical options and
site information that made up the input for this study.  The EERC worked with PPI to
apply analytical models to evaluate the cost and performance of a series of upgrade
options.  The results of the model analysis and related information on the technical
options analyzed by the EERC and PPI were integrated by PPI into a comprehensive
written report on the feasibility study, including recommendations for implementing the
study findings.  The cost-benefit analysis was performed using ICECAP, an integrated
coal evaluation, cost, and performance model developed by the U.S. Department of
Energy.<p>
<hr> 
<b> Project Manager:</b>  Michael L. Jones <br>
<b>E-mail Address: </b>   <a
href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5130<br>
<b> Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b> Duration of Project: </b>February 1994 to April 1995 <br>
