<head>
<title>Technology Information Exchange - Commingling</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center>
<h1>Technology Information Exchange - Commingling</h1> 
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Commingling with respect to gasoline is the art of mixing two or more fuels in an automobile fuel
tank.  This is recognized as a potential cause of increased emissions of volatile organic compounds
(VOC).  Concern over commingling could result in a reduction of ethanol usage in reformulated
gasoline (RFG), since most of the attention on commingling is directed toward mixing ethanol and
nonethanol RFGs.  Because of the interest of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, oil
companies, and ethanol producers, scientific dialogue is mounting.  The controversy surrounding the
issue is largely based on scarce scientific data.  Most discussion centers on ethanol-gasoline blends
and their effect when added to partially filled automobile fuel tanks.  Because of the controversial
nature of the topic and the opposing views of the vested interests, it is important that the current state
of the technology be known and available to interested parties.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives of this project were to serve as an information source on the
subject of commingling and to facilitate communications on the subject
between the Renewable Fuels Association (RFA) and government and private
organizations with concerns over the issue.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     During 1993, the ethanol industry was faced with two major concerns in its
efforts to keep a share of the fuels market.  The first was the vapor pressure
increase resulting from blending gasoline and ethanol to get E10, which
received most of the public attention.  The second concern, commingling,
received less publicity although some interests believed it was no less
important.  The lower profile of this issue was, in large part, due to a lack of
sufficient hard scientific data.  Although related to the blending issue, there
was disagreement on the magnitude of the problem relative to blending.  The
RFA required up-to-the-minute information on the political status of E10 as
well as the most current technical information on the tank mixing of different
gasolines.  To accommodate its needs, the EERC performed detailed searches
of literature and government publications, attended national meetings
concerning ethanol, and kept abreast of current developments through the
news media and through contact with key individuals on both sides of the
ethanol issue.  The information was compiled and forwarded to the RFA
routinely and on a demand basis.  This information enabled RFA to effectively
plan strategies and promote the continued use of ethanol as an oxygenate in
gasoline.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b> Project Manager:</b> Ronald C. Timpe/<a href=mailto:rtimpe@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rtimpe@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5219<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>Renewable Fuels Association<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>July 1993 to February 1994
