<head>
<title>Barriers to the Increased Utilization of Coal
Combustion/Desulfuization By-Products by
Government and Commercial Sectors</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>
Barriers to the Increased Utilization of Coal Combustion/Desulfuization By-Products by
Government and
Commercial Sectors
</h2>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Increasing costs and regulation of solid waste disposal are making ash disposal an undesirable
option. 
For this reason, Section 1334 of the Energy Act of 1992 charged the Secretary of Energy to
"conduct
a detailed and comprehensive survey on the institutional, legal, and regulatory barriers to
increased
utilization of coal combustion by-products by potential governmental and commercial users."<p>

     The EERC has performed numerous research projects that provide information to aid our
understanding of the technical and political issues related to increased coal by-product utilization. 
This program was conducted in support of the U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy
Technology Center (DOE METC) efforts to produce a report to Congress containing a detailed
survey
of the institutional, legal, and regulatory barriers to increased utilization of coal combustion
by-products and
recommendations for action to be taken to increase the utilization of coal combustion
by-products.<p>

<h3>Objectives</h3>

     The overall objective of this project was to prepare a report for METC
summarizing the issues associated with the utilization of coal combustion by-products.  In order
to meet the
objective of this project, input from several
governmental and private agencies involved with coal by-product utilization
was solicited.  Data pertinent to the project goals were collected and
commented on by experts in the field of coal by-product utilization.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The information compiled by the EERC originated from the following sources: 
1) previous works in the literature to assess the current state of understanding
and to identify information gaps, 2) identification of the government agencies
and private concerns involved with coal by-product utilization, 3) personal
interviews to fill knowledge gaps and to assess issues of primary concern, 4)
two open forums designed to solicit input from industry, and 5) input from a
workshop designed to facilitate comments on the draft version of reports by
government and industry experts and to assist in shaping recommendations.<p>

     The EERC assessed of the current state of ash utilization in the United States. 
The investigation found that the nearly 90 million tons of coal combustion
by-products produced annually in the United States is a valuable national
resource that is vastly underutilized.  Current use of about 30% of the coal ash
and only 2% of the flue gas desulfurization products represents a failed
opportunity when compared to the utilization potential in the United States
and the nearly complete utilization already achieved in some western European
countries.  Future opportunities can be seized by concerted action to offer
substantial benefits to the nation's electric generation, construction, and
manufacturing industries, to agriculture, and to the environment, whereas
failure to act will create literally mountains of solid waste, an unnecessary
legacy of future energy production.<p>

     The investigation concluded that because of the profound economic and
environmental benefits of increased coal by-product utilization, it is critical
that we adopt by-product utilization as a key element of rebuilding our
national <b></b>energy infrastructure.  Actions must be taken now in order to remove
many of the regulatory, legal, and technical barriers to increased by-product
use.  Swift, decisive action is needed in order to ensure that we derive the
maximum environmental and economic advantages afforded by efficient by-product utilization. 
Although the
need for federal leadership in this area is
clear, an equal commitment is needed from state and local governments as well
as the industrial sector.  Partnerships with industry and state agencies are
necessary to ensure that appropriate regulations and specifications are used and
to ensure the commercial viability of new technologies and strategies developed
for by-product use.  Although a myriad of activities aimed towards increasing
by-product use is presently under way, a distinct lack of coordination of these
efforts exists within both the public and private sectors.  A coordinated team
effort is needed to achieve by-product utilization goals; this effort must be
championed by the federal government, with a single agency charged with the
responsibility of leading the effort and coordinating the activities of the
participants.<p>
<hr>
<b> Project Manager:</b>  Edward N. Steadman<br>
<b>E-mail Address: </b>   <a
href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: <b>(701) 777-5157<br>
<b> Sponsor: </b> U.S. Department of Energy  Morgantown Energy Technology 
Center <br>
 <b> Duration of Project: </b>June 1993 to January 1994<br>
