<head>
<title>Natural Gas Industry Chemicals</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>A Review of Issues Related to the Subsurface Occurance of Selected Natural Gas Industry Chemicals
</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<p>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Subsurface contamination by volatile aromatic hydrocarbons has been the focus of
characterization and remediation activities at natural gas processing plants for some
time; however, subsurface contamination related to process chemicals such as glycols
and alkanolamines and process waste components such as organosulfur compounds has
only recently become the subject of significant concern and some attention.  In an
effort to aid both the natural gas industry and regulators in responding appropriately to
this growing concern, Dr. John Headley of the National Hydrology Research Institute
in Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, with funding from the Canadian Panel for Energy
Research and Development and the cooperation of the Canadian natural gas industry,
recently initiated a long-term research program to investigate analytical and transport
and fate issues related to subsurface contaminants other than volatile aromatic
hydrocarbons at Canadian natural gas processing plants.<p>
<p>
     In response to an invitation from Dr. Headley, the EERC has undertaken the task of
acquiring, evaluating, and synthesizing presently available information and data of use
to him in investigating some of the chemicals of interest, as well as to those involved in
assessing and mitigating subsurface contamination related to the same chemicals.  The
chemicals of interest include glycols and alkanolamines that are commonly used by the
natural gas industry and selected organosulfur compounds that result from industry
activities.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The objective of this project is to provide natural gas industry personnel,
researchers, and others with a summary of available information and data that
may be of use in addressing subsurface contamination issues involving selected
alkanolamines, glycols, and organosulfur compounds commonly associated with
industry activities. <p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Information and data from approximately 250 published and unpublished
documents and more than 50 personal contacts with experts in industry,
academics, and the government have been used to produce a draft document
that includes up-to-date summaries of those aspects of the alkanolamines and
glycols of interest that bear on their role as potential subsurface contaminants. 
Specifically, the document focuses on the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Use by the natural gas industry<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Potential sources and mechanisms of subsurface contamination<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Physical and chemical properties and their environmental implications<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Regulations and guidelines in the United States and Canada, both on the
national level and in selected states and provinces that are important in terms
of natural gas industry activity<br>
     <p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Subsurface transport and fate, with an emphasis on the controlling
processes<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Toxicological characteristics <br>
</ul>
<p>
     This draft document, which will be available for widespread distribution upon
completion, also includes recommendations for further research that holds
particular promise for helping to address subsurface contamination issues
related to the alkanolamines and glycols of interest.<p>
<p>
     Initially, similar information and data specific to the selected organosulfur
compounds were to have been included in the preceding document.  However,
only a very limited amount of work has been focused on these compounds,
thus producing significantly less that is of use in this context.  What is
available is being provided under separate cover to the funding entities for
their use and will not likely receive wider distribution.<p>

<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Craig R. Schmit
/<a href=mailto:cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu>cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b> Phone:</b> (701) 777-5259 <br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Gas Research Institute
<li>National Hydrology Research Institute
(under contract to the Canadian Panel for Energy Research and
Development)
<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b><li>January 1994 to June 1995
