<head>
<title>Stratigraphic Evaluation of North Dakota Lignite</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center><h2>Stratigraphic Evaluation of North Dakota Lignite</h2>

</center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     As a component of the National Coal Resources Data System (NCRDS) program, this
project is designed to provide coal data to aid in the accurate determination of coal
resources in the United States.  The projected coal reserves of North Dakota are vast
and thus contribute significantly to estimates of coal availability.  Most of North
Dakota's coal-bearing strata have received some investigation, although the level of
detail and usefulness varies considerably.  Previous regional coal studies were
conducted prior to the availability of large-scale U.S. Geological Survey (USGS)
topographic maps, limiting the value of many observations.  Studies on North Dakota's
lignite resources were carried out by A.G. Leonard and others of the North Dakota
Geological Survey and summarized in 1925.  This work was subsequently revised by
USGS resource evaluations by M.R. Campbell in 1929 and R.A. Brant in 1953.  The
later investigation remains the definitive work after more than 40 years.  The resource
estimates from these early surveys were, quite naturally highly speculative in that many
assumptions were made on coal bed correlation, lateral continuity of thickness, and
inferred location to expedite calculations.  In all studies after Leonard, who evaluated
North Dakota's coal resources almost single-handedly, resource evaluations were
generalized and did not consider the details of coal bed correlation.<p>
     North Dakota coal is exclusively lignite, which occurs predominantly in Paleocene
strata in the western half of the state.  Lignite beds are interbedded with unconsolidated
to semiconsolidated claystones, siltstones, and sandstones, along with a few isolated
limestones.  These strata were derived from a variety of freshwater and marginal
marine environments.  The Paleocene section in North Dakota is made up mainly of the
Fort Union Group (= Formation of USGS usage), which includes in ascending order
the following formations:  1) The nonmarine Ludlow Formation, representing the basal
Paleocene unit in North Dakota, which has, in some areas, a thick coal at its top; 2)
The nonmarine Slope Formation (= upper Ludlow of the USGS), which contains
several coal beds and intercalates with the marginal marine and marine Cannonball
Formation (locally, well-correlated coals are found subjacent to tongues of the
Cannonball in western North Dakota); 3) The nonmarine Bullion Creek Formation (=
Tongue River of others), which contains mined coals in its lower portion, but has coal
beds throughout its thickness; and 4) The Sentinel Butte Formation, which also contains
important mined coal beds in north-central North Dakota.  The Fort Union Group
attains a maximum thickness of 568 m (1879 ft) (Carlson, 1985) near the center of the
Williston Basin in western North Dakota.  The most extensive exposures of Fort Union
strata occur in the drainages of the Missouri and Little Missouri Rivers.  Thus most
sedimentological and coal stratigraphic studies and nomenclature have been derived
from surface-based research.  Regional coal correlation problems will, however, be
resolved from a knowledge of subsurface coal stratigraphy.<p>

<h3>Objective</h3>

     For the purposes of the NCRDS program, the objective of this research was to compile
and annotate previously reported lignite observations in southwestern North Dakota,
focusing specifically on Bowman County.<p>


<h3>Results</h3>

     To date, a total of 711 surface and subsurface observations have been recorded for
Bowman County.  Previous work for the NCRDS program by Craig Schmit (EERC)
reported on the unpublished location and lignite beds of 440 of the 586 subsurface
records currently documented.  The locations of all observations were evaluated on
USGS 7.5-minute (1:24,000) topographic maps and digitized.  Locations were digitized
using the geographic information system program Atlas GIS<sup>TM</sup> (by Strategic
Mapping,
Inc.).  Reference, location, and stratigraphic data were computerized and entered in
EERC databases.  Using the relational database management program Access&reg; (by
Microsoft Corporation), reference and location data are merged with the geologic
section descriptions (LNO and MNO databases, respectively) into forms designed in the
NCRDS format.  The accompanying NCRDS form for measured Section M7775
represents a coal section made in 1952 in what was then the north wall of the Peerless
mine (Kepferle, 1955; Location 93).  Kepferle (1955) identified the three lignite beds
in the section as the Harmon lignite, which Leonard (1925) identified as the Scranton. 
As noted, compilations that reevaluate and reinterpret previous observations establish
precedent for consistent nomenclatural usage.<p>

<h3>References</h3>
               Brant, R.A., 1953, Lignite resources of North Dakota:  U.S. Geological Survey,
Circular
226, 78 p.<br>
                         Campbell, M.R., 1929, Coal resources of the United States:  U.S.
Geological Survey, press release, 6 p.<br>
               Carlson, C.G., 1985, Geology of McKenzie County, North Dakota:  North Dakota
Geological Survey, Bulletin 80--Part I, 48 p.<br>
               Kepferle, R.K., 1955, Strippable lignite deposits, Slope and Bowman Counties, North
Dakota:  U.S. Geological Survey, Bulletin
1015-E, p. 123-182, pls. 14-20.<br>
               Leonard, A.G., 1925, Bowman and Slope Counties, <i>in</i> Leonard, A.G., Babcock,
E.J., and Dove, L.P., eds., The lignite deposits
of North Dakota:  North Dakota Geological Survey, Bulletin, v. 4, p. 58-77, 21 pls.
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b> Joseph H.  Hartman<br>
<b> E-mail Address: </b>   <a
href=mailto:jhartman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhartman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-2351<br>
<b> Sponsor: </b>U.S. Geological Survey<br>
<b> Duration of Project: </b> September 1993 to August 1994<br>
