<html>
<head>
<title>Red River Riparian Demonstration Project</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Red River Riparian Demonstration Project</h2> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2> 

     Riparian (streamside) wetland areas are valuable habitats and function to protect and enhance
water quality.  These ecosystems provide optimum food for stream communities and purify water by
removing sediments and non-point-source pollution.  <p>
<p>
     Riparian buffer strips will be restored at four research sites.  Restoration will include planting a
mixture of grasses and woody vegetation to decrease hydrologic sediment and nutrient inputs. 
Grazing will be restricted at some of the sites to promote vegetation growth and bank stabilization. 
Site monitoring will include a vegetation inventory and photo-point documentation to assess buffer
strip restoration during the project.  <p>
<p>
     Ground- and surface water interactions will be studied at two localities within one of the riparian
sites.  One area has been severely impacted by grazing, whereas the other exhibits a healthy,
undisturbed riparian ecosystem.  Fluxes of water, solutes, and fauna will characterize the
groundwater-stream water interface.  Meiofauna (stream invertebrates) will be identified and used as
bioindicators to determine community health at both riparian localities.<p>
   <p>
<h2>Objectives</h2> 
     The objectives of this research project are to identify and demonstrate Best
Management Practices (BMPs) by restoring riparian areas and subsequently
reducing non-point-source pollution and to transfer this technology to
producers and natural resource professionals throughout North Dakota.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2> 
     Riparian plantings are scheduled for the summer of 1995 at the four test sites. 
Instrumentation for the meiofauna investigation was initiated in May 1995.  Prior to
planting, sediment cores from this site were collected and described.  This information will
be used to assess the effects of riparian buffer strip restoration.<p>

<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Gale G. Mayer/<a href=mailto:gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5108<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
