<html>
<head>
<title>The Palenontology and Stratigraphy of the Uper
Cretaceous and Paleocene of the Mahajanga Basin,
Northwestern Madagascar</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center><h2> The Palenontology and Stratigraphy of the Upper Cretaceous and Paleocene of the
Mahajanga Basin,
Northwestern Madagascar </h2> 
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The origins of marsupial and placental mammals have not been well delineated by the
extensive research of paleontologists in the well-exposed strata of the Upper Cretaceous
of the Western Interior of North America and Mongolia.  Thus the hypothesis has been
put forward that the transition record from Early Cretaceous pantotheres to many
modern mammal groups took place during the Late Cretaceous on the Gondwanan
continents of Australia, India, Madagascar, Africa, South America, and/or Antarctica. 
The Late Cretaceous record of mammals from India includes a couple of teeth,
suggesting an affinity with Laurasian or northern hemisphere forms.  The relatively
rich South American record appears highly endemic, indicating isolation from
Laurasian faunas, and, therefore, not directly related to the major lines of mammalian
evolution.  No Late Cretaceous mammals were known from Africa, Australia,
Antarctica, or Madagascar.  Previous explorations in Madagascar by French and
Japanese paleontologists did not discover mammals, but other vertebrate fossils were
found in some abundance and diversity, suggesting, along with the record in India, that
mammals should or might be present.  In addition to these considerations, the diverse
and endemic subfossil and modern-day occurrence of lemurs in Madagascar strongly
indicates that these primates existed in Madagascar well before their oldest fossil record
of about 8000 years. <p>

<h3>Objectives</h3>

     This investigation of Malagasy fossils and strata was undertaken to discover
additional records of Late Cretaceous mammals in the southern hemisphere
and place these finds into a litho- and chronostratigraphic context.  <p>

<h3>Results</h3>
     As a result of support from a "Small Grant for Exploratory Research" from the National
Science Foundation, a 6-week expedition was undertaken to northwestern Madagascar. 
Previous work by Malagasy paleontologists and stratigraphers had indicated the existence
of Upper Cretaceous rocks of nonmarine origin in the Mahajanga (Majunga) Basin.  These
strata were interpreted by Besairie and Collignon (1972) as Campanian in age and that
they were overlain by marine strata of Maastrichtian (uppermost Cretaceous) and Danian
(Lower Paleocene) age.  Through the course of field studies near the village of Berivotra,
a single mammalian tooth was discovered in strata referred to as the Maevarano
Formation (part of the Campanian map unit of C<sup>8-6</sup> of the Majunga-Ambalakida
geologic
quadrangle, 1960, produced by the Service de G&eacute;ologique).  The discovery of this tooth
was announced by Dr. David W. Krause at the Fourth Congress of the European Society
of Evolution and Biology in Montpellier, France, at the annual meeting of the Society of
Vertebrate Paleontology in Albuquerque (Krause, 1993; Krause and others, 1993) and in
<i>Nature</i> (Krause and others, 1994).  In addition to the surface-picked mammal tooth, bulk
samples, representing the screened concentrate from approximately 20 m<sup>3</sup> of
sediment,
were taken at three localities.  Individual Cretaceous mammal teeth are very small (1 to 2
mm) and are typically discovered through the examination of sediment with the use of a
microscope.  Bulk samples will hopefully contain additional evidence of Late Cretaceous
mammals in Madagascar.<p>

     Besides the oldest record of mammals in Madagascar by 70 million years, the crew also
discovered about 100 fossil localities that yielded many important nonmammalian
vertebrates and invertebrates.  Significant vertebrate finds include the collection of bony
fishes, sharks, rays, frogs, turtles, snakes, lizards, mesosuchian and eosuchian crocodiles,
and theropod and sauropod dinosaurs.  Besides the additions to the described vertebrate
fauna of the Campanian Marovoay and Maevarano Formations, many of the specimens
collected in 1993 represent the only existing specimens for a number of taxa.  Many of the
smaller specimens reposited in Madagascar by the French and Japanese are lost through
inadequate collection management.<p>

     In addition to the vertebrates, a number of invertebrate specimens were collected.  From
the beds of the Maevarano Formation, the first record of bivalved arthropods, known as
conchostracans, and nonmarine bivalves and snails were discovered.  Marine invertebrates
were found in some abundance in the overlying strata of the Berivotra Formation and
overlying unnamed map unit assigned to the Danian.  Collections are dominated by
mollusks, including neogastropod snails, gryphaeid, ostreid, and other bivalves, and
ammonite cephalopods.  Collections also include a number of echinoderms, represented
mostly by echinoids.<p>

     Fossil localities where located using a global positioning system (GPS).  In addition to
these observations, a number of GPS fixes were taken on formational contacts, photo
locations, and cultural features, such as kilometer posts, survey markers, and bridges. 
With satellite reception being generally available without difficulty, GPS technology
proved an invaluable tool for the location data gathering.  This information was imported
into geographic information system (GIS) programming (Atlas GIS<sup>TM</sup> by Strategic
Mapping, Inc.) to construct and revise previously published maps.<p>

     Field studies also resulted in an initial revision of the lithostratigraphy in the Berivotra
area.  Formational boundaries and nomenclature were reevaluated through the course of
the placement of fossil localities relative to formational contacts.  This effort will lead to
the determination of possible formational stratotypes to reform the admixture of
lithostratigraphic and geochronologic units traditionally employed in the Malagasy
literature (i.e., time or time-rock units used as map units in a vague formational
connotation).  As a result of 1993 collections,  studies are also under way that assess the
specific age of the Upper Cretaceous strata.  Vertebrate and invertebrate fossils from the
Marovoay and Maevarano Formations are being studied to compare them to faunas
elsewhere to directly interpret the age of the enclosing strata.  Fossils from the overlying
marine Berivotra Formation will be used to place a "youngest" age on the underlying
nonmarine strata.  Rock samples taken through the Berivotra Formation are being
analyzed for their paleomagnetic signature.  The resulting reversal stratigraphy will be
correlated with the global marine standards to provide an additional means to date the
nonmarine and marine sequence.<p>
<h3>References</h3>

               <b>Besairie, Henri, and Collignon, Maurice</b>, 1972, G&eacute;ologie de
Madagascar.  I. 
Les Terrains S&eacute;dimentaries:  Annales G&eacute;ologiques de
Madagascar, Fascicule no. 35, 463 p., 89 pls.<p>

               <b>Krause, D.W.</b>, 1993, The biogeographic origins of the modern orders of
mammals: 
Did the Indian subcontinent and Madagascar play a
role?:  Fourth Congress of the European Society for Evolutionary Biology (Montpellier, France),
p. 237.<p>

               <b>Krause, D.W., Hartman, J.H., Wells N.A., Buckley, G.A., Lockwood, C.A., Wall,
C.W.,
Wunderlich, R.E., Rabarison, J.A., and
Randriamiaramanana, L.L.</b>, 1993, Late Cretaceous vertebrates from Madagascar:  Society of
Vertebrate
Paleontology, Annual
Meeting, Albuquerque, New Mexico.<p>

               <b>Krause, D.W., Hartman, J.H., Wells, N.A., Buckley, G.A., Lockwood, C.A., Wall,
C.E.,
Wunderlich, R.E., Rabarison, J.A., and
Randriamiaramanana, L.L.</b>, 1994, Late Cretaceous mammals [from Madagascar]:  Nature, v.
368, p. 298.<br>
