<html>
<head>
<title>Timing of the Deposition of Uppermost Cretaceous
and Paleocene Coal-Bearing Deposits in the Greater
Glendive Area, Montana and North Dakota</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Timing of the Deposition of Uppermost Cretaceous and Paleocene Coal-Bearing Deposits in
the Greater
Glendive Area, Montana and North Dakota </h2>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Changes in paleoclimate and paleofloral patterns and past land and water configurations
produced both temporally and paleogeographically different coal depositional histories. 
The effective and efficient utilization of coal resources depends on accurate
characterization, which is best accomplished with a knowledge of a coal's geologic
setting.  To date, coal analysis and coal resource assessments have only rudimentarily
considered the temporal context of coal deposits from one coal-producing region to
another, thus significantly limiting our ability to interpret the regional geologic and
paleoenvironmental settings of coal occurrence.  In addition, coal composition and
quality are documented largely as analytical results without reference to their
stratigraphic correlation or paleoenvironmental significance.  Without temporal and
geologic context, coal sample characterizations have been treated as isolated
observations, which are generally incapable of providing information that can lead to
the determination of regional trends in coal distribution, geochemistry, preservation,
and thickness.  Expensive drilling programs provide valuable coal correlation data, but
provide no understanding of the timing of coal deposition.  Without temporal control,
the correlation and characterization of coal-forming environments may erroneously
compare coals originating at different times, which will necessarily result in inaccurate
resource interpretations.  Presently, an understanding of trends in coal quality is made
almost impossible by the absence of temporal and paleoenvironmental context for
many, if not most, coal sample observations in the Fort Union Coal Region (Hartman,
1992).<p>
     This jointly sponsored research program supports a number of activities that directly
bear on providing a more thorough understanding about the timing of sedimentation
through the transition from the Cretaceous to Tertiary (K/T) periods.  This time
boundary is well known to the scientific community and general public because of its
association with the extinction of the dinosaurs (and many other plant and animal
groups) and possible bolide (large meteor) impact(s).  The transition from Cretaceous
to Tertiary strata is also coincident with the onset of extensive coal-forming
paleoenvironments in many areas in the northern plains.  In the Glendive area, the
sequence of formations exposed along the Yellowstone River and its tributaries are (in
ascending order) the Fox Hills, Hell Creek, Ludlow, Slope, and Tongue River
Formations.  In this area, the K/T boundary is relatively accurately marked by a bed,
known as the contact coal, occurring at the contact between the Hell Creek and
overlying Ludlow Formations.  A working "field" definition to stratigraphically locate
the beginning of the Tertiary has been based on determining the occurrence of the
lowest, laterally persistent coal bed occurring above the highest dinosaur fossils. 
Present studies indicate this field method works well in the Glendive area.  Current
geological practice delimits the K/T boundary on the presence and absence of certain
palynomorphs in conjunction, where possible, with an anomalously high concentration
of iridium.  Even with these criteria and the generally well-marked lithic differences
between formations, the reasons for the change from noncoal to coal-forming
paleoenvironments is not well understood.<p>
     Following the extinction of dinosaurs at or near the end of the Cretaceous,
mammals underwent a major radiation during the Paleocene (about 10 million
years in duration) to form the lineages that will give rise to all of the major
mammalian groups living today.  The Paleocene also represents a time of major
peat accumulation, yielding the vast lignite and subbituminous coal reserves of
the Western Interior of North America.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     This research was concerned with the determination of the timing of coal deposition in
the Fort Union Coal Region, as developed in Glendive and adjacent areas in Montana
and North Dakota.  The project objective was to develop a framework that allows for
the temporal comparison of coal deposits and, thus, the occurrence of coal-forming
conditions, through the transition from strata largely barren of coal in the Hell Creek
Formation into the coal-bearing strata of the Ludlow and Slope Formations in the Fort
Union Coal Region.  The development of a regional coal chronostratigraphic
framework permits both local and regional interpretations of the paleoenvironmental
conditions leading to coal formation.  An understanding of the controlling factors of
coal quality and thickness contributes significantly to effective resource evaluation and
utilization.  <p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Ongoing research (Hartman, 1991a, b; Hartman and Kihm, 1991; Kihm and Hartman,
1991; Hartman and Kihm, 1992) has provided chronostratigraphic control for various
portions of the Fort Union Group in the Fort Union Coal Region.  To date, most of this
research has focused on coal-bearing deposits of the middle and upper Paleocene.  This
collaborative research project, with Dr. David W. Krause of the State University of New
York at Stony Brook, was focused on the transition from environments essentially devoid
of peat accumulations to those in which peat-forming areas are an important component of
the paleoenvironment.  Very frequently, this transition is lithostratigraphically marked by a
laterally extensive coal bed, such as the Z coal (or coal bed complex) in the western
portion of the Fort Union Coal Region.  This bed and its stratigraphic equivalents appear
to represent a very nearly isochronous horizon, as indicated by paleontological and
geochemical data.  In the area of Glendive, the coal near the K/T boundary is referred to
as the contact coal, in reference to its placement at the contact between the Hell Creek and
Ludlow Formations.  The K/T transition in the Fort Union Coal Region is, however, quite
controversial and far from being understood precisely, because of problems interpreting
the stratigraphic setting due, in part, to incomplete or complex geologic sections.  The
geologic section of the Makoshika State Park was chosen, in part, because the
stratigraphy representing the K/T transition is sufficiently complete to avoid the
controversies often associated with the proper sequencing of fossil occurrences and
paleomagnetic samples in less continuous sequences.<p>
     Research has resulted in the recognition of the K/T boundary on the basis of pollen in two
stratigraphic sections in Makoshika State Park in Dawson County, Montana (Kroeger and
others, 1993).  Associated with this research was the discovery of a fern spike.  The brief
dominance of ferns is believed to represent the rapid flourishing of opportunistic species
after the "catastrophic destruction of existing plant communities" (Fleming and Nichols,
1990), followed by reintroduction of angiosperm taxa that soon diminish the significance
of ferns in the Paleocene paleoflora.  In the Makoshika sections, the palynomorph-based
recognition of the K/T boundary and fern spike occur just below (5 to 25 cm) the lignite
used to stratigraphically mark the contact between the Hell Creek and overlying Ludlow
Formations.<p>
     Ongoing studies have resampled and discovered uppermost Cretaceous and Paleocene
mammalian and molluscan fossil localities in the greater Glendive area.  Mammals are
known from the uppermost Cretaceous Muddy Tork (L6205) and QV (L6261) localities
and the early and middle Paleocene Hiatt (L5418) and School Well (L6256) localities. 
The most important nonmarine molluscan occurrences are Localities L6206, L6207, and
the School Well locality (L6256).  Also found was a single, poor impression of a
freshwater clam (L6260) from beds directly overlying the Contact coal.  In addition to the
temporal control that will be provided by the fossils, paleomagnetic samples have been
collected in the geologic section that includes the fern spike.  These samples will be
analyzed for paleomagnetic signature by Dr. Steven P. Lund of the University of Southern
California.  Using biochronologic control provided by the palynomorph, mammalian, and
molluscan fossils, the paleomagnetic reversal stratigraphy will be interpreted for
Makoshika State Park.  A well-founded paleomagnetic section will provide the
opportunity to correlate the sequence of fossils and coal beds in the greater Glendive area
with other similar paleomagnetic studies elsewhere in the United States and Canada.<p>
<h3>References</h3>
              <b>Butler, R.D.</b>, 1980, Stratigraphy, sedimentology, and depositional environments
