<html>
<head>
<title>Biochronology and Evolution of Latest Cretaceous
and Paleocene Nonmarine Mollusca of the Northern
Great Plains: The Riverside Locality of North Dakota</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2> Biochronology and Evolution of Latest Cretaceous and Paleocene Nonmarine Mollusca of the Northern
Great Plains: The Riverside Locality of North Dakota </h2> </center> 
<hr>
 <h3>Background</h3>
     The precision to which the geologic record can be interpreted and understood is limited
only by our ability to resolve time in earth history.  The resolving power for geological
interpretation is based on the quality and quantity of paleontological observations in any
given stratigraphic section.  Nonmarine mollusks are among the most abundant animal
macrofossils in the Upper Cretaceous and Paleocene sedimentary record of western
North America and, along with other fossil groups, make possible the correlation of
geologic events and previous earth configurations within relatively narrow time
constraints.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3> 
     The overall objective of this project was to construct a nonmarine molluscan
biostratigraphic zonation of uppermost Cretaceous and Paleocene strata in the
northern Great Plains.  Research specifically concerned the cocorrelation of
molluscan and mammalian localities and their constituent taxa through the
Lancian (uppermost Cretaceous), Puercan, Torrejonian, Tiffanian, and
Clarkforkian (lower, middle, upper, and uppermost Paleocene, respectively) in
portions of the Williston Basin in western North Dakota, northeastern
Montana, and southern Saskatchewan; the Powder River Basin in northeastern
Wyoming and southeastern Montana; and the Crazy Mountains Basin of
south-central Montana.  Studies also included research on the character of the
transition of nonmarine molluscan faunas through the end of the Paleocene
and into the Lower Eocene.  This work encompassed faunas from the Powder
River and Williston Basins and northern Bighorn Basin of northwestern
Wyoming and south-central Montana.  Each area contains strata and fossils
that best define or delimit a particular portion of the overall span of geologic
time.  Sufficient overlap exists between each area to provide a composite
biostratigraphically controlled biochronology for nonmarine mollusks for the
northern Great Plains.  <p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Studies focused on establishing the stratigraphic distribution, geologic context,
and correlation with mammalian local faunas of molluscan localities and taxa
in the northern plains.  The results of research undertaken on the Riverdale
Locality are given here as an example of the nature of studies undertaken to
construct a nonmarine molluscan biostratigraphic zonation.  This locality was
selected for review because its analysis is both typical of work on many
localities, but also unusual in its individual significance and collecting history.<p>
     The original Riverdale Locality (L1) was discovered by vacationers in the early
1960s on the shores of Lake Sakakawea near Riverdale in McLean County,
North Dakota.  Although this fossil occurrence has been known primarily for
its well-preserved skull of the mammal, <i>Titanoides primaevus</i> (Gidley), a few
interesting terrestrial mollusks and mammal teeth were part of the original
collections (Holtzman, 1978; Hartman, 1976).  The Riverdale Locality was
subsequently destroyed by water being trapped by the Riverdale Dam, but low
lake levels of the late 1980s exhumed a comparable molluskiferous lithology at
slightly higher elevations at the same location in the Sentinel Butte Formation. 
The Riverdale sites discovered over the last few years (e.g., L5507 and L6200)
are stratigraphically slightly above the original Riverdale Locality.  What
distinguishes the combined Riverdale local fauna from other northern plains
localities of similar age is its diverse pulmonate assemblage (air-breathing
mollusks).  An average number of species at a Paleocene locality in the Fort
Union Coal Region is about four, typically representing an assemblage of
freshwater snails (mesogastropods) and clams (unionids).  In contrast, the Riverdale fossil assemblage
contains at least 26 taxa and is dominated by aquatic and terrestrial pulmonates.  The investigation of this
terrestrial mollusk portion of the assemblage is undertaken in collaboration with Dr. Barry Roth, an associate
of the Museum of Paleontology of the University of California at Berkeley.  Many, if not most, of the taxa, are
undescribed.  The named taxa, <i>Viviparus leai</i>, <i>V. retusus</i>, <i>Grangerella mcleodensis</i>, and
New Genus T <i>planoconvexa</i> indicate a late Paleocene age (Hartman and others, 1993).  In addition, the
terrestrial assemblage is remarkable in that it shares no taxa in common with the middle late Paleocene-age
(Tiffanian 3 biochron) Judson local fauna from near the Slope-Bullion Creek formational contact in Morton
County, North Dakota.  The record of <i>G. mcleodensis,</i> known previously from Paleocene formations of
Alberta, is its first report in the United States.  The record of New Genus T <i>planoconvexa</i> is its first
report in North Dakota since it was first described in 1857 from the Sentinel Butte Formation near Fort
Berthold on the Missouri River by Meek and Hayden (1860).  <p>   

     A preliminary evaluation of slightly younger molluscan assemblages dominated
by terrestrial taxa in the latest Paleocene (Clarkforkian 2) of the Hoback Basin,
northwestern Wyoming (Barry Roth, 1994, written comm.), and the latest
Paleocene and early Eocene (Clarkforkian and Wasatchian) of the northern
Bighorn Basin (Hartman, 1993; Hartman and Roth, in progress) suggests
virtually no species in common with the Riverdale Locality (Tiffanian 4).  The
temporal control on the molluscan record is on the basis of a revised
interpretation of the ages of the mammalian localities in North Dakota
(Hartman and Kihm, 1991; Kihm and Hartman, 1991; Hartman and others,
1993; Kihm, 1993).  The distinctiveness of the molluscan faunas through time
is significant and indicates that apparently dramatic changes began to occur in
the composition of molluscan assemblages and evolutionary lineages in the
later part of the Paleocene in the northern plains.  These changes are probably
associated with a change from subtropical to more temperate conditions.  This
transition to a terrestrially dominated molluscan fauna may be foreshadowed
by the generally terrestrial nature of the older middle Paleocene (Torrejonian)
molluscan fauna to the south in the Nacimiento Formation of the San Juan
Basin of New Mexico (Hartman, 1981).<p>
<h3>References</h3> 
