<head>
<title>Subsurface Remediation Technology Research and</title>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Subsurface Remediation Technology Research and Demonstration </h2>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Recognizing the potential impacts of sour gas plant operations on the subsurface
environment, the Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers (CAPP), formerly the
Canadian Petroleum Association (CPA), and Environment Canada initiated a
multiphase investigation focusing on research related to the development and
demonstration of remedial technologies for soil and groundwater contamination at these
facilities.  The first phase of the project was completed in 1990 and consisted of a
comprehensive review of all soil and groundwater monitoring data submitted to Alberta
Environment by sour gas plants in accordance with the Canadian Clean Water Act
(1980).  That review indicated that all but one of the 45 sour gas plants for which data
were available exhibited some form of impact on soil and groundwater quality.  The
investigation identified the most frequently occurring contamination situations at the
sites and classified them according to sources and types of contaminants and the
hydrogeological characteristics of the contaminated setting.  The project steering
committee subsequently selected the Strachan Gas Plant, located near Rocky Mountain
House, Alberta, as a field research and remediation technology demonstration site.<p>

<p>
    The next phase of the work consisted of a detailed review of available subsurface
remedial technologies that could be applied to specifically identified problems. 
Established and innovative technologies were assessed, and those with the most promise
for dealing with the type of contamination situations at sour gas-processing facilities
were recommended for further development and/or demonstration.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     This current research is being conducted in response to the direction provided    in the
previous phases.  The overall objective is to assist industry in selecting and applying
remediation technologies that will most efficiently, effectively, and economically solve
their subsurface contamination problems at the sites in question.  This will be
accomplished by demonstrating not only appropriate new technologies and techniques,
but also approach and methodology.  <p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<h3> Bioventing</h3>
<p>

     The EERC is working jointly on this task with Komex International, Inc., of Calgary,
Alberta, Canada.  Bioventing is the process of enhancing in situ, aerobic
biodegradation of contaminants in the unsaturated zone by providing oxygen to the
subsurface.  Field demonstrations at the Strachan Gas Plant have indicated significant
increases in rates of contaminant biodegradation through bioventing.<p>
<p>
     Two types of bioventing tests were performed.  The objective of the first bioventing
test was to determine the optimum air extraction rate at which biodegradation was
maintained and volatilization was minimized. During the test period, biodegradation
accounted for significantly greater mass removal, with approximately 1150 kg of hydrocarbons removed by
volatilization as opposed to an estimated 11,800 kg of hydrocarbons removed by biodegradation.<p>
<p>
     The second test consisted of respiration testing during the winter, where the
biodegradation rate was determined by monitoring the oxygen consumption and carbon
dioxide production rates.  Biodegradation rates were substantial, averaging
approximately 200 kg of hydrocarbon biodegraded per day, throughout the winter
months when subsurface temperatures dropped from 9&#176; to 4&#176; C. <p>

<h3> Ex Situ Bioremediation of Groundwater</h3>
<p>

     Biological treatment of groundwater is used to remove organic compounds and certain
inorganic compounds through biochemical oxidation to carbon dioxide, water, and
other end products.  Bench-scale treatability testing of groundwater samples collected
from the Strachan site showed that effective groundwater treatment was feasible using a
two-stage attached-growth system in a coupled nitrification-denitrification
configuration.  At the bench scale, the system did not require pretreatment to control
scale formation and equipment fouling associated with air-stripping operations.  The
system exhibited high removals of biodegradable organics and ammonia.<p>
<p>
     Beginning in the spring of 1995, pilot-scale groundwater treatability will be conducted
using the coupled nitrification-denitrification concept.  The goals of pilot-scale testing
are to demonstrate the efficacy of the biological treatment system under field
conditions, obtain process performance data under a range of hydraulic and
contaminant-loading conditions, and provide a preliminary economic evaluation.<p>
<p>
<h3> Laboratory Assessment of In Situ Bioremediation</h3> 
<p>
     The overall goal of this task was to determine conditions under which the rate and
extent of microbial degradation of hydrocarbon compounds within contaminated soils
could be enhanced.  The results of this work could then be used to assist in selecting
operating conditions for technologies to be applied for remediation of subsurface
contamination at natural gas-processing facilities.<p>

     Aerobic and anoxic respirometry tests were conducted using contaminated soil samples
collected from a depth of 6 meters at the Strachan Gas Plant.  A statistical analysis was
performed using sample carbon dioxide production results to determine the overall
effectiveness of each test parameter in conjunction with all other parameters.  The
parameters evaluated included temperature, moisture content, and nutrient addition for
aerobic respirometry testing and temperature, nutrient addition, and nitrate addition for
anoxic respirometry testing.  Gas chromatographic analyses were conducted on the
samples to verify the degree of contaminant destruction.<p>
<p>
     Significant reductions of petroleum hydrocarbons were observed under a variety of
conditions and enhancements.  Temperature showed the greatest effect in contaminant
degradation under aerobic conditions.  While this is not surprising, it does indicate that
the subsurface microorganisms are not strict psychrophyles (cold-loving bacteria) and
that thermal enhancements would be expected to dramatically increase the rate and
extent of hydrocarbon degradation during bioventing.<p>
<p>
     Moisture content also influenced the rate of contaminant biodegradation under aerobic
conditions, but to a limited extent under the conditions tested.  Nutrient levels did not
appear to have a significant effect on biodegradation rates, except under low-temperature conditions.  At
7&#176;C, the average subsurface temperatureat the Strachan Gas Plant, the highest rates of
biodegradation were associated with samples incubated under conditions where moisture and nutrients were
the highest.<p>
<p>
    Samples incubated under anoxic, nitrate-reducing conditions exhibited biodegradation
rates comparable to those observed under aerobic conditions.  Anoxic samples had
hydrocarbon removals of greater than 90% after 90 days of incubation.  Anoxic
respirometry data suggest that nitrate addition to the subsurface could also be a viable
enhancement to bioremediation.<p>
<p>
<h3> Freeze Crystallization</h3> </font> 
<p>
     Freeze crystallization is a physical treatment process that uses freezing to concentrate
and remove contaminants from water.  As the contaminated water is gradually frozen,
pure water ice crystals are formed and removed, while contaminants are concentrated in
the remaining solution.  An artificial freeze crystallization process was developed under
subcontract to Resource Technology Corporation of Laramie, Wyoming.  A 6-gal/hr
prototype unit has been designed, fabricated, and shaken down.<p>
<p>
     Shakedown testing has shown the system to be capable of effectively concentrating both
organic and inorganic contaminants.  Field testing at the Strachan Gas Plant began June
1995.
<br><br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Daniel J. Stepan/<a href=mailto:dstepan@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dstepan@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5247 <br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers 
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>October 1993 to September 1995<p>
