<head>
<title>Analytical Methods Development: Center for Air Toxic
Metals Program Area 2</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h1>Analytical Methods Development: Center for Air Toxic Metals Program Area 2 </h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2> 
     The Center for Air Toxic Metals (CATM) at the Energy &amp; Environmental Research
Center (EERC) of the University of North Dakota (UND) emphasizes research,
development, demonstration, and commercialization of innovative environmental
cleanup technologies through partnerships between government, industry, and the
EERC in the areas of applied science and engineering.  CATM was established by the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and is focused on minimizing the effects
of air toxic metal pollutants on the environment.  The Clean Air Act Amendments
(CAAA) of 1990 require regulatory actions addressing 189 substances, including air
toxic metals.  In order to develop regulations, CATM is working with industry and
government to develop sufficient information on air toxic metals to provide a scientific
basis for preventing and controlling the emissions and evaluating the fate and impacts
of air toxic metals on plants and animals, including humans.  CATM-related programs
are focused on the development of methods to minimize the release of air toxic metals
via practical prevention and control methods based on scientific understanding and
principles.  To facilitate research efforts and dissemination of information, CATM is
organized into five integrated program areas:  Program Area 1 - Air Toxic Metals
Transformation Mechanisms, Program Area 2 - Analytical Methods Development,
Program Area 3 - Control Technologies, Program Area 4 - Modeling and Database,
and Program Area 5 - Technology Commercialization and Education. <p>
<p>
     When the CAAA were released, little up-to-date information on the behavior of trace
metals in energy systems was available, partly because of the inadequacy of the existing
analytical techniques.  Program Area 2 is aimed at developing sufficiently versatile
instrumentation methods with the appropriate sampling procedures to detect and
quantitatively measure atomic and molecular species, solid or gaseous, that are present
at a variety of locations throughout bench-, pilot-, and commercial-scale conversion
systems.  Trace metals that are most likely to be subjected to increased regulatory
control, such as mercury, are emphasized. <p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The major objective of CATM Program Area 2 is to advance the understanding of the
transformation of major, minor, and trace inorganic species associated with fuels and
wastes during combustion and pollution control processes.  The steps chosen toward
meeting that goal include determining the abundance and association of trace metals in
fuels and wastes and in combustion, incineration, and gasification products; developing
a continuous emission monitor to make on-line measurements of solid and gaseous
atomic and molecular species in process streams; and developing quality control "flags"
to use in assessing data.<p>
<p>
     Program Area 2 efforts were initially planned by discussing analytical needs with
investigators working under other program areas.  The approach is two-pronged:  1)
analytical methods suitable for determining a wide range of the trace metals identified
in the CAAA will be identified, with the intent of obtaining basic information useful     in
initial investigations of substances of possible concern and 2) once an element of
particular interest has been identified, efforts will focus on determining the best
methods for measuring it in all of its forms.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2> <p>
     In response to industry's need for convenient, real-time mercury measurements, CATM
has devoted a major part of its Program Area 2 efforts to the evaluation and
development of an on-line mercury analyzer.  Of the several possible approaches, an
ultraviolet (UV) absorption technique appears to be the most promising.  An on-line
UV analyzer with detection limits of approximately 0.3 &#181;g/m<sup>3</sup> has been developed at
the EERC.  The analyzer is intended to provide an easy-to-use alternative to EPA
Method 29.  The analyzer has initially been developed to detect vapor-phase elemental
mercury (Hg<SUP>0</SUP>) in a flue gas environment.  The mercury analyzer was
tested using a permeation tube Hg<sup>0</sup> source.  A known, calibrated mercury source of
very low concentration is critical to the successful development of the analyzer.  The
permeation tube source is calibrated in terms of mass lost per unit time, in this case
835 ng/min.  The rate of mercury emission from the source is very sensitive to
temperature, and so a water bath is used to maintain the permeation tube at a constant
temperature of 100&#176;C.  Exact measurement of gas flow rates is also critical to proper
operation of the analyzer.  A bubble flowmeter is used to measure flow rates to within
&#177;0.01 cm<sup>3</sup>/min.  The next phase of this work will be development of the capability for
differentiation of Hg<SUP>0</sup> and mercury compounds.<p>
 <p>
     Manufactured mercury analyzers have also been investigated for possible use with flue
gas.  Although a number of commercial mercury analyzers are available, none
presently is capable of tolerating the wide ranges of temperature and atmosphere found
in a power plant environment, while simultaneously achieving the low detection limits
necessary for flue gas monitoring.  Most mercury analyzers designed to monitor
ambient air have the requisite detection limits, but cannot tolerate a hot, dirty boiler
setting.  Investigations of several promising commercial mercury analyzers are ongoing
at the EERC.<p>
<p>
     In order to better understand the behavior of trace metals during fuel conversion, it is
necessary to comprehend their form of occurrence in coal, ash, and other fuels and
wastes.  Several analytical methods have been tested and applied for this purpose. 
Three coals, Blacksville bituminous and Absaloka and Comanche subbituminous, and
ten corresponding ash samples produced in pilot-scale combustion testing were used for
development of the analytical methods.<p>
<p>
     Energy-dispersive x-ray fluorescence (EDXRF) analysis shows that the three coals are
generally similar in their major element compositions.  Wavelength-dispersive x-ray
fluorescence, a technique being developed specifically for measurement of trace metals
in coals, ashes, sorbents, and other materials, however, showed differences in the Cr,
Ni, and Pb levels in the Absaloka, Blacksville, and Comanche coals.  The Absaloka
sample is highest in Nix (15 ppm) and in Pb (8 ppm).  The Blacksville sample is highest
in Cr (14 ppm).  Cr is thought to occur in similar mineral associations as does Hg, and
thus the elevated level of Cr in the Blacksville coal corresponds to the greater amounts
of Hg associated with minerals in that fuel.<p>
<p>
     Individual mineral grain analyses of the four coal samples were obtained using
computer-controlled scanning electron microscopy.  Blacksville coal contains the
highest levels of iron oxide (4.6 wt%), pyrite (26.2 wt%), pyrrhotite (3.1 wt%), and
oxidized pyrrhotite (6.1 wt%).  These minerals are associated with Hg, As, Cr, and
other trace metals, as determined using scanning electron microscopy with wavelength-dispersive
spectrometry, a technique which is being developed for determination of
trace metals in individual mineral grains in coal and ash.<p>
<p>
     Hg has also been measured in individual particles of Absaloka ash at levels of 0.01 to
0.07 wt% (on a C- and O-free basis).  Hg was found in 24% of individual ash
particles, each from 5 to 20 &#181;m in diameter.  The Hg-bearing ash particles were mainly
Ca- and Al-bearing silicates with some S present.  Hg was not detected in individual
particles in a second sample of Absaloka ash to which a lignite-based activated carbon
sorbent had been added, suggesting that the sorbent was effective in trapping Hg and
possibly other trace metals.<p>
<p>
     X-ray diffraction (XRD), used to identify crystalline phases in bulk solids, showed that
the Blacksville ash contained approximately 6 wt% hematite (Fe<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>).  Hematite
was notdetected in the Absaloka or Comanche ash samples.  Hematite and other Fe-rich
minerals such as pyrite (FeS<sub>2</sub>) are often associated with Hg and other trace metals, and
these results thus make sense considering the higher levels of Hg found associated with
minerals in the Blacksville coal.  Major elemental data, obtained using EDXRF, show
that Blacksville ash is high in Fe<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> (approximately 21 wt%), corroborating the
XRD results.
<hr>
<b>CATM Directors:</b> 
<li>Steven A. Benson/<a href=mailto:sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
 Phone: (701) 777-5177<br>
<li> John H. Pavlish/<a href=mailto:jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
Phone: (701) 777-5268<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<p>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>October 1993 to September 1998<br>
