<html>
<head>
<title>Verification of Method 29 for Mercury
Speciation: Phase I</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Verification of Method 29 for Mercury Speciation: Phase I  </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     The 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments require that the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency (EPA) assess the health risks associated with mercury emissions.  Therefore, it may
be necessary that mercury emissions from power plants and combustion facilities, such as
municipal solid waste incinerators, be controlled.  However, before control strategies can
be evaluated, mercury measurement methods that have been proven to be reliable and
accurate at the very low mercury concentrations found at the exit of coal combustion
power plants must be developed.  In addition, it also appears that the rate of mercury
deposition from the atmosphere and the type of control strategies used may depend upon
the type of mercury emitted (i.e., whether it is in the oxidized or elemental form).  It has
been speculated that EPA (Draft) Method 29 can speciate mercury by selective absorption;
however, this claim has yet to be proven.  The Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) and
the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) have contracted with the EERC to evaluate EPA
(Draft) Method 29 at the pilot-scale level.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of the work is to determine whether EPA (Draft) Method 29 can reliably
quantify and speciate mercury in the flue gas from coal-fired boilers.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Bench-scale results indicate that HCl does not influence mercury speciation by EPA (Draft)
Method 29 when injecting either elemental or oxidized mercury.  At the pilot-scale level, it has
been shown that very precise mercury measurements with little bias can be obtained with EPA
(Draft) Method 29.  Also, it was found that when elemental mercury is spiked into a flue gas
stream while a medium-sulfur bituminous coal is fired, a substantial portion is collected in the
peroxide impingers.  The question, then, is whether EPA (Draft) Method 29 is speciating the
mercury correctly or some type of conversion of the elemental mercury is occurring in the flue
gas stream prior to sampling.  Further testing is necessary to answer this question.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Dennis L. Laudal/<a href=mailto:dlaudal@eerc.und.nodak.edu>/dlaudal@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5138<br>
<b>Sponsors: </b> <ul plain> Electric Power Research Institute<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  June 1994 to September 1995<br>
