<html>
<head>
<title>Evaluation of Supercritical Fuid
Extraction for Analysis of Petroleum
Industry Waste</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1> Evaluation of Supercritical Fuid Extraction for Analysis of Petroleum Industry Waste </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>

     Supercritical fluid extraction (SFE) provides a potentially rapid and quantitative method to
extract fuel components from complex matrices, while reducing technician time and the
production of toxic waste solvents.  Analytical-scale SFE is also useful for determining
optimal conditions for industrial processes ranging from supercritical carbon dioxide cleaning
of contaminated solids to polymer fractionation.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The use of SFE and SFE directly coupled with capillary gas chromatography (SFE-GC) for
the rapid and quantitative extraction of fuel hydrocarbons and polycyclic aromatic
hydrocarbons (PAHs) from a variety of important petroleum-related samples was investigated. 
Supercritical extraction utilizing CO<sub>2</sub>, N<sub>2</sub>O, and CO<sub>2</sub> containing
organic modifiers under
different pressure/temperature conditions was optimized for samples ranging from the
extraction of fuel components from contaminated soils, to diesel oil in drilling muds, to
heteroatom-containing aromatics on poisoned catalysts.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Quantitative SFE methods were developed and successfully tested to determine total petroleum
hydrocarbons (TPHs), BTEX (benzene, toluene, ethylbenzene, and xylene), PAHs, and
heteroatom-containing PAHs in petroleum industry wastes.  SFE conditions were developed
that were appropriate for extracting a broad range of solids, including soils and sediments,
waste sludges, drilling muds, and source rock.  SFE gave quantitative recovery of organic
pollutants in less than 30 minutes (compared to conventional methods requiring several hours)
and reduced or eliminated the use of hazardous organic solvents.  An on-line SFE-GC method
was developed for volatile and semivolatile fuel components (gasoline to diesel range) that
yields ppb sensitivities and eliminates all solvent usage.  SFE methods were also demonstrated
in the field for determining total petroleum hydrocarbons.  Peer-reviewed publications
describing the results of this investigation are available upon request.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu>shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5256<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy 
<li>American Petroleum Institute 
<li>Chevron Research and Technology Company 
<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>October 1991 to August 1994<br>
