<head>
<title>Supercritical CO<sub>2</sub> Extraction at Elevated
Temperatures</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1> Supercritical CO<sub>2 </sub>Extraction at Elevated Temperatures  </h1></center>
<hr>

<h2>Background</h2> 
<p>
     Extraction of organic pollutants from soils and sediments with supercritical carbon dioxide has
been shown to be greatly enhanced at higher temperatures (e.g., up to 200&#176;C).  This enhancement
was not expected since the density of the supercritical fluid drops as the temperature is raised (if
pressure remains constant).  Unfortunately, there are no solubility data in the literature for
environmental pollutants at elevated temperatures to support theoretical and engineering studies
on the use of supercritical carbon dioxide for the extraction of organic pollutants.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The solubility of several common organic pollutants in supercritical carbon dioxide will be
determined at temperatures from 50&#176; to 250&#176;C and pressures from 150 to 400 bar.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2> 
<p>
     Contrary to accepted beliefs, the solubility of several polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs)
has been shown to increase with higher temperatures much more dramatically than with higher
pressures.  For higher-molecular-weight PAHs such as benzo[<i>ghi</i>]perylene, the solubility at
conventional extraction conditions (e.g., 450 atm and 40&#176;C) is so low that efficient extraction
cannot be achieved.  However, when the temperature is raised to 250&#176;C at the same pressure, the
solubility increases by more than 1000-fold.  These results demonstrate that high-solubility
conditions can be achieved with elevated temperatures at relatively low pressures of supercritical
carbon dioxide; therefore, the use of supercritical CO<sub>2</sub> for remediation and chemical synthesis
may be enhanced more by designing systems capable of higher temperatures than higher
pressures.  Peer-reviewed publications describing the results of this investigation are available
upon request.
<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu> shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5256<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>September 1994 to September 1996<br>
