<html>
<head>
<title>Supercritical Fluid Extraction
Methodology for Laboratory and Field
Use</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Supercritical Fluid Extraction Methodology <br>for Laboratory and Field Use </h1>
</center><hr>

<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Supercritical fluid extraction (SFE) has the potential for providing rapid and quantitative
extraction of priority pollutants from water, soil, and air samples prior to instrumental
analysis.  SFE has the additional potential to reduce the cost and the use of toxic solvents
required by conventional U.S. Environmental Protection Agency extraction methods.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     Rapid and cost-effective methods for measuring organic pollutants in the field are needed
to provide information for emergency response to chemical spills as well as to support the
cleanup and characterization of spill and hazardous waste sites.  The mobile analysis of
pollutants in air, soil, and water samples is primarily limited by the slow and cumbersome
liquid solvent extraction methods (e.g., Soxhlet extraction) used to prepare the samples for
analysis.  In contrast, supercritical fluids have several characteristics that should make them
superior to liquid solvents for extracting analytes from environmental samples, both in the
laboratory and in the field.  SFE has been shown to yield quantitative extraction and
recovery of organic pollutants from a variety of environmental matrices, including soils, air
particulates, and sorbent resins in 10 to 30 minutes, while yielding a concentrated sample
immediately ready for analysis.  This project investigated and developed the use of SFE and
SFE coupled with gas chromatography (SFE-GC) for the rapid and quantitative extraction
and analysis of organic pollutants from environmental matrices related to chemical spills,
including soils and sediments, water, and air samples collected on resins.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     SFE methods were developed that are suitable for the extraction of many organic priority
pollutants from the samples listed above.  SFE methods were shown to be 10 to 100 times
faster to perform and virtually eliminated the need for the hazardous solvents that are
required for other extraction techniques.  SFE was demonstrated to be easily field-portable. 
Several important fundamental processes that control SFE rates from heterogeneous
environmental solids were identified and exploited to increase SFE extraction efficiencies. 
These include the following:  1) matrix-analyte interactions are often more important than
the identity of the analyte to determine extraction behavior, 2) the commonly used practice
of "spiking" studies to determine analytical extraction efficiencies is completely invalid
regardless of whether conventional liquid solvent extraction or SFE methods are used, and
3) raising temperature is the single most effective approach to increasing extraction
efficiencies of most organic pollutants from environmental solids.  Peer-reviewed
publications describing the results of this investigation are available upon request.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/
<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu>shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5256 <br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> </font>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy 
<li>U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<br> 
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>July 1991 to September 1994<br>
