<html>
<head>
<title>Sulfur Forms in Coal</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Sulfur Forms in Coal </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3> 
     Methods presently used to determine the forms of sulfur in coal rely heavily on indirect
measurements of the individual sulfur forms and thus result in a poor degree of
understanding of the chemical types of sulfur in various coals.  Organic sulfur, which is the
most difficult form to remove, is determined by difference, compounding all of the other
errors.  Better analytical methods are needed in order to support coal-cleaning technologies
aimed at the removal of sulfur prior to utilization.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3> 
     This investigation was a continuation of promising work to develop an analytical method
to permit direct determination of organic sulfur in coal and char.  The objectives were as
follows:<p>

<ul plain>
 <IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To develop reliable methods of quantitating the organic sulfur forms as well as
the major inorganic forms (i.e., pyrite, sulfate, sulfite, sulfide, and elemental) based on direct (not indirect or
calculated) measurements of each sulfur type.  These methods should be capable of achieving mass balance
with conventional total sulfur analysis.
<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To investigate the interconversion of sulfur forms (e.g., the possible incorporation
of elemental sulfides and polysulfides or pyritic sulfur into organic sulfur during pyrolysis) that occur during
coal processing (e.g., gasification and combustion).
</ul><p>
 <h3>Results</h3>

     Conventional ASTM methods for determining sulfur forms were found to give poor mass
balance as well as to misassign some sulfur forms (e.g., assigning elemental sulfur to the organic
fraction).  In this project, reliable methods for determining all major sulfur forms by direct
measurement were developed and validated by mass balance and sulfur isotope studies. 
Extraction with supercritical CO<sub>2</sub> followed by gas chromatography with atomic emission
detection gives accurate determinations of elemental sulfur.  Sulfatic sulfur is then extracted with
formic acid.  Next, pyritic sulfur is extracted using chromous acid (which is more specific than
the traditional nitric acid extraction).  Pyrolysis combined with supercritical fluid extraction is
used to determine the reactive organic sulfur species, and the nonreactive sulfur organic species
are determined in the residue.<p>
     The results of this work have also shown that selective removal of sulfur using combined
supercritical fluid extraction and pyrolysis can be achieved.  For example, both CO<sub>2</sub> with added
methanol and water can be used as extraction fluids to remove ca. 75% of total coal sulfur.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu>shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5256 <br>
<b>Sponsor:  </b>U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology
Center <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  July 1989 to December 1993<br>
