<html>
<head>
<title>Analysis of Plastics Decompostion
Liquids</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Analysis of Plastics Decompostion Liquids  </h2> </center> 
<hr>
 <h3>Background</h3>
     The Energy and Environmental Research Corporation (EER) in Santa Ana, California, is
investigating continuous processes for the thermal depolymerization of waste plastics. 
One aspect of the research involves generation of liquids that could be processed at oil
refineries as gasoline or diesel fuel feedstocks.  This requires that the liquids meet
volatility, density, pourability, and chemical composition requirements to ensure their
compatibility with processing conditions and equipment.  One important requirement is
that feedstocks contain no more than trace levels of chlorine (maximum tolerable chlorine
levels may vary depending on upgrading conditions, but a good estimate is 200 parts per
million).  Higher concentrations of chlorine can corrode reactor components and/or
deactivate catalysts, resulting in costly repairs and replacements.  Chlorine is a component
of polyvinyl chloride (PVC), which constitutes a significant portion of waste plastics
streams (PVC is used to make pipe and clear plastic bottles).  In order to effectively
develop technologies to utilize waste plastics, plastic decomposition liquid must be
characterized by analytical methods to accurately quantitate both organically and
inorganically associated chlorine that may be present in waste plastics depolymerization
products.  The EERC has the analytical capability to quantify organic chlorine in plastics
depolymerization products using gas chromatography coupled with atomic emission
detection.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of this project was to quantify organic chlorine in depolymerization products
from the thermal depolymerization of waste plastics.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Organic chlorine concentrations in the EER liquids ranged from 0 to about 11,000 &#181;g/g. 
The results of the analyses also showed that the bulk (about 75%) of the organic chlorine
content in each of the liquid samples was contributed by the same five compounds
(identified by boiling point only).  The number of organic chlorine-containing compounds
detected in the samples ranged from 0 to about 75.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Ted R. Aulich/<a href=mailto:taulich@eerc.und.nodak.edu>/taulich@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-2982 <br>
<b>Sponsor: </b> Energy and Environmental Research Corporation <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  June 1993 to October 1993 <br>
<hr>
