<html>
<head>
<title>Gas Industry Groundwater Research
Program</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Gas Industry Groundwater Research Program </h1> 
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Many current regulations governing waste management focus on the protection of groundwater
quality, particularly the quality of shallow groundwater, because of its significance as a source
of water for drinking and agriculture.  Gas industry activities, including exploration,
production, gas conditioning and processing, and product transmission and distribution result
in a variety of waste streams, many of which are managed at or near the earth's surface and
are, therefore, subject to those regulations.  At the same time, the shallow subsurface (up to
300 ft in depth) is the zone where adverse impacts related to gas industry wastes have most
often been observed.  In response to these observations and other pressures, stricter and
potentially more costly groundwater-related regulations are now being developed that will
likely play an increasing role in gas industry waste management issues.<p>
<p>
     In order to enable the gas industry to be responsive to, and a knowledgeable and active
participant in, relevant, evolving, waste-related groundwater issues, a long-term, laboratory-
and field-based research program has been identified as necessary. Specifically, such a
program must first develop a fundamental understanding of both gas industry wastes and
waste-site interactions with relevance to the gas industry.  In turn, this understanding must be
utilized to develop the "tools" required for the gas industry to manage its wastes in ways that
effectively protect groundwater, while at the same time being efficient and economical.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objective of the program is to undertake activities fundamental to the design and
execution of complementary laboratory and field phases of a long-term research program
focused on groundwater as it relates to gas industry waste management issues.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Activities during the last 2 years have evolved from the information/data acquisition and
evaluation phase to the integrated laboratory and field testing phase and the remediation
evaluation phase of the program.  Much of the research focus has been on mercury
contamination at gas metering sites.  The highlights of these activities are detailed below.<p>
<p>
<h3>Mercury-Related Activities</h3>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a document entitled "Critical Review of Mercury
ContaminationIssues Relevant to Manometers at Natural Gas Industry Sites."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a model for prioritization of gas industry sites, "User's Manual
for HgSCREEN<sup>TM</sup>:  A Risk-Based Screening Model for Mercury-Contaminated Sites."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a document entitled "Sampling and Analysis for Mercury in
Environmental  Media of Importance to the Natural Gas Industry."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The characterization, instrumentation, and sampling of soil and groundwater at
six field sites in New Mexico, Louisiana, and Pennsylvania. <br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The development of a document entitled "Field Studies of the Occurrence,
Transport, and Fate of Mercury at Gas Metering Sites."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The conduct of a comparative investigation of four rapid field screening
techniques for the analysis of mercury in soils.  This work was done in cooperation with Oak Ridge National
Laboratory, General Electric, BioNebraska, and Spectrace.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a document entitled "Selected Laboratory Studies on
Mercury."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The continued development of a database on remediation technologies available
or being developed for application to mercury contamination.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a document entitled "A Review of Remediation Technologies
Applicable to Mercury Contamination at Natural Gas Industry Sites."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The development of a document entitled "Remediation Technologies Applicable to
Mercury Contamination at Natural Gas Industry Sites - Database Update."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The conduct of a comparative investigation of two commercial soil remediation
technologies for treating mercury.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The conduct of a workshop in New Orleans entitled "Mercury in the Oil and Gas
Industry." The workshop will be repeated in Pittsburgh and San Diego in late 1995.<br>
</ul><p>

<h3>Activities Related to Other Contaminants<</h3> <p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The continued development of the groundwater component of Gas Research
Institute's Environmental, Health, and Safety Information System, including a mercury component to the
database.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The development of a document entitled "Review of Recently Completed and
Ongoing North American Investigations Focused on Subsurface Issues of Interest to the Gas Industry." <br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The continued development of two databases incorporating relevant information
on 1) more than 600 organizations funding and/or conducting research of interest to this program and 2)
more than 3000 recently completed or ongoing research projects with which these groups are involved.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a document entitled "Assessment of Groundwater Models for
Gas Industry Application."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The development of a document entitled "Environmental Monitoring and the Gas
Industry:  A Handbook for Program Managers."<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The application of a geographic information system (GIS) for the management
and evaluation of data specific to drilling wastes and produced water generated by the gas industry.<br>

<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a document entitled "Atlas of Gas-Related Produced Water for
1990."<br>
<p>
 The completion of a document entitled "Atlas of Gas-Related Drilling Wastes for 1990."</br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The completion of a white paper on the potential usefulness of optical-cone
penetrometry.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The development of a three-dimensional groundwater model package under a
Windows<sup>TM</sup> interface (3DCUBE).<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The development of a document entitled "Background Report on Environmental
Issues Pertaining to Natural Gas Sweetening and Dehydration Operations."<br>
</ul><br><br>

