<html>
<head>
<title>An Assessment of the Subsurface Fate of
Monoethanolamine at Sour Gas
Processing Plant Sites</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1> An Assessment of the Subsurface Fate of Monoethanolamine at Sour Gas Processing Plant Sites </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2> 
<p>
     Alkanolamines are commonly used by the natural gas industry to remove hydrogen sulfide,
carbon dioxide, and other acid gases from the natural gas in which they occur ("sour" gas if
hydrogen sulfide is present).  At sour gas processing plants, as at all plants that use
alkanolamines for acid gas removal, spills and the on-site management of wastes containing 
alkanolamines and their thermal reaction products have commonly resulted in subsurface
contamination that is the focus of some environmental concern.  Generally, adequate data exist to
confirm the presence of alkanolamines and at least some of their thermal reaction and biological
degradation products in soils, sediments, and groundwater at the sites in question.  However,
analytical and other difficulties have typically prevented the nature and extent of alkanolamine-related
contamination from being delineated in detail at individual sites.  At the same time,
limited work has been done on the behavior of the chemical species in question in the subsurface;
therefore, little is known about their subsurface transport and fate.  This places the natural gas
industry in the difficult position of having to effectively address a contamination issue that is
neither well defined nor well understood.<p>
<p>
     The research project presently under way is the initial phase of a three-phase program designed
to investigate the natural attenuation processes that control the subsurface transport and fate of
alkanolamines commonly used by the natural gas industry.  The intention is to provide the
natural gas industry with data and insights that will enable it to 1) significantly improve the
assessment of subsurface alkanolamine-related contamination at sites where it is known or
expected to occur and 2) make soundly based decisions concerning the remediation of that
contamination.<p>
<p>
     This project, which is specifically focused on monoethanolamine (MEA), includes activities that
can be grouped into three areas as follows:  1) laboratory-based activities investigating the
biological fate of MEA, 2) laboratory-based activities investigating the interaction of MEA with
soils and sediments, and 3) activities focused on adapting selected analytical capabilities,
particularly for the analysis of MEA in groundwater, soils, sediments, and various experimental
residues.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The objective of this project is to investigate the natural attenuation processes that control the
fate of MEA in an effort to provide the natural gas industry with presently unavailable data and
insights that will enable MEA-related contamination to be more effectively addressed where it is
known or suspected to occur in the subsurface.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Project activities have thus far accomplished the following:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  A series of samples for project activities have been obtained from a presently
inactive sour gas processing plant site in Alberta.  This plant has a history of MEA use for acid gas removal; is
extensively characterized in terms of geology, hydrology, and subsurface contamination; and is the present
focus of a variety of other research activities focused on the subsurface contamination that has been
observed.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Experiments designed to determine the effects of temperature and
concentration of MEA on the rate of MEA biodegradation in soil/sediment have been completed.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Experiments designed to estimate the biodegradability of organic compounds in
soil/sediment exposed to MEA-containing "sweetening" wastes have been completed.<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Experiments designed to determine whether high concentrations of MEA are
toxic or inhibitory to microorganisms in soil/sediment are under way.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Experiments designed to determine the impact of alternative electron acceptors
on the biodegradation of MEA in soil/sediment are under way.  The electron acceptors being investigated are
oxygen, nitrate, sulfate, and carbonate.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The experimental design has been completed for an assessment of the role of
interactions between MEA and soil/sediment in the transport and fate of MEA in the subsurface.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Available ion chromatography (IC) capabilities have been adapted for the
quantitation of MEA in liquids at levels down to 10 ppb.  Some work has also been done on adapting these
capabilities for the quantitation of MEA thermal reaction products in liquids at ppm levels.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  An effective method for the extraction of MEA from soil, sediment, and solid
experimental residues for IC analysis has been developed.  This method involves the use of a dilute
methanesulfonic acid solution.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> A joint effort is under way with Dr. John Headley (National Hydrology Research
Institute) to compare liquid chromatography/mass spectrometry methods with IC methods for the detailed
analysis of MEA and MEA-related compounds in selected liquid and solid samples.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Selected analytical support has been provided to other investigators who are
more comprehensively evaluating the toxic effects of subsurface contaminants at the noted sour gas
processing plant site. <br>
</ul><br><br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Craig R. Schmit/<a href=mailto:cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu>cschmit @eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <p>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5259<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsosr:</b>
<li>Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers
<li>Canadian Occidental Petroleum Ltd.
<li>Environment Canada
<li>National Energy Board (Canada)
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>April 1994 to June 1995 </b><p>
