<head>
<title>Feasability Study for Underground Coal
Gasification at the Krabi Coal Mine Site,
Thailand</title>
</head>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h1>Feasability Study for Underground Coal Gasification at the Krabi Coal Mine Site, Thailand </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Underground coal gasification (UCG) is a clean coal technology that converts in situ coal into a
low- to medium-grade product gas, thus eliminating the expense of mining and reclamation. 
Accordingly, UCG can be used to extract energy from coal resources that are not economically
recoverable or that are otherwise unacceptable for conventional coal utilization processes. 
Conceptually simple, UCG involves drilling two or more holes into a suitable coal seam and
ensuring that the holes are "linked" by natural or induced permeability.  Injected air, oxygen,
and/or steam are used to initiate and maintain coal combustion.  The injected gases, together with
the heat produced by combustion, in turn, promote both pyrolysis and gasification of the
remaining coal.  The extracted product gas, which consists mainly of methane, carbon dioxide,
and hydrogen, can be used as a fuel and/or chemical feedstock.  Critical to the successful
application of UCG are careful site selection and site-specific process design, both based on a
detailed knowledge of the site.<p>
<p>
     Research and development on UCG has taken place for more than 100 years, although
commercial application has been limited to the former Soviet Union.  However, the future of
UCG on a commercial scale will be largely based on the results of an extensive series of U.S.
field tests, most of which have been conducted since 1970.  These tests, which have focused
primarily on subbituminous and lignite coal in the western United States, culminated in the
Rocky Mountain 1 test program in south-central Wyoming.  This program, in which the EERC
was a key participant, provided a unique opportunity to assess the interrelationships between the
UCG process and the environment and resulted in insights that will significantly enhance the
technical and environmental acceptability of new commercial UCG initiatives wherever they
might be considered.<p>
<p>
     Thailand's Krabi coal deposits, which are located 620 miles (990 kilometers) south of Bangkok,
consist of five lignite-bearing areas that have been targeted for possible exploitation.  Three of
these areas (Bang Pu Dum, Bang Mark, and Wai Lek) have been surface-mined to feed a local
electric power-generating plant with an initial production capacity of 60 MW.  As coal extraction
reaches a depth of over 60 meters in the most recent mining area, Wai Lek, the limit of
economical surface mining under prevailing conditions is being reached.  In order to meet the
continued need for power in the region, the Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand (EGAT)
is reviewing a number of options for power production once surface mining at Krabi ceases. 
Included among the options being considered is the utilization of gas from the in situ gasification
of the substantial coal resources that remain unmined in the five deposits.  Preliminary
indications suggest that there is significant potential for the successful application of UCG
locally, and EGAT, with funding from the U.S. Trade and Development Agency (TDA), has
selected the EERC to undertake a detailed evaluation of the feasibility of developing a
commercial-scale UCG operation utilizing Krabi coal.<p>

<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     To determine the technical, environmental, and economic feasibility of developing,
demonstrating, and commercializing UCG at the Krabi mine site in southern Thailand.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     The project was initiated in January 1995 and focused on the review of readily available
geologic, hydrologic, climatic, and other information and data specific to the Krabi coal mining
area.  This review enabled the development of a preliminary work plan and schedule and
provided the basis for a trip to Thailand to discuss project details and logistics with EGAT
personnel and to make a reconnaissance visit to the Krabi area.  The principal EERC project
participants made this 2-week trip in May, following the finalization of formal agreements
involving TDA, EGAT, and the EERC.  The results of the trip are presently being used to
complete the work plan and schedule for the remaining project activities, which will include a
variety of selected site characterization activities designed to supplement existing information
and data, followed by the detailed evaluation of all relevant, site-related information and data to
determine the feasibility of applying UCG at the site.  The final project report will review the
design, conduct, and results of all project activities, and if feasibility is established, will provide
UCG process design recommendations, as well as recommendations for subsequent
demonstration activities at the site.<p>
<br><br>

<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand 
<li>U.S. Trade and Development Agency<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>January 1995 to July 1996<br>
<hr>
