<html>
<head>
<title>Impacts of Agricultural Chemicals on
Groundwater Quality</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Impacts of Agricultural Chemicals on Groundwater Quality </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Agriculture is a highly successful industry in the United States, with pesticides and fertilizers
playing a key role in increasing the food production and overall standard of living.  After
agricultural chemicals are applied to the landscape, their environmental fate is determined by a
number of factors, including the types of pathways into the subsurface and their potential to
transport the chemicals to groundwater.  We urgently need to identify the conditions that lead
to groundwater contamination because groundwater forms 99% of our total freshwater
supplies, with 90% of the rural population and 50% of the urban population dependent on it as
their primary supply of fresh water.<p>
<p>
     Not very long ago, the nature and extent of groundwater contamination due to agricultural
chemicals were poorly understood, and as a result, arguments were made for and against the
role of these chemicals as a source of groundwater quality problems.  With the availability of
significant new information from field research projects in the past 5 years, this picture is
becoming more clear, with both favorable and unfavorable results emerging.  Under certain
field conditions, the potential for groundwater degradation is much higher than previously
thought, and the pathways by which chemicals are transported are more varied.  Our research
program seeks to add to the information available on agricultural chemicals in groundwater
through long-term, comprehensive studies of multiple field sites in the northern Great Plains. 
This type of research program will provide a scientific basis for effectively managing these
chemicals and a model to resolve specific problems experienced by the agricultural
community.<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The overall objective of this groundwater research program is to generate information that is
needed to understand the occurrence, transport, and fate of agricultural chemicals in
representative field settings in the northern plains region.  This information will be used to
conserve and protect our vital irrigation and drinking water resources, increase agricultural
efficiency, improve chemical management practices, and provide a scientifically valid basis for
meaningful regulation of the chemicals.  The approach focuses on defining and understanding
the geologic, hydrogeologic, geochemical, and microbiological conditions and processes along
vulnerable pathways from land surfaces into the subsurface at representative field sites and the
relationship of these conditions to the transport and fate of applied chemicals.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2> 
<p>
     To date, eight field sites in the northern plains region are being examined to determine the
potential for groundwater contamination from agricultural chemicals.  These sites vary as to
geology, hydrology, climatic conditions, crops grown, and farm management practices.  Specific
factors being investigated include chemical and biological processes occurring in the subsurface
environment, effects of irrigation or type of irrigation on agricultural chemical movement, the
role of preferential flow mechanisms on pesticide transport and fate, the role of denitrification on
nitrate occurrence and fate, the function of wetlands in agricultural settings, and the importance
of focused recharge on agricultural chemical movement and resulting implications for
monitoring.  Work at the field sites is being supplemented by laboratory studies on soil
characteristics, pesticide partitioning, denitrification, and airborne particulate pesticide transport.<p>

<p>
     Key findings from the current research program significant to both the agricultural industry and
regulatory agencies are briefly summarized here.<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Nitrate contamination of groundwater is of greater concern than pesticide
contamination of groundwater in the northern plains region.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> An understanding of agricultural chemical occurrence in groundwater requires a
knowledge of physical, chemical, and biological processes in the soil affecting transport and fate, as well as
management practices and climatic factors.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Denitrification plays a significant role in the occurrence and distribution of
nitrates in aquifers in the northern plains region.  Dissolved organic matter in groundwater, normally the
limiting factor for (heterotrophic) denitrification, has been found to be sufficient to allow denitrification to
occur.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> An alternate denitrification process (autotrophic), in which inorganic compounds
serve as the electron source rather than organic matter, appears to also play a role in nitrate occurrence and
distribution.  This finding is important because it provides an additional mechanism by which nitrate may be
naturally remediated and also provides an alternate mechanism for the geochemical evolution of
groundwater.<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Preferential flow studies at two of the field sites indicated this to be an important
mechanism for movement of water and contaminants.  The relative importance of preferential flow
mechanisms varied with depth at the two sites and was found to be dependent on factors such as lithology,
stratigraphy, climate, and agricultural practices.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> At a glacial till site, fractures provided the primary pathway for water movement
until textural boundaries were encountered and funnel flow became important.  Over 90% of preferential flow
occurred along fractures, with minor flow occurring along root channels and through finger flow.  Funnel flow
became important at the 2- to 4-m depth.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> At a glaciolacustrine site, about 80% of preferential flow occurred through
fractures and as finger flow to depths of approximately 80 cm.  Beyond this depth, approximately 90% of flow
was along root channels, with funnel flow also being important.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Wetlands were found to act as a barrier between nitrate-contaminated runoff
and groundwater.  Denitrification is believed to be responsible for the degradation of nitrate in the
wetlands.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Nitrate contamination was found to be associated with land use in the wetland
setting.  Nitrate-contaminated groundwater was associated with agricultural fields but not pasture lands.
<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Laboratory studies relating partitioning coefficients of pesticides to soil
characteristics indicated a good correlation between soil organic matter and Kd values.  Similar soil
samples/types gave similar analytical and Kd values, indicating good precision.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Rapid adsorption of malathion to soil was found to be followed by an increase of
malathion (or degradation products) in the water phase.  This suggests that adsorption and desorption
mechanisms need not be reversible and raises the question of which soil/water partitioning coefficients should
be used in modeling pesticide movement.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Kd values for trifluralin indicate little potential for movement through soils. 
Trifluralin occurrence in groundwater was consistent at a glaciolacustrine field site, indicating the importance
of  preferential flow at this site.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The use of flow models that do not account for preferential flow could severely
underestimate the rapidity and depth of pesticide movement in soils (e.g., trifluralin at the glaciolacustrine
site).<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Studies of pesticide transport on airborne particulates indicate this to be an
important transport mechanism.  Over a 4-year period, 22 different pesticides were detected in our sampling
program, with several being consistently found during the summer months and from year to year.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The magnitude of pesticide concentrations in airborne particulate samples would
tend to indicate that this transport mechanism could be important in the movement of contaminants to
recharge areas where groundwater could then become potentially contaminated. <br>
</ul><br><br>

<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Gale G.  Mayer/<a href=mailto:gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5108<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
