<head>
<title>Nitrate Stratification in Sand Plain
Groundwater Systems under Irrigated
Corn Production</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Nitrate Stratification in Sand Plain Groundwater Systems under Irrigated Corn Production </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Nitrate contamination of shallow aquifers continues to be an important water quality issue,
both in terms of health and as an indicator of anthropogenic impacts on groundwater.  The
goal of this research program is to understand the occurrence and distribution of nitrates in a
sand plain groundwater system under irrigated corn production.  This will provide a
scientifically valid basis upon which the best management practices can be developed and used
to avoid nitrate contamination of groundwater and provide the most productive use of the land
for agricultural crop production.<p>
<p>
    Research activities are focusing on the microbiological characterization of two sites (one with
subsurface tile drains and one without subsurface drainage) and on modeling groundwater flow
in response to subsurface drainage.  Characterization of the microbiology of the saturated zone
will allow the determination of the role of biological denitrification in controlling nitrate
contamination in the aquifer.  Modeling groundwater flow will allow the determination of the
effect of subsurface drainage on nitrate transport and fate.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     This work is part of a cooperative effort between North Dakota State University and the
EERC.  The objectives of this cooperative effort are to:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Assess the temporal and spatial variability of nitrate concentrations in
groundwater as a result of irrigation and subsurface drainage in irrigated cornfields.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Determine the effect of subsurface drainage on the distribution of nitrate in the
top 4 ft of the saturated zone.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Quantify the biological and chemical processes which control nitrate
concentration in the top 4 ft of the saturated zone in an irrigated sand plain aquifer.<br>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Instrumentation was installed at the two sites in May 1994.  Sediment cores were collected in
June 1994 to determine the different physiological groups of microorganisms present at each
site.  Water samples were collected in August 1994 and May 1995 and analyzed for biological
oxygen demand and total bacterial counts and denitrifiers.  Preliminary results are pending.
<p><br><br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Gale G. Mayer/<a href=mailto:gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gmayer@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5108 <br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Bureau of Reclamation/North Dakota  State
University<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>June 1994 to September 1995<br>
