<head>
<title>Preliminary Environmental Assessment
of the Devils Lake Sioux Reservation: 
Phase I</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Preliminary Environmental Assessment of the Devils Lake Sioux Reservation:  Phase I </h1> 
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     In response to the short- and long-term environmental goals of the Devils Lake Sioux Tribe,
studies were initiated to evaluate the environmental impact of the municipal landfill, wastewater
treatment lagoons, and groundwater in the area of water supply wells.  The studies were to
provide factual information on the potential environmental problems associated with these
facilities.  The Phase I research effort focused on gathering baseline data to provide for the
development of a comprehensive plan designed to provide sufficient information for managing
these facilities in an environmentally sound manner.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
     <p>
     The Phase I work plan for the environmental assessment of the Devils Lake Sioux Reservation
consisted of three objectives.  Each objective was designed to provide preliminary data for
assessing the scope and magnitude of potential problems related to current and proposed
facilities and developing a plan for managing these facilities in a manner consistent with state
and federal regulations.  <p>
<p>
     The first objective related to the potential groundwater impacts due to the tribal landfill.  The
second objective concerned problems related to operation of the reservation wastewater treatment
lagoon system, with a primary focus on developing an operation and maintenance plan and a
secondary focus on the impact of the lagoons on groundwater.  The third objective related to
concerns about potential impacts on groundwater quality due to nitrate occurrence in the vicinity
of the tribal water supply wells. <p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Work performed at the landfill consisted of drilling and installing groundwater-monitoring wells.
The monitoring network was designed to provide information on site stratigraphy, groundwater
occurrence, direction and rate of groundwater flow, and groundwater quality.  Drilling and
installation of monitoring wells were also performed in the vicinity of the wastewater treatment
lagoons for the determination of potential groundwater impacts.  Several monitoring wells were
installed in the vicinity of the tribal water supply wells to supplement the existing monitoring
network in this area.  These wells will be used to determine the vertical distribution of
agricultural nitrates and the potential role of denitrification on nitrate distribution.<p>
<p>
     Sampling and analysis are being performed on the groundwater from the  monitoring wells at the
above areas.  The resulting data are currently being compiled and evaluated to interpret the
geologic, hydrogeologic, and geochemical conditions in the vicinity.  Results of these efforts will
be used to estimate the scope and magnitude of impacts to groundwater and to provide data
needed to develop plans for sound environmental management of these facilities on the
reservation.  <p>
<br><br>

<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Daniel J. Stepan /<a href=mailto:dstepan@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dstepan@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5247<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li> Administration for Native Americans U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>November 1993 to June 1995<br>
<br>
