<html>
<head>
<title>Ultraclean Coal Preparation and
Evaluation</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Ultraclean Coal Preparation and Evaluation </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     North Dakota lignites, because of their availability and low cost, are a potential fuel source for
fluid-bed combustion (FBC) applications.  Because of the inherent alkali elements (sodium and
calcium) and the lower temperatures of FBC (relative to pulverized coal firing), the potential for
attaining compliance levels for SO<sub>2</sub> emissions is high because of in-bed sulfur capture.  Grand
Forks Activation Technologies has proposed that incorporating ionic calcium into the coal
structure on an atomic level can improve the efficiency of sulfur capture during combustion. 
Further, it is proposed that a significant level of calcium-for-sodium substitution will occur, with
the resulting fuel having a reduced propensity for bed agglomeration or heat-transfer surface
deposition.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of this program is to evaluate the potential for preparing a low-sulfur, low-fouling
lump fuel using a North Dakota lignite.  The specific goals of this project are to 1) perform
calcium addition and/or physical cleaning on the select lignite, 2) evaluate the combustion
characteristics (SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub> emissions, fouling, and agglomeration) of the fuels in
a fluid-bed reactor (FBR), and 3) characterize the FBR combustion residues for their potential
engineering/construction applications.<p>
 <h3>Results</h3>
     Upgraded lump fuel was prepared from a seam lignite from Beulah, North Dakota.  The
upgrading methodologies included stage crushing, classifying, and physical beneficiation
(cleaning).  Beneficiation was performed using a pilot-scale dense-media (suspended, pulverized
magnetite slurry) separator to effect a reduction in ash and sulfur (via removal of pyrite).  A
pretreatment step was also incorporated into the process, whereby the crushed coal was contacted
with a calcium additive to effect a calcium-sodium exchange.  The upgraded fuels (and their
high-temperature ashes) were subjected to chemical and physical analysis.<p>

     Preliminary results indicate that sulfur reduction by wet physical cleaning, impressive at 40 wt%,
was insufficient to produce a 1.2 lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu emission-compliant fuel.  Bench-scale
washability tests performed in 1995 confirmed these pilot-scale results.  In contrast, tests
associated with the program "North Dakota Lignite Upgrading," performed in 1994,
demonstrated that an SO<sub>2</sub> emission-compliant fuel could be made with lignite procured from the
same mine.<p>

     Results of the pretreatment process are inconclusive regarding uptake of calcium.  Further
bench-scale tests are being performed by the project sponsor.  Combustion tests are pending the
outcome of the pretreatment phase.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Mark A. Musich /<a href=mailto:mmusich@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmusich@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5263 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> Grand Forks Activation Technologies <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  February 1995 to July 1995 <br>
