<html>
<head>
<title>Physical Cleaning of Lignite</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Physical Cleaning of Lignite </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     North Dakota lignites have unique properties differentiating them from most other coals except
Saskatchewan lignites.  Fresh from the mine, they contain approximately 40 wt% moisture. 
During air-blown hammer milling, this is reduced to about 30 wt%.  Further air drying reduces
the moisture to 15-20 wt%.  However, lignite becomes more pyrophoric as the water content
decreases.  Mineral matter is very finely dispersed or present as ion-exchangeable cations
associated with organic matter.  However, bands of pyrite can collect along seam fractures in the
mine, resulting in nodules high in pyrite.  Methods for reducing ash and sulfur need to be
supplemented for some lignites to reduce their sodium content, since excess sodium increases ash
fouling during combustion.  Conventional processes for upgrading coals are generally successful
when applied to lignites.<p>
     Typically, no process has been found to economically clean a run-of-mine stream of lignite.  In
this work, the concept of inexpensive, single-pass grinding followed by splitting the coal into
separate size fractions was studied.  The possibility of producing a specification-grade product by
drying a selected fraction or by drying and briquetting or pelletizing was also studied. <p>
<h3>Objectives</h3> 
     The objective of this project was to produce a cleaner fuel from lignite (lower sulfur, ash, and
sodium contents and higher Btu) in approximately 1-in. lumps using physical cleaning,
briquetting, and drying methods.  The goal of the project was to determine the best conditions
under which to produce a specification product.  These conditions could then be used to produce
a ton quantity for use in combustion testing.<p>
<h3>Results</h3> 
     A large quantity (about 1500 lb) of run-of-mine lignite from the Beulah mine was successfully
pulverized, screened, physically cleaned, briquetted (about 300 lb), dried, and treated to produce
a product that meets sulfur emission requirements and represents a higher-heating-value product. 
High yields of about 80% were achieved.  With optimization, these should approach 92%.  The
lignite was physically cleaned from about 1.2 wt% sulfur based on a moisture-free coal basis
(mf) and 9.5 wt% ash mf to as low as 0.5 wt% sulfur mf and 6.1 wt% ash mf.  The sodium
content of the ash was 4.5 wt%, determined as sodium oxide.  Locally available binders (feed
wheat [4 wt%] and waste newspaper [3 wt%]) were investigated and found to produce briquettes
with compressive strength values of 50 psi even after soaking in water.  Surface spray treatment
with oil or emulsified asphalt at a rate of 0.5 to 1 wt% per ton of briquettes was found to help
preserve strength during soaking in water.  Equilibrium moisture values were about 18-20 wt%. 
Product heating values were 9754 Btu/lb at 9 wt% moisture and 9208 Btu/lb at 14.8 wt%
moisture.  Predicted sulfur emissions would be about 1.0 lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu based on the sulfur
content of the product, which makes this a compliance fuel.<p>

     In follow-on work, the processing conditions determined in this work were used to produce a ton
quantity of briquetted product to be used in combustion tests by Babcock &amp; Wilcox.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Curtis L. Knudson/<a href=mailto:cknudson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>/cknudson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5185 <br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>    <ul plain>Knife River Coal Mining Company<br>
     ND Industrial Commission<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> January 1994 to September 1994 <br>
