<html>
<head>
<title>North Dakota Lignite Upgrading</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>North Dakota Lignite Upgrading </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3> 
     Presently, many utilities with bituminous-design power plants are investigating coal blending
as one of several options for achieving present and future Clean Air Act Amendment-mandated
sulfur dioxide emission levels.  Coal blends being touted include those incorporating
low-sulfur subbituminous coals from the western United States and low-sulfur bituminous
coals from the eastern United States.  North Dakota lignite, if upgraded to the desired
specifications, could be substituted for the higher-Btu-content eastern bituminous coals.<p>
     Marketing studies have indicated that upgraded North Dakota lignites have the near-term
potential to secure a market of up to 3.5 million tons per year in Minnesota and Wisconsin. 
Factors contributing to this potential include the low mining cost and shorter rail haul
distances of the lignites relative to the bituminous coals.  However, prior to their acceptance,
blends incorporating upgraded North Dakota lignites must meet specific performance criteria
for fuel handling, pulverizing, combustion, and emissions.  Preliminary evaluation for
attainment of these criteria can be performed by pilot-scale combustion tests.  The EERC was
contracted to prepare upgraded North Dakota lignites for evaluation by Babcock &amp; Wilcox
(B&amp;W).<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of this project was to produce, from each of two select North Dakota lignites, 1
ton of upgraded fuel meeting targeted specifications for strength, stability, and composition as
a blending feedstock.  The goal was to demonstrate the preparation of the upgraded lignites
using pilot-scale technologies that have a high potential for commercial viability.  <p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     A Beulah mine lignite and a Falkirk mine lignite, each from North Dakota, were upgraded at
the EERC and then shipped to B&amp;W for combustion testing.  Both upgraded lignite fuels met
or exceeded several property target specifications for sulfur, ash, and sodium contents, size,
and theoretical sulfur dioxide emissions.  The delivered upgraded Beulah mine lignite had the
following analysis:  0.45 wt% sulfur, 8.9 wt% moisture, 5.6 wt% ash, 9850 Btu/lb, 0.91 lb of
SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu, and 3.5 wt% sodium (as oxide) in ash.  The delivered Falkirk mine lignite had
the following analysis:  0.56 wt% sulfur, 14.3 wt% moisture, 5.2 wt% ash, 9580 Btu/lb, 1.16
lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu, and 0.2 wt% sodium (as oxide) in ash. <p>
     The processing scenario for the upgraded Beulah mine lignite included crushing and
classifying, physical cleaning to remove liberated minerals and pyrite, briquetting to improve
density and handling, and thermal drying to improve heating value.  The processing scenario
for the upgraded Falkirk mine lignite included crushing and classifying, physical cleaning,
hot-water drying for irreversible moisture removal, and briquetting.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>Mark A. Musich</<a href=mailto:mmusich@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmusich@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5263 <br>
<b>Sponsors:</b><ul plain> Cooperative Power/United Power Association<br>
     Falkirk Mining/North American Coal  Company<br>
     North Dakota Industrial Commission (Lignite Research Council)<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology    Center<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> June 1994 to November 1994 <br>
