</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Compliance Coal Production for
Fluidized-Bed Combustion</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Compliance Coal Production for Fluidized-Bed Combustion </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Sulfur dioxide (SO<sub>2</sub>) emissions from coal-fired boilers are generally acknowledged to
contribute to acid rain formation.  Most methods for controlling SO<sub>2</sub> emitted from combustion of
noncompliance coal involve reaction with limestone-derived calcium to yield calcium sulfate
(CaSO<sub>4</sub>).  Commercial calcium-based SO<sub>2</sub> control technologies include
high-efficiency (high-cost) wet scrubbing, lower-cost spray drying, and low-efficiency, low-cost furnace or duct
injection of sorbents.  These techniques all involve the association of calcium from an injection source with
SO<sub>2</sub> from coal, either during or after combustion.  This project was performed to investigate the
effectiveness of an economical precombustion calcium treatment process in capturing SO<sub>2</sub>
emissions, using a small-scale fluid-bed combustor (FBC).  The economics of the technique are based on
utilization of waste calcium carbonate from a water treatment facility (this material is normally landfilled) in a
low-tech, "stockpile" calcium treatment process.  The process was designed to be less mechanically intensive
and less expensive than current commercial FBC SO<sub>2</sub> control technologies and to increase
calcium utilization efficiency and reduce sodium-related ash fouling by calcium-for-sodium ion exchange. 
Commercialization of the process would enable simplification of FBC design and lower operation and
maintenance costs, since a separate calcium feed system would not be required to meet SO<sub>2</sub>
emission compliance requirements.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of the project were to 1) quantitate the effect of the proposed calcium ion-exchange
process on SO<sub>2</sub> control during combustion of North Dakota lignite in a research-scale FBC unit,
2) investigate the minimum level of technology required for the process to work, 3) investigate the effect of
increased ionic strength of the processing solution on calcium incorporation into the coal matrix, and 4)
estimate the technical feasibility of utilizing landfill-destined calcium to control SO<sub>2</sub> in a small- to
medium-scale, commercial FBC unit.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The project demonstrated that coal ash modification by calcium ion exchange can change ash fusion
temperatures and increase sulfur capture during combustion and that waste calcium-rich water treatment
sludge applied to lignite can result in ash fusion temperature increases of 100&#176; to over 400&#176;F. 
Increasing ash fusion temperature to a level significantly higher than the optimum FBC operating temperature
is beneficial in that it reduces ash fouling of heat-transfer surfaces.  FBC testing of calcium carbonate
sludge-treated raw lignite resulted in sulfur emissions of 1.26 lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu, which just
exceeds the current compliance specification of 1.2 lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu.  However, a slight
processing difference (not rinsing excess sludge) further reduced FBC emissions to 0.36 lb of
SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu, and FBC testing with a physically cleaned (via an economical dense-media pyrite
separation technique), calcium-treated lignite resulted in measured emissions of only 0.27 lb of
SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu.  These latter two results qualify these fuels as compliance fuels. 
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu> byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> Grand Forks Activation Technologies<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> September 1994 to May 1995<br>
