<head>
<title>Coal-Upgrading Program for &Uacute;st&iacute; nad
Labem, Czech Republic</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Coal-Upgrading Program for &Uacute;st&iacute; nad Labem, Czech Republic </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) is working with the U.S. Department
of Energy (DOE) to assist many countries in East Central Europe with energy and environmental
issues.  A critical concern for &Uacute;st&iacute; nad Labem in the Czech Republic is the substantial pollution
created by three large district heating systems as well as small, residential, coal-fired stoves.<p>

     As part of a larger investigation in association with Gilbert/ Commonwealth, Inc., Reading,
Pennsylvania, to explore methods to reduce sulfur pollution from coal, the EERC conducted a
program to upgrade low-rank coals (LRCs) mined in the region of Northern Bohemia and used in
the city of &Uacute;st&iacute; nad Labem.  One part of this program involved reviewing the technologies used
in
upgrading coals of the region and the existing and proposed emission standards for residential and
commercial heating systems.  The North Bohemia Economic Association (NBEA) provided
assistance with this part of the program.  The program also included a limited technical
investigation of the potential for upgrading select Czech Republic coals.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

     The overall goal of the investigation was to assist the city of &Uacute;st&iacute; nad Labem in
developing cost-effective alternatives, including the upgrading of LRC for reducing emissions from the district
heating systems and other polluting stationary sources.  The objectives of the EERC program
involving NBA were to 1) review the cost-effective LRC upgrading technologies for reducing
particulates and gaseous pollutants and 2) undertake a brief experimental investigation of the
potential for upgrading up to six LRC samples from the Northern Bohemia region of the Czech
Republic.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Three coals from the Czech Republic, including B&iacute;lina and Nastup lignites from North Bohemia
and Ostrava bituminous coal from Moravia, were subjected to a limited technical investigation at
the EERC to assess the potential for upgrading.  All coals were analyzed for ash and sulfur
contents, forms of sulfur, and ash composition.  B&iacute;lina and Nastup lignites were treated by wet
and dry physical cleaning methods to reduce ash and sulfur content.  Physically cleaned B&iacute;lina
lignite and raw Ostrava bituminous coal were carbonized to reduce volatile matter content.  Select
raw, physically cleaned, and carbonized coals were aggregated (tableted) with a starch binder (and
calcium carbonate as a sulfur capture agent).  The aggregated fuels were analyzed for ash and
sulfur contents and ash composition, then subjected to bench-scale combustion tests to evaluate
their potential application as district heating and home heating fuels.<p>
     The ash and sulfur contents of the B&iacute;lina lignite were reduced by 42 and 36 wt%, respectively,
at
Btu yields of 90% using float-sink testing.  Further, dry physical cleaning via rare earth magnetic
separation (REMS) produced significant sulfur reduction (27 wt%) at a Btu recovery of 95%. 
Nastup lignite was not amenable to sulfur reduction at 1/4-in.  20 mesh via float-sink or REMS.<p>

     The tablet fuel analyses were compared to quality standards established in the Czech Republic for
the allowable maximum sulfur content (g/MJ basis) of indigenous briquettes.  Fuels prepared from
raw Ostrava bituminous coal and float-sink-cleaned B&iacute;lina lignite would qualify as fuels for steam
raising in business and energy installation applications.  Further, tablet fuels prepared from
carbonized Ostrava bituminous coal and carbonized B&iacute;lina REMS product would qualify as
smokeless fuels for home heating applications by virtue of their sulfur and volatile matter
contents.  The B&iacute;lina lignite-derived fuels have potential emission-effective sulfur contents
comparable to the Ostrava fuels because of the sulfur capture agent.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael L. Jones/<a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>/mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5130<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology
Center <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  March 1994 to February 1995 <br>
