<html>
<head>
<title>Biodesulfurization</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Biodesulfurization </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Conventional catalytic hydrodesulfurization involves high costs largely due to hydrogen
consumption and heavy metal deactivation of the catalyst.  A potentially lower-cost treatment is
microbiological or enzymatic desulfurization.  Advances at the EERC improved the understanding
of sulfur-specific microbial desulfurization pathways in Rhodococcus bacteria, but further work
was needed to develop a practical technology based on biodesulfurization.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The main focus of this project was the application of desulfurization enzymes to remove sulfur
from crude oil, diesel fuel, or resid precursors for needle cokes.  The most important question to
be answered was how to utilize the Rhodococcus desulfurization complex in a nonaqueous
solvent or medium, such as the oil itself.  Successful application of nonaqueous enzymology to
this problem involved finding ways to stabilize the active conformations.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The pathway for desulfurization of the model compound dibenzothiophene (DBT) was completely
elucidated for nongrowth Rhodococcus bacteria.  Experiments with <sup>18</sup>O-enriched intermediates
were successful in demonstrating which of three potential pathways linking several intermediates
was the correct one.  This knowledge was needed for subsequent experiments in enzyme isolation
and determination of regulatory mechanisms.<p>
     The 4S pathway for DBT degradation in Rhodococcus utilized one enzyme to convert DBT to
the sulfoxide and subsequently the sulfone.  The sulfone is converted by a second enzyme to
2-hydroxybiphenyl-2-sulfinate, which is cleaned by a third enzyme to 2-hydroxybiphenyl.  A
nonenzymatic reaction of the sulfuric acid forms the sulforic acid via a dimer mechanism.  The
sulforic acid is converted to 2,2<sup>1</sup>-dihydroxybiphenyl by the same enzyme that converts the
sulfone to the sulforic acid.<p>
     The problem with the pathway is that two of the reactions require a reducing cofactor, NADH,
which must be supplied if the enzymes are removed from the interior of the bacterial cell.  Present
efforts are directed toward improving the efficiency of this process.<p>

<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edwin S. Olson/<a href=mailto:eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5155 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy  Morgantown Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  March 1994 to December 1997<br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
