<head>
<title>Organic Sulfur Removal from Coal with
Super- and Subcritical Water</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Organic Sulfur Removal from Coal with Super- and Subcritical Water </h2> </center> 
<hr>
 <h3>Background</h3>
     One of the major problems that still eludes the coal utilization industry is the lack of
cost-effective methods for precombustion sulfur removal from coal.  With the diminishing
supply of low-sulfur coal and more restrictions imposed on the use of high-sulfur coal, sulfur
removal from coal prior to combustion has become important.<p>
     Despite numerous attempts to remove sulfur from coal for low-sulfur clean coal combustion
applications, physical methods (e.g., selective agglomeration, flotation, or magnetic separation)
have enjoyed limited success for pyritic sulfur removal, and similar physical separation methods
are ineffective for organic sulfur removal from coal.  Cost-effective and technically sound
methods for removing organic sulfur from coal are not available.  While, in principle,
high-concentration chemical reagents (e.g., molten caustic leaching method) are effective for
removing organic sulfur from coal, little attention has been given to the economic feasibility and
the potential environmental impacts associated with their use.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

     The main objective of the investigation is to develop an economically feasible method for the
removal of organic sulfur from Illinois Basin high-sulfur coals for clean coal and niche market
applications.  Subcritical water will be used as an extraction fluid rather than the traditional
liquid solvents.  The proposed work will take advantage of subcritical water (acting as both
solvent and reactant) for the removal of organic sulfur by simply controlling the extraction
temperature and pressure.  Previous drawbacks of using supercritical water, such as the high 
temperatures (&gt;374&#176;C) and pressures (&gt;221 atm) required, high corrosivity of supercritical
water, high engineering costs, and significant coal mass loss through dissolution, can be avoided. 
In addition, water is inexpensive, widely available, nontoxic, and environmentally acceptable.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>

     Preliminary results indicate that physical cleaning (column flotation) of Coal IBC-101 reduced
the total sulfur content by &lt;10%, an amount approximately equal to the sulfatic content of the
coal.  However, the supercritical water extraction removed nearly three-fourths of the pyritic
sulfur and one-half of the organic sulfur while increasing the Btu/lb for extracted physically
cleaned coal.  Less severe conditions (subcritical water conditions) are being tested to determine
whether similar sulfur removals can be accomplished while retaining more of the volatile matter.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Peter K.K. Louie/<a href=mailto:PLOUIE@eerc.und.nodak.edu>plouie@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5279<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b><ul plain> Illinois Clean Coal Institute<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> September 1994 to August 1995 <br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
