<head>
<title>Stability Issues with Upgraded Low-Rank
Coals</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Stability Issues with Upgraded Low-Rank Coals</h2> 
</center>
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     Low-rank coal (LRC) utilization has largely been restricted to power generation at the mine or
within a short hauling distance because of the high moisture content and low heating value of
this coal type.  Continuing a trend of the last decade, bituminous-fired utilities in the midwestern
and eastern United States are investigating low-sulfur subbituminous coals for switching and/or
blending to achieve SO<sub>2</sub> emissions compliance.  A major challenge for coal producers is the
development of cost-effective coal-drying processes to enhance LRC heating value and reduce
transportation costs.<p>
     The LRC-upgrading technologies currently demonstrated include evaporative and
nonevaporative drying and mild pyrolysis/gasification.  An obstacle facing their development is
the stability of the product with regard to dusting, moisture reabsorption, and spontaneous
combustion.  Upgrading may enhance the instability of the product with respect to spontaneous
heating and dusting.  Because stability phenomena are often given only minor attention, the
development of improved stability-testing methods was deemed a necessary and complementary
component in the successful demonstration of upgrading technologies.  Currently, American
Society for Testing and Materials (ASTM) procedures which address the physical stability of
coal or coal-derived products concern equilibrium moisture, abrasion resistance, Hardgrove
grindability, drop shatter, and impact resistance.  To date, an accepted procedure for the
determination of propensity to dust does not exist, and the stability of the equilibrium moisture
procedure for raw and upgraded LRCs has been questioned.<p>
     The EERC has participated in the assessment and development of a variety of LRC-drying
technologies.  With the development of these drying technologies, the EERC has commenced a
systematic program to investigate the major stability issues of dried LRCs.<p>

<h3>Objectives</h3>

     The objective of this project was to develop methods and modify existing ASTM standards used
to evaluate coal and coal products in terms of their propensity to dust.  Dust generation is a major
concern for the future integration of LRC and its treated products.  The impact of various stress
levels experienced during handling and transporting severely affects the stability and uniformity
of the fuel, especially for dried products.  The height of loading and unloading equipment,
distance and methods of transport, climate and location, and the type of utilization station must
be taken into consideration in the design of a coal-upgrading facility.  Laboratory- and pilot-scale
systems were designed based upon existing ASTM and coal-handling procedures to evaluate the
handling characteristics of raw and dried LRCs.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Three raw coals and their dried coal products were evaluated by various strength and stability test
methods.  Three drying methods (air, hot water, and saturated steam) were used to generate
low-moisture, upgraded products for physical stability measurements.  Standard test methods as
well as methods developed at the EERC were used to evaluate the propensity of lump western
LRCs (raw and dried) to produce dust and absorbed water.  <p>
     Indices for dust generation and friability were generated for raw and upgraded coals to observe
the effect of moisture removal and upgrading methodology on coal stability.  A pilot-scale
conveyor test loop was developed at the EERC to more accurately simulate actual handling
operations to appreciate viability and slacking tendencies and a drop point to simulate the coal
loadout or transfer areas all in one system.  The conveyor test offers a procedure for use with
larger coal volumes and an environment in which to review the effectiveness of dust suppression
techniques.<p>
     The results show that the moisture content is decreased and the amount of dust generated is
substantially increased to unacceptable levels (i.e., fines less than 0.5 mm not to exceed 10 wt%). 
Tests performed to evaluate the tendency for moisture reabsorption of dried LRCs indicated that
coals tend to reabsorb the moisture during air drying, whereas hydrothermal treatment processes
do not allow reabsorption.<p>
     Through development of these laboratory techniques, there is the potential for improving the
prediction of stability of LRCs when subjected to transport handling and storage procedures. 
This is extremely important when marketing the virtues of a particular western coal type, as the
coal is transported long distances to eastern or foreign markets.  If commercial drying of LRCs is
to be successful, efforts must continue on stability analysis and the development of
cost-effective, stable products.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Chris M. Anderson/<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5120 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  March 1994 to March 1995<br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
