<html>
<head>
<title>Powder River Basin Coal Enhancement
Program</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Powder River Basin Coal Enhancement Program </h2> </center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The purpose of the program was to simulate coal drying/fluidized-bed pyrolysis at low
temperatures with partial oxidation.<p>
    The tests were conducted in two stages.  The first stage included a drying step using the EERC
controlled spontaneous reactor.  500 lb of feed coal was processed in this step.  The dried
material was then pyrolized at various conditions using a 1-4-lb/hr bench-scale continuous fluid-bed reactor
(CFBR) to determine tar yield from a Powder River Basin (PRB) Cordero mine coal.<p>

<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of the program were to determine the yield of tar from the PRB coal to as high a
degree as possible in a fluid-bed reactor under particular conditions.  The following were specific
objectives:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Determine the difference in tar yield with wet vs. dry quench/condensation<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Determine the difference in tar composition with wet vs. dry
quench/condensation<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Collect char for use in future test programs<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Acquire samples of water streams for analysis</li>
</ul>
<p>
 <h3>Results</h3> 
     Because of the proprietary nature of the program, detailed results cannot be described.  During
the drying tests, 440 kg of product was produced.  The dried product had a moisture content less
than 0.2%.  Analysis of the wastewater indicated the TOC was about 1600 mg/L, due entirely to
coal fines, and the gas contained only N<sub>2</sub> and CO<sub>2</sub>, which indicates that
devolatilization was not occurring.  25 material balances were completed under the second stage of the
program.  Statistical analysis of the results indicated the char, condensables, water, and gas yields were
reproducible within &#177;2.5%, &#177;0.9%, &#177;1.8%, and &#177;2.3%, respectively.<p>

     Even though the coal was dried in the first stage, there were significant amounts of water
produced in the pyrolysis step because of Fischer water.  Typically, moisture tests only analyze
for surface moisture, while pyrolysis releases chemically bound or adsorbed moisture.  The
yields of moisture were typical for a Wyodak coal.  Char, condensables, water, and gas yields
were within the range generally observed for a Wyodak seam coal.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu> rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5209 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>Kennecott Energy Company<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1995 to June 1995<br>
