</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Alaskan Low-Rank Coal-Water Fuel
Environmental Attributes and
Combustion Test Marketing</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>

<h1>Alaskan Low-Rank Coal-Water Fuel Environmental Attributes and Combustion Test Marketing </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Pilot-scale tests at the EERC established that premium coal-water fuels (CWFs) could be made
from hot-water-dried (HWD) subbituminous coal from Alaska's Beluga coalfield at costs
competitive with imported oil and bituminous CWF in Japan.  LRCWF contains no chemical
additives; it is simply coal particles suspended in water and, as such, should pose no
environmental threat if spilled on land or in a body of water.  LRCWF is nonflammable and not
explosive and, therefore, avoids costly handling and transportation procedures usually required
for hydrocarbon liquids.  The next step in developing a commercial low-rank coal-water fuel
(LRCWF) plant in Alaska is a commercial-scale demonstration of LRCWF production and
utilization to allow potential end users to see firsthand LRCWF production followed by
combustion in an oil-designed boiler.  They will then be able to make their own economic
projections, as well as test excess LRCWF in their own facilities.  Early end-user involvement in
the demonstration will hasten the acceptance of this new fuel form and encourage users to seek
equity positions in the first LRCWF commercial plant in Alaska.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2> 
<p>
     The objectives of this program were to build on contacts developed by the Alaska CWF
Consortium with a number of foreign and U.S. boiler makers/users and to develop interest for
testing Alaskan LRCWF in potential user facilities.  Based on experience to date, potential
opportunities include the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Hawaii Electric Company<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  U.S. companies, including TRW and Donlee Tech, Inc., that are developing a
slagging combustor and atmospheric fluid-bed combustors (FBCs), respectively, for Alaskan applications<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Mexican utilities looking at existing oil-fired and new dual fuel-fired facilities<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Advanced combustion systems, including Cooper-Bessemer's CWF-fired
diesels<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Selected potential users in Japan, Korea, and Taiwan</li>
</ul>
<p>
     The project sought documentation from environmental protection agencies, including the
Alaskan Division of Environmental Conservation and the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency, on the environmental attributes of LRCWF use as compared to oil.  Documentation of
the nonhazardous nature of CWFs in comparison to the problems associated with the spill or
leakage of petroleum-based fuels will be a valuable asset to assist marketing LRCWF.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     A one-page brochure describing in nontechnical terms LRCWF production, utilization,
environmental attributes, its potential role in opening the Beluga coalfield, and the proposed
demonstration project was prepared, and over 1500 copies were distributed.  It was well received
and proved invaluable in developing broad-based support for the demonstration project in the
Alaskan Legislature.<p>
<p>
     Numerous domestic and international entities interested in developing the technology to
commercial scale were identified, including coal companies, industrial and utility boiler vendors,
advanced power system developers, and various countries interested in expanding the uses for
indigenous coal supplies.  These contacts will be maintained throughout demonstration project
development.<p>
<p>
     An order-of-magnitude economic evaluation was performed on commercial development of
LRCWF.  The production cost ranged from $0.77 to over $2.00 per million Btu.  The range of
cost estimates vividly illustrates the need for demonstration-scale testing to narrow the
uncertainty in process costs and to define actual performance in oil-designed boilers.  It also
illustrates the need for private and government cost sharing to reduce the risk of providing
definitive financial and performance data needed by potential LRCWF producers and consumers.<p>
<p><br><br>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael L. Jones/<a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5193<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
