<html>
<head>
<title>Evaluation of Methanol-Coal Slurries</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Evaluation of Methanol-Coal Slurries </h2>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     The EERC has investigated numerous drying and conversion technologies that can be applied to
low-rank coals (lignite and subbituminous) to upgrade coal quality.  Moisture removal may occur
by evaporative or nonevaporative drying processes.  Evaporative techniques have the advantages
of being both low-cost and simple; however, the product quality can be a drawback. 
Conventional evaporative drying can economically remove all moisture to produce a dried fuel
that is acceptable if consumed immediately by using flue gas produced at the utility. Two
evaporative drying methods, air drying and oven drying, have been tested with a selected Alaskan
Beluga subbituminous coal.<p>

 <h3> Objectives</h3>
     The objective of this project was to determine the options available for converting raw, pulverized
subbituminous coal into a viable liquid fuel by initially drying the coal and then adding methanol to
produce coal-liquid fuels.  The work focused primarily on the rheological characteristics of the
fuels and the effects of changing methanol concentration, particle size, and moisture.  Three tasks
were identified to evaluate the potential for coal-methanol fuels.  The initial specific tasks were
conceived in three phases:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Phase I     Evaluation of raw Beluga coal and coal-methanol fuels<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Phase II    Evaluation of air-dried Beluga coal and coal-methanol fuels<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Phase III   Evaluation of oven-dried Beluga coal and coal-methanol fuels<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Testing with raw Beluga coal was used to determine baseline rheological characteristics of the
fuel with reference to solids loading, stability, and particle-size distribution.<p>
     Moisture analysis, specifically equilibrium moisture, of the three samples tested indicates that no
significant changes to the coal structure occurred between Phase I and Phase II samples. 
Analysis of the Phase III sample possibly indicated some structural changes in the coal because
the equilibrium moisture content was approximately 40% lower than for Phase I and II samples.<p>
     Stability of the fuels varies greatly, depending on the solids concentration of the fuels.  The fuels
with solids concentrations yielding viscosities between 500-650 cP appear to be very stable. 
However, the initial yield stress necessary to get these fuels to flow is so great that it is not
possible to produce a pumpable fuel at these conditions.  When further blending takes place, the
higher-viscosity fuels are more stable and could be pumped more easily.  At lower viscosities,
settling occurs more readily, but the fuels are much more pumpable, with further blending not
having nearly the effect it has at higher viscosities.  Energy densities of the fuels at 250 cP
indicate that Phase II and Phase III fuels have heating values greater than 9000 Btu/lb.  The
higher inherent moisture content of the Phase I fuel leads to a heating value of less than 8000
Btu/lb.
<p><hr>
<b> Project Manager:</b> Chris M. Anderson /<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5120 <br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> MethanEx Corporation<br>
Placer Dome U.S. Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> July 1993 to April 1994<br>
