<html>
<head>
<title>Pilot-Scale Production of Refuse-Derived Slurry Fuel</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Pilot-Scale Production of Refuse-Derived Slurry Fuel </h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
As public concern grows and government regulations become increasingly strict, numerous municipalities and
industries face exorbitant costs for solid waste disposal that run head-on into bottom-line profits. 
Concurrently, markets for lignite coal have been limited primarily because of its high moisture content, which
results in a low heating value per unit of weight and a high transportation cost per unit of energy.  In addition,
most of the North Dakota lignite reserves have sulfur contents that produce emissions that exceed the 1990
Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAA) Phase II emission limits of 1.2 lb of SO<sub>2</sub> per MMBtu for power
plants.
<p>
To address these issues, EnerTech Environmental, Inc., and the EERC collaborated to develop a new method of
using both low-rank coals and low-sulfur solid waste materials.  The technology, called slurry carbonization,
was investigated as a means to efficiently produce homogeneous, high-energy slurry fuels with reduced
SO<sub>2</sub> emissions relative to that of the coals, offering a much more environmentally conscious
means of utilizing the energy potential of the solid waste.
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
The overall objective of this research program was to demonstrate the EnerTech-EERC process of slurry
carbonization for producing homogeneous, pumpable fuels from refuse-derived fuel (RDF) with pilot plant
facilities.
<p>
<h2>Results</h2> 
Carbonized RDF slurry fuels were produced with the EERC 7.5-tpd (wet basis) pilot plant facility.  A hose
diaphragm pump pressurized a 7-10 wt% feed RDF slurry, with a viscosity of 500 cP, to approximately
2500 psig.  The pressurized RDF slurry was heated by indirect heat exchangers to 585&#176;-626&#176;F,
and its temperature and pressure were maintained in a downflow reactor.  The carbonized slurry was flashed,
concentrated in a filter press, and ground in an attritor.  During operation of the pilot plant, samples of the
feed RDF slurry, carbonization gas, condensate, carbonized solids, and filtrate were taken and analyzed.
<p>
Pilot-scale slurry carbonization experiments with RDF produced a homogeneous pumpable slurry fuel with a
higher heating value of 3000-6600 Btu/lb (as-received basis) at a viscosity of 500 cP at 100 Hz decreasing
and ambient temperature.  Greater-heating-value slurry fuels were produced at higher slurry carbonization
temperatures.  During slurry carbonization, polyvinyl chloride plastics in the feed RDF also decompose to form
hydrochloric acid and salts.  Pilot-scale slurry carbonization experiments extracted 82%-94% of the feed RDF
chlorine content as chloride salts.  Higher carbonization temperatures and higher alkali additions to the feed
slurry produced a higher chlorine extraction.
<p> 
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Chris M.  Anderson/<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5258<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b> 
<li>EnerTech Environmental, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>October 1994 to January 1995 
<br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
