<head>
<title>Feasibility Study for Slurry Carbonization
of Automobile Shredder Residue</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Feasibility Study for Slurry Carbonization of Automobile Shredder Residue </h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Used cars are extensively recycled for ferrous and nonferrous metals, generally using
shredding and air classification technologies.  However, a waste residue, referred to as
automobile shredder residue (ASR), is generated that is high in plastics, including polyvinyl
chloride (PVC).  Hence, thermal recycling and utilization of ASR are costly and
environmentally opportunistic because of its high PVC (chlorine) content.<p>
<p>
     EnerTech Environmental, Inc., and the EERC have developed a technology, slurry
carbonization, to decompose and extract organically bound chlorine and, concurrently,
improve the heating value of low-rank fuels and wastes.  In the simplest description of
slurry carbonization, raw ASR is mixed with water to form a pumpable slurry.  The ASR
slurry is then pumped and heated to specific temperature and pressure conditions
(225&#176;-350&#176;C and pressure sufficient to keep the slurry substantially liquid) in the absence
of air or oxygen.  At these conditions, the ASR molecularly rearranges, and PVC
decomposes to hydrochloric acid, so that, upon cooling, the carbonized ASR can be
dewatered and washed to remove the chlorine.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To establish the effects of slurry carbonization on the chemical and physical
properties
of the ASR slurry.</li>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To establish optimal operating conditions to minimize the chlorine content of the
carbonized ASR slurry fuel.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To characterize the gas and water effluents produced from bench-scale slurry
carbonization.<br>
<p>
</ul> 
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Raw ASR contained a significant chlorine content at approximately 2.9 wt% (dry basis). 
During slurry carbonization, chlorine was extracted from the ASR as soluble chloride salts. 
On average for the bench-scale experiments, the slurry carbonization treatment extracted
over 87% of the feed ASR chlorine, with a maximum extraction of approximately 90%. 
The percentage of chlorine extraction was slightly dependent on the maximum slurry
carbonization temperature.<p>
<p>
     Unexpectedly, raw ASR contained a significant oxygen content (dry basis) and a low
heating value.  On average, the slurry carbonization treatment improved the heating value
of ASR by approximately 16% on a moisture-free basis and over 68% on a moisture-ash-free basis.  Based
upon these preliminary data, the heating value of the carbonized ASR
appears to be independent of the slurry carbonization temperature or percentage of alkali
added to the feed slurry.<p>
<p>
     The carbonized ASR was reconstituted with water and its rheology determined.  On
average for bench-scale experiments, the solids loading of the carbonized ASR slurries was
52.1 wt% total solids at a viscosity of 500 cP (@ 100 Hz decreasing), over 110% higher
than the feed slurry at a similar viscosity.  This solid loading is comparable to coal-water
slurry fuels.  This resulted in carbonized ASR slurry fuels with an average heating value of
4900 Btu/lb (wet basis), which is slightly lower than the raw solid ASR (dry basis).  It is
expected that these slurry fuels would exhibit excellent combustion characteristics.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Chris M. Anderson/<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5120<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>EnerTech Environmental, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>January 1995 to March 1995 <br>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
</DOC>
