<html>
<head>
<title>Prefeasibility Study for the Production of
Form Coke from Indian Low-Rank Coals</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h2>Prefeasibility Study for the Production of Form Coke from Indian Low-Rank Coals </h2> <hr>
</center>
<h3>Background</h3>

     India has estimated coal reserves of over 176 billion tonnes; however, only a small fraction is
metallurgical grade.  Consequently, India has become a major importer of coke and/or
metallurgical coal.  These imports amount to over 5 million tons per year and are increasing in
response to growth in the steel industry.<p>

     The Formcoke&reg; process, developed in the United States by FMC Corporation, was designed to
make a metallurgical coke substitute using low-cost low-rank coals (LRCs).  During
development, several full-scale blast furnace tests were conducted using Formcoke&reg; made from
LRC, which proved to be a suitable replacement for the more costly, conventional coke produced
in coke ovens from bituminous coals.<p>
     The ability to produce formed coke from all ranks of coal takes on added significance in areas
like India where indigenous coking coals are scarce or of poor quality, but quantities of
reasonably good-quality LRCs exist.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     Using the EERC database on coproduct yields from gasification of LRCs, the objectives are to
estimate Formcoke&reg;  yields from representative Indian LRCs and estimate the economics of
Formcoke&reg;  production in India and develop a commercialization program.<p>
<h3>Results</h3> 
     Several Indian lignites from the states of Gujarat and Tamil Nadu were low enough in ash and
had sufficient predicted yields to be considered as Formcoke&reg; feedstocks.<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Capital costs for a Formcoke&reg; plant are expected to be below those for a
conventional coke plant.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Plant economic projections are enhanced with cogeneration of electricity.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> With a nominal 15% internal rate of return, Formcoke&reg; is projected to be
competitive with conventional coke, even in today's depressed coal market.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Bench-scale testing at the EERC was proposed as the next step to validate
theoretical estimates of product yields and quality. 
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> CERA and Dhrangadhra Chemical Works, Ltd., Bombay,
India<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> September 1993 to January 1994 <br>
