<head>
<title>Novel Briquette Binders</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Novel Briquette Binders </h2></center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     Recent advances in the processing of lignocellulosic material to provide inexpensive
intermediates afford an opportunity to devise an inexpensive polymeric binding material for
making coal briquettes or coal logs from coal fines, as a way of transporting and using this
lower-value coal.  The recent environmental interest in pyrolysis conversion of plastic waste to
usable feedstocks has generated some unique gels that were investigated for the preparation of
briquette binders.  Markets are urgently needed for products resulting from both of these
technologies.<p>
 <h3>Objectives</h3>

     The objective of this project was to produce high-strength coal briquettes using inexpensive
binders derived from waste plastic pyrolysis tars and from lignocellulose hydrolysates.<p>

<h3>Results</h3>
     Lignin has been known to be a good binder for producing coal briquettes.  Hot pressing methods
gave pellets with high compression strength (236 psi).  Cold pressing was generally not
successful with any of the binders, nor was hot curing after cold pressing.  Conversion of lignin
to a cross-linked Novolak structure by adding one-carbon linkages via formaldehyde gave a
viscous material that proved to be a poorer binder than the original lignin.<p>

     High-strength pellets were produced from phenol Novolak using a hot press method.  Here the
cross-linking is essential to bonding the coal particles together.  Low-rank coal chars were also
strongly bonded by the Novolak.  Mixing the phenol Novolak with lignin gave a strong pellet,
but did not offer any additional strength.  A composite Novolak prepared from a mixture of
lignin and phenol was an ineffective binder.<p>
    Several binders prepared from calcium tall soap, a polyurethane prepared from diphenolic acid,
and some starch graft copolymers were reasonably good binders.  A number of coal-derived tars
and low-severity liquefaction products and the Orimulsion bitumen were poor binders.<p>
     Using a proprietary process, high-strength pellets were prepared from waste plastic packing
materials.  A plastic-derived binder was the only binder that could be used with the bituminous
char.  Waste plastic pyrolysis tars were not very effective binders.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>Edwin S. Olson/<a href=mailto:eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5155 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy  Morgantown Energy Technology
Center <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1994 to March 1995<br>
