<html>
<head>
<title>Direct Liquefaction of Low-Rank Coal</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Direct Liquefaction of Low-Rank Coal </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     A multistep direct liquefaction process designed to take advantage of the inherent reactivity of
low-rank coals has been developed at the EERC.  The process consists of 1) a preconversion
treatment to prepare the coal for solubilization, 2) solubilization of the coal in the solvent, and
3) polishing using solubilization solvent to complete solubilization of the remaining material. 
The product of these three steps can then be upgraded during a traditional hydrogenation step. 
Positive results of research on this process indicated that additional studies should be performed
to more fully develop the process.<p>
<h3> <b>Objective</b></h3>

     The project objectives are to determine the recyclability of the solvent used during solubilization
and to determine the minimum hydrotreatment severity required to upgrade the liquid product of
the multistep EERC process.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Testing is scheduled to be performed in two tasks.  The first task consists of ten cycles of the
multistep process in which the solubilization solvent is recycled from the polishing step of one
cycle to the pretreatment step of the next cycle.  A composite solvent consisting of cresylic acid
and hydrotreated coal-derived anthracene oil was prepared to use as the solubilization solvent for
the ten test cycles.  It is expected that both Tasks 1 and 2 will be completed in June 1995. 
Preliminary results of Task 1 indicate that 1) the composite solvent works well in the process,
2) the conversions attained for each cycle are very consistent, and 3) the solvent appears to be
lining out as it continues to be recycled through the process.

<p><br><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  John R. Rindt/<a href=mailto:jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5296<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>July 1994 to July 1995<br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
