<head>
<title>Investigations of Novel Methods for
Production of Iron-Based Catalysts Used
in Coal Liquefaction</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Investigations of Novel Methods for Production of Iron-Based Catalysts Used in Coal Liquefaction </h2>
</center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     Coal is the most abundant fossil fuel resource in the world.  The major use of coal in the U.S. is
for the generation of electricity.  A variety of options have been considered for transforming coal
into liquid fuels.  Although this transformation is possible technically, economics have precluded
the use of liquid fuels produced from coal under normal market conditions.<p>
    To improve the economics of catalytic coal liquefaction, work has been focused on developing
more efficient and economical catalyst systems.  Problems with molybdenum-based systems
include short life times, high cost, and system material disposal.  Iron-based catalyst systems
may offer an opportunity to overcome many of these shortcomings, improving the economics of
coal liquefaction options.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project are to investigate novel methods for preparing iron-based catalysts
and to investigate the catalytic activity of these catalysts with coal samples.<p>
<h3>Results</h2>
     Several options for preparation of iron-based catalysts were investigated.  Materials were
produced that demonstrated yields of coal liquids similar to or better than those noted with
conventional systems.  Activities were comparable to those noted with the more expensive
molybdenum catalysts.

<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael L. Jones/<a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5130<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b> Universal Fuel Development  Associates<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> February 1991 to September 1993<br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
