<head>
<title>Effects of Coal Chemistry on Gasification
at the Great Plains Gasification Plant</title>
</head>
<body><center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Effects of Coal Chemistry on Gasification at the Great Plains Gasification Plant</h2> </font> 
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The Great Plains Gasification Plant, owned and operated by the Dakota Gasification Company,
has demonstrated many technological advances in the production of synthetic natural gas (SNG). 
Test data have indicated correlation between gasification rates and some chemical
characteristic(s) of the coal fed to the gasifiers.  While extensive plant data are available, testing
to identify more economical and efficient plant operating conditions is limited by the variability
between gasifiers and production needs.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h2>
     The objective of this project was the optimization of the gasifiers at the Great Plains Gasification
Plant.  Previously, more than 50 analytical methods were used to determine properties of six coal
samples to identify correlations with observed gasifier operability and SNG production.  The
next phase of that work was to examine the promising properties for 42 additional samples to
improve the value of any statistical correlations with observed gasifier operability.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
     The larger group of samples collected from different areas of the mine increased the variability of
characteristics of the coal.  The highest correlations with plant performance were found for the
energy of activation of the char-steam reaction and the Btu content of the coal.  While the
statistical correlations were significant, whether they are strong enough to help guide plant
operations is yet to be determined.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven J. Cisney/<a href=mailto:scisney@eerc.und.nodak.edu>scisney@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5114 <br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>Dakota Gasification Company<br>
U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>September 1992 to September 1993 <br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
