<head>
<title>Chlorine Removal from Recycled Plastics</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Chlorine Removal from Recycled Plastics</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     This project is a follow-on to the project entitled "Thermal Recycling of Plastics," whose purpose
was to examine the thermal decomposition products of plastics.  While the thermal recycling
process shows promise, several key areas must be examined before commercialization of thermal
recycling is pursued:  the elimination of organochlorides, the measurement of organochlorides,
and the industrial specifications of the process products.  Since essentially all end uses of these
products will be in chemical applications (e.g., introduction into a refinery or fuel blending),
organic chlorine in the product liquids is unacceptable.  Identification of where organochlorides
form is necessary before a decision can be made on where chlorine will be removed in the
process.  If it is found that organochloride formation occurs in the decomposition process, then
chlorine removal would be necessary either in the bed or in the feed system.  If formation occurs
during condensation, postreactor filters would be possible.<p>
     Presently, no applicable analytical methods are standard (e.g., American Society for Testing and
Materials [ASTM]) for measuring organochlorides in these types of liquids.  Total chlorine is
measured using a variation of ASTM Method D808-91.  Organically associated chlorine is
measured using gas chromatography-atomic emission detection.  A database will be established
to support these techniques.  Characterization of the product liquids according to refinery and
fuel standards is also planned.  The resulting liquid products should be characterized according to
these standards to help facilitate acceptance of this novel product.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this program are to identify where organochloride formation occurs (i.e.,
during condensation or decomposition), verify and document the analytical methods for
organochloride quantitation, and characterize the product liquids in terms familiar to the
petroleum and fuel industries.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Tests completed were very successful in precluding organochloride formation using both an in-bed
and postreactor filter.  Organochlorides were reduced from 3000 ppm to less than detection
limits of 10 ppm.  Sorbent utilization varied with CO<sub>2</sub> partial pressure, ranging from 30%-100%. 
Product liquid characterization indicates the distribution of liquids produced varied from diesel
fuel and JP4 (jet fuel).  This distribution can be shifted with temperature or bed material choice,
as can the aliphatic-to-aromatic ratio.
     A round-robin of organochloride analytical techniques was completed between the EERC,
British Petroleum, and Conrad Industries.  This work was conducted to establish whether
particular analytical techniques were reliable and consistent.  Final reports on the sorbent testing
and round-robin research are available.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>American Plastics Council <br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> May 1993 to August 1993<br>
<a href="p00i.htm#Fuel">Return to Fuel and Chemical Formulation</a> |
<A href="../index.html"> EERC Home Page</a> | 
<a href="infocntr.htm">Info Center</a> | 
