<html>
<head>
<title>Utility Experience Blending Eastern and
Western Coals</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Utility Experience Blending Eastern and Western Coals </h2> </center>
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     The 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments have forced a number of utilities currently firing high-sulfur
coals to find methods to reduce emissions of SO<sub>2</sub> to levels mandated by current law. 
Methods of compliance include flue gas desulfurization, fuel switching, fuel blending, and
emission allowance trading.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of this project was to review the current status of coal blending as a compliance
strategy.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The final report for this project provides an overview of the experience of those utilities that have
investigated or have elected to blend low-sulfur subbituminous coals from the Powder River
Basin (PRB) with higher-sulfur bituminous supplies to attain compliance.  The report includes
power plant descriptions and performance data collected from 12 units at 11 sites, representing 9
utilities.  Methods used to obtain the data reported included questionnaires, site visits, interviews,
and telephone and mail correspondence.  The units surveyed included seven Combustion
Engineering (CE) (six tangentially fired and one wall-fired, all dry bottom) and five Babcock and
Wilcox (B&amp;W) (four wall-fired [one wet-bottom] and one cyclone-fired) units.  The potential
areas affected by the blends included fuel transportation, coal handling and storage, mill
performance, furnace wall slagging, convective pass fouling, particulate collection/emissions,
and gaseous emissions of SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub>.  In addition, modifications to existing
equipment or operating procedures required or under consideration as a result of firing the blended fuel were
documented.  The key findings of the investigation are summarized as follows:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Sulfur emissions can be reduced to meet regulations by blending PRB coals with
bituminous coals.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> PRB coal transportation, handling, and storage can be accomplished without
major modifications to equipment or procedures.<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Blending can be successfully accomplished by a variety of methods, including
off-site blending at the rail-to-barge transloading facility, on-site blending on the conveyors by control of belt
speeds (or using weigh feeders) from separate reclaims, or in the boiler by controlling the distribution of
bituminous coal to the lowest pulverizer/burner sets and using one or more of the upper pulverizer/burner
sets for combustion of the PRB coal.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The pulverizer is generally the first area affected by the blend, which may impose
a limitation to achieving rated load.  The higher-moisture PRB coal tends to suppress the mill outlet
temperature below the design minimum for bituminous boilers.  Attempts to maintain this temperature result in
boiler derate.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Mills that use higher levels of carrier gas can accommodate higher blend ratios
of subbituminous coal without boiler derate, because the carrier gas has a greater capacity for moisture,
preventing significant reductions to mill exit temperatures.  <br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> There is a characteristic change to the distribution of heat in a bituminous-design
boiler firing a blend containing subbituminous coal.  More heat is carried out of the furnace because of
inadequate surface area in the furnace, lower flame temperatures (reduced radiation of heat to surfaces),
and higher flue gas heat capacity.  Some boiler operators reported a "reflective" ash on waterwalls that may
also contribute to this phenomenon.<br>

<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Furnace wall slagging and convective pass fouling of heat-transfer surfaces may
increase.  Increased furnace wall blower and convective pass sootblower operation can effectively be used to
manage the blend deposits.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Baseloaded units tend to have more difficulty with deposition than those
incurring regular load swings.  Decreasing temperatures in the convective pass allows for shedding of
deposits at reduced load.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Finned-tube economizers may present a problem.  Chunks of sootblown
convective pass ash-fouling deposits and fly ash tend to collect between these surfaces, insulating them and
potentially blocking the flue gas flow through these difficult-to-sootblow regions.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Particulate collection can be impaired by the blend because of the lack of
SO<sub>3</sub> present in the flue gas.  Larger electrostatic precipitators (ESPs, with specific collection area
[SCA] greater than 300 to 350 ft<sup>2</sup>/1000 acfm) tend to provide adequate collection of the
resultant fly ash.  Smaller precipitators require the addition of new fields or the use of flue gas conditioning to
achieve adequate collection.  Intermediate blend ratios present the greatest impairment to ESP performance
because of the transition from SO<sub>3</sub> conditioning (100% bituminous coal) to Na<sub>2</sub>O
conditioning (100% subbituminous coal) of the fly ash.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Flue gas NO<sub>x</sub> emissions may decrease, in large part, because of the
lower combustion flame temperature.<br>
<p>
</ul>
Recommendations or suggestions for use of PRB coals in boilers designed for bituminous coals
include the following:<p>


<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  On-site storage of PRB coals should be accomplished by compacting the
stockout piles to reduce the potential for air infiltration, which could lead to problems with self-heating during
storage of the higher-reactivity PRB coal.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> In general, increased housekeeping around transfer points can alleviate any
potential problems with self-heating of the higher-reactivity PRB coal in spillage areas of the coal-handling
system.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Mill safety procedures should be reviewed and considered where none exist to
alleviate the chance for mill fires and puffs, particularly during start-up and shutdown.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Utilities should check with their boiler vendors to determine the minimum mill
outlet temperature (for a given coal pipe size) that will allow adequate transport of the fuel to the burners. 
The higher reactivity of the subbituminous coal will allow for adequate flame stability even at
lower-than-design mill outlet temperatures.<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Sootblower maintenance and increased boiler inspection may be required to
maintain/sustain boiler operation.  <br>

 <p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Units with smaller ESPs should perform parametric testing of existing capacity to
determine whether additional fields or flue gas conditioning is required to adequately collect the blended coal
fly ash.<br>
</ul>
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Jay R. Gunderson/<a href=mailto:jgunderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jgunderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5258<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>U.S. Department of Energy <br>
     Electric Power Research Institute<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  January 1992 to December 1993<br>
<hr>
