<html>
<head>
<title>Prediction of Ash Behavior During Coal
Conversion</title>

</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Prediction of Ash Behavior During Coal Conversion </h2></center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The behavior of inorganic components in coal is the most important factor determining
combustion system design for utility boilers.  Great interest exists in mathematically modeling
coal behavior during combustion as a tool for research and design.  To this end, the National
Science Foundation has funded a major program, the Advanced Combustion Engineering
Research Center (ACERC) at Brigham Young University and the University of Utah to produce
a three-dimensional code for a full-scale, coal-fired boiler.  A major component of this program
will be submodels to describe mineral matter behavior during combustion.  Because of the
EERC's strong background in this area, Dr. Steven A. Benson has been asked to head up
activities concerned with mineral behavior in the ACERC program.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objective of this program is to obtain information on the combustion behavior of the mineral
matter in a selected suite of test coals to serve as the basis for development of mathematical
models.  To this end, the following goals are being pursued:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Characterization of the inorganic portion of the selected coals, including both
chemical fractionation to determine organically bound cations and computer-controlled scanning electron
microscopy to determine discrete mineral phases.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Determination of the characteristics of intermediate ash materials and deposits
formed during conventional combustion, low-NO<sub>x</sub> combustion, and advanced coal conversion
using bench-scale drop-tube furnace (DTF) reactors.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Management of all mineral matter activities in the ACERC program, including
determination of priorities and long-range goals.<br>
</ul>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Combustion testing was performed to examine mineral and ash transformations under
low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions.  The approach was to combust several ACERC coals of varying rank in a
bench-scale DTF system under both conventional and low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions.  Fly ash from these
coals was collected on bulk filters and examined by scanning electron microscopy (SEM) to determine the size,
morphology, and composition of the ash particles.  Three coals were prepared as 70% to 80% -200-mesh
samples and combusted in a bench-scale DTF under both conventional and low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions. 
On-line gas analysis was used to monitor CO, CO<sub>2</sub>, O<sub>2</sub>, and NO<sub>x</sub>
concentrations.  Samples of the fly ashes were collected on bulk filters for subsequent analysis.  Ash
particle-size distributions and carbon carryover were determined by Malvern and thermogravimetric analysis,
respectively.  Detailed analyses of the fly ashes were performed using a modified version of the EERC scanning
electron microscopy point count (SEMPC) program to determine mineral phases and elemental compositions of
individual particles.  The particles analyzed were also manually sized by measurements from SEM
photomicrographs.  In collaboration with Dr. C.H. Bartholomew of Brigham Young University, portions of the fly
ash will be examined by M&ouml;ssbauer spectroscopy to determine the iron oxidation states present.<p> 
     For conventional combustion, the DTF system gas temperature at the coal injection point was
maintained at 1530&#176;C, a gas temperature at the deposition point of 1230&#176;C with a residence
time of approximately 3.5 seconds, and an air level of 19%.  Low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions were simulated
by lowering the furnace temperature profile to 1430&#176;C and introducing 3% air with the secondary gas
stream.  Nitrogen was used to transport the coal in the primary gas stream.  The lower temperature and
slower mixing of fuel and air extended the burning time and significantly reduced both the thermal and fuel
NO<sub>x</sub> produced for a total NO<sub>x</sub> reduction of about 50%-60%, while still maintaining
an acceptable level of carbon burnout.  Samples of each fly ash were collected on a bulk filter; particle-size
distribution was determined by Malvern sizing and degree of carbon carryover by thermogravimetric
analysis.<p>  
     Results of particle-sizing analysis of the fly ash indicated a small but consistent increase in mean
particle size for the low-NO<sub>x</sub> as compared to conventional combustion conditions.  This may be
the result of the longer, cooler burning time, reducing coal particle fragmentation and allowing
increased coalescence of the mineral matter under low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions.  The major effect of
low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions on ash mineral composition appears to be a decrease in the amount of pure
mineral phases present, with a concurrent increase in mixed phases.  The ash of the subbituminous Powder
River Basin coals that were tested showed a decrease of quartz, calcium oxide, and kaolinite phases, along
with an increase in calcium aluminosilicate, under low-NO<sub>x</sub>  conditions.  A significant increase in
amorphous mixed-silicate mineral phases was observed.  No similar trends were obvious for the bituminous
Illinois No. 6 coal.  Liquid-phase viscosities, calculated based on the SEMPC chemical analyses of individual fly
ash particles, did show slightly lower values for the low-NO<sub>x</sub> fly ash for all coals tested.<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven A. Benson/<a href=mailto:sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5177<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> Brigham Young University Advanced Combustion Engineering
Research Center<br>
     National  Science Foundation<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> June 1988 to April 1996<br>
<hr>
