<html>
<head>
<title>Development of Fireside Combustion
Performance Indices: Convective Pass
Fouling and Fly Ash Collectibility</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Development of Fireside Combustion Performance Indices: Convective Pass Fouling and Fly Ash
Collectibility </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
     A number of purely operational options are available to reduce ash-related problems in coal-fired
boilers,
including switching or blending coals, using additives, or changing the temperature profile of the boiler. 
Predicting the effects of a proposed operational change is difficult, because although a variety of empirical
indices involving simple American Society for Testing and Materials (ASTM) analyses are available, the
complex nature of coal means that finding the most economical solution involves some experimentation. 
However, experimentation with a 500-MW boiler is a complicated proposition because failures can be
expensive and the solutions chosen may not be the most efficient.  For these reasons, computer simulations
of key parameters affecting ash deposition are often used first to reduce the size of the experimental matrix. 
The EERC is developing advanced indices that rank coals according to their fouling and slagging propensity
in utility boilers.  The indices are termed "advanced" because they are based on more sophisticated
analytical techniques for identifying and quantifying coal inorganics, greatly improving their reliability
compared to conventional indices.<p>
<h3> Objectives</h3>
     The goal of this consortium project was the reliable prediction of coal-related aspects of boiler
performance, including slagging and high- and low-temperature fouling (for both conventional and
low-NO<sub>x</sub> burners); slag tapping; stack emissions opacity; steam tube erosion; and mill
performance.  These indices are intended to provide an economical means of reducing the amount of full-scale
testing needed to determine the best approach to minimize ash-related problems encountered when coal is
burned in pulverized coal-fired boilers.  The index calculations were performed by a single IBM PC-compatible
computer program, termed "PCQUEST," an acronym for Predictive Coal Quality Effects Screening Tool.<p> 
     Extensive bench-scale testing, analysis of coal and ash, and operational data were used to formulate
the
index algorithms.  At the completion of the project, PCQUEST contained enough data to allow the
evaluation of entirely new coals with the input of the appropriate chemical and mineralogical data and
selected boiler parameters.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The first step in formulating the advanced indices is to obtain complete characterization of
discrete minerals and organically associated inorganic components in selected coals and then to
compare these characteristics to the performance of the coals in full-scale systems.  The optical
drop-tube furnace (ODTF) at the EERC has the ability to generate slagging and fouling deposits
and fly ash samples from a variety of coals using conditions similar to those in full-scale
systems.<p>
     The index value calculations are based on data from coal inorganic content and limited
combustion conditions.  Certain quantifiable coal inorganic parameters, which are considered the
most important factors governing the formation of utility boiler deposits, have been assembled
into an algorithm that outputs an index value expressing the degree of fouling or slagging
propensity.  A higher number represents more fouling or slagging.  Assumptions used in
weighing the relationship between the key inorganic constituents are based on years of
investigating coal inorganic content and ash deposition mechanisms in a variety of coal
combustion systems.  The indices are not based on complex or comprehensive mechanistic
modeling concepts.  The software is designed to be relatively simple to use, with a minimum
amount of computer processing time.  Criteria used in developing the indices and their relation to
combustion behavior include the quantities of key mineral forms such as small included clays
and quartz, pyrite, and calcite and the quantities of organically bound constituents such as
sodium, calcium, and magnesium.<p>
     The EERC conducted site visits to each utility sponsor in order to obtain samples of feed coal at
the power plant under normal operating conditions, measure gas temperatures in selected regions
of the boiler under normal operating conditions while the test coal is being burned, document
fouling and slagging at temperature measurement locations, and obtain grab samples of deposits
that form during combustion of the test coal.  The temperature measurements and observations,
combined with pertinent boiler operating data logged at the time of the measurements, provide an
elementary database to assist in development of the performance index algorithms.  Four site
visits were completed:  Union Electric's Labadie Station, Minnesota Power's Clay Boswell
Station,  Kansas City Power and Light's Iatan and Hawthorn Stations, and Northern States
Power's Sherburne County Station. <p>
     Preliminary results confirmed PCQUEST as a simple yet powerful screening tool with the
potential to save utilities and consumers thousands of dollars by preventing inefficiencies and
unscheduled plant shutdowns that can occur because of poor coal selection.  The fouling and
slagging indices contained in PCQUEST have performed reasonably well in predicting the
deposition behavior of seven sponsor-selected coals.  PCQUEST is capable of calculating seven
parameters:  1) a fouling index to predict fouling propensity for both high- and low-temperature
zones; 2) an opacity index which uses fly ash resistivity calculated from computer-controlled
scanning electron microscope data; 3) a slag formation index based on the results of chemical
analyses and bench-scale testing; 4) a slag-tapping index based on predicted slag viscosities; 5) a
grinding index to evaluate the potential for mill abrasion based on maceral, mineral, and moisture
variations; 6) a steam tube erosion index founded on both bulk and individual particle
characteristics of the coals; and 7) a sootblowing index to predict the ease or difficulty of
sootblowing for deposits produced when a coal of interest is burned in a particular boiler, based
on coal and ash composition and particle size.  The indices are designed to apply to either
conventional or low-NO<sub>x</sub> conditions and also include more boiler-specific parameters, allowing
for more reliable prediction of the performance of coals in various boilers. <p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Christopher J. Zygarlicke/<a href=mailto:czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu>czigarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>(701) 777-5123<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>Electric Power Research Institute<br>
     Kansas City Power and Light<br>
     Minnesota Power Company<br>
     Northern States Power Company<br>
     Union Electric, Inc.<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> July 1992 to March 1995<br>
<hr>
