<head>
<title>Combustion Characterization of
Beneficiated Coal-Based Fuels</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Combustion Characterization of Beneficiated Coal-Based Fuels </h2> </center> 

<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The ash formed when a coal is burned in a boiler system can reduce process efficiency,
damage equipment, and form potential environmental pollutants.  Some of the problems can be
reduced a priori by specifically designing the boiler system to reduce them.  However,
predictions of specific problems are difficult because the inorganic matter in coal undergoes a
complex series of interactions during combustion as it is turned into ash.  Although a variety
of measures can be taken  to limit the individual difficulties as they occur, removal of the
inorganic material from the coal prior to combustion provides a single solution to many of the
ash-associated operational problems.  All coal beneficiation processes leave behind a portion of
the inorganic material.  In order to investigate the changes in combustion performance and
ash-related problems caused by coal cleaning, the U.S. Department of Energy Pittsburgh
Energy Technology Center has contracted with ABB Combustion Engineering, Inc. (CE), to
determine the combustion characteristics of beneficiated coal-based fuels (BCFs).<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The two main objectives are to develop an engineering database that will provide detailed
information on the properties of BCFs that influence combustion, ash deposition, ash erosion,
and particulate emissions and to apply this technical database to predict the performance and
economic impacts of firing the BCFs in various commercial boiler designs.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The EERC has been working with two other major subcontractors,  the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology and PSI Technology Company, to provide experimental, analytical, and
technical assistance to CE in determining the effects of coal beneficiation on combustion
behavior of the fuels.  Approximately fifteen fuels have undergone bench- and pilot-scale
combustion testing to date, including five parent coals and ten beneficiated fuels.  Three
beneficiation processes have been investigated:  the microbubble flotation process, the
spherical oil agglomeration process, and microagglomeration.  In all cases, beneficiation
reduced the ash content of the fuels.  However, some minerals were removed more efficiently
than others, thereby changing the chemical composition and behavior of the remaining ash.  In
some cases, the ash became more problematic than that from the parent coal.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  John P. Hurley/<a href=mailto:jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5159 </b>
<b>Sponsor:</b> ABB Combustion Engineering, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> June 1989 to December 1995<br>
<hr>
<a href="p00i.htm#Conventional">Return to Conventional Power Systems</a> |
<A href="../index.html"> EERC Home Page</a> | 
<a href="infocntr.htm">Info Center</a> | 
