<head>
<title>FT-IR Spectroscopic Investigation of
Fireside Deposits in a Pilot Plant
Combustor</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> FT-IR Spectroscopic Investigation of Fireside Deposits<br> in a Pilot Plant Combustor </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The increasing emphasis on control and, where possible, the elimination of the formation of ash
deposits on heat-exchange surfaces of coal combustion boilers and turbine blades has highlighted
the need for improved understanding of the formation processes and enhanced analytical
techniques.  The type and strength of the deposits formed are dependent on the nature of the coal
(rank, type, mineral composition), the combustion/reducing conditions, the temperature of the
radiant and convective surfaces, and the location and material of the heat-exchange surfaces.<p>
     Low-rank coals in particular, as a consequence of the presence of alkali and alkaline earth
materials, can lead to severe fouling and slagging, but even bituminous coals can yield low-melting-point
phases (e.g., pyrite and illite) that form significant ash deposits on radiative and
convective surfaces.  For most coals, the recalcitrant deposits are largely composed of sulfates or
silicates.  The primary techniques for deposit analysis have been x-ray diffraction and scanning
electron microscopy.  These techniques require samples to be removed from the combustion
system.  Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectrometry has been demonstrated elsewhere to be
a powerful technique for monitoring deposit changes in a bench-scale environment, but its
applicability with an appropriate deposit-viewing geometry at the pilot-scale requires
investigation.  With an FT-IR spectrometer, the EERC has set up a deposit-viewing system
typical of those found in combustion systems, allowing application to field testing.  This project
was undertaken to set up and test an FT-IR spectrometer on a fully operating pilot-scale coal
combustor.<p>
<h3>Objectives </h3>
     The objective of this project was to examine the applicability of an FT-IR spectrometer to
monitor in situ the mineral species causing fouling and slagging deposits in a pilot-scale
coal-fired combustor.  The specific objectives were to correlate spectral changes in the reflected
and emitted energy from deposits to their mineral constituents and to relate the deposit character
to the combustor operating conditions.  This research  also provided information allowing design
of remote-sensing deposit detection techniques, which will be utilized in deposit control
measures.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     In April 1995, the infrared emission sampling probe (IESP) was used to monitor deposits during
16 hours of coal-fired combustion testing.  This test used Antelope (Powder River Basin)
subbituminous coal fired at 1200&#176;C.  Coal-fired tests revealed a minor flaw in the design of the
IESP, causing the objective lens to become covered with fine ash particles.  During the test, the
IESP was modified to eliminate ash buildup on the probe by increasing the lens temperature
above the dew point.  Results of this test have identified  IR wavelengths, which are useful for
determining the thickness of ash and slag deposits.  This type of detection technique will not
require a spectrometer, since it is based on a two-wavelength measurement in the IR. Therefore,
a relatively simple two-wavelength detector system can be designed that uses the IESP as an
interface to the furnace and that can act as a deposit monitor.<p>
     Assuming successful field testing with the IESP-FT-IR spectrometer, it is envisaged that this
new technology be applied to power generation facilities for control of sootblowing.  The probe
would be modified to use flexible fiber-optic cables to transfer infrared emissions from the IESP
to the spectrometer. Several IESP units may be multiplexed to a single spectrometer, allowing
monitoring of several points in the combustion system.  Information obtained from the IESP
would be used by process control hardware in the combustion system to control sootblowing.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> Electric Power Research Institute <br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> December 1993 to September 1994<br>
<hr>
