<html>
<head>
<title>Root Cause Analysis for the
Independence Plant Explosion</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Root Cause Analysis for the Independence Plant Explosion </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     On Wednesday, August 11, 1993, the Unit Two boiler at the Entergy Independence Plant
exploded, resulting in severe structural damage.  Fortunately, no one was seriously injured.  At
the time of this work, the cause of the explosion was not clearly known or understood.  To assist
Entergy in determining the root cause of the problem/incident, the EERC was contracted to
analyze four ash samples in hopes that information discovered during the investigation could be
used to provide insight into the circumstances/conditions that led to the failure.  The four
samples studied were extracted from different locations throughout the Unit Two boiler after the
explosion.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     Specific objectives for analyzing these ash samples were as follows:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Characterize physical and chemical properties of the ash samples<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Identify mechanisms of formation<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Estimate combustion conditions under which the samples were formed<br>
</ul>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Four ash/deposit samples were analyzed to aid in evaluating the cause of the explosion at the
Independence Plant.  The following is a brief description of the Independence Plant and the ash
samples that were received by the EERC.<p>
<h3>Plant Description</h3>

     The Independence Plant consists of two Combustion Engineering 800-MW pulverized coal units
firing western subbituminous coal at a maximum firing rate of 492 tons/hour.  The boilers are
tangentially fired and have a furnace division wall extending from the bottom ash hopper to the
nose.  Furnace zones are referred to as Furnace A and Furnace B.  Each boiler has a total of 64
burners evenly divided among eight burner levels.  Because of the division wall, there are eight
burners per level:  four at the outside corners and four at the division wall corners.  Each boiler is
capable of producing 6,023,000 lb/hr of steam at 1000&#176;F and 2400 psi at turbine throttle
conditions.  Coal is provided to each burner level by a separate pulverizer, for a total of eight
pulverizers.  Each pulverizer is rated at 100 tons/hr, with six of the eight pulverizers normally
needed in service for full load, one in ready reserve standby, and one out for routine
maintenance.  Bottom ash is conveyed through a wet sluice system manufactured by United
Conveyor System.  The bottom ash is removed through one of two sluice lines fed from the three
bottom ash hoppers via one of six clinker grinders.<p>
<h3>Location of Ash Samples </h3>
     A total of four ash samples were collected by personnel of Arkansas Power &amp; Light (AP&amp;L),
a
subsidiary of Entergy, and shipped to the EERC for analysis.  The samples were collected at
strategic locations from the Unit 2 boiler after the explosion.  One sample was collected from the
slope tubes just above the Hopper C opening, and the other three samples were taken from
Hoppers A, B, and C.<p>
<h3>Appearance of Ash Samples</h3>

     All ash samples were visually inspected, and observations are summarized below.<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Furnace B sample.  This sample is brownish yellow (somewhat rusty) in color,
exhibiting an irregular, coarse surface typical of sintering ash particles.  <br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Hopper A sample.  This sample is light to dark brown in color and has a granular
(or sandlike) particle structure.  Throughout the sample, there are larger, friable agglomerations.  <br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Hopper B sample.  This sample is gray in color, with a uniform surface structure.
A cross-sectional view of the sample shows internal and external mineral structure to be similar. <br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Hopper C sample.  This sample is gray to dark black in color, with a somewhat
glassy appearance and a uniform surface structure.  A cross-sectional view of the sample shows internal and
external characteristics to be similar, but highlights the existence of large gas bubbles during formation.  <br> 
</ul>

 The EERC applied advanced analytical methods to investigate the characteristics of four ash
samples.  Analytical lab data/results for each sample were interpreted and studied in an attempt
to determine the mineral transformations that occurred during combustion and the conditions
under which the samples were formed.  Each sample was examined to determine its crystalline
and/or amorphous phases and chemical composition distribution.  The morphology of each
sample was investigated to determine the mechanism of formation (i.e., impaction, coalescence,
condensation) and the degree of sintering that occurred.  With these data and the chemical
composition data provided from microbeam analysis, the viscosity of each sample was calculated
for various compositions to determine the temperature under which the samples formed. 
Thermochemical equilibrium computer models were run under simulated combustion conditions
to support phase formation analysis.  <p>

     In short, the four samples analyzed contained no evidence of volatile components or explosive
matter that would have contributed to the explosion at the Independence Plant Unit Two boiler. 
In particular, there was no evidence of surface incorporation of carbon or reduced species, which
would indicate burner flameout or an unburned coal and/or a gasification zone.  However, such
evidence simply may not have been present in the samples received for investigation.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b> John H. Pavlish/<a href=mailto:jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5268<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  Entergy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  October 1993 to March 1994<br>
