<head>
<title>Combustion and Ash Characterization   of Selected Coals</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Combustion and Ash Characterization of Selected Coals </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Coal fly ash quality and consistency are of the utmost importance to successful commercial
marketing of fly ash.  It is well documented that coal fly ash characteristics vary with different
feed coals, utility systems, and operating parameters; however, coal fly ash characteristics can
be expected to be consistent within a range from a single electric generation facility given a
consistent feed coal.  Changes in coal type or characteristics have the potential to greatly
impact the characteristics of the coal by-products produced.  Since coal fly ash is the most
commonly utilized by-product, the characteristics, quality, and consistency of that specific
material are very significant to the coal by-product industry.  Changes in the quality of the
coal fly ash are a concern to both the producer and marketer.  Historical evidence has shown
that the unsuccessful use of coal fly ash has a broad-reaching impact on the coal fly ash market
within a region.  Since changes in the coal result in changes in the by-products, it is a
reasonable precaution to pretest a coal for ash production prior to implementing its use by a
station currently utilizing and marketing its by-products.  Characteristics and utilization of coal
fly ash are widely researched, and numerous publications are available on a wide variety of
applications.  The most common use of coal fly ash is in cement and concrete products.<p>

     The Rosebud SynCoal Partnership produces a beneficiated coal (SynCoal) from a Montana
subbituminous coal for use in coal-fired electric utilities.  The Rosebud SynCoal Partnership
believes the SynCoal will provide benefits to the utilities when blended and combusted with
the subbituminous coal.  Rosebud SynCoal is produced from coal obtained from the Rosebud
mine.  Coal from the same mine and seam is utilized in the Montana Power Corette Station. 
The Corette Station coal fly ash is successfully marketed and used in Montana and throughout
the region.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project were to produce fly ash from the Rosebud SynCoal in a
bench-scale reactor at the EERC and to compare the characteristics of that fly ash to Corette
Station fly ash.<p>
     The EERC has bench-scale combustion facilities that can provide information regarding the
behavior of a fuel under specific combustion conditions.  One such bench-scale combustor, the
atmospheric drop-tube furnace (ADTF), can produce fly ash for chemical and mineralogical
characterization at a low cost.  The EERC has an experienced coal by-products research staff
familiar with these materials and conventional as well as advanced use applications.  <p>
<h3>Results</h2>
     Limited chemical and mineralogical characterization techniques applied to the Rosebud SynCoal
ash produced in the ADTF provided information to indicate the potential impact on utilization of
ash produced at a pulverized coal-fired unit using Rosebud SynCoal blended with subbituminous
coal.  The bulk chemical compositions of the SynCoal ash and the Corette fly ash are very
similar.  Some differences can be noted in the concentrations of the major components; however,
these differences are within the range typical over time in coal fly ash samples from a single
electric generation unit firing a single coal.  According to American Society for Testing and
Materials chemical specifications, the Corette fly ash chemical composition fits the Class C
designation, while the SynCoal ash fits the Class F designation.  The calcium content of both
materials, reported as CaO, is relatively high and indicates that these materials may have the
potential to be self-hardening or cementitious.  Cementitious behavior is typical of Class C fly
ash.  The qualitative, empirical hydration test performed indicated that the SynCoal ash as well
as the Corette fly ash may have some cementitious properties.  The empirical heat of hydration
test required a subjective evaluation of both heat generation and hardening, and the results should
only be given limited consideration.  The two materials did appear to behave similarly on
hydration, but larger quantities of ash should be evaluated in a more objective and quantitative
procedure to provide definitive information on the cementitious nature of the materials.  Overall,
the bulk chemical composition of the two ash samples was very similar, and the chemical
composition of the SynCoal ash is similar to other samples of low-rank coal fly ash represented
in the EERC's Coal Ash Properties Database (CAPD).
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Christopher J. Zygarlicke/<a href=mailto:czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu>czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5123<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> Rosebud SynCoal Partnership<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  June 1993 to September 1993<br>
