<html>
<head>
<title>Predicting Fireside Performance of
Powder River Basin Fuels</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Predicting Fireside Performance of Powder River Basin Fuels </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     Knowledge of the propensity of a coal to form fouling and slagging deposits in coal-fired utility
boilers is of great practical and economic interest to coal suppliers and users, particularly when a
new coal is being considered for use.  The EERC has developed a set of indices that are
calculated using a newly developed software package called Predictive Coal Quality Effects
Screening Tool (PCQUEST).  PCQUEST uses advanced coal analysis techniques to predict
fouling and slagging behavior without the necessity of expensive pilot- or full-scale test burns. 
PCQUEST was used in this project to evaluate the fireside performance of coals in pulverized
coal-fired boilers.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of the work performed here was to analyze several Powder River Basin (PRB)
coals and use the analyses for calculation of PCQUEST slagging and fouling indices.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Five PRB coals were evaluated for ash deposition behavior.  Coal samples were ground to a
standard combustion grind of 70%-80% -200 mesh and then analyzed using proximate/ultimate,
ash fusion, computer-controlled scanning electron microscopy (CCSEM), SEM image analysis
(SEM-IA), x-ray fluorescence (XRF), and chemical fractionation.<p>
     CCSEM yields information on the quantity and size distribution of mineral grains within the
coal, whereas  chemical fractionation quantifies the finest size fraction (less than 1 micron in diameter) of
minerals and other inorganic material in coal.  In general, the proximate/ultimate analysis and ash
fusion analyses were typical of  western subbituminous PRB coals.  XRF analysis showed that
silicon, aluminum, calcium, and sulfur are the dominant elements present, along with lesser
amounts of magnesium and iron.  Chemical fractionation results indicated that the bulk of the
calcium, magnesium, and sodium were organically bound.  A significant portion of potassium
and phosphorus was also organically bound, as was a small portion of iron and titanium. 
Approximately half of the total mineral content was equally divided between quartz and
kaolinite.  Montmorillonite, pyrite, and calcium-aluminum phosphate species were also present
in significant amounts. <p>
     The results of the preceding analyses were used to calculate fouling and slagging indices for the
coal samples.  High-temperature fouling indices indicated low to moderate fouling in the front of
the convective pass for all of the coals analyzed.  Low-temperature fouling was predicted to be
high for two of the coals.  Blends of the coals showing greater low-temperature deposit formation
with two of the low-fouling coals were nearly identical in predicted fouling and slagging
behavior.  The slagging indices, which are an indication of the slagging propensity in the lower
furnace box, indicated medium slagging potential for all of the coals.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Managers:</b>
<ul plain>
 Kevin C. Galbreath/<a href=mailto:kgalbreath@eerc.und.nodak.edu>kgalbreath@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b> Phone: </b> (701) 777-5127<br>
Christopher J.  Zygarlicke
/<a href=mailto:czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu> czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5123<br>
</ul>
<b>Sponsors:</b><ul plain> Associated Electric Cooperative, Inc.<br>
     Kerr-McGee Coal Corporation<br>
     Northern States Power Company<br>
</ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  August 1993 to June 1995  <br>
