<html>
<head>
<title>Combustion and Environmental Control
System Performance Evaluation</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Combustion and Environmental Control System Performance Evaluation </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background </h3>
     Information relating coal quality to the performance of boiler and environmental control
equipment is critical to both the coal producer and user.  Of particular concern is the impact of
coal mineral matter on boiler fouling and particulate emissions.  Pilot-scale testing can
significantly aid in developing needed information, but requires the existence of defined
correlations between pilot- and full-scale systems.  To assist electric utilities, industrial coal
users, and mining companies interested in coal combustion behavior, the EERC operates a
combustion test service to provide basic pilot-scale data on individual coals and coal blends.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The test service provides standardized test data that can be used to evaluate new coal supplies,
assess coal quality impacts on proposed and existing combustion systems, and predict the effects
of coal blending, switching, and beneficiation on combustor performance.  Services provided to
previous customers included the determination of ash-fouling rates and the strength,
composition, and structure of fouling deposits; the evaluation of the effectiveness of additives to
mitigate boiler tube and ash fouling; the evaluation of electrostatic precipitator (ESP)
performance; the evaluation of combustion characteristics of coal-water slurries; the
investigation of high-temperature baghouse operation and performance; the evaluation of sorbent
injection for SO<sub>2</sub> control; and the evaluation of flame stability as a function of swirl under full
load and turndown.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Combustion tests were performed on the EERC's combustion test facility (CTF), a bottom-fired,
refractory-lined furnace that generates between 130 and 160 scfm of flue gas, depending on the
firing rate.  Various combustion tests have been performed for the clients listed.  Since most of
the projects involved proprietary information, results of individual test programs cannot be
presented here.  The following is a general description of the procedures used to evaluate
combustion characteristics of solid fuels.  Although some of the procedures described do not
apply, coal-water fuels have also been evaluated extensively in the CTF.<p>
    To assess fouling potential, each fuel was fired at a rate sufficient to maintain a specified furnace
exit gas temperature and excess air level, usually between 2000&#176; and 2200&#176;F at 20% to 30%
excess air.  Fuel feed rates and air flows were adjusted accordingly to maintain the specified
operating conditions.  Fouling deposits were collected on steam-cooled probes for a duration of
5.25 hours on each fuel.  Typically, the deposits were removed, weighed, and analyzed using
standard ASTM techniques and advanced, scanning electron microscope (SEM) techniques. 
Deposit characteristics, composition and morphology were compared with fuel characteristics to
determine the transformations resulting in deposit growth and strength development.  The
majority of the more than 700 tests performed to date were performed to characterize the
differences between a baseline fuel and a new fuel or fuel blend.  Where appropriate, deposit
characteristics were compared with previous, nonproprietary results to give a relative indication
of fouling potential.  Pilot-scale deposits have compared favorably with those formed at full
scale.<p>
     To assess ESP performance, dust-loading measurements were taken at the inlet and exit of the
pilot ESP using EPA Method 5.  The pilot ESP is a single-wire, tubular precipitator that is 8 ft
tall.  A portion of the flue gas was diverted through the ESP to maintain a velocity of
approximately 5 ft/sec, resulting in a specific collection area of approximately 160 ft<sup>2</sup>/1000
acfm. 
The voltage was set at the maximum level attainable without sparkover, usually about 60 kV. 
Sampling was performed concurrently with fouling tests over a 5.25-hr test period.  Inlet and
outlet samples were isokinetically extracted simultaneously during each of three sampling
periods.  One of the inlet samples taken during each test was performed using a multicyclone to
establish the fly ash size distribution.  The ESP was rapped at the completion of each sample
period, and ash was collected in a hopper for analysis.  Similar to fouling deposits, ash samples
were submitted for standard ASTM analyses and advanced SEM analyses.  Fly ash resistivity
was determined by laboratory methods to determine resistivity as a function of temperature.<p>

     To assess flame stability, the standard burner was replaced by a secondary air swirl generator
designed to International Flame Research Foundation (IFRF) specifications.  The IFRF-type
burner uses movable blocks to impart a swirl to the secondary air.  Swirl is defined at the ratio of
radial momentum to axial momentum.  Swirl was adjusted to determine the range of stability for
each fuel at full load and turndown.  Measurements were taken at each swirl setting to establish
combustor operating conditions including air flow rates, fuel feed rates, gas composition, flame
temperature, and furnace wall heat flux.  Photographs of the flame were also taken at each setting
to provide a visual record of flame shape, location, and intensity.  Fly ash samples were collected
to establish carbon levels as a function of swirl setting.<p>
    Fuels tested have come from domestic and international sources and have represented all ranks of
coal (bituminous, subbituminous, and lignitic coals), as well as petroleum coke and other
process-derived fuels.  In addition to the standard tests described, special tests have also been
devised, such as a 100-hour test designed to investigate corrosion in conjunction with fouling and
ESP performance.  <p>
     Much of the current work has centered around the effects of fuel blending.  One ongoing project
is a multiclient joint venture to determine the effects on boiler operation of blending eastern
noncompliant bituminous coals with subbituminous coals from the Powder River Basin.  The
project will evaluate the effect of the blend on mill performance, flame stability, furnace wall
slagging, boiler tube ash fouling, and ESP performance.  There has also been considerable
interest in the utilization of petroleum coke as a supplemental fuel for power production. 
Combustion testing of petroleum coke has been performed on various blends with lignites and
subbituminous coals as well as at 100%.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Managers:</b>
<ul plain>
 Jay R. Gunderson</font>/<a href=mailto:jgunderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jgunderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5258<br>
Michael D.  Mann/<a href=mailtommann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5193<br>
</ul>
