<html>
<head>
<title>Slagging and Fouling Assessment of Coal
and Coal Chars</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Slagging and Fouling Assessment of Coal and Coal Chars</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     In the past several years, the Illinois Clean Coal Institute and the U.S. Department of Energy
(DOE) have funded research programs to produce premium liquids by the mild gasification of
coal.  The principal by-product is a char which still contains a considerable amount of sulfur. 
Reducing the sulfur level could create a market for the char as a utility fuel blend.  A program to
reduce the char sulfur level was instituted by the Illinois State Geological Survey (ISGS) through
an integrated process of physical coal cleaning, mild gasification, and char desulfurization.  A
portion of this program was an evaluation of the slagging and fouling propensity of the chars and
coal-char blends, which would impact their suitability as a fuel feedstock.<p>

     A coal and two coal-char blends were submitted by the ISGS for evaluation of their fouling and
slagging propensity.  The coal was an Illinois Basin coal designated IBC-102.  One of the
coal-char blends was made from this coal by a low-temperature oxidation process, followed by
blending with the original coal.  This blend was designated LTO char + IBC-102 blend.  The
second coal-char blend was produced by adding hydrated lime, oxidizing under
high-temperature conditions, and blending with the original coal.  This second char was
designated HSAHL CFCO char + IBC-102 coal.  For the purposes of this summary, the materials
are referred to as "coal," "LTO char blend," and "HSAHL char blend."  This project was
undertaken as a joint venture program in collaboration with the DOE Morgantown Energy
Technology Center.  <p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of the project was to evaluate the fouling and slagging propensity of the coal and
coal-char blends as part of a determination of the suitability of the coal-char blends as a utility
boiler feedstock.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The coal and blends were examined with conventional proximate/ultimate analysis, Malvern
particle sizing, and x-ray fluorescence analysis (XRFA), as well as by advanced
computer-controlled scanning electron microscopy (CCSEM).  Deposits from the coal and blends
were produced in an optical drop-tube furnace (ODTF) combustion facility.  Deposit growth
rates, sticking coefficients, and crushing strengths were determined under simulated fouling and
slagging conditions, and initial slagging temperatures were determined under simulated slagging
conditions.<p>
    The results of the analyses were used as input to PHOEBE, a program that predicts mineral
phases and viscosities as a function of temperature, based on equilibrium thermodynamics and
XRFA.  The coal composition data obtained from proximate/ultimate, XRF, and CCSEM
analysis were entered into an in-house EERC program which produces a fouling and slagging
index.  This index produces a unitless number indicative of the degree of fouling or slagging
propensity.  The index results were then compared with those of other Illinois Basin coals.  All
diagnostic tests and calculations showed that the HSAHL char blend would cause severe
slagging, high-temperature fouling and, possibly, low-temperature fouling problems.<p>
     The coal was seen to be slightly worse than the LTO char blend for slagging and high-temperature
fouling behavior.  Both the coal and LTO char blend slagging behaviors were
similar to that of an Illinois No. 6 coal and are controllable.  <p>
     If considered as a boiler feedstock, the LTO char blend would be the most attractive because of
lower slagging and fouling potential, lower sulfur content, and higher Btu content than the parent
coal.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Donald P. McCollor/<a href=mailto:dmccollor@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dmccollor@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5121<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b><ul plain>Illinois State Geological Survey<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> July 1993 to August 1993<br>
<hr>
