<html>
<head>
<title>Preparation and Combustion of
Yugoslavian Lignite</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Preparation and Combustion of Yugoslavian Lignite </h2></center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Coal-water fuels are the most promising of all alternative coal-based fuels.  The traditional
coal-exporting countries of East Central Europe have a strong interest in this new market for
coal.  Converting coal into an easily transported liquid fuel could make it an ideal candidate to
displace not only costly imported oil, but also the more polluting high-sulfur coal from other
mines in Eastern Europe.  The economic merits of coal-water fuels are attractive because on a
heating unit basis, coal is cheaper than oil.  The quasi-liquid form maintains that differential,
since the higher cost of dry bulk coal handling and storage is avoided.  The technology opens up
new markets to coal producers, while it offers price stability and security of supply for the fuel
end users.<p>
     Yugoslavia's interest in lignite-water fuel (LWF) stems from its involvement in an unusual
power project at Kovin in northern Serbia.  In the early 1980s, Electric Power of Serbia (EPS)
proposed constructing a 600-MW power plant that would be fueled by lignite found in deposits
along and under the Danube River.  Trial coal-dredging operations have successfully been
completed.  The government of Serbia and EPS have decided to continue developing the
dredging technique and investing in the mine over a 6-year period.<p>
     Since dredging methods produce a coal slurry containing 85% to 90% water, a consortium of
Yugoslavian companies has entered into a scientific agreement with the EERC to assess the
conversion of dredged lignite into a LWF using hot-water-drying (HWD) technology.  HWD is a
high-temperature, nonevaporative drying technique carried out under high pressure in water that
permanently alters the structure of low-rank coals.  Changes effected by the drying process
include irreversible removal of moisture, micropore sealing by tar, and enhancement of heating
value by removal of oxygen, thus enhancement of the slurrying ability of the coal with water.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of this project was to determine the response of Kovin lignite to physical cleaning
and hydrothermal treatment.  An assessment of the fuel performance was to be made, using an
integrated scenario that included cleaning prior to HWD in order to produce premium
replacement fuel for retrofitted oil-fired boiler systems.  The evaluation included combustion
characteristics and combustion efficiencies of the potential fuels.  The prospective fuel behavior
of the mixtures was also to be determined with respect to a review of the potential pipeline
system as well as a preliminary technical and economic evaluation for producing and
transporting HWD LWF from Kovin lignite.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Two lignite samples were received from the Danube dredging test area for bench-scale testing
using EERC equipment.  Physical cleaning results on one sample indicated a 51 wt% reduction
in ash content, with a 76 wt% yield for the lignite.  In addition, physical cleaning produced a
cleaned slurry that had a higher attainable solids loading than a raw, uncleaned coal slurry. 
Combustion studies were then performed on the raw and physically cleaned samples, with the
results indicating both samples were very reactive, making them excellent candidates for HWD. 
Bench-scale results showed that HWD increased energy densities of the two raw lignite samples
by approximately 63% and 81%.<p>
     An order-of-magnitude cost estimate was conducted by the EERC to evaluate the HWD and
pipeline transport of Kovin LWF to domestic and export markets in Europe and to determine
selling prices of the fuel.  The delivered selling price of LWF per MMBtu, assuming a 10%
return on investment, was estimated to be US$3.90, US$2.90, and US$2.55 for a 1-, 3-, and
5-MMton/yr plant, respectively.  Alternately, for these respective plant sizes, the delivered
selling price per ton was estimated at US$46.80, US$34.80, and US$30.60.  <p>
     The Yugoslavian energy sector has been devastated by ongoing war, reshuffling energy flows
into several separate zones.  Whatever the outcome of the civil war, major concerns will be,
again, imported oil and increasing environmental restrictions on conventional power plants. 
Accordingly, dredging and HWD now make LWF a viable fuel option for electric power
generation in Yugoslavia.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Chris M. Anderson/<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5120<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy/EERC Jointly Sponsored Research
Progam with the University of Novi Sad<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> October 1990 to December 1993<br>
<hr>
