<html>
<head>
<title>Lignite Resource Characterization and
Evaluation for Mitigation of Ash
Deposition</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2> Lignite Resource Characterization and Evaluation <br>for Mitigation of Ash Deposition </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The Montana-Dakota Utilities Co. (MDU) Coyote Station near Beulah, North Dakota, is a one-unit,
400-net-MW cyclone-fired boiler.  The unit has been experiencing costly ash slagging and
fouling.  The plant is a minemouth plant burning lignite from the Knife River Coal Mining
Company (KRCMC) Beulah mine, with no alternative fuel source.  The EERC is coordinating a
research effort to evaluate and optimize plant and mine operations with respect to ash-fouling
and slagging occurrences as they relate to characteristics inherently found in lignite from the
Beulah mine.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The overall goal of this project is to maximize the quality of the  coal delivered from the Beulah
mine and to minimize the slagging and fouling severity at the Coyote Station.  Two key
deliverables are required to meet this goal:  1) development of a reliable indicator and/or
predictor of coal quality in terms of fouling and slagging behavior and 2) identification of
optimum fuel blends and plant operating conditions and procedures that will minimize
problematic slagging and fouling.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     A planning meeting was held at the Coyote Station to coordinate a future on-line boiler test for
determining the root causes of problematic ash deposition at the station.  Boiler sampling
locations were identified during a lengthy boiler tour.  A boiler survey is being put together by
EERC engineers  and MDU operators to assess current boiler operation.  A site visit was also
made to the mine.  Several core samples of coal were acquired from KRCMC for two currently
mined pits.  The coals are representative of fuel that will be fed to the boiler within the next two
years.  Work has begun on devising an algorithm that will predict slagging and fouling potential
for coal, which corresponds to specific locations in the mine.  This algorithm will be used to
develop blending strategies and to institute planned, controlled fouling and slagging mitigation
measures.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Christopher J. Zygarlicke/<a href=mailto:czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu>czygarlicke@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5123<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b><ul plain>Knife River Coal Mining Company<br>
     Montana-Dakota Utilities Co.<br>
     North Dakota Industrial Commission<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br>
</ul>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> July 1995 to August 1996 <br>
