<head>
<title>Commercialization of the Controlled
Spontaneous Reactor</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Commercialization of the Controlled Spontaneous Reactor</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     A novel concept was developed during previous programs at the EERC.  This fuel upgrading
system takes advantage of several of the unique properties of western subbituminous coals and
lignites.  It is projected that this system, which can use low (stack)-temperature flue gas as the
primary working fluid, can be customized to serve a number of facilities as a primary fuel
conditioner.  The process centers around a controlled spontaneous reactor (CSR).<p>
     The system can be operated and controlled over a wide range of temperatures, and offers an
excellent opportunity to provide users of subbituminous and lignite coal with an effective,
inexpensive tool to accomplish the following:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  A fuel conditioner to regain unit capacity in bituminous units switching to
subbituminous coals</br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> A fuel conditioner to improve subbituminous coal accommodation in cyclone-fired
boilers designed for bituminous coals</br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Reburning for NO<sub>x</sub> control in cyclone-fired boilers</br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  A dryer for subbituminous coals and lignites<br>

 <IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> A fuel conditioner for all types of fluid-bed combustors (FBCs) to increase
capacity, provide greater fuel flexibility, and improve turndown, start-up, and shutdown characteristics<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Char production from subbituminous coals and lignites<br>
</ul>
In addition to the use of flue gas as the primary working fluid and operation over a wide range of
temperatures (100&#176;-1300&#176;F), the CSR has several unique characteristics:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Very high throughput--relatively small size<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Simplicity of operation and control<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">   A wide range of feedstock particle sizes (up to 4-in. top size) accepted<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Significant moisture reduction achievable at relatively low operating
temperatures<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Product particle size affected by design and operating parameters<br>
</ul>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The EERC has taken the CSR through the proof-of-concept stage and has a patent pending on the
technology.  The overall objective of the EERC and Otter Tail Power Company is the
commercialization of the CSR.  The steps by which this new technology can be moved in a
timely fashion from the proof-of-concept stage to and through installation and operation in a
commercial plant have been identified.  The objective of this effort is to ensure performance of
the necessary steps in an effort that develops a product to serve the widest possible market in the
most cost-effective manner (maximum attractiveness to utilities) and, upon completion of the
technical development program, results in a product that can quickly move into the marketplace. 
Specific goals of Phase I are to establish a vendor/manufacturer as a commercialization partner,
assess the market potential for the various applications, perform preliminary budgetary
calculations, and perform the first-level design effort for a pilot plant to develop scaleup data.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     One segment of the market targeted early in the program was cyclone-fired boilers.  These
boilers currently have limited options for NO<sub>x</sub> control, with the CSR potentially offering a low-cost
option. 
Current uncertainty in the regulatory statutes have caused this option to be
temporarily put on hold.  If regulations are put into effect for cyclones, over 100 units producing
over 26,000 MW of electricity will be affected.<p>
     The second segment of the market addressed was those utilities suffering derates as the result of
switching from bituminous to low-sulfur subbituminous coal.  It is anticipated that
approximately half of those utilities required to lower sulfur emissions to meet Phase I and II
standards will switch fuels.  The CSR will be an attractive option for regaining lost capacity at a
time when competition between power producers is increasing.<p>
     The EERC currently has not actively pursued markets for the other potential uses of the CSR.  A
pilot-scale design of a 3-ton/hr CSR has been completed.  This design not only provides the
flexibility to obtain the final data required for scaleup, but also integrates a test furnace to allow
testing of the reburn applications.<p>
     Otter Tail Power Company and the EERC are working together to find a partner to help
commercialize the CSR. <p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael D. Mann/<a href=mailto:mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5193 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> Otter Tail Power Company<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> September 1994 to December 1995<br>
<hr>
