<html>
<head>
<title> Mitigation of SO<sub>3</sub> During Combustion of
Venezuelan Flexicoke </title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Mitigation of SO<sub>3</sub> During Combustion of Venezuelan Flexicoke</h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The Lagoven Amuay refinery in Venezuela is one of the world's largest oil refineries. 
Processing of the crude at this facility produces a petroleum coke by-product that has a high ash
content composed mainly of vanadium and nickel.  The high vanadium content of the coke
makes it an attractive source of this element.  Past operations have generated massive quantities
of the high-vanadium-content coke, which are currently stockpiled at the refinery site.  To reduce
the stockpile, produce some process steam, and recover the vanadium in the coke, the refinery is
in the process of building two pulverized coke-fired boilers.  The fly ash generated will be
collected in a pulse-jet baghouse facility.  Previous work performed at the EERC determined the
combustion properties of the fuel, the ash fouling and slagging propensity, and the corrosion
potential during combustion.  The work also indicated a potentially troublesome application for a
baghouse, with very acidic ash species collected on the fabric filter and accumulated on metal
surfaces of the baghouse and postbaghouse ductwork.  The acidic ash species were the suspected
result of increased flue gas SO<sub>3</sub> content resulting from the presence of vanadium pentoxide in
the fly ash.  Vanadium pentoxide will act as a catalyst in the flue gas ductwork, converting SO<sub>2</sub>
to SO<sub>3</sub>.  Condensed acid species and vanadium sulfate compounds were found to have been
formed either prior to collection or upon reaction with flue gas SO<sub>2</sub>/SO<sub>3</sub> in the
baghouse.  <p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives </h2>
     The goals of this project were to determine the level of SO<sub>3</sub> present in the flue gas, its
mechanism of formation, and baghouse performance with and without using a hydrated lime sorbent precoat
for control of the flue gas SO<sub>3</sub> content.  Pilot plant studies and laboratory tests and analyses
were performed to fulfill project goals.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Two 100-hour tests were performed on the particulate test combustor (PTC) at the EERC
combustion pilot plant. During the first test, the flexicoke was fired to determine the baseline
concentrations of SO<sub>3</sub> and the collectibility of the fly ash in a pulse-jet baghouse.  Baghouse
operating parameters were established through discussions with the baghouse vendor, ABB
Environmental Systems.  Results indicated that the baghouse would perform adequately with no
hydrated lime precoat; however, levels of SO<sub>3</sub> generated were at or near their dew point at the
expected operating temperature of the baghouse.  During the second week of testing, hydrated
lime was used to precoat the fabric filters to capture the SO<sub>3</sub> in the flue gas, preventing these
species from corroding baghouse components.  Baghouse performance was shown to improve
with the precoat, and levels of flue gas SO<sub>3</sub> leaving the baghouse were reduced.  <p>
<p>
     Laboratory analyses were performed to provide insight into the mechanism of formation and also
to characterize fly ash properties.  Hygroscopicity testing was performed to determine the degree
to which the fly ash will sorb moisture from the air as a function of temperature.  The acidic
nature of these ash species had been shown to form sulfate hydrates that are very hygroscopic.  In
fact, a sample of dry ash exposed to ambient conditions in the combustion pilot plant sorbed
enough moisture from the atmosphere to form a liquid phase.  Therefore, the nature of the ash
will have a significant impact on ash-handling systems at the refinery.  In addition, the heat
capacity of the fly ash was also determined as a function of temperature for use in heat balances
surrounding the ash-handling system.  To determine the extent of SO<sub>3</sub> formation in the baghouse,
a series of laboratory tests were performed exposing the ash generated during pilot tests to a
constant SO<sub>2</sub> level.  Results indicated that SO<sub>3</sub> can be formed at normal baghouse
operating  temperatures from the catalytic reaction of SO<sub>2</sub> over a supported  vanadium catalyst
(fly ash held by the fabric filters).  For this reason, it was recommended that periodic injection of the sorbent
be performed at full scale to capture any SO<sub>3</sub> present in the flue gas entering the baghouse and
that portion generated in the baghouse. 
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Jay R. Gunderson/<a href=mailto:jgunderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jgunderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5258<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li> PDVSA, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>September 1994 to May 1995<br>
<hr>
