<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000277-B036-341</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.eerc.und.nodak.edu:80/9395bien/p160.htm 134.129.141.26 19970113181630 text/html 8890
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:20:48 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 02-May-96 20:51:45 GMT
Content-length: 8700
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Power Generation from an Alaskan
Low-Rank Coal-Water Fuel (Little Tonzona Creek Coal)</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1> Power Generation from an Alaskan Low-Rank Coal-Water Fuel (Little Tonzona Creek Coal)  </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Alaska's estimated coal resources total over 5 trillion tons.  Almost all those of immediate
significance, those close to year-round ports or to the Alaskan Railroad, are low-rank coals
(LRCs).  Like their counterparts worldwide, Alaskan LRCs suffer from high inherent moisture,
which usually restricts their use and has, until the breakthrough in LRC beneficiation technology
at the EERC, prevented their use in the expanding coal-water fuel (CWF) market.  Conventional
evaporative drying processes are useful only if the dried coal is used immediately; otherwise
moisture reabsorption or severe handling problems arise, including dust generation and
spontaneous combustion.  The extremely low sulfur content of most Alaskan coals, usually
below 0.2 wt%, would make them a highly sought fuel if they could be converted into
concentrated CWFs or stable, dried LRC aggregates.<p>
<p>
     Hot-water drying (HWD) is a nonevaporative drying process that offers an efficient means to
dewater LRCs while producing a safe, easily transported liquid fuel.  HWD is a high-temperature/high-pressure
process that causes chemical changes, reducing the equilibrium
moisture levels in LRCs to levels comparable to those of bituminous coals.  HWD enables the
production of low-rank coal-water fuels (LRCWFs) with solids loadings rivaling those made
from high-rank coals and with energy densities approaching those of the raw coals, without the
requirement for costly additives.<p>
     LRCWFs are designed to replace heavy oil and/or bituminous CWF in existing oil-fired boilers,
not to replace bulk steam coal.  The use of CWFs is being aggressively pursued by both Japan
and Korea to produce a lower-cost, more stable supply of liquid fuel.  The magnitude of the
potential market for CWFs can be gauged by the consumption levels of heavy oil in electric
utilities in Japan, Korea, and Taiwan alone.  In 1990, the combined total of 200 million barrels of
oil used by utilities in these countries was equivalent to about 80 million tonnes of LRCWF.  In
addition to the enormous export market potential, there is a growing need to develop a low-cost
substitute for the costly, highly subsidized fuel oil used in remote North American communities.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives of the first phase of the project were to determine the technical feasibility of
producing clean-burning LRCWF from Beluga Coal Company's subbituminous coal, located
west of Anchorage, Alaska; to assess the process economics and export market potential; and to
design a commercial demonstration program.  The second-phase objectives were to assess the
potential of HWD interior Alaskan LRCs to produce stable bulk coal and/or LRCWF, to
determine the combustion efficiencies of the beneficiated coal, and to assess transportation
options for remote Alaskan applications.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
<h3>Phase 1</h3>
<p>
     The technical feasibility of producing a premium LRCWF from the Beluga coal was
demonstrated in the EERC HWD pilot plant.  The LRCWF was tested in the EERC combustion
test facility, giving almost complete carbon burnout, low boiler tube fouling, and SO<sub>2</sub> emissions
well below even the most stringent air quality standards.  A preliminary economic assessment
indicates that Alaskan LRCWFs could be delivered to Japan at costs well below those for
imported fuel oil and competitive with imported bituminous CWFs made in China.  Based on
these encouraging economics, the Alaskan Low-Rank Coal Consortium was formed by the
EERC, Hobbs Industries, Inc., and Usibelli Coal Mine, Inc., and has developed a program to
demonstrate the technology in a small commercial power station in Anchorage, Alaska. 
Cofunding for the demonstration project is being sought from the state of Alaska, the Department
of Energy, and a number of private end users in Hawaii and the Pacific Rim countries. <p>
<p>
<h3>Phase 2</h3>
<p>
     A team composed of the EERC, the Mineral Industry Research Laboratory (MIRL) of the
University of Alaska- Fairbanks, Doyon, Ltd., an ANCSA Corporation, and the Alaska Division
of Energy, formerly the Alaska Energy Authority, has initiated characterization and HWD tests
of Doyon's Little Tonzona Coalfield (LTC) coal, a subbituminous coal from Alaska's interior.<p>
<p>
    After field work by Doyon, Ltd., and MIRL, bench-scale testing was performed at the EERC
with the following conclusions:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The easily recovered reserves in the LTC coal are sufficient to warrant continued
efforts on Doyon's part to use LTC as a fuel for local boilers.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  It would be feasible to develop a small, local mine to supply several villages near
the LTC.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Use of a local indigenous fuel would significantly lessen the impact of the loss of
Power Cost <br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Equalization subsidies, while providing additional jobs in the region.<br> 
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Most of the ash in LTC coal is inherent rather than extraneous and, therefore, 
not easily removed by conventional physical cleaning techniques.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> LTC coal responded well to HWD, and LRCWFs with solids content over 60% were
easily achievable.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  LTC, with or without HWD, showed high reactivity and nearly complete carbon
burnout even at reduced residence times in the drop-tube furnace.<br>
</ul>
<p>
     Approximately 600 kg of LRCWF made from HWD LTC coal was produced in the EERC
7.5-ton/day continuous HWD unit.  Results from pilot-scale HWD indicated a reduction in
equilibrium moisture from 30 to 16 wt%, with the heating value increasing from 7080 to 9400
Btu/lb and the LRCWF energy density improving by over 36%.  Bench-scale HWD results had
indicated an energy density increase of 45% for similar temperature and pressure treatment.  The
difference was caused by the extended residence time above 200&#176;C for bench-scale testing.<p>
<p>
     Pilot-scale testing in the CTF indicated excellent combustion properties, with carbon conversion
greater than 99.25%.  The fouling deposits collected were very low in weight and indicated a
very low fouling potential for the Little Tonzona CWF.  The low fouling potential was attributed
to the low sodium content of the CWF. <p>
<p>
     Sulfur dioxide emissions were reported at 1025 ppm (1.94 lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu).  Compared with
the input sulfur content of 2.63 lb of SO<sub>2</sub>/MMBtu, there is an apparent 26% sulfur retention in
ash.  NO<sub>x</sub> emissions were recorded at 531 ppm (0.72 lb of NOx/MMBtu) and indicate the
potential for higher NO<sub>x</sub> levels at full scale.  Electrostatic precipitator (ESP) performance tests
indicated a somewhat lower collection efficiency (98.66%) for Little Tonzona CWF.  This most
likely reflects the low sodium content of the fuel (0.2% Na<sub>2</sub>O in ash) and the small size of the
pilot-scale ESP (SCA=159 ft<sup>2</sup>/1000 acfm).  It is recommended that care be taken to adequately
size the full-scale ESP or provide for SO<sub>2</sub> conditioning.<p>
<p><br><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Chris M. Anderson/<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.educ>anderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5120<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b><ul plain>
U.S. Department of Energy/EERC Jointly Sponsored Research
Program with University of Alaska- Fairbanks, Alaska<br>
Department of Community and Regional Affairs<br>
 Division of Energy (formerly the  Alaska  Energy
Authority)<br>
</ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
 July 1990 to June 1994 <br>
