<head>
<title>Fuel Evaluation for Fluidized-Bed</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Fuel Evaluation for Fluidized-Bed Combustion</h2> </center> 

<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The design fuel and any potential fuels that may be used in an atmospheric fluidized-bed
combustor (AFBC) system must be specified prior to the design of the system, as fuel
properties can have a significant impact on design and operation.  These design-point
conditions can be projections from pilot-scale tests, extrapolations from similar fuels or
systems, or copies of existing successful systems.  Care must be taken to ensure that the fuel
system is designed to handle not only the typical properties of a particular coal supply, but
also the extremes.  With proper information, experienced designers and operators can exercise
independent control of many parameters to achieve desired performance and costs, while
taking into account fuel type and fuel properties.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The overall objectives of this program are to perform test burns to obtain information for the
design of new units, to provide air and solid waste emission data for permitting, to evaluate
the impact of switching fuel or limestone type in an existing unit, and/or to investigate and
resolve a particular operating problem.  The test burn can be performed in either a bubbling or
circulating mode.  The objectives of the test burns performed included  1) obtaining
information to finalize a design for contracted units, 2) obtaining design information for
feasibility studies, 3) generating design information to issue bid specifications and start the
permitting process, and 4) evaluating the impact of switching fuels in an existing unit.  <p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     For each test, fuel and limestone are shipped to Grand Forks from the mine to supply the
proposed or operating plant.  Test burns are typically 120 hours in length and include several
different test periods, as specified by the client.  To quantify the effect of FBC design and
operating parameters and the effects of fuel and sorbent properties, a number of important
performance variables are measured.  Environmental performance is evaluated by measuring
sorbent addition and utilization to achieve the designed SO<sub>2</sub> control; NO<sub>x</sub>,
N<sub>2</sub>O, and CO emissions; particulate collectability; and waste characterization and disposal. 
Evaluation of thermal performance is accomplished through measurement of combustion efficiency; heat flux;
moisture, ash, and sorbent thermal losses; and fouling in the convective pass.  Operational performance is
qualitatively assessed by examining for fouling and deposition on heat-transfer surfaces, agglomeration or
sintering of ash or bed material, changes in coal or ash particle size, and evidence of erosion or corrosion. 
Detailed final reports are prepared that can be used to complete feasibility studies, to issue to vendors for bed
specifications, or to use in obtaining environmental permits.  Tests can be performed in either bubbling or
circulating test units.  Fuels evaluated include all ranks of coal from the United States, lignites from Pakistan
and Thailand, petroleum coke, and wood.<p> 

     Examples of recently completed projects are summarized below:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Wisconsin Electric Power Company (WEPCO) commissioned two test burns in the
EERC circulating fluidized-bed combustor (CFBC) facilities to generate emissions data and ash samples to aid in
permitting a power plant repowering project.  WEPCO estimated a $7.1 million savings in capital cost, schedule
reduction, and reduced operator risk resulting from the pilot plant testing.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand  used the EERC CFBC for a test
burn to determine the feasibility of burning Mae Moh lignite using CFB technology.  To date, two units of 300
MW each are under construction, with several more in the planning stage.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Suncor, Inc./CU Power Canada, Ltd., used the EERC CFBC facilities for a test burn
of their petroleum coke to obtain solid samples and emissions data to support permitting activities.  Several
boiler vendors had representatives on sight to observe and obtain information to use in formulating their
proposals to Suncor.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The County Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County used the EERC CFBC to
generate solid samples for support in permitting activities for its CFBC boilers designed to burn dried municipal
sewage sludge and to gain engineering and operating data on the combustion characteristics of their
fuel.<br>
</ul>
<hr>
Project Manager: Michael D. Mann/<a href=mailto:mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5193<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b><ul plain>
Burns and Roe, Inc.<br>
     Combustion Systems, Inc.<br>
     Community Energy Alternatives, Inc.<br>
     Foster Wheeler Energy Corporation<br>
     Iowa Energy Policy Council<br>
     Northern States Power Company<br>
     Stanley Consultants, Inc.<br>
     Suncor, Inc./CU Power Canada, Ltd.<br>
     Valmont Industries, Inc.<br>
     Wisconsin Electric Power Company<br>
     U.S. Department of Agriculture<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br>
</ul>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>  August 1989 to Present <br>
