<head>
<title>Fluidized-Bed Combustion Deposition
and Agglomeration</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Fluidized-Bed Combustion Deposition and Agglomeration</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Agglomeration and deposition in fluidized-bed combustors (FBCs) have been noted by users of
several different FBC designs firing a number of different fuels.  These ash-related phenomena
have been shown to cause a loss in steam temperature, operating difficulties and, in some
cases, unplanned shutdowns.  To predict and ultimately mitigate ash-related problems,
information must be gathered on the abundance and association of ash-forming constituents in
the fuel and the ash transformations that occur under the typical operating conditions of the
fluid bed.  Responding to these needs, the EERC has begun a 3-year program to determine the
factors that influence ash partitioning, agglomerate formation, ash deposition on heat-transfer
tubes and refractory, and deposit strength development.  The ultimate goal is to develop a
method to aid in the prediction of ash behavior prior to firing the fuel in an actual system and
to provide methods to reduce or mitigate agglomeration and deposition associated with
problem fuels.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The overall objective of this program is to advance the knowledge of ash behavior in FBCs so
that methods can be generated to predict and ultimately mitigate ash-related problems in FBCs. 
Specific goals are as follows:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  To determine the mechanisms of inorganic transformation that lead to inorganic
partitioning, ash deposition, and bed material agglomeration<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To determine the factors that influence the sintering behavior and strength
development of agglomerates and deposits under FBC conditions<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To develop a means of predicting the behavior of inorganic components as a
function of fuel composition and bed material selection<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To develop methods that can be used to reduce or mitigate ash-related problems
associated with particular fuels<br>
</ul>
<h3>Results</h3>
     During the first two years of this program, a number of major activities were completed. 
Highlights include the following:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> A sampling protocol was developed that provides FBC operators with a
systematic method for determining the source of their ash-related problems.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Samples were collected from three full-scale FBCs.  Analyses of these samples
were used to determine the mechanisms causing the ash-related problems and to validate the work being
performed at the bench scale.<br>

<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> A bench-scale reactor was built to provide a cost-effective method of
determining the ash-related problems with particular fuels prior to firing them in full-scale units.<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Bench-scale testing was performed to determine mechanisms and rate of
deposition of agglomeration as a function of fuel variables and operating conditions.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Computer models are being developed that can be used to determine relative
differences in deposition and agglomeration tendencies.<br>
</ul>
     Preliminary conclusions derived from the first two years of this program are as follows:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The mechanisms of adherence and growth of deposits and agglomerates appear
to be via a molten sulfate matrix, through the fluxing action of sodium with calcium.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> There is a definite interaction between the bed material and the ash that forms
agglomerates.  Proper selection of bed material is one potential method of mitigating agglomeration.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Factors which enhance the formation of agglomerates include local reducing
conditions in the bed, high temperature, increased pressure, and the presence of a fluxing agent.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Methods to predict the effect of coal properties and operating conditions on
deposition for conventional coal-fired systems can be tailored to predict problems in FBCs. 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael D. Mann/<a href=mailto:mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5193<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b><ul plain>Ahlstom Pyropower, Inc.<br>
     DB Riley Stoker Corporation<br>
     Electric Power Research Institute<br>
     ND State Industrial Commission<br>
     Northern States Power Company<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> September 1992 to August 1995<br>
