<head>
<title>Sorbent Regeneration from CFBC</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Sorbent Regeneration from CFBC</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The use of circulating fluidized-bed combustors (CFBCs) is an efficient method for burning
high-sulfur fuels to meet stringent SO<sub>2</sub> requirements.  One concern when burning
high-sulfur coal is the large volume of limestone required and, consequently, the relatively large
amounts of solid waste for disposal.  Community Energy Alternatives (CEA) is the operator of
several CFBC facilities in California that use petroleum coke as fuel.  CEA conceived a process to
significantly increase the 30% to 50% utilization of the available calcium in the limestone for a
once-through system.  This two-step process involves regeneration of spent bed material and
pelletization of fly ash, with recycle of these materials back to the CFBC.<p> 
     Iowa State University (ISU) and Argonne National Laboratory have demonstrated a process to
convert CaSO<sub>4</sub> to CaO.  The process uses a fluid-bed reactor and has been
demonstrated to recover SO<sub>2</sub> and lime from waste gypsum.  A regenerator based on
this process coupled with the EERC CFBC pilot plant system was used to investigate the regeneration
and recycling of the spent sorbent bed material.  Regeneration allowed the reduction of waste by a
factor of 15, compared to a maximum of about 3 times with a recycling process.  Petroleum coke
was a good candidate for this process, because of its high sulfur content and low ash content. 
Reducing limestone consumption was especially attractive, both economically and environmentally,
with a high-sulfur fuel.  Low amounts of ash allow for less dilution and potential interference for
regeneration of the bed material composed mostly of calcium sulfate.<p> 
     To ensure that all of the limestone is utilized in the CFBC, the portion that escapes with the fly
ash must be collected and processed in such a way that it is a usable sorbent material.  If
recycled as fine fly ash, the material would simply blow out of the system again, without a
chance for any significant sulfation.  To further maximize the use of material, fly ash can be
pelletized before it is fed back into the CFBC.  The EERC also studied how pelletizing could
be used to make the recycling and regeneration process more efficient.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project were to 1) demonstrate the sulfation capacity of pelletized fly ash
pellets compared to limestone while burning petroleum coke; 2) design, construct, and test a
regenerator meeting CEA specifications based upon EERC results from Phase 1 testing along
with available design information from ISU; and 3) perform testing with the EERC CFBC pilot
plant system to investigate the regeneration potential, incorporating the elements of CFBC
operation, fly ash pelletizing, bed material regeneration, and the overall recycling process.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Testing proceeded in three phases.  During Phase 1, the EERC successfully demonstrated the
effectiveness of pelletizing and recycling fly ash for reducing limestone consumption and solid
waste disposal by over 25%.  For Phase 2, a bubbling FBC was successfully modified and tested
for use as a fluidized-bed material regenerator.  For Phase 3, cyclic operation of the CFBC,
pelletizer, and regenerator was investigated, demonstrating a potential reduction in limestone
consumption ranging from 65% to 85% for five cycles of testing.<p>
     Fluid petroleum coke and limestone used for all EERC testing for CEA were from the same
source as that utilized by CEA's GWF Power Systems (GWF) CFBC facilities.  Based upon the
success of Phase 1 testing with pellets made from GWF fly ash, Phase 1B testing proceeded
using the fly ash generated during combustion in the EERC 1-MWth CFBC.  The fly ash was
collected, pelletized, and recycled back to the CFBC to enhance the sorbent utilization.  Using
only limestone for sulfur capture to establish a baseline condition, 0.37 lb of limestone per lb of
coke (Ca/S of 3.1) was required to achieve 89.9% retention of the sulfur in the coke.  For the
fourth cycle, using EERC fly ash pellets, the limestone consumption was reduced by 21.6% to
0.29 lb of limestone per lb of coke to achieve 91.7% sulfur retention (Ca/S of 2.7).<p>
     Phase 2 shakedown conditions for the regenerator were selected to obtain optimal removal of
sulfur from the sulfated bed material.  Shakedown tests were successfully conducted with EERC
bed material from Phase 1B testing and then with GWF bed material.  This resulted in about 90%
conversion of calcium sulfate to calcium oxide for both types of bed material tested.<p>
     For Phase 3 testing, each CFBC test cycle was approximately 24 hours in duration.  The spent
bed material and fly ash collected from any given cycle were respectively regenerated and
pelletized during the following 24 hours before being reintroduced back into the CFBC for
additional sulfur capture.  Fly ash was pelletized in the same manner as for Phase 1B testing. 
Regenerator thermocouple failures were numerous and at times difficult to detect.<p>
     Baseline limestone usage for Phase 3 was 0.31 lb of limestone per lb of coke (Ca/S of 2.9),
achieving 89.6% sulfur retention.  During the fourth cycle of testing, limestone consumption was
reduced 85.5% to 0.045 lb of limestone per lb of coke (nearly a sevenfold reduction in limestone
consumption) when fly ash pellets and regenerated bed material were used to achieve 89.3%
sulfur retention at a total Ca/S ratio of 3.9.  Although the pilot-scale tests clearly demonstrated a
significant reduction in limestone consumption by combining fly ash pelletization and bed
material regeneration, it is doubtful that the test was of long enough duration to reach a true
steady-state condition.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Douglas R. Hajicek/<a href=mailto:dhajicek@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dhajicek@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5172<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> <ul plain> Community Energy Alternatives, Inc.<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1993 to September
1993<br>
