<html>
<head>
<title>Test Burn of Dried Municipal Sewage Sludge</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Test Burn of Dried Municipal Sewage Sludge </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The County Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County (CSDLAC) has three Babcock and
Wilcox (B&amp;W) circulating fluidized-bed (CFB) boilers designed to burn dried municipal
sewage sludge (DMSS).  Representative solid samples generated from combustion of DMSS in
the boilers were required for analysis in support of CSDLAC permitting activities.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives of this project were to generate solid samples under representative CFB test
conditions for solid waste disposal characterization to support CSDLAC solid waste permitting
activities and provide engineering and operating data on the combustion characteristics of the
fuel.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     The EERC successfully conducted a test burn with its 1-MW pilot-scale CFB combustor using
DMSS supplied by CSDLAC.  Three complete sets of solid samples at different operating
conditions were obtained and analyzed according to U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
guidelines.  Overall, good results were obtained for fuel combustion efficiency, operational
and thermal performance, and flue gas emissions.<p>
<p>
     Bed inventory control is an important parameter with DMSS.  Because the configuration of the
B&amp;W boilers that will burn this fuel is designed to operate with a relatively high percentage of
secondary air, the ratio of bottom ash to total ash will also be high, based on the results seen
at the EERC.  In general, the higher the cyclone efficiency, the greater the bottom ash removal
rates.<p>
<p>
     Combustion temperature control will have a significant effect on emissions.  Both
SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub> emissions increased with increasing temperature
during the EERC test burn.  Sulfur retention of 94% could be achieved at high temperatures, but a
much greater calcium-to-sulfur ratio is required.<p>
<p>
     Temperature is also an important factor during start-up.  For the EERC test, fuel feed was
initiated at a combustor temperature of 770&#176;F, which is near the limit of the unit's preheat
capabilities.  The fuel burned readily, but the resulting odor was unpleasant until the
combustor temperature reached about 1100&#176;F. Starting fuel feed at a higher furnace
temperature would alleviate the odor problem.<p>
<p>
     Based on ash-fouling probe temperatures during the run and postrun inspections of the ash-fouling
section, there appeared to be some deposition on the probes early in the run, but the
deposits that formed during this test dropped off under their own weight.  At full scale,
sootblowing may be required to keep boiler tubes clean.  There was no evidence of
agglomeration in the drained bed material or upon postrun inspection of the combustor and
external heat exchanger distributor plates.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Douglas R. Hajicek/<a href=mailto:dhajicek@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dhajicek@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5172<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> 
County Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
October 1993 to May 1994<br>
