<html>
<head>
<title>Investigation of Tidd PFBC
Agglomeration :  Chemical
Characterization</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Investigation of Tidd PFBC Agglomeration:  Chemical Characterization </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     American Electric Power Service Corporation (AEP) and Ohio Power Company observed that
egg-shaped agglomerates formed during operation of the pressurized fluidized-bed combustor
(PFBC) at the Tidd Station PFBC demonstration plant.  A few of these agglomerates formed
during a majority of the testing when dolomite was used as a sorbent.  The agglomerates could
be removed from the bed using the normal bed drain without causing major operational
problems due to poor fluidization quality.  In contrast, when the sorbent type was switched to
limestone, these egg-shaped agglomerates formed at a much higher rate, causing a decrease in
fluidization quality that eventually led to shutdown of the unit.  Severe agglomeration was also
noted with the dolomite sorbent when the unit was operated at full load.  The EERC
performed a detailed chemical characterization of material from the Tidd PFBC.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The overall objective of this project was to perform a detailed chemical characterization of
material from the Tidd Station PFBC to determine the mechanisms of formation of the
agglomerates and the differences between the limestone and dolomite sorbents.<p>
<h3>Results </h3>
     To develop a good understanding of the problem, the coal, sorbents, eggs, and spent-bed material
were characterized.  Analyses were performed on the fuel, limestone, dolomite, spent bed
material, and dolomite and limestone eggs.  After the chemical analyses were completed, an
interpretation was made.  This interpretation focused on the chemical composition on a
microscopic scale of the dolomite and limestone eggs.  Some limited thermochemical
equilibrium work was performed to look at the free lime, CO<sub>2</sub>, and the water-vapor
reactions that had been proposed by others.  This work involved finding appropriate phase
equilibrium diagrams to model the system and evaluating the fit of the AEP data.  Some detailed 
modeling  was performed using PHOEBE, a computer modeling program for complex
gas/liquid/solid phases.  The potential cause for differing degrees of agglomeration between dolomite
and limestone was identified, and mitigating measures were recommended.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b> Project Manager:</b>  Michael D. Mann/<a href=mailto:mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5193<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> American Electric Power Service   
Corporation<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  October 1993 to February 1994
<br>
