<html>
<head>
<title>Transport Reactor Demonstration Unit</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Transport Reactor Demonstration Unit </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Integrated gasification combined-cycle (IGCC) electricity generating plants are currently under
development to provide a clean, highly efficient coal-fueled generating option.  The gasifier
system converts coal into a clean, combustible gas that fuels a combustion turbine.  The
combustion turbine exhaust heat is used to produce steam, which drives a steam turbine
generator.  The primary area of integration involves the recovery and transfer of heat from the
gasifier syngas coolers to the combined cycle block.  In addition to the heat recovery system,
the gasifier section also contains a raw gas cleanup section that includes particulate and sulfur
removal systems.  <p>
    In order to provide process and mechanical data for the development and scaleup of hot-gas
cleanup devices, a nominally 2-ton/hr gasification facility with hot-gas cleanup capability was
constructed and operated at Wilsonville, Alabama.  The gasifiers that were under consideration
were the KRW fluidized-bed gasifier and the transport gasifier.  The transport technology is
based on a high-velocity circulating fluidized-bed reactor being developed by M.W. Kellogg. 
The EERC constructed and operated a 200-lb/hr intermediate-scale transport reactor
demonstration unit (TRDU) to provide the engineering information used in the Wilsonville
gasifier design.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The overall objective of this program was to obtain scalable kinetic, hydrodynamic, and
integrated data from the TRDU for the design of the transport reactor that was to be built in
Wilsonville, Alabama.  The TRDU was to address the two-stage gasification-adiabatic dense-phase
mixing
concepts.  The six parameters that were to be studied included temperature, riser
density, calcium-to-sulfur ratios, coal feed size, coal feed staging, and riser gas velocity.  The
parameters were to be compared to overall gasifier operation.  <p>
<h3>Results</h2>
     The TRDU was installed and two extended shakedown runs occurred.  The unit was operated
in combustion mode during heatup and gasification mode using Wyodak coal.
<hr>
<b> Project Manager</b>: Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> <ul plain>Electric Power Research Institute<br>
U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br></ul> 
<b>Duration of Project:</b> February 1992 to September
1994<br>
