<head>
<title>Hot-Gas Filter Testing</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Hot-Gas Filter Testing</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h2>
     The U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center (METC) has a Hot-Gas
Cleanup (HGC) program intended to develop and demonstrate gas stream cleanup options
for use in combustion- and/or gasification-based advanced power systems.  One objective of
the METC HGC program is to support the development and demonstration of barrier filters to
control particulate matter.  The goal is not simply to meet current New Source Performance
Standards (NSPS) with respect to particulate emissions, but also to protect high-efficiency gas
turbines adequately and control particulate emissions to sufficiently low levels to meet more
stringent regulatory requirements anticipated in the future.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The objective of this work is to demonstrate acceptable performance of hot-gas filter elements
in a pilot-scale system prior to long-term demonstration tests.  The general approach is a
phased effort involving modifications and upgrades to the existing transport reactor
demonstration unit (TRDU) and the assembly, installation, and operation of a filter vessel
capable of operating at elevated temperatures and pressures.  This filter vessel will be used in
combination with the TRDU in order to evaluate the performance of selected hot-gas filter
elements for gasification applications.<p>
     The primary focus of the experimental effort will involve testing hot-gas filter elements. Filter
element performance will be evaluated as a function of particulate collection efficiency, filter
differential pressure, filter cleanability, and durability as a result of short-term operation
(&lt;200 hours).<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Phase I and II efforts are currently ongoing.  Phase I efforts are focused on upgrading the TRDU
based on past operating experiences.  Additions and upgrades being installed include a nitrogen
supply system purge, LASH auger, coal feed line, coal hopper system, disengager, seventh-floor
addition, J-leg fluffing gas system, and other minor subsystems.  Instrumentation upgrades will
be conducted in order to integrate the hot-gas filter system.<p>
     Phase II includess filter vessel assembly and installation.  Design of the filter vessel is complete. 
The completed system will include a filter vessel capable of operating at elevated temperatures
(1650&3176;F) and pressures (130 psig), heat-transfer requirements to control gas stream
temperature at the inlet to the filter vessel, ports for sampling HAPs, and options for varying
particulate mass loading to the filter vessel.  The initial piping design will allow operation of the filter
vessel system at temperatures ranging from 1000&#176;-1300&#176;F.<p>
   Phase III, which is planned for the fall of 1995, will be the first hot-gas filter test using the
TRDU operated in a gasification mode.  Filter elements from Industrial Filter &amp; Pump, 3M
Company, and Pall Advanced Filter Technologies will be tested.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael D. Mann/<a href=mailto:mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5193<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> December 1994 to December
1995<br>
