<html>
<head>
<title>Hot-Gas Cleanup</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Hot-Gas Cleanup </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) is promoting the development of coal-based advanced
power systems under the direction of the Morgantown Energy Technology Center (METC). 
This activity covers a broad range of technologies involving combustion, gasification, and the
integration of combustion and gasification technologies. The objective is to maximize cycle
efficiencies and to provide for a stable, secure, and environmentally sound energy future.<p>
     Specific combustion program areas include the development of heat engines such as direct
coal-fired turbines and diesels and pressurized fluidized-bed combustors (PFBC).  Gasification
technology development includes mild gasification for coproducts and hydrogen and methane
production for fuel cell applications.  Integrated gasification combined-cycle (IGCC)
technology promotes high cycle efficiencies by combining coal gasification with direct product
gas firing in turbines.  In all these cases, hot-gas cleanup systems are required to achieve
acceptable process performance and to meet current and future environmental emission
standards.<p>
<h2>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project at the EERC were to design and build a bench-scale hot-gas filter
vessel to be operated in conjunction with the bench-scale pressurized fluid-bed reactor (PFBR),
to design and build a hot-gas sampling system to be used in conjunction with bench- and pilot-scale
advanced
systems currently in operation at the EERC, to design and initiate construction
of a pilot-scale hot-gas filter vessel to be operated in conjunction with one of two pilot-scale
gasification systems, to determine and model the various ash-alkali corrosion mechanisms for
ceramic barrier filter materials, and to develop corrosion-mitigating options.  The
corrosion-mitigating options
focused primarily on gettering techniques.  Eventually these techniques will
be verified at the pilot scale using a hot-gas filter vessel.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The bench-scale filter vessel was designed to operate at a temperature of 1550F and a pressure
of 150 psig with external heating in order to adequately control temperature.  Process gas flow
rates from the PFBR are expected to be roughly 30 scfm.  The filter vessel was designed  to
house three candle filters roughly 2.75 in. in diameter by 20 in. long and permit operation at filter
face velocities of 4 to 12 ft/min.  The intent is to clean the filters on-line using a heated nitrogen
backpulse (up to 1500&#176;F and 800 psig).<p>
     A high-temperature, high-pressure particulate-sampling system was developed for use with
bench- and pilot-scale advanced systems at the EERC.  The particulate-sampling system was
designed to sample at pressures up to 150 psig at a temperature of 1800&#176;F under both oxidizing
and reducing conditions.  A sampling probe is inserted into a process gas stream, and a
particulate-laden gas sample is withdrawn isokinetically.  The sampling probe is considered to be
disposable (based on wear).  Different materials are used for different operating conditions.  The
gas sample passes through a multicyclone train and/or borosilicate filter to remove all particulate
matter, then through a quench train to remove any condensables, followed by gas meters to
determine flow.  The probe, cyclone, and filter assembly are electrically heated to maintain the
gas temperature until it reaches the quench train.<p>
     Initial activities focused on reviewing the availability of existing filter vessels that may meet the
requirements for use with the transport reactor development unit  (TRDU).  The purpose for
reviewing the availability of existing filter vessels was to potentially minimize the cost of
designing and constructing a new vessel.  Three existing filter vessels were originally considered. 
The first vessel was designed and built by the Allison Gas Turbine Division of GM Corporation. 
Based on an on-site inspection and information provided by Allison personnel, EERC personnel
determined that the Allison filter vessel would not be a cost-effective alternative to designing and
constructing a new vessel because of its condition.  The second vessel was salvaged from the
former KRW test facility and is currently owned by Stanton Energy Industry Consultants, Inc. 
However, the filter vessel was too long for the available space in the gasification tower, and the
owner was not interested in selling the equipment but preferred a lease arrangement.  Therefore,
EERC personnel elected to not pursue this option.<p>
     A third existing filter vessel is currently being considered for use.  This vessel was built by
Aerodyne Development Corporation in the late 1970s.  The vessel was originally built for use as
a pressurized filter vessel in support of a pilot-scale PFBC system operated at the NASA Lewis
Research Center.  The EERC acquired the pressure vessel as surplus equipment in the late 1980s. 
Initially,  this vessel appeared to be an alternative to designing and constructing a new vessel. 
However, after completion of a preliminary design, EERC personnel determined that estimated
modification costs for this were significantly higher than originally anticipated.  As a result, a bid
package was prepared and issued to vendors for the construction of a new filter vessel.<p>
     The only significant difference in the new vessel design versus the modified vessel design was an
increase in diameter from 36 in. to 48 in.  A larger diameter was chosen to permit greater vessel
flexibility and eliminate design constraints relative to refractory selection and wall thickness,
shroud design and installation, and filter diameter and spacing.  Responses to the bid package
were received from six out of nine potential fabricators, with cost estimates ranging from
$14,700 to $33,200.  Based on the bid packages received, the EERC determined that
manufacturing a new, slightly larger filter vessel was a more prudent approach than modifying
the NASA Lewis vessel.  Therefore, a purchase order was issued to Arrow Tank &amp; Engineering
Company (Cambridge, Minnesota) to construct the new filter vessel at a cost of $14,700.  The
new vessel has been received.<p>
     Filter element performance will be evaluated in future tasks as a function of particulate collection
efficiency, filter differential pressure, filter cleanability, and filter durability.  Important operating
parameters to be evaluated include gas stream composition, temperature, face velocity, inlet dust
loading, and approach to filter cleaning.<p>
     A hot-gas reaction furnace was constructed and shakedown testing completed.  The furnace is
used to simulate the environment inside hot-gas cleanup vessels in order to perform long-term
corrosion and sintering tests of candidate ceramic barrier filters.  The reactor consists of a mullite
retort 6 in. in diameter and 6 ft long, with a 48-in. heated length.  The end caps have ports to
allow introduction and exhaust of gases and ports for introduction of water vapor, the
measurement of pressure, and the measurement of exit gas temperature and relative humidity. 
The retort pressure, exhaust gas temperature, and relative humidity data are acquired by
computer for overnight monitoring of changes in the system during the course of experiments.<p>
     The furnace has three independently controlled temperature zones:  one 24-in. center zone and
two 12-in. end zones.  The total 48-in. heated length provides a uniform heated length of
approximately 30 in.<p>
     The furnace has a maximum operating temperature of 1100&#176;C.  Simulated coal combustor
flue gas saturated with sodium sulfate and sodium chloride vapor is passed through sections of a
barrier filter coated with a thin layer of fly ash for up to 500 hours at 900&#176;C.  The filter is then
cut into C-rings 1 in. wide for compressive strength testing.  The C-ring tests are performed at
900&#176;C in the same atmosphere using an Instron 8562 universal testing machine fitted with a
high-temperature muffle furnace.  Scanning electron microscopy analyses are used to determine
interactions between the gas, ash layer, and the filter material.<p>
     An electron beam evaporator was used to determine if electron beam deposition was a valid way
to apply thin coatings of tantalum pentoxide to silicon carbide-based barrier filters to give them
corrosion protection.  Tantalum pentoxide was investigated because it has a similar coefficient of
thermal expansion to silicon carbide and because of reports in the literature that it affords
protection from alkali salt corrosion.  Extremely uniform and amorphous coatings from 0.1 to
several microns thick could be obtained on dense silicon carbide coupons.  Any degree of
oxidation could be obtained from pure tantalum metal to fully oxidized tantalum pentoxide. 
Experiments with anodic oxidation of metal coatings were performed to determine its effect on
the crystal morphology of the final oxide.  However, tests with liquid coal ash at 1300&#176;C (used
to
speed corrosion) showed that the tantalum pentoxide coatings were prone to corrosion in the
presence of silicate ash.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Greg F. Weber/<a href=mailto:gweber@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gweber@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5222<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown
Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b> Duration of Project:</b> July 1990 to June 1995<br>
