</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Gas Separation and Hot-Gas Cleanup</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Gas Separation and Hot-Gas Cleanup</h2> </center> 
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     Catalytic gasification of coal to produce H<sub>2</sub>-, CO-, and
CH<sub>4</sub>-rich gases for
consumption in molten carbonate fuel cells is currently under development; however, to optimize the
fuel cell performance and extend its operating life, it is desired to separate as much of the inerts (i.e.,
CO<sub>2</sub> and N<sub>2</sub>) and impurities (i.e., H<sub>2</sub>S and
NH<sub>3</sub>) as possible from the fuel gas before it enters the fuel cell.  In addition, the
economics of the integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC) can be improved by separating as
much of the hydrogen as possible from the fuel, since hydrogen is a high-value product.  Researchers
at the EERC are currently investigating pressure-driven membranes as a method for accomplishing
this gas separation and hot-gas cleanup. These membranes are operated at temperatures as high as
800&#176;C and pressures up to 300 psig.  These membranes have very small pore sizes which
separate the undesired gases by operating in the Knudsen diffusion region (30-50 &#197; ) or in the
molecular sieving region (&lt;5&#197;) of mass transport phenomena.<p>
     Technological and economic issues that must be resolved before these membranes are
commercially viable include improved gas separation efficiency, membrane optimization,
sealing of membranes to metal vessels, high burst strength of the membrane, pore thermal
stability, and material chemical stability.  Hydrogen separation is dependent on temperature,
pressure, pressure ratio across the membrane, and ratio of permeate flow to total flow.  For
gas separation under Knudsen diffusion, increasing feed pressure and pressure ratio across the
membrane should increase the gas permeability, and decreasing temperature and permeate-to-total
flow
ratio should also increase the gas permeability.  In the molecular sieving regime of
mass transport, the inlet pressure and pressure ratio should have no effect on gas permeability,
but increasing temperature should increase permeability.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The selectivity of the ceramic membranes for removing the undesired gases while allowing the
desired gases to be concentrated in the permeate stream must be determined.  Specific questions
to be answered included:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> What are the effects of ceramic membrane properties (i.e.,
surface area, pore size, coating thickness) on permeability and selectivity of the desired gases?<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  What are the effects of operating conditions (i.e., temperature,
pressure, and flow rate) on permeability and selectivity?<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  What are the effects of impurities (i.e., small particulate,
H<sub>2</sub>S, HCl, NH<sub>3</sub>) on membrane
performance?<br>
</ul>
<h3>Results</h3>
     A 4-lb/hr continuous fluid-bed reactor (CFBR) was used for the fluidized-bed gasification tests
with a Wyodak subbituminous coal from the Powder River Basin, since its low sulfur and ash
levels would allow the lower contaminant levels to reach the Bend Research, Inc., membranes. 
The Bend Research membranes tested were either 0.03-mm-thick palladium-silver or 0.06-mm-thick
palladium
membranes of approximately 0.2 ft<sup>2</sup> of surface area.  The hydrogen separation
membrane was repiped into the existing gasification system along with a set of gas-sampling
lines for measuring gas concentration upstream and downstream of the fixed-bed zinc oxide
sorbent vessel utilized to control the H<sub>2</sub>S gas concentration entering the membrane. 
Gas samples
of the permeate and raffinate streams were also obtained for analysis by gas chromatography.<p>
     Initially, short-term performance tests were conducted using the membrane to separate hydrogen
from the mixed-gas stream.  Subsequent tests looked at the effects of H2<sub>S</sub> impurities
via injecting a known amount of H<sub>2</sub>S into the gas stream.  Further testing then
looked at the effect of other impurities (i.e., H<sub>2</sub>S, HCl) by operating the membrane
using actual coal-derived fuel gases from the same CFBR equipment.  The gas composition of the
coal-derived gas stream was adjusted by adding some bottled hydrogen gas to the gas stream entering
the reactor.  Results indicate that high separation factors can be achieved with these membranes,
since the permeabilities of the undesired gases (i.e., CO<sub>2</sub>, CO,
H<sub>2</sub>O, CH<sub>4</sub>) are very low.  However, the permeability of hydrogen
gas is also much lower than those reported for ceramic membranes.  The change in hydrogen
permeabilities indicates how sensitive the palladium-based membranes are to hydrogen sulfide in
the feed gas.  The permeability also is significantly affected by membrane temperature and
hydrogen partial pressure, but does not appear to be significantly affected by product gas feed
rate through the membrane.<p>
     X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy was performed on a prototype hydrogen-permeable membrane
produced by Bend Research.  The membrane was exposed to hydrogen sulfide in the CFBR
reactor during a test to simulate coal gasification conditions.  The objective of the analysis was to
determine the composition of a thin white coating which was deposited on the retentate side of
the membrane during the test run.  From this analysis, the coating appears to be predominantly
elemental sulfur, with a small quantity of a sulfatelike compound also detected.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Michael L. Swanson/<a href=mailto:mswanson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mswanson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5239 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1994 to March 1995<br>
