<head>
<title>Small Power-Generating Systems</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Small Power-Generating Systems</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The EERC has worked in the development and operation of fluidized-bed combustors and
gasifiers for the past 20 years.  The EERC sees a market opportunity for small-scale power
generation systems based on these technologies for application in remote areas such as Alaska,
Indonesia, and the Philippines and other areas where constructing electrical lines is not practical. 
This includes certain regions in China, India, Central and South America, and the United States. 
The EERC is engaged in the development and promotion of power systems tailored to the needs
of small, remote sites.  The goal is a highly flexible system that burns a variety of solid fuels and
can be configured to meet site-specific issues and conditions such as climate, load patterns, and
fuel choices.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The development activities for small power systems are designed to incorporate a number of
elements that are important to any energy solution:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> An integrated solution that addresses energy, heating,
transportation, and waste disposal needs<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> An emphasis placed on improving the health of community
members<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Attention centered on the environment and identifying power
systems that are environmentally friendly<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Power generation options that are more cost-effective than diesel
generators<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The use of local resources to create more jobs and keep more
dollars in the local economy<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Demonstration of technologies that can meet many or all of these
needs<br>
</ul>
<p>
 <h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Development of an energy system for a particular site will involve tailoring existing systems or
developing new systems.  The generic attributes that the EERC is promoting for these power
systems include the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Size range of 0.2 to 20 MW<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Ability to burn environmentally benign solid fuels<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Ability to generate electricity, steam, and/or hot air<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Control of gaseous and solid pollutants<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Reliability and ease of operation and maintenance<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Levelized cost of electricity competitive with diesel
generators<br>
</ul>
<p>
     The EERC has developed a strategy to incorporate these attributes into a system for remote
applications.  This strategy is based on experience gained over the past 20 years on similar-sized
systems at the EERC.  Components of this strategy are listed below:<p>
<p>
<ul palin>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Focus on overall system functionality<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Capitalize on existing commercial designs and EERC experience
for subsystem design<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Use a "smart" control system to eliminate the need for
around-the-clock supervision<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Design a system to burn a variety of indigenous fuels, including
coal, oil, coal bed methane, municipal solid waste, wood wastes, and sewage sludge, either alone or
any combination<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Control SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub> within
the main combustion or gasification system, with a back-end system to control particulates<br>
</ul>
<p>
     Within the scope of the EERC's current plans, the potential customers for the small-scale power
systems include remote community, town, and village governmental agencies and service
organizations; utility firms and cooperatives; industrial firms; schools; hospitals; and other
institutions.  The EERC is seeking financial participation in the development program leading to
a demonstration of a small power system.  This may include teaming arrangements that will lead
to installation of a power system tailored to meet the specific demands of the end user.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael D. Mann/<a href=mailto:mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mmann@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5193<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li> January 1995 to December 1995
