<head>
<title>Remote-Site Power Generation Opportunities for Alaska</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Remote-Site Power Generation Opportunities for Alaska</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The U.S. Department of Energy (DOE), together with the Alaska Division of Energy (ADE),
Doyon Limited, and a number of native corporations, has undertaken a project to develop
alternative small-scale power generation technology options for application in remote villages of
Alaska.  The EERC is working with the DOE Morgantown Energy Technology Center (METC)
to assess options for using the tremendous reserves of high-quality coal found in Alaska in small-scale
power units fired on indigenous resources such as coal, coal-bed methane, and municipal
solid waste.<p>
<p>
     Typically, remote villages in Alaska use diesel generators fueled with expensive fuel oil for
electricity production.  The high cost of diesel power in rural Alaska is heavily subsidized by the
state through the Power Cost Equalization program (PCE), which amounts to about $20 million
annually.  Fuel oil is also used extensively for residential and public building heating.  The goal
of this activity will be to reduce the use of fuel oil in Alaskan villages by developing small, low-cost
power generation applications.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The overall objective of this project is to demonstrate viable technology options for providing
power to remote areas of Alaska.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     The Small Alternative Power Generation Workshop was held in Anchorage, Alaska, as a first
step in the development of safe, reliable, and efficient energy systems throughout Alaska.  The workshop
was a success; it established good three-way communication among government policymakers,
suppliers of technology, and end users, the rural Alaskans.  As a result of the interactive
presentations and breakout discussion groups during the workshop, the needs of the Alaskans were
heard and a number of technology options were offered that could meet their needs.<p>
<p>
     The technology options that appear to offer the best opportunity today are fluidized-bed
combustion, using both indigenous coal and municipal solid wastes as fuel, and coal bed
methane coupled to a fuel cell.<p>
<p>
     The role of the EERC in this project has recently been expanded to include overall project
management.  The goal remains the same, namely, demonstration of viable technology options for
providing power to remote areas of Alaska.  The goal is to begin the demonstration activity in 1996. 
Successful demonstration will create opportunities for export of these technologies to many parts of
the world with similar needs for remote power generation.<p>
<p>
     A second workshop, entitled "Alaska Native, American Indian, and Native Hawaiian Remote-Site
Power Generation Workshop:  Transferring the Alaskan Experience" will be held in Seattle,
Washington, on September 25-26, 1995.<p>
<p>
     The goal of the workshop is to share the results of activities undertaken to meet the energy needs
of remote villages in Alaska and to explore the opportunities that exist to commercialize the
technologies and transfer related information to other indigenous communities.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Michael L. Jones/<a href=mailto:mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mjones@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5130<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li> Alaska Science &amp; Technology 
Foundation  
<li>ENPAC Energy Pacific Company 
<li>International Coal Preparation Consultants Limited 
<li>Major International
<li>Placer Dome U.S. Inc. 
<li>University of Alaska-Fairbanks 
<li>Usibelli Coal Mine, Inc. <br>
