<head>
<title>Combustion 2000:  Engineering
Development of Coal-Fired, High-Performance Power-Generating Systems</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Combustion 2000:  Engineering Development of Coal-Fired, High-Performance
Power-Generating Systems
</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Modern pulverized coal-fired utility boilers are approximately 35% efficient at converting the
chemical energy in coal into electrical energy.  The most limiting step in the process is the
steam cycle that requires water to be boiled to make steam, which is expanded through a
turbine, then condensed so that it can be pumped back into the system.  The condensation
process occurs at such a low temperature that capturing the energy released is not practical,
and so the heat of vaporization is lost to the environment.  To improve efficiency and
subsequently reduce fuel costs as well as the production of environmental pollutants, advanced
systems will employ energy cycles that do not require the production of steam.  One effort to
develop such a system is being funded by the U.S. Department of Energy through the
Combustion 2000 program, a multiphase program to develop a commercially viable, advanced
coal-fired combustor by the year 2000.  It must be designed to increase efficiency by one-third, while
producing very low levels of environmental pollutants.  For the first phase, two
awards of over three million dollars each were made for two years of work.  One was received
by United Technologies Research Center (UTRC), the other by Foster Wheeler Development
Corporation.  The EERC is aiding the UTRC effort.  At the end of two years, a proposal with
a test plan for a demonstration of the feasibility of key system components in a 50-million-Btu/hr
demonstration coal combustor was submitted to DOE.  At least two awards for a total
of approximately fifty million dollars will be made for testing in Phase 2.  If the UTRC group
is one of the awardees, the EERC is slated to host the construction of a 2-MMBtu/hr slagging
coal combustor that will be used to test slag control, materials properties, and ceramic
engineering issues under slagging conditions. <p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objective of Phase 1 of Combustion 2000 is to develop a design and test plan for a
demonstration high-temperature advanced furnace (HITAF), which will then be constructed
under Phase 2 of the project.  The furnace will be the primary component of the high-efficiency
electricity production system.  To reach such high efficiencies, the furnace will employ a ceramic
heat exchanger that will be used to heat air to 2500&#176;F before it passes through a new
high-temperature turbine.  A ceramic heat exchanger is also being developed for an all-coal system
which will heat air to 2500&#176;F.  The EERC role in the UTRC effort is to help in the design of
the HITAF so that problems related to the formation of molten coal ash in the furnace are reduced. 
The EERC is also providing testing of alloy and ceramic materials in a coal-fired pilot-scale
combustor and developing corrosion-resistant refractory coatings for the air heater. <p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Initial design of the HITAF system has been completed.  It is intended to reduce the emissions
of environmental pollutants by over 80% of present levels and be approximately 49% efficient
at converting the chemical energy in coal to electrical energy.  The efficiency increase will
decrease the emission of greenhouse gases by approximately 39% over present systems.  It
will employ two ceramic air heaters:  one operating at high temperature (3000&#176;F) and the
other at low temperature (2000&#176;F).  Examination of the reactivity calculations of the
thermodynamic equilibrium of ash species at these temperatures shows that the high-temperature
heater will be prone to direct corrosion by the coal slag, whereas the low-temperature heater will be
attacked by alkali sulfates condensed from the gas stream.  A pilot-scale test will be performed at the
EERC to test the durability of alloy heat-exchanger components and refractory coatings. 
Long-duration experiments have been performed to determine the resistance of different forms of
silicon carbide (SiC) and SiC-alumina composites to corrosion by coal slag at 2000&#176; and
2300&#176;F for the all-coal ceramic heat exchangers.  Strength measurements were also performed
to determine strength loss due to slag corrosion.  Scanning electron microscopy and x-ray
photoelectron spectrometry were used to determine mechanisms of corrosion and failure.  In general,
the composite materials showed little strength loss after the experiments.  Other SiC ceramics,
especially SiC that contained residual metal, showed excessive corrosion and strength degradation at
the higher temperature.<p>
     In addition to these experiments, many monolithic refractories have been tested for slag
corrosion resistance to determine their applicability as protective coatings for the air heater. 
Two SiC-based refractories have been found to be suitable for temperatures up to 2600&#176;F in
the presence of either iron-rich slags from eastern bituminous coals or calcium-rich slags from
Powder River Basin subbituminous coals.<p>
     Another aspect of the project is to perform an overall economic evaluation of by-product
utilization.  For this work, a vicinity near Kenosha, Wisconsin, has been selected for the site
of the high-performance power system power plant.  The site was selected because of its
proximity to major U.S. cities which utilize significant amounts of coal combustion by-products and
because of the availability of water transportation.  An important aspect of assessing marketability of
by-products will be the use of an integrative technology data manipulation software known as Atlas
Geographic Information Systems (GIS)<sup>TM</sup>.  Information regarding by-product
characteristics, plant location, transporting of materials, and competing materials will be put into the
GIS system to completely evaluate utilization potential.<p>
<h3> UTRC Alloy Panel Test</h3>
     UTRC contracted with the EERC to provide a 100-hour combustion test to determine the
level and extent of slag corrosion for an alloy panel covered with various refractory
materials as an add-on to existing work in support of the Combustion 2000 program.  The
test fired an Illinois No. 6 bituminous coal obtained from Illinois Power Company's
Baldwin Station.  The fuel was fired at a rate sufficient to achieve a furnace exit gas
temperature of 2400&#176;F at an excess air level near 20%.  These conditions were previously
used to simulate a wet-bottom boiler in the EERC's pilot-scale combustion test facility
(CTF).  The CTF is a bottom-fired, refractory-lined furnace that uses a balanced draft.  To
achieve the specified test conditions, a 2-in. refractory liner was poured to minimize heat
loss through the furnace walls and elevate the flame temperature and flue gas temperature
leaving the furnace.  A flame temperature between 2600&#176; and 2700&#176;F was expected. 
Combined with fuel properties, these conditions provided adequate slag generation and
flow to simulate the characteristics of a wet-bottom boiler.  Testing was performed the
week of June 19, 1995.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  John P. Hurley/<a href=mailto:jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhurly@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5159 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li> PowerTech International<br>
<li>United Technologies Research Center<br>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy Pittsburgh Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>March 1992 to August 1995<br>
