<head>
<title>Coal Ash Behavior in Reducing
Environments</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Coal Ash Behavior in Reducing Environments</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     A key factor in the successful design and operation of coal gasification and advanced
combustion systems is the ability to control and mitigate ash-related problems.  Some of the
major ash-related problems are slag flow control, slag attack on the refractory, ash deposition
on heat-transfer surfaces, corrosion and erosion of equipment materials, and emissions control. 
Such problems are closely tied to the abundance and association of the inorganic components
in coal and the system conditions.<p>
     In general, the inorganic components are associated in the coal as minerals or organic
complexes (salts of carboxylic acid groups or organic coordination complexes).  The minerals
associated in coal vary widely in size, composition, and juxtaposition.  Juxtaposition refers to
the association of the mineral grains with other mineral grains and coal particles.  These
associations directly influence the chemical and physical transformations that occur during the
gasification process.  Depending upon the type of gasification system, the inorganic
components are initially partitioned into intermediate species in the form of inorganic gases,
liquids, and solids.  The state of these species at any position in the gasifier directly influences
their behavior at that stage.  The transformations and partitioning of the inorganic species
directly influence slag flow behavior, extent and type of slag attack on the refractory, and
corrosion and erosion of materials, as well as growth rate, quantity, and type of ash deposition
on heat-transfer surfaces. <p>
     Conventional analytical methods for coal and coal ash materials do not provide adequate detail
regarding their complex chemical and mineralogical properties.  Advanced analytical
techniques are currently being used to determine the association and forms of inorganic
components in coals and coal ash-derived materials.  In addition, other laboratory-scale
techniques are routinely used to determine viscosity, surface tension, sintering behavior, and
deposit strength development.  Reducing environments can be simulated in pressurized drop-tube
furnace
systems to produce intermediate species that can be used to determine inorganic
transformations.  Utilization of advanced analytical techniques, coupled with laboratory
methods, can potentially provide significant advances in understanding the behavior of
inorganic components during gasification that will ultimately lead to better methods to predict
and mitigate ash-related problems.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The Coal Ash Behavior in Reducing Environments (CABRE) project was a 4-year, multiclient
program to determine the behavior of coal inorganic components in reducing environments using
advanced methods of analysis coupled with laboratory experiments.  The objectives were as
follows: <p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To further develop advanced ash and deposit characterization
techniques to quantify the effects of the liquid-phase components on strength development in ash
deposits<Br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To determine the mechanisms of inorganic transformations that
lead to inorganic partitioning, ash deposition, and slag formation under gasification conditions<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To determine the factors that influence the sintering behavior of
coal-derived ashes under gasification conditions<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To develop a better means of predicting the behavior of inorganic
components as a function of coal composition and reducing conditions<br></ul>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The CABRE project recently completed its fourth and final year of research.  The four years of
experimental and theoretical research have provided a large amount of information pertaining to
the interactions of inorganics during coal gasification.  Significant advancements have been
made in the three foundational areas of the project:  analytical characterization, inorganic
transformations and deposition, and physical and chemical properties.  The analytical
characterization of samples produced under gasification conditions was enhanced by taking
advanced techniques previously used in combustion research and adapting them for gasification
samples.  The advanced techniques developed utilize a scanning electron microscope/microbeam
to provide particle-by-particle chemical and physical information on the micron scale.  Two
software packages were developed to aid in the characterization of gasification materials: 
MINCLASS and VISCALC.  MINCLASS was designed to interpret data from advanced
analytical techniques to allow the user to define the chemical transformations under gasification
conditions.  VISCALC takes the information produced from MINCLASS and predicts the
viscosities of the phases to allow the user to predict the slagging and fouling properties of the
ash.<p>
    The transformations of inorganic species during gasification and the deposition processes were
studied using a state-of-the-art pressurized drop-tube furnace capable of high temperatures and
pressures.  This furnace system allowed gasification samples to be produced under closely
controlled conditions which provided valuable information on the transformation mechanisms
and identified differences between organically associated and mineral form inorganic materials.<p>
     The investigation of chemical and physical properties of gasification samples provided major
breakthroughs in and understanding of the development of strength in deposits and phase
interactions.  Indices were developed for ranking the effects of high- and low-temperature
deposition problems for several coals.  Much of this work has application beyond the research of
coal gasification.<p>
     The fundamental results gained from this project are expected to provide a basis for future
applied research activities.<p>
<hr>
Project Manager: Thomas A. Erickson/<a href=mailto:terickson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>terickson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
Phone: </font>(701) 777-5153<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li> Dow Chemical Company
<li> Electric Power Research Institute 
<li> Energieonderzoek Centrum Nederland (ECN) 
<li> Shell Development Company 
<li> Texaco Inc. 
<li> U.S. Department of Energy <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> November 1990 to February 1995
<br>
