<html>
<head>
<title>Testing of Sodium Bicarbonate as an
Entrained-Flow Chloride Sorbent</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Testing of Sodium Bicarbonate as an Entrained-Flow Chloride Sorbent </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>
     General Electric is proposing to use a moving-bed system to clean contaminants from the
product gas of coal gasifiers.  Zinc titanate sorbent material is used to capture hydrogen
sulfide from the gas stream.  It has been found that hydrochloric gas in the stream reacts with
zinc in the sorbent to form zinc chloride, which vaporizes when the sorbent is heated in the
bed regenerator.  As the gas leaving the regenerator is cooled, zinc sulfate condenses from the
gas steam, forming deposits that can grow to reduce the flow of gas through the system.  In
order to prevent the hydrochloric gas from vaporizing the zinc, it has been proposed to use a
powdered additive injected into the duct upstream of the zinc titanate bed.  However, the high
concentration of sulfur dioxide in the regenerator product gas makes the commercial
production of sulfuric acid viable.  Therefore a hydrochloric acid-absorbing material that does
not absorb sulfur is preferred as the additive.  In-duct injection of sodium bicarbonate is one
proposed method to absorb the chlorine.  The sodium bicarbonate decomposes in situ to form
a high-surface-area sodium carbonate, which then reacts with HCl vapor to form sodium
chloride solid.  The spent particles can then be separated from the gas stream.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The overall objective of the work was to determine the chlorine absorption efficiency of sodium
bicarbonate under pressurized gasification conditions.  The EERC pressurized drop-tube furnace
(PDTF) system was used as the reactor.  Several different reaction times, sorbent/vapor ratios,
and sorbent particle sizes were tested.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
     Operation of the PDTF went routinely after several issues were resolved.  First, the high level of
moisture in the gas stream forced operation of the filter to nearly its maximum capacity of
130&#176;C, which may have led to some chloride absorption by the particles on the filter.  The
introduction of the water and hydrogen chloride below the point of syngas introduction allowed
the syngas to reform, making soot.  The soot sometimes dislodged and was collected on the filter. 
It also increased the cost of running the tests by clogging insulation and generally increasing
cleanup costs.<p>
     Thermogravimetric analysis showed that calcination of the bicarbonate to carbonate was
essentially complete, even at the shortest residence time with the largest particles.  Chloride
capture was monitored by scanning electron microscopy analyses of the spent particles collected
on the system filter.  Capture efficiencies of between 16% and 92% were measured, although
some of this capture occurred after collection on the filter.  Scatter in the chloride capture
efficiency data was great, but did indicate several trends.  At residence times of around
0.4 seconds, about half of the chlorine was captured by the Grade No. 3 DF material at a
sodium-to-chlorine
feed rate of 2 or 3 to 1.  Approximately 90% capture was measured at 5 to 1. 
Although the porosity of the particles increased from around 5% to 20% to 30% during
calcination, chlorine was not captured in the internal pores.  Only surface capture was detected,
indicating that smaller particles with their higher surface-area-to-volume ratios would be more
efficient at removing chloride.  This was borne out in the PDTF testing.  Fragmentation of the
larger Grade No. 2 particles during calcination occurred inconsistently and not nearly so much as
to reduce the overall size distribution to that of the Grade No. 3 DF particles.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  John P. Hurley/<a href=mailto:jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu> jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b> Phone:</b> (701) 777-5159 <br>
<b> Sponsor</b>: GE Corporate R&amp;D<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> September 1993 to July 1994<br>
<hr>
