<html>
<head>
<title>Catalytic Coal Gasification</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Catalytic Coal Gasification</h2> </center> 
<br>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Catalytic steam gasification of low-rank coals under mild, near-atmospheric conditions to
produce a hydrogen-rich gas stream has been investigated with bench and continuous
equipment at the EERC.  Reasonable gasification rates were obtained using alkali and some
alkaline earth catalysts, but only with low-rank coals.  Bituminous coals were found to be
relatively unreactive with even the best-known catalysts at optimum conditions.  An economic
assessment performed by Black and Veatch suggested that a promising application for catalytic
gasification would be to provide hydrogen for fuel cells.<p>

     Subsequent work with the Energy Research Corporation (ERC) and Fluor-Daniel showed that
electrical generation efficiency could approach 60% by close-coupling a catalytic gasification
process with a fuel-flexible molten carbonate fuel cell (MCFC).  This process uses hydrogen
and methane as fuel and would rely on a hot recycle stream of hydrogen, superheated steam,
and an exothermic hydrogenation reaction to provide process heat.  Close-coupling effectively
limits gasification temperatures to around 650&#176;C.  To date, marginally acceptable gasification
rates have been achieved with known gasification catalysts, but only with low-rank coals.  In
the effort to obtain suitable gas production at 650&#176;C, a brief investigation of some nickel and
iron catalysts was undertaken.  The catalysts tested were nickel-substituted synthetic mica
montmorillonite (NiSMM), NiSMM-supported molybdenum, iron hydroxyoxide, iron nitrate,
iron-calcium-impregnated salts, and nickel uranyl oxide (Ni-U).  All catalysts except the
Ni-U were tested for their effect on the reaction ratio of steam gasification.  The NiSMM and
the Ni-U were tested for their tar-cracking properties.<p>

     In previous parametric studies at the EERC, all tests were carried out at atmospheric pressure. 
However, when the production of a gas stream for fuel cell feed was studied, it was found that
pressure plays a major role in providing proper gas composition.  Thermodynamics predict that a
change in pressure during the steam gasification of coal will increase the methane content of the
gas.  Since methane plays a major role in temperature control of the operating fuel cell, this
laboratory-scale work on catalytic gasification was carried out under increased pressure, i.e., 50
psig, and the product gas was analyzed on-line with Fourier transform infrared analysis.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

     Work on catalytic gasification directly supports efforts to integrate gasification and MCFCs. 
The primary goal was to identify a suitable hydrogasification catalyst to achieve coal residence
times on the order of minutes in a gasifier operating on naturally reactive low-rank coals at
nominal conditions of 650&#176;C and increased pressure (up to 150 psi) under hydrogasification
and steam gasification conditions.  The EERC gasification model will be integrated into
existing state-of-the-art codes.<p>
<h3>Results </h3>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Synthetic pillared-clay transition metal catalysts developed at the
EERC showed little positive effect on the rate of steam gasification of coal apart from increasing
methane production.<br>
 <br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">   Earlier tests using nickel- and nickel-molybdenum-loaded
synthetic clays slightly showed that they do not sinter, because nickel is incorporated into the
synthetic clay structure and it retains hydrocracking activity even when sulfided.<br>
<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Both nickel and iron catalysts were successful in raising methane
production.<br>
<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The steam/oxygen/hydrogen-coal gasification equilibrium model
has been developed as a macro-driven Lotus spreadsheet to calculate the equilibrium gas composition
and heat balance for coal gasification with steam, oxygen, and/or hydrogen.<br>
<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Fe-Ca catalysts showed promise as a steam-coal gasification
catalyst.  Methane production was also enhanced in the presence of this catalyst.<br>
<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Fe-Ca is the least expensive of the catalysts tested.<br>
<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Ni-U increased methane production more than other catalysts
tested.  It, like the pillared catalysts, was not easily poisoned and did not sinter at the test
temperatures, i.e., up to 600&#176;C.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:ytoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> <ul plain>Energy Research Corporation<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  January 1993 to April 1994<br>
