<html>
<head>
<title>Catalytic Tar Cracking</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<h2> Catalytic Tar Cracking</h2> </center> 
<hr><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The need for on-line cracking of gasification tars is common to many types of gas stream
cleanup systems.  Aerosol tars are not readily removed from gas streams by conventional
means and, as a consequence, often end up plugging filters or fouling fuel cells, turbines, or
sorbents.  Catalytic cracking of these tars to molecular moieties containing ten or fewer carbon
atoms would prevent the problems commonly attributed to the tars.  As an example, a moving
fixed-bed gasifier, by virtue of its efficient countercurrent heat exchange and widespread
commercial use, may offer the lowest-cost integrated gasification combined-cycle system, if tar
generation and wastewater contamination can be minimized.  This project investigated the use
of selected catalysts to crack pyrolysis gases and vapors from two coals.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project were 1) to determine if selected catalysts such as zeolite or
dolomite would yield products which do not contaminate filtering devices or turbines and 2) to
investigate the feasibility of obtaining a desired liquid and/or gas stream from the use of the
selected catalysts.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>

     The cracking catalysts selected for testing were dolomite and Engelhard extruded and finely
divided zeolites.  Lignite from Beulah, North Dakota, was gasified with steam at each of five
temperatures, i.e., 250&#176;, 400&#176;, 550&#176;, 700&#176;, and 800&#176;C, in the
integrated bench-scale gasifier.  Volatile tars as well as gaseous products were passed through a bed
of dolomite at 50&#176;-100&#176;C below the reactor temperature.  Tests under the same
conditions were performed with the zeolite catalyst.  Similar tests with both catalysts were carried out
on Beluga subbituminous coal from Alaska.  The results indicate that the dolomite is a better cracking
catalyst than the zeolite at the conditions tested. 
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown
Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  March 1994 to March 1995<br>
<hr>
