<head>
<title>Underground Coal Gasification Environmental Assessment Research</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Underground Coal Gasification Environmental Assessment Research</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2></font>
<p>
         In general, U.S. underground coal gasification (UCG) tests have focused on the development
of the process itself.  Comparatively little effort has been devoted to the critical issues of site and
materials characterization and environmental monitoring.  These issues must be addressed if the
development of UCG as a viable coal utilization alternative is to continue.<p>
<p>
         The recent Rocky Mountain 1 (RM1) UCG test in Carbon County, Wyoming, was designed
to include, for the first time, many activities critical to adequate preburn site and materials
characterization, as well as an extensive set of multidisciplinary tasks focusing on the
identification, assessment, and prevention/minimization of the environmental impacts associated
with the test.  The technical assistance and research involvement of the EERC were designed to
address specific key aspects of these issues that were not included in the original RM1 test
program.<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
         The objectives of this project were to:<p>
<p>
<ul plain> 
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  Provide technical assistance to aid the Gas Research Institute
(GRI) program manager in maintaining the quality, scope, and timeliness of all activities related to
the environmental assessment portion of the RM1 UCG test program in south-central
Wyoming.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Perform research supplementary to other contracted RM1
environmental assessment activities in order to maximize the overall assessment effort.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Synthesize the results of all environmental and process activities
in order to develop an understanding of process:site interactions related specifically to the RM1 test
and to in situ gasification in general.<br>
</ul><p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
         Research activities during the past two years have resulted in the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of a plan to more thoroughly evaluate the
UCG-related hydrothermal regime at the RM1 site through the collection of additional groundwater
temperature data and the more rigorous analysis of all available subsurface temperature data utilizing
previously unavailable advanced computer capabilities.  (See "Supplementary Research Related to the
Rocky Mountain 1 Underground Coal Gasification Test Program.")<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of a report reviewing the design, conduct, and results
of the effort to 1) describe and chemically and mineralogically characterize the available thermally
altered materials from the RM1 site and 2) use the characterization data to reconstruct the test-related
thermal history of the site.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of a plan to complement the noted characterization
report with an "atlas" of mineral and amorphous phases identified during the characterization
activities.  (See "Supplementary Research Related to the Rocky Mountain 1 Underground Coal
Gasification Test Program.")<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of a draft report reviewing the design, conduct, and
results of the laboratory investigations of 1) the short- and long-term leaching potential of
UCG-related, thermally altered materials from the RM1 test site and 2) the chemical attenuation
capacity of those thermally altered materials, as well as unaltered materials from the vicinity of the
RM1 test cavities.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of the integrated evaluation of all available process
and environmental data generated/collected in conjunction with the RM1 test program.  This effort,
which has been undertaken largely by John Boysen (formerly of Resource Technology Corporation,
Inc.) under subcontract to the EERC, is primarily intended to improve the present understanding of
UCG-related process:site interactions so that future UCG operations can be better designed, sited,
conducted, and evaluated.  Specifically, activities in this regard have resulted in the following:<br>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of an energy balance model for the RM1 test based on
process data and observations and incorporating a consideration of the effects of site-related
geological and hydrological factors.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Refinement of the previously developed preliminary RM1 material
balance model in response to more involved evaluation of available process data and an assessment of
the effects of site-related geological and hydrological factors.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Development of a numerical method for estimating the daily
growth of the extended linked-well cavity at the RM1 site that corresponds with available data and
observations.  A similar attempt focused on the controlled retracting injection point cavity was much
less successful, primarily due to critical deficiencies in the available data and observations.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Finalization of a report entitled "Detailed Evaluation of Process
and Environmental Data from the Rocky Mountain 1 Underground Coal Gasification Field
Test--Background, Approach, and Preliminary Results,"  which reviews the initial activities of the
integrated assessment of all available RM1 data.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Completion of a draft report entitled "Detailed Evaluation of
Process and Environmental Data from the Rocky Mountain 1 Underground Coal Gasification Field
Test--Final Report," which comprehensively reviews the integrated data assessment effort and its
results.<br>
</ul></ul>
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Craig R. Schmit/<a href=mailto:cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu>cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a><br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5259 <br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Gas Research Institute
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>October 1986 to June 1995<br>
