<html>
<head>
<title>Supplementary Research Related to the
Rocky Mountain 1 Underground Coal
Gasification Test Program</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2> Supplementary Research Related to the Rocky Mountain 1 Underground Coal Gasification
Test Program
</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Since 1986, the EERC has been involved in providing technical assistance and performing
research as part of the Rocky Mountain 1 (RM1) underground coal gasification (UCG) test
program sponsored by a consortium headed by the U.S. Department of Energy and Gas Research
Institute.  During the course of evaluating the activity-specific results, producing the attendant
reports, and progressing with the integrated data evaluation effort for the program, several
mechanisms were identified for enhancing the utility and/or accessibility of certain program
results, thus increasing the contribution of the RM1 program to the overall development of UCG. 
The result was two additional RM1-related initiatives, each of which builds upon work that has
already been completed as part of earlier program activities.<p>

     The first of these initiatives was an expansion of work initially done for  the EERC by Dr.
William Gosnold on the analysis of the UCG-related hydrothermal regime at the RM1 site,
utilizing PC-based computer capabilities.  Specifically, this initiative involved the more rigorous
analysis of the RM1 hydrothermal regime utilizing previously unavailable, enhanced computer
capabilities in the form of the University of North Dakota (UND) Cray X/MP supercomputer
system.  This additional analysis will allow insights into UCG-related process:setting interactions
that are presently not possible, yet which may have important implications in the design, siting,
and conduct of long-term UCG operations in particular.<p>

     The second initiative was focused on the development of an "atlas" of mineral and amorphous
phases that were identified during the EERC efforts to chemically and mineralogically
characterize unaltered and thermally altered subsurface materials recovered from the RM1 site. 
This document will make available, in a readily usable form, all the phase-related data,
information, and insights that may be of some value to those charged with designing, siting,
conducting, and evaluating future UCG operations.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project were to:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Expand the analysis of the UCG-related hydrothermal regime at
the RM1 site through the application of previously unavailable, advanced computer capabilities
utilizing all subsurface temperature data collected during the test program.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Produce an "atlas" of the mineral and amorphous phases that
were identified during the characterization of available unaltered and thermally altered materials from
the RM1 site.<br>
</ul><p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     The initiative focused on the UCG-related hydrothermal regime at the RM1 site has resulted
in:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Acquisition of an additional detailed set of subsurface
temperature data from the site and a comprehensive review of all site-related temperature
data.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Completion of 1) the conversion, for use on UND's Cray system,
of the PC-based computer code that was developed and used for the initial analysis of the RM1
hydrothermal regime; 2) the compilation and testing of the transformed code on the Cray system; and
3) the refinement of the Cray-based code to address execution problems, reduce the execution time,
and more accurately simulate the physical phenomena related to the RM1 hydrothermal
system.<br> 

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Development of visualization routines to represent the model
output utilizing the visualization capabilities associated with the Cray system.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Completion of the development of a three-dimensional simulation
of the heat flux from the two RM1 cavities for the late posttest period, that is, after the second cavity
cleanup effort in August 1989. The predominant heat source during that period was the residual heat
in the cavities, while the primary heat distribution mechanism was the groundwater moving through
the target coal seam.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Completion of a draft report comprehensively reviewing this
analysis of the UCG-related hydrothermal regime at the RM1 site.<br>
</ul>
 Activities related to the "atlas" initiative have resulted in the completion of an initial draft of the
document, the primary focus of which is more than fifty sections specific to the significant
phases that were identified during the RM1-related materials characterization effort.  Each of
these sections consists of:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The phase name (mineral, mineral group/series, other).<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The chemical formula(s).<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Identification criteria for relevant techniques, which typically
include x-ray diffraction (XRD), x-ray fluorescence, optical microscopy (OM), scanning electron
microscopy (SEM), and electron probe microanalysis.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Selected illustrative material to supplement the identification
criteria, typically including representative chemical analyses, XRD patterns, and OM and SEM
photomicrographs.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Observations on the mode of occurrence in unaltered RM1
near-cavity geological materials and in test-related thermally altered materials along both the heating
and cooling paths.  This section also includes comments on the origin of the phase, the phases with
which it is typically associated, and the frequency of occurrence.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Comments on the UCG-related implications of the phase, that is,
what the knowledge of the phase can contribute to 1) the reconstruction of conditions at or near the
gasification site during the time that the phase was formed and 2) the assessment of environmental
impacts resulting from UCG process:setting interactions. </ul>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Craig R. Schmit/<a href=mailto:cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu>cschmit@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5259<br>
<b>Sponsors: </b><ul plain> Gas Research Institute<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> August 1993 to June 1995<br>
<hr>
