<html>
<head>
<title>Modeling of Gasifier Operations at the
Great Plains Gasification Plant</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Modeling of Gasifier Operations at the Great Plains Gasification Plant</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     The Great Plains Gasification Plant (GPGP), owned and operated by the Dakota Gasification
Company (DGC), is strongly interested in understanding plant operation for the purposes of
optimization and control.  The two possible routes to that understanding are direct
experimentation or modeling. Plant experimentation is very expensive (in terms of time and
money) and very limited in terms of the variables that can be studied and their allowable ranges. 
Therefore, modeling the plant on a computer is a far better alternative if it can be done.  GPGP
selected ASPEN/SP from Simulation Sciences (SimSci) as the framework for this computer
model and asked that an existing ASPEN module (called RGAS) be modified to adequately
describe gasifier operations.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

     There were two objectives for this project, which approached modeling from the two opposite
extremes:  modeling from first principles and "curve fitting" of plant data.  The first objective
was to improve the ASPEN (RGAS) model, which is based on first principles.  Specifically, the
parameters in the model (reaction rate constants, activity coefficient of the coal, heat-transfer
coefficient, heat of devolatilization, and devolatilization schedule) were to be changed to
correspond to the coal actually being used.  The second objective was to use neural networks to
see if information could be gleaned from historical plant data that could be used for process
control.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
<h4>ASPEN/RGAS</h3>
     Great strides were made in improving the RGAS model.  Now all responses are being predicted
within the accuracy of the data:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The RGAS program was modified so that parameters could be
optimized automatically.  Formerly, this was a three-month effort.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The reaction rate model was expanded to include an activity
coefficient for the coal.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> The linear devolatilization temperature profile was examined and
found to be adequate.<br>
</ul>
<h4>Neural Nets</h4>
     Daily data from over 2 years of plant operation were used to train a neural network to predict gas
liquor flow rate from levels of operating variables and coal properties.  If that could have been
done with any precision, then the steam/oxygen ratio could have been maximized, which, in turn,
would maximize profit.  The results were disappointing, the neural net did not perform any better
than the linear regression model.  More data (or perhaps more relevant inputs) are being sought
from DGC.  Examination of these data may result in a neural network with the ability to
effectively predict gasifier performance.  This activity is suggested as a future project.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> John Erjavec<br>
(UND Dept. of Chemical Engineering)/<a href=mailto:jerjavec@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jerjavec@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-4244<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b><ul plain> Dakota Gasification Company<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy<br> </ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> May 1990 to December 1993<br>
