<html>
<head>
<title>Fuel Utilization Properties</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h2>Fuel Utilization Properties </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The mission of the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and the EERC Cooperative Agreement
is to promote the clean and efficient use of energy resources through a program of research
and development efforts.  These efforts include research characterization, air quality impacts
and controls, advanced power systems, and advanced fuel forms.  The goals of the
Cooperative Agreement are energy efficiency, preservation of the environment, securing the
domestic energy supply, diversifying the coal industry, and fortifying the foundations in
research, education, and technology commercialization.<p>

     The purpose of this project is to determine the impacts of specific coal properties and additives
on ash formation and deposition in advanced power systems.  The first year focused on
integrated gasification combined-cycle (IGCC)-type systems, whereby small-scale furnaces
were employed to simulate gasification or highly reducing conditions in order to produce
entrained ash and deposits for analysis.  A lesser emphasis was placed on analyzing deposits
from a small-scale pressurized fluid-bed reactor (PFBR).  Limited work was also directed
toward surveying the types of ash partitioning and ash deposition that could occur in PFBRs.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

     The overall objectives of this project are to determine key fuel properties and mechanisms that
impact ash formation and deposition in advanced power systems and to propose and test
measures for mitigating ash deposition.  Specific goals for this year's work in the area of ash
formation and deposition in advanced power systems include:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Determining the general chemical and physical properties of
simulated entrained ash and deposits that may lead to operational problems.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Identifying and testing methods to mitigate deposition in
IGCC-type systems.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
<h4>Inorganic Transformations under Gasification or Highly
Reducing Conditions</h4>

     Determination of mechanisms of coal inorganic transformations under reducing or gasification
conditions is being accomplished using a pressurized drop-tube furnace (PDTF).  Entrained ash
is produced from coal using gas compositions, pressures, and temperatures similar to those used
in current IGCC systems, and the composition of the ash is compared to original inorganic
constituents in the coal.  A first-generation model of inorganic transformations under gasification
conditions will be formulated by revising an existing EERC model called ATRAN, which
predicts entrained ash particle-size and composition distribution for a conventional pulverized
coal combustion system.  The ATRAN code will be enhanced with currently available data at the
EERC as well as with data generated from the PDTF ash production tests.  The initial
enhancements to be made to the ATRAN model will focus on the kinetics of the decomposition
of sulfides and carbonates.  A preliminary assessment has been made, and the current ATRAN
code does have the structure and flexibility to be converted so that it can be used for predicting
ash transformations under reducing environment conditions.  The coals have been tested  in the
PDTF under atmospheric pressure and a series of different reducing environments.  Black
Thunder subbituminous coal shows decreased interaction of organically associated calcium with
clays and quartz during coal conversion under reducing conditions.  Illinois No. 6 coal shows
decreased interaction of iron with aluminosilicates but more production of iron sulfide species
during coal conversion under reducing conditions.<p>

<h4>Mechanisms of Deposit Formation in IGCC-Type
Systems</h4>

     Deposits have been generated in a DTF for three coals to determine the effects of coal
characteristics, system aerodynamics and transport mechanisms, pressure, temperature,
and gas composition on the degree of deposit severity.  Deposit severity was assessed
based on the hardness, growth rate, and liquid-phase viscosity of the deposits that are
formed.  Deposit analysis was accomplished using scanning electron microscopy (SEM), x-ray
fluorescence,
x-ray diffraction, and physical strength analysis.  Generally, deposits from
low-rank coals such as the Black Thunder (Wyoming) subbituminous coal showed lower
amounts of oxidized mineral species, but the bulk of the deposit-forming material was
similar to what was observed for conventional deposits.  Calcium aluminosilicate material
dominated the deposits.  Deposits formed from higher-rank bituminous coals such as the
Illinois No. 6 did show more reduced iron species and iron aluminosilicates.<p>

<h4>Fouling Deposit Mitigation Measures</b>
</h4>
     Mitigation measures were proposed based on their ability to reduce deposit physical strength or
accumulation rates.  A kaolinite additive was used in the precombustion mode to try to render the
alkali ineffective for depressing melting points of entrained ash and deposit material.  It is the
lower melting point and lower-viscosity phases that cause entrained ash to stick and deposits to
form and acquire strength.  This additive and lime may also act to physically weaken deposits by
diluting the bad-acting components or by creating a more porous and weakened deposit structure. 
One baseline coal and several coal additive mixtures were tested in the drop-tube reactor under a
limited set of gasification conditions to produce deposits with the addition of kaolinite and lime
additives.  Physical and chemical-mineralogical analysis of the deposits using SEM techniques
showed that the kaolinite and lime additives do reduce deposit strength and cohesiveness at
higher-zone collection temperatures.  Lower-temperature-zone collection tests produced deposits
that were very friable and weak for both types of coals.  Impacts of additives on the
lower-temperature
deposits were neglible.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b> Greg F. Weber</<a href=mailto:gweber@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gweber@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5222<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>   U.S. Department of Energy Pittsburgh Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> January 1993 to December 1995<br>
<hr>
