<head>
<title>Wind Resource Assessment for the Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa Indians on the Turtle Mountain Reservation</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Wind Resource Assessment for the Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa Indians on the Turtle Mountain Reservation </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The wind industry has progressed significantly in the last 12 years and may be on the verge of
major expansion into the midwest region of the United States.  Wind resources in North Dakota
are among the highest of any state.  The Turtle Mountain Indian Reservation, which is located in
north-central North Dakota just below the Canadian border in the Turtle Mountains, has winds
rated at a power class of  5 or higher.  The Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa Indians Tribe is
interested in developing its wind energy resources and the potential environmental and economic
benefits that will result from this activity.<p>
<p>
     This project consists of three major tasks:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  An environmental impact assessment to determine any adverse
impacts to local wildlife that may occur if a large-scale wind farm were to be constructed and
operated. <br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> A resource assessment of the Turtle Mountain
Reservation.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">  A demonstration turbine installed and operated by the tribe for a
period of one year.<br>
</ul>
<p>
     Following one year of operation and wind data collection, an assessment will be made to
determine the economic feasibility of constructing and operating a large-scale wind farm.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The primary goals of this wind energy project are the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To perform the resource assessment of the wind energy potential
of the Turtle Mountain Reservation and to collect the microsite wind data that will be necessary to
strategically site wind turbines in the future.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To perform an environmental assessment of the Turtle Mountain
Reservation with regard to potential wildlife impact from wind farms.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To provide actual performance data and hands-on experience for
students, instructors, researchers, political leaders, and tribal planners with regard to the development
of large-scale wind energy projects.<br>
<p>
To perform the preliminary economic assessment of a large-scale wind farm site on the Turtle
Mountain Reservation.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To increase the awareness and acceptance of wind energy
development on the Turtle Mountain Reservation and to provide a working example of current wind
energy conversion technology.<br>
</ul>
<h2>Results</h2> <p>
This project was initiated in June 1995. The wind turbine and wind-monitoring equipment will be
installed this summer.
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Jay S. Haley/<a href=mailto:jhaley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhaley@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5260<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa  Indians Tribe
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>June 1995 to September 1996<br>
