<head>
<title>National Alternative Fuels Laboratory</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>National Alternative Fuels Laboratory</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2></font>
<p>
     The National Alternative Fuels Laboratory (NAFL) at the EERC was founded in 1988 to serve as
the "Underwriter's Laboratory" for oxygenated fuels through the support of the U.S. Department
of Agriculture.  NAFL efforts have included work with the Governors Ethanol Coalition, the
National Corn Growers Association, the American Coalition for Ethanol, and producers.  The
NAFL's problem-solving approach recognizes the uniquely linked needs of growers, producers,
consumers, industry, and the environment.  An NAFL program linked with industry will
integrate ethanol-related projects with other alternative energy projects.  The driving forces for
alternative fuels development and utilization and issues that the NAFL is concerned with are
highlighted below.<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> There is a national desire to enhance markets for U.S.
agricultural products.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Alternative fuels based on agricultural products are a key
component of energy independence for the United States.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 established a gasoline
program mandating the use of oxygenates in areas of the United States with high carbon monoxide
levels.<br>
 <p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Biomass-based alternative fuels have the potential to minimize
the
environmental impacts of an expanding society.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Some oxygenates currently used to reduce carbon monoxide
emissions and ozone formation are nonbiodegradable and have been detected in precipitation and
groundwater.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The formation and the degree of toxicity of airborne pollutants
due to gasoline evaporative emissions are dependent upon the type of oxgenate used.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The health effects of the use of the oxygenate MTBE (methyl
<i>tertiary</i>-butyl ether) have been questioned.  The potential for adverse health effects and
detrimental performance with the use of MTBE and other oxygenates must be more clearly
understood.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Ethanol and ethanol-based oxygenates are produced mainly from
corn grown by U.S. farmers, while MTBE (26% of which will be imported in 1995) is derived
largely from natural gas.  Imports of MTBE are projected to reach 90,000 barrels per day in the near
future.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives of the program are as follows:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To collect and disseminate information on alternative fuels, with
an emphasis on fuels derived or partially derived from renewable resources.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To perform experimentation on motor fuel component behavior
and properties for use in the regulatory process.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To develop, demonstrate, and commercialize processes and
products to expand the use of alternative fuels.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To develop alternative oxygenates to meet stringent
environmental
requirements on fuels.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Results </h2>
     <p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> NAFL has working partnerships with industry, including the
National Corn Growers Association, ethanol producers, and the Pellet Fuels Institute, to develop
information on efficient and environmentally acceptable use of alternative fuels.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Various ethanol denaturants have demonstrated their potential to
reduce the increased vapor pressure of 10% ethanol fuels.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Automobile fuel evaporation canisters have been demonstrated
and compared with ethanol-blended (and other oxygenated) fuels and base fuels.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> NAFL has developed partnerships with other laboratories and
institutions in research programs, resulting in data sharing, literature tracking, and database
development.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> At-the-pump survey and analysis of fuels sampled from across
the
United States comparing advertised with actual fuel compositions were performed by NAFL.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> NAFL performed compositional analysis of evaporative
emissions
for improving the understanding of atmospheric activity and ozone formation.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Future Directions</h2>
<p>
     The NAFL program will evaluate the environmental and economic impacts of alternative fuel
use on our nation, focusing on the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Continuing the test program on fuel evaporative emissions to
determine the effects of oxygenates and denaturants on environmental and performance issues. 
Overall environmental issues to be addressed include solubility and partitioning characteristics,
cosolvency, and biodegradation of oxygenates.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Providing objective criteria for the public and industry regarding
evaluation of environmental and economic aspects of alternative fuel use.  These include involvement
in programs of the Governors Ethanol Coalition, the North Dakota Alternative Fuels Task Force, the
American Coalition for Ethanol, the U.S. Department of Energy, and the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Pursuing research and development leading to commercialization
opportunities in partnership with industry to determine the chemical and physical characteristics of
oxygenates, remediation technologies affecting the alternative fuels industry, and development of
improved and new oxygenates.</ul> <p><hr>
<b>Project Managers:</b>
<li> Curtis L. Knudson/<a href=mailto:cknudson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>cknudson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5185<br>
<li>John H. Pavlish/<a href=mailto:jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5268<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> 
<li>U.S. Department of Agriculture<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>May 1988 to April 1996<br>
