<html>
<head>
<title>Reactivity and Analytical Support for Oxygenate Project</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Reactivity and Analytical Support for Oxygenate Project </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The addition of oxygenates to gasoline has been mandated by the 1990 Clean Air Act
Amendments to lower pollution caused by deleterious exhaust emissions in urban areas.  This
project contributed to the development of a new technology for production of the tertiary ether
oxygenates, methyl <i>tertiary</i>-butyl ether (MTBE) and <i>tertiary</i>-amyl methyl
ether (TAME), whose
addition to gasoline will give a cleaner-burning fuel with lower hydrocarbon and carbon
monoxide emissions.  Agricultural and waste products were used to achieve this environmental
improvement.  Thus renewable energy sources can contribute substantially to reformulated fuel
production.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     Ether oxygenates that will be in high demand for addition to reformulated gasoline can be
prepared from agricultural products or by-products.  The objective of this work was to evaluate
new catalysts for the conversion of the biomass precursors to olefins with a branched structure
which are required for preparation of tertiary ethers, such as MTBE and TAME.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     The catalysts were successful in removing oxygen from the biomass precursors, as well as in
reforming the structures to the desired branched isomers without converting much of the biomass
precursor to aromatics.  This project developed a concept for an economical process to produce
these important fuel components from renewable energy sources.  Feed materials for the process
included starch, hemicellulose, and cellulose components, and thus a wide variety of agricultural,
forestry, and waste products can be utilized.<p>
<p>
     The best results were obtained using 2-butanone as an intermediate in the process.  This is
produced by bacterial fermention and acid treatment of the aqueous medium.  The 2-butanone
was converted catalytically to hydrocarbon mixtures in 90% yields.  The products were mainly
the C<sub>3</sub> to C<sub>5</sub> olefins, with about equal amounts of isobutylene and
butylenes.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Ronald C. Timpe/<a href=mailto:rtimpe@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rtimpe@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5219<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>Universal Fuel Development Associates
<hr>
