<head>
<title>Preparation and Combustion of
RDF-Coal Slurry Fuels</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg">
<center><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<h1>Preparation and Combustion of RDF-Coal Slurry Fuels</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     In 1992, the EERC and EnerTech Environmental, Inc., began conducting research using an
innovative municipal waste reuse technology developed by EnerTech to address a major
environmental challenge:  disposal of municipal solid waste (MSW).  The refuse-derived fuel
(RDF) carbonization process produces an enhanced slurry fuel, reporting increases in energy
density of 400%, reductions in chloride concentration of 80%, and reductions in the sulfur
content of 50%.  Based on these results, in 1993, the EERC and EnerTech developed a
RDF-lignite slurry fuels project to integrate the waste reuse technology with methods currently
under development at the EERC for converting low-rank coals to energy-dense liquid fuels. <p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The goal of this project was to evaluate a new and innovative process to make better use of solid
waste materials by disposing of them in an environmentally benign way, while simultaneously
generating energy.  This program was intended to assess the feasibility of blending a MSW slurry
with lignite in an aqueous phase:  specifically, blending an upgraded North Dakota lignite slurry
fuel with a low-sulfur, carbonized RDF slurry and reviewing combustion characteristics in a
bench-scale pressurized fluidized-bed combustion (PFBC) unit.  Use of the blend not only
reduces the SO<sub>2</sub> emissions from the fuel but also utilizes the energy from
MSW.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     EnerTech supplied a dried, pelletized sample of RDF from Thief River Falls, Minnesota, having
an as-received heating value of about 8000 Btu/lb.  Slurry samples were carbonized in a batch
autoclave, resulting in a fuel with a dry heating value of about 13,000 Btu/lb, thus increasing the
heating value of the solid fuel by 50%.  The carbonized RDF could be slurried with water to
about 42 wt% concentration.  The energy density of a slurry of pumpable viscosity was improved
about 400%.  In addition, the chloride concentration of the RDF material was also reduced by
over 60%, most of which transferred to the aqueous phase.  This reduction is extremely
important, since high chlorine concentrations lead to the formation of furans and dioxins during
combustion.  A similar carbonization investigation was also completed on a lignite with an
as-received heating value of 6300 Btu/lb.  Carbonization tests with the lignite indicated that the
lignite slurry heating value increased by over 60%, with an achievable solids concentration of
over 55 wt%.<p>
<p>
     Approximately 40 pounds of carbonized RDF slurry fuel, RDF-lignite slurry fuel, and lignite
slurry fuel was produced using a 2-gal autoclave system at the EERC.  This fuel will be used for
the combustion test program to be completed at a later date.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Chris M. Anderson/<a href=mailto:canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>canderson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5120<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center 
<li>EnerTech Environmental, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>August 1993 to August 1994<br>
