<head>
<title>Value-Added Carbons</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Value-Added Carbons </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Coal is a versatile material from which a variety of value-added products can be produced. 
Current research at the EERC is focused on investigating special carbon products derived from
coal to which value is added.  These carbons have application, for example, in the power
generation, municipal waste incineration, metal, and automotive industries.  Substantial
environmental benefits are afforded from their use through conservation of energy and resources,
reduction in gaseous emissions, and prevention of water and soil pollution.<p>
<h3>Objective</h3>
     The pivotal question to be addressed is whether unique, cost-effective activated carbons can be
produced by taking advantage of the inherently porous and reactive structure of low-rank coals,
e.g., lignite and subbituminous coals.  Carbon products will be evaluated in relation to their use
in air toxic control and other applications.  In addition to developing carbons for specific market
needs, the program also seeks to develop a fundamental understanding of the extent and quality
of the porous surface required to achieve rapid, high-capacity adsorption of gaseous and toxic
metal pollutants and the processing conditions for converting coal into superior carbon
products.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     A rotary kiln was constructed and used for activation of North Dakota lignite with potassium
hydroxide (KOH) at high temperatures (900&#176;C).  However, highly porous carbons were not
formed, and difficulties with plugging were encountered.  A new high-temperature stirred reactor
was designed and built.  Carbons prepared with powdered KOH have high iodine values (1100
mg/g).  Carbons prepared by making a paste with KOH and NaOH had lower iodine values. 
Methods for preparing ultraporous carbon for supercapacitors are under investigation.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown
Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> January 1995 to December 1995<br>
