<html>
<head>
<title>Carbon Molecular Sieves</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Carbon Molecular Sieves</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Separations of gas components can be effected with molecular sieves made from carbons by
developing a pore-size distribution in the subnanometer range.  The required pore-size
distribution can be achieved by filling the numerous larger pores in a coal char with a liquid
phase, which is a good precursor for carbons when thermally activated.  This technique was to
be performed with some recently available materials from waste and coal pyrolysis.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objective was to examine the feasibility of preparing microporous composite carbons from
inexpensive or waste products that exhibit high selectivity properties suitable for gas
separations.  Although many tarry and polymeric materials had been investigated previously,
the pore-filling materials utilized in this project were unique.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     Two new methods for cross-linking coal tars and plastic pyrolysis tars were developed.  Both the
methylal condensation product and the aluminum phenoxide-catalyzed alkylation product were
waxy resins.  The resinous products from these processes have potential as binders for pelleting
as well as pore fillers for making molecular sieves.  The molecular sieves were prepared by
impregnation of macroporous chars with the resinous materials and thermal activation to develop
the micropore structures.  The chars that were impregnated with these materials were heated to
activate them and convert them to molecular sieve materials.<p>
     Carbons were impregnated with biomass-derived resins and recarbonized.  They were tested for
catalytic reduction of NO<sub>x</sub> with ammonia at 150&#176;C.  The carbons effectively
catalyzed the reduction of NO<sub>2</sub> to N<sub>2</sub>, but the reduction of NO
was partial.  Further testing of molecular sieve carbons for gas separation is in progress.<p>

     The set of molecular sieve carbons being prepared by pore-filling the char with plastic pyrolysis
resin and activating at various temperatures will be tested for selective gas adsorption.  Further
work is needed to understand and improve the selective catalytic reduction ability of these
carbons.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edwin S. Olson/<a href=mailto:eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5155<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> March 1994 to March 1995<br>
<hr>
