</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>New Methods for Preparation of
Stabilized Carbons</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>New Methods for Preparation of Stabilized Carbons </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     The use of chars and carbons as adsorbents and catalyst supports could be expanded if their
stability to reactive gases were improved.  The purpose of this project was to develop methods
for applying surface coatings of boron carbide, silicon carbide, and titanum carbide on the char. 
Formation of these composites will increase stability and improve structural strength and,
consequently, resistance to abrasion.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The first objective of this project was to develop methods for coating low-rank coal (LRC) chars
and carbons by chemical vapor deposition (CVD) to produce high-surface-area composites that
are inert to reactive atmospheres.  The proposed coating layers were to be formed from elements
known to form extremely hard and stable carbide materials.<p>

     The second objective was to determine the feasibility of using supercritical fluid extraction (SFE)
to prepare an activated carbon with a very high surface area.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>

     CVD treatments of carbons and chars with boron carbide gave coated carbon products with
substantially higher resistance to oxidation in an air stream.  Products were stable to 600&#176;C,
whereas carbons initially decomposed at 350&#176;-500&#176;C in air.<p>

     Previous SFE experiments generated low-porosity chars with areas of 175 m<sup>2</sup>/g,
owing to collapse of pores during depressurization.  Pore collapse was reduced by dropping the
pressure very slowly while maintaining the critical temperature.  The new procedure gave chars with
surfaces as high as 361 m<sup>2</sup>/g from a North Dakota lignite.  Inorganic pillars were
introduced into the pores by injecting soluble precursor reagents under supercritical conditions.  The
pillars prevent some of the pore collapse during depressurization and give char with surface areas as
large as 328 m<sup>2</sup>/g.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edwin S. Olson/<a href=mailto:eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5155<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1994 to June 1995 <br>
<hr>
