<html>
<head>
<title>Upgrading Coal Chars and Coal Liquids</title>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Upgrading Coal Chars and Coal Liquids </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
     Current technology for the production of activated carbon involves a two-step process.  The first
step is carbonization, usually in an inert atmosphere.  The second step, activation, usually
involves mild oxidation with CO<sub>2</sub>, air, or steam, although chemical activation may
also be used. 
Activation parameters include heat treatment conditions, reagent gas, residence time, and
inorganic content.  The naturally high reactivity of low-rank coals, because of their relatively
high surface area and oxygen content, is advantageous for producing activated carbons tailored to
gas and water treatment applications.  Activated carbons are used to remove sulfur and nitrogen
oxides, trace metals, and heavy organics from stack gas.  Water and wastewater treatment
consumes large quantities of activated carbon.  However, the optimum technology for realizing
this potential for activated carbon is still lacking.<p>

     Coal liquids produced during mild gasification of coals are known to be unstable and to
polymerize during recovery, storage, or secondary upgrading.  Primary devolatilization products
can undergo additional fragmentation by the extension of residence time at temperatures over
300&#176;C in the presence of catalysts such as limestone, dolomite, or iron compounds.  For
instance, calcium-based catalysts increase the dehydroxylation of phenolics to simpler aromatics. 
The CO<sub>2</sub> acceptor gasification process, which uses a dolomite bed material,
reported essentially no tar formation, implying that the bed material was catalytic.  In the catalytic
steam gasification of low-rank coals at the EERC using a limestone bed, only light hydrocarbons and
naphthalene were formed.  The presence of iron can aid in hydrogen scrambling from long-chain
paraffins to decrease coking.  In order to improve liquid quality, an in-process (close-coupled)
reaction system is needed essentially to complete the reformation in the gas phase before reactive coal
liquids condense and have the opportunity to form refractory polymers.<p> 

<p>

     Compounds containing nitrogen functionalities in coal liquids are the most difficult and costly of
the compounds that must be removed during refining.  These troublesome compounds, on the
other hand, contain valuable chemicals which, if separated inexpensively, could yield substantial
income to the process.  Preliminary tests have shown that they can be selectively adsorbed onto
spent nickel-based catalysts.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of the project were to 1) assess preparation/activation methods and characteristics
of low-rank coal char that contribute to its adsorptivity for pollutants in wastewater and/or gases,
2) determine methods of enhancing the activity of the char, and 3) investigate the feasibility of a
catalyst bed close-coupled to a fluid-bed carbonizer to crack the emerging coal liquids into more
valuable products.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     This project has been completed, and the three objectives have been accomplished.  One Alaskan
(Beluga) subbituminous coal and two North Dakota coals (Beulah lignite and leonardite) were
pyrolyzed under nitrogen and activated with steam and carbon dioxide-argon atmospheres in the
EERC-constructed integrated bench-scale gasifier (IBG) of nominal 100-g capacity.  Staged
heating, i.e., dropping the coal charge in at 500&#176;C, heating to a final temperature of
850&#176;C, and activating with steam, tended to give chars with enhanced adsorption.  In the case
of Beulah lignite, staged heating produced increased methane and carbon monoxide in the gaseous 
products.  However, preliminary experiments indicated that rapid heating to lower temperatures
yielded more adsorptive chars.  The steam-activated leonardite char exhibited substantially greater
adsorption of sulfur dioxide (SO<sub>2</sub>) at 100&#176;C than the steam-activated Beulah
lignite and Alaskan char, but the latter two showed SO<sub>2</sub> adsorption comparable to
commercially available activated coal chars.  Pellets formed from the steam-activated Beulah lignite
char and polyvinyl alcohol showed improved water resistance and apparent hardness.<p>           

<p>

     Preliminary tests on activating leonardite with potassium hydroxide indicated increased
SO<sub>2</sub> adsorption at 100&#176;C for freshly prepared char under rapid heating
conditions.<p>
     Coal liquid upgrading was carried out in the IBG by passing all hot gases formed during
pyrolysis through a catalyst bed.  The solid catalyst was supported in a heated module flanged
directly to the top of the reactor.  The module was heated by the reactor and was typically
50&#176;-100&#176;C below that of the reactor.  Fourier transform infrared on-line analysis of the
pyrolysis
gases indicated an increase in light hydrocarbon gases in the gas stream after passing through a
Ni catalyst bed compared with that of the raw stream, indicating that catalytic cracking of tars is
accomplished.  In the follow-on project, less expensive catalyst forms will be tested in an attempt
to find more economical, less easily poisoned catalyst materials.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  January 1993 to April 1994<br>
<hr>
