<head>
<title>Coke Evaluation and the Development of
a Tailored Form Coke for the Foundry
Industry</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2> Coke Evaluation and the Development of a Tailored Form Coke for the Foundry Industry
</h2> </center> 
<hr>



<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     Cupolas are used to produce over 70% of iron castings.  Coke is essentially the universal fuel
for cupola melting.  The increasingly stringent environmental regulations, beginning
1998-2003, will lead to supply problems of coke from traditional coke ovens.  Form coke is
the most viable alternative to foundry coke.  It is produced in a closed system from low-cost
(often low-rank) coals.  This project evaluated the applicability of form coke for foundry use
and the development of a tailored form coke incorporating iron waste and alloying agents as a
means to use these materials more efficiently in the cupola operation.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The overall objective was to produce, via environmentally friendly processes, a low-cost
alternative fuel--form coke--for cupola melting.  The aim was to produce form coke
briquettes having superior properties to those of conventional foundry coke.  The work was
divided into five phases.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The EERC procured three foundry cokes and two metallurgical cokes for evaluation.  The
foundry cokes included one domestically produced slot oven coke, a Korean form coke produced
by stamping and then calcining a coke breeze-anthracite-pitch binder mixture, and a U.S. form
coke produced by briquetting and then calcining a coal char-coal pitch-caking coal mixture.  The
metallurgical cokes included a Japanese form coke produced by briquetting and then calcining a
coal char-coal pitch binder mixture and a South Korean coke which is prepared by briquetting a
noncoking coal and then calcining the briquettes with a coking coal in a slot oven.<p>

<p>

     Property (chemical, physical, mechanical) determinations included sulfur, ash, volatile matter,
and carbon contents, composition of coke ash, heating value, ash fusion temperatures (reducing
atmosphere), true and apparent densities, surface area and pore volume, reactivity (by Japanese
"I" test), abrasion (tumble) resistance, and tensile strength.  Abrasion resistance, tensile strength,
and organic vapor emission measurements were performed on coke exposed to reactive
atmospheres or elevated temperatures that simulate cupola operating conditions.<p>

<p>

     Preliminary results indicated that when chemical, physical, and mechanical properties are
considered together, none of the form cokes are equivalent to the traditional oven coke.  The
chemical properties (sulfur, ash, and carbon contents) of the form cokes (foundry and
metallurgical) were typically inferior to the oven coke, but the mechanical properties (abrasion
resistance and tensile strength) of the form cokes were similar or better.  However, the
mechanical properties of foundry form cokes exposed to a simulated cupola atmosphere were
somewhat diminished relative to the oven coke.  The chemical, physical, and mechanical
properties of the form cokes can be modified to the desired levels by proper feedstock selection
and by processing adjustments.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:ddaly@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b> American Foundrymen's Society, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>   April 1994 to March 1995<br>
