<html>
<head>
<title>Sorbent Carbon Development</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Sorbent Carbon Development</h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>

     Increasing attention is being directed towards carbons in powdered, granular, and pelletized
form for environmental applications associated with energy production, by-product recoveries,
and waste incineration as well as water purification and wastewater cleanup.  Typically,
carbons are activated to increase the surface area and, hence, the sorption capacity.  This
physical activation is usually carried out with steam or carbon dioxide at elevated
temperatures, whereas chemical activation involves treatment, e.g., with potassium hydroxide,
phosphoric acid, or zinc chloride, followed by pyrolysis at temperatures generally lower than
those used in physical activation.  <p>

     Sources of sorbent carbons include coals of various rank, coal-derived chars and cokes, and
carbonized bone, wood, and coconut shell.  A significant margin exists to reduce the
production cost by producing carbons from low-cost, highly reactive low-rank coals (LRCs). 
However, several aspects of sorbent carbon production, activation, and utilization from LRCs
are unclear, including how adsorption capacity and chemical/mechanical stability relate to coal
rank, coal properties, inherent or added cations, and carbon preparation conditions. Models
relating carbon properties to adsorption effectiveness for specific species are also lacking.  A
systematic development program on LRC-derived carbons is now being undertaken at the
EERC.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>

     The primary objective of this work was to transform LRCs economically into effective sorbent
carbons for gas- and liquid-phase contaminant removal.  Initially, the aim of the work was to
compare the sorption of carbons prepared from a North Dakota lignite or leonardite with that
of coal-derived commercial carbons and to examine the relationship between coal properties
and adsorption characteristics of coal-derived carbons.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     A reaction vessel was designed to produce up to 20 lb of char in a single batch at a maximum
temperature of 1000&#176;C.  Steam or carbon dioxide activation of the char can be carried out in
the vessel, denoted as the "kiln" reactor.  Shakedown testing of the kiln reactor using 25 lb of North 
Dakota lignite indicated that the system performed according to the design criteria.  20 lb of char
was prepared from a North Dakota leonardite under optimal conditions for later activation
development.<p>
     The kiln reactor was assembled from a Cress Model X31TC kiln containing a stainless steel
cylindrical vessel wrapped on the outside with stainless steel tubing.  The kiln is rated for
2500&#176;F (1370&#176;C).  The vessel has a capacity of 2700 in.<sup>3</sup> (44,480
cm<sup>3</sup>) and is designed to be operated in the fixed-bed mode.  It has a distributer plate
on the bottom through which gas, preheated by the kiln as it passes through the external coils on the
vessel, enters to permeate the coal bed.  The tars, oils, moisture, and effluent gases exit through the
top of the vessel and pass through a series of two air-cooled condensers before being vented to the
outside of the building.  Georesources leonardite (-10  +30 mesh), received in June 1994, was used
as feed to the reactor.<p>

Washability testing was performed on raw leonardite and leonardite char prepared in the kiln
reactor at 450&#176;C under flowing N<sub>2</sub>.  The results indicated that physical
cleaning will reduce the ash in either the raw or carbonized leonardite by more than 55% with
72%-75% recovery of the feed (on a dry basis) in the float fraction.<p>

     The mineral content of the leonardite was quite high.  The presence of the large amount of ash
substantially reduced the available sorbent carbon per unit mass.  Therefore, to evaluate the
sorbent characteristics of the carbon, ash was reduced 55% by physical means (float-sink) and
98% by chemical means.  The physically cleaned char adsorbed 10.9 char wt%
SO<sub>2</sub>, while the chemically cleaned char adsorbed 8.1 char wt%
SO<sub>2</sub> at ambient conditions.<p>

     Steam activation for 20 minutes at 750&#176;C produced an SO<sub>2</sub> sorbent
superior to one produced at 20 minutes of steam followed by 5 minutes of 3.5% oxygen.  Oxidation,
even if slow as in the case of the low-oxygen activation gas, resulted in loss of pore surface area and
a corresponding loss in sorption sites in the char.  Similarly, steam activation for 20 minutes at
750&#176;C  resulted in more SO<sub>2</sub> sorbent than a char activated for 20 minutes
with steam at 850&#176;C.<p>

     Char was prepared at three carbonization temperatures, 350&#176;, 480&#176;, and
550&#176;C, to determine the effect of this operating parameter.  A slightly greater
SO<sub>2</sub> sorption was obtained with char which was carbonized at 350&#176;C than
that prepared at 550&#176;C.  Lower carbonization temperature gave slightly better carbonized
product for activation.  It appears that the tars, when heated and then cooled without volatilizing,
undergo change such that when heated to activation temperature, they carbonize and provide
additional active sites.<p>


     Char-steam contact time carried out indicated that activation with steam probably does little to
increase the sorptive capacity for SO<sub>2</sub>.  The SO<sub>2</sub> sorption (9 wt%)
obtained at ambient temperature at low or no steam activation time approximated those obtained in
work on previous projects involving char preparation.  Optimum SO<sub>2</sub> sorption was
obtained with char which had been activated with steam between 0 and 20 minutes.<p>

     Char prepared from the 1.4 float fraction of the physically cleaned leonardite adsorbed 10.9% of
its weight in SO<sub>2</sub> and had an iodine number of 435.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Brian C. Young<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy  Morgantown Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1994 to March 1995<br>
<hr>
