<html>
<head>
<title>Hot-Gas Filter Ash Characterization</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2> Hot-Gas Filter Ash Characterization </h2> </center> 
<hr>
<h3> Background </h3>
     Large-scale hot-gas filter testing supported by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) and
the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) over the past 10 years has revealed numerous cases of
cake buildup on filter elements that has been difficult, if not impossible, to remove.  Physical
factors--including particle-size distribution, particle shape, and the aerodynamics of
deposition--certainly contribute to the difficulty in removing the cake.  However, circumstances
have also existed where critical temperatures and subsequent irreversible effects appeared to have
played a role.  Possibly, chemical and physical effects are helping to bond the ash to the filter or
to itself.<p>
     Therefore, both the physical and chemical aspects of ash formation and detachment from hot-gas
filters must be investigated.  EPRI has organized a consortium of companies in partnership with
DOE to fund the research necessary to determine the factors that cause hot-gas cleanup filters
either to be blinded by ash or to develop deposits that can bridge the filters and cause them to
fail.  The EERC is the sole contractor for this research.<p>
     This project is funded by the U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology
Center and a consortium of companies, which includes Westinghouse, Lurgi Lentjes Babcock,
Netherlands Energy Research Foundation, PowerGen, Schumacher Filters America,
Electicit&eacute; de
France, and ABB/Carbon AB.  The Electric Power Development Corporation of Japan is
strongly interested in joining the consortium.<p>
<h3>Objectives</h3>
     The objectives of this project are threefold:  to determine the mechanisms by which a
difficult-to-clean
ash is formed and how it blinds or bridges hot-gas filters, to develop a method to determine
the rate of blinding or bridging, based on analyses of the feed coal and sorbent and the operating
conditions, and to provide suggestions for ways to prevent filter blinding and bridging by the
troublesome ash.<p>
    The work is investigating both the physical and chemical processes that are occurring within the
filter cake of high-temperature filters for a variety of coal and sorbent combinations and is
developing a predictive methodology to identify fuel characteristics and process conditions that
produce tenacious ashes.  The predictive capabilities will be organized into a user-friendly
computer model.<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
     This work is ongoing and the project is expected to be completed in March 1997.  Plans are to
examine 1) ashes from large-scale operating filters, 2) ash originally from a large-scale
pressurized fluidized-bed combustor (PFBC) or gasifier that has been reentrained in a
laboratory-scale rig
and deposited on a filter in a simulated environment, and 3) newly generated ashes from
small pilot- or bench-scale facilities where parametric evaluations will be employed.  The
problem will be defined through full-scale sampling.  Then parametric testing will be done at the
laboratory
and bench scale to determine the factors leading to the problem.  Finally, the data will
be used to develop a user-friendly computer model to help predict the occurrence of the problem,
choose appropriate fuels or operating conditions, or design the system to reduce the blinding and
bridging problems.  Solutions predicted by the model will be tested on the bench scale with
single-filter elements.<p>


     To identify and evaluate the mechanisms of ash interaction that may be occurring, laboratory-
and bench-scale test facilities and advanced analytical scanning electron microscopy (SEM)
equipment will be used to generate the ash and to determine the quantities and composition
distributions of inorganic phases in the coal, fly ashes, deposits, and system materials.  An
advanced SEM method, fine-particle technique (FPT), to determine particle-size and composition
distributions of submicron ash is being developed as a part of this project.  In parallel studies,
physical properties of the cakes will be measured in an attempt to relate both physical and
chemical phenomena to the ability to clean a hot-gas filter.  The physical properties data will be
enhanced by that provided by EPRI and DOE contractors in public reports.<p>



     Because interactions in the ash involve inorganic species whose basic chemistries are not well
understood, fundamental studies may also be required to fill these gaps.  Therefore, the analyses
of the ash will include developing a profile of the physical and chemical species as a function of
the depth of the deposit.  To achieve this goal, a sampling protocol will be developed to collect,
intact, a cake deposit from an operating filter, whether it be in the laboratory or in the field.  Both
problematic and easy-to-clean filter cakes will be reproduced in the laboratory to better
understand their formation mechanisms.  This will be done using both pressurized fluidized-bed
combustor and gasifier test facilities to generate new ashes.<p>



     Five tasks will be performed:  Task 1 - Field Sampling, Task 2 - Laboratory-Scale Testing, Task
3 - Bench-Scale Testing, Task 4 - Computer Modeling, and Task 5 - Reporting.  The following
parameters will be considered for investigation at each scale:  ash size and composition
distributions, coal/sorbent (sulfur, ash composition, chlorine), gaseous species
(H<sub>2</sub>S, HCl, SO<sub>2</sub>, alkali), additives, dust loading, face velocity,
temperature, pressure, time, operating change in pressure, oxidizing/reducing environments, and
fluid dynamics of dust and gas.<p>


     These primary variables affect the cleanability of the dust cake.  A subobjective will be to
determine the importance of these variables and their relationship to each other.  Test plans will
be developed by the EERC for each of these testing tasks, detailing the number and range of
parameters to be evaluated.  These test plans will be distributed to the sponsoring organizations
for approval at the semiannual meetings prior to commencing work.<p>



     To date, samples of coal, sorbent, and ashes from several test series at the American Electric
Power (AEP) Tidd Station PFBC, in Brilliant, Ohio, have been analyzed for chemical and
physical properties.  Results of the analyses indicate that with regard to ash particle size and
composition, ashes that have larger particle-size distributions and have experienced less sulfation
produce less problematic ash.  Therefore, controlling the particle size of ash entering a filter
vessel may result in less sticking and sintering of the ash.  Surface analyses of the filter ashes are
also being conducted to determine the effects of surface chemistry on ash sintering behavior. 
Analysis of archive samples from the Grimethorpe PFBC are also under way.<p>
<hr>
Project Manager: John P. Hurley/<a href=mailto:jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5159<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> <ul plain>Electric Power Research Institute<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center <br></ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> April 1994 to March 1997<br>
