<head>
<title>Engineering Performance of Advanced
Structural Materials</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Engineering Performance of Advanced Structural Materials </h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Background</h3></font> <p>

     The structures inside advanced coal-fired energy systems will be exposed to much higher
temperatures and much more corrosive environments than in today's steam cycle systems.  These
conditions require the use of advanced structural materials such as ceramics for construction of
subsystems.  Advanced ceramics such as silicon carbide (SiC) are resistant to corrosion and are
very strong at much higher temperatures than today's metals.  For example, SiC sublimes
without melting at temperatures over 2000&#176;C.  This makes SiC difficult to use in the
fabrication of large structures, because pieces made from SiC cannot be joined together in the same
way that metals can be welded.  Therefore, the size of the monolithic ceramic structures that can be
manufactured is limited by the size of the sintering furnaces (approximately 10 ft for sintered alpha
silicon carbide).  In order to make larger objects such as directly fired turbine parts or large heat
exchangers, many small ceramic pieces must be fused or joined.  In addition, field repair of the
objects will require the use of field joining techniques.  At present, no joining techniques for
high-temperature structural ceramics are routinely available.<p>

     The primary work of this project is to develop data and techniques that will promote the use of
advanced structural materials in the construction of advanced energy systems.  Currently, the
focus is to develop new methods of joining silicon-based nonoxide ceramics in field applications. 
The work will include testing the corrosion resistance of the joints and joined materials in
high-temperature
coal utilization environments. The corrosion behavior of the materials and joints will
be incorporated in the Fuel Quality Advisor computer model being developed under another
project.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font>


     The overall objective of this work is to develop a patentable technique for joining large,
silicon-based
advanced ceramics in the field.  The key to a successful technique will be the use of
reactive joining compounds to ease the creation of the joint.  Special efforts will be made to
transfer the developed technologies to the materials industry via licensing agreements through
the EERC Foundation.<p>

     Test bars of sintered silicon carbide (SiC) and silicon nitride
(Si<sub>3</sub>N<sub>4</sub>) will be bonded together using joining agents that will fuse
when heated.  The joining materials will be formulated to sinter at temperatures below
1500&#176;C, forming compounds that will bond the ceramics and have a similar coefficient of
thermal expansion.  The joining materials will be prepared by forming high-viscosity slips of
mixtures of near-micron-sized powders or by using sol-gel techniques.  They will then be fashioned
into a ceramic tape and cut in a green state to fit the joint.  SiC joints will be heated by attaching
electrodes to the bars on either side of the joint and passing current between them to heat the joint
(Joule heating).  Both high- and low-frequency AC will be used.  The
Si<sub>3</sub>N<sub>4</sub> bars and joints will be heated in a muffle furnace.  The
joints will be tested for strength at 1400&#176;C using a fully articulated, high-temperature
four-point flexure tester in an Instron 8562 universal multitester and compared with the strength of
the bulk material.  Joining conditions will then be optimized to produce the strongest joint by varying
the composition of the joining agent and the reaction time, temperature, and atmosphere.<p>


     There will be two main efforts this year.  The first is joining of silicon carbide using Joule
heating with reaction- sintered joining compounds and resistive heating.  The most successful
joints will be chemically and physically tested.  The reaction products in the joining compound
and between the compound and the SiC will be determined by x-ray diffraction, scanning
electron microscopy (SEM), and scanning Auger electron analysis of joints fractured in ultrahigh
vacuum.  Strength will be determined in four-point flexure at 1400&#176;C. 
Si<sub>3</sub>N<sub>4</sub> will be joined with SiAlON compounds by heating in a
furnace. <p>

     The relative resistance of the ceramics and their joints to coal slag attack will be determined by
heating joined bars in slag baths at 1400&#176;C for up to 100 hours.  The corrosion data will be
supplied to the investigators developing the Fuel Quality Advisor computer model being
constructed under another project.<p>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Results </h3></font> 
     The electrical resistance of silicon carbide is inversely related to temperature so that as it is
heated, its resistance drops.  When resistive heating is used, the drop in resistance causes a
greater electricity flow for a given voltage.  Therefore, if a simple voltage controller is used to
vary the power to the bars to be joined, the temperature is prone to runaway, i.e., uncontrolled
heating at rates of over 300&#176;C/min.  Therefore, we have developed an experimental power
supply to successfully control the temperature of silicon carbide after SiC specimens have been
preheated to a temperature of about 300&#176;C.  Methods of controlling temperature without
preheating are being investigated.<p>



     Pellets of joining material composed of silicon carbide, silicon powder, and graphite powder
were prepared for use as a joining material.  They contain only 2.1 wt% binder and have an
average porosity of 17%, which is considered very low.  SEM analyses showed good particle
distribution but possible problems due to a high percentage of excessively large silicon and
graphite particles.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  John P. Hurley/<a href=mailto:jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5159<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> January 1995 to December
1995<br>
