<html>
<head>
<title>Support Services for Ceramic
Fiber-Ceramic Matrix Composites</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2>Support Services for Ceramic Fiber-Ceramic Matrix Composites </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Background</h3></font> <p>


     To increase national self-sufficiency for the near future, energy systems will be required to fire
low-grade fuels efficiently.  The steam cycle employed at present uses a maximum steam
temperature of 550&#176;C and has an energy conversion efficiency of 35%.  To boost efficiency,
higher working fluid temperatures are required. Subsystems must operate at much higher
temperatures and in much more corrosive environments.  Problems of concern are corrosion and
fatigue of high-temperature heat exchangers and hot-gas cleanup filters.  To prevent subsystem
failure, advanced materials (ceramics) must be used for construction. <p>



<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives</h3></font> <p>



     The EERC is working with researchers funded through the Advanced Research and Technology
Development Materials Program administered at Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) to
design tests of ceramic materials that simulate the corrosive conditions occurring in advanced
coal-fueled energy systems.  Combustion and gasification systems will be studied, primarily
those being developed in U.S. Department of Energy programs.  Two types of corrosion
conditions are being investigated:  those in hot-gas cleanup systems where alkali vapor may
contribute to corrosion and those in high-temperature heat exchangers where the main corrodent
is coal ash slag.<p>



<font color="#990066"><h3>Results</h3></font> 

     Ash produced at the American Electric Power Tidd Station pressurized fluidized bed was chosen
for hot-gas filter corrosion testing.  Subbituminous coals were chosen for heat-exchanger
corrosion testing:  an Illinois No. 6 coal slag, to represent the eastern U.S. bituminous coals, and
a Powder River Basin coal slag, to represent the western U.S. coals.  To assure that the slags
were at thermodynamic equilibrium for testing, they were  collected from cyclone-fired utility
boilers.<p>



     A 55-gal drum of hot-gas filter ash was received from the Tidd Station and analyzed by x-ray
fluorescence and x-ray diffraction.  Suggested conditions for corrosion testing with this ash are
900&#176;C (although many other researchers do not go above 850&#176;C) in 15%
CO<sub>2</sub>,
15% H<sub>2</sub>O, 3% O<sub>2</sub>, 0.5% SO<sub>2</sub>, and 10 ppm of
NaCl, with a balance of N<sub>2</sub>.  Samples were distributed to Penn State University,
West Virginia University, and 3M Company.<p>


     A 55-gal drum of slag was received from each of three power plants.  The Northern States Power
Company provided slag from its Riverside plant produced while burning a coal from the Powder
River Coal Company Rochelle mine, Wyoming.  A drum of Illinois No. 6 slag was provided by
the Central Illinois Public Service Coffeen plant.  Analyses showed abnormally high calcium
concentrations caused by limestone additions to the coal to reduce slag viscosity.  Therefore,
another drum of Illinois No. 6 slag was requested from the Illinois Power Company Baldwin
plant.  Viscosity versus temperature and composition determinations were performed on each of
the three slags, and samples were distributed to researchers at Penn State University, Argonne
National Laboratory, and ORNL.  Suggested initial conditions for slag testing are 1090&#176;,
1260&#176;, and 1430&#176;C in air, although the viscosity tests show that water vapor may
significantly affect slag viscosity and so, perhaps, should be included at a level of about 15%.  This
effect is still being investigated.  The slag layer thickness should be approximately 5 mm. 
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>John P. Hurley/<a href=mailto:jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jhurley@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5159<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> Martin-Marietta Energy Systems, Inc. <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  October 1994 to September
1995<br>
