<html>
<head>
<title>Air Toxic Metals Transformation
Mechanisms Center for Air Toxic Metals
Program Area 1</title>
</head>
<body>

<center><img src ="gifs/eerc_hd.gif">
<h2>Air Toxic Metals Transformation Mechanisms <br>Center for Air Toxic Metals Program
Area 1
</h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Background</h3></font>

     The Center for Air Toxic Metals (CATM) at the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center
(EERC) of the University of North Dakota (UND) emphasizes research, development,
demonstration, and commercialization of innovative environmental cleanup technologies
through partnerships between government, industry, and the EERC in the areas of applied
science and engineering.  CATM was established by the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency (EPA) and is focused on minimizing the effects of air toxic metal pollutants on the
environment.  The Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 require regulatory actions addressing
189 substances, including air toxic metals.  In order to develop regulations, CATM is working
with industry and government to develop sufficient information on air toxic metals to provide a
scientific basis for preventing and controlling the emissions and evaluating the fate and impacts
of air toxic metals on plants and animals, including humans.  CATM-related programs are
focused on the development of methods to minimize the release of air toxic metals via practical
prevention and control methods based on scientific understanding and principles.  To facilitate
research efforts and dissemination of information, CATM is organized into five integrated
program areas:  Program Area 1 - Air Toxic Metals Transformation Mechanisms, Program
Area 2 - Analytical Methods Development, Program Area 3 - Control Technologies, Program
Area 4 - Modeling and Database, and Program Area 5 - Technology Commercialization and
Education. <p>

     The form and quantity of trace elements emitted from a fuel energy conversion system are a
function of the trace metal concentrations, forms, and associations in the fuel, the conversion
process, and operating conditions.  System conditions such as oxygen fugacity, gas-phase
composition, pressure, and temperature can be controlled in bench-, intermediate-, and pilot-scale
combustion
and gasification systems.  Thus fuels can be tested using the same conditions
to deduce the effects of fuel properties on trace metal transformations.  Alternatively, the same
fuel can be tested using various conversion processes and operating conditions to examine the
effects of parameters independent of the fuel.<p>
     Program Area 1 will provide the information essential for developing pollution prevention and
control strategies.  As a result of gaining knowledge about trace metal transformation
mechanisms, additional goals can be accomplished, such as 1) development of air toxic metal
pollution prevention methodologies, 2) development of models that predict trace element
emissions, and 3) development of effective strategies to control air toxic metal emissions.<p>
<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives</h3></font>

     The primary objective of Program Area 1 is to decipher the fundamental trace metal
transformation mechanisms that occur during coal and waste conversion processes.  Specific
secondary objectives are as follows:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Determine trace metal transformation mechanisms by conducting
combustion and partial gasification experiments in bench- and pilot-scale systems.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Construct an intermediate-scale combustion and gasification
system that is designed specifically for trace metal transformation studies and perform combustion
tests on this unit using coal, oil, and other non-fossil fuel oil fuels to elucidate trace element
transformations.  Rigorous testing will be done initially to determine some of the important factors in
mercury speciation during coal combustion.<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Validate theories developed and proposed through the bench- and 
pilot-scale testing at the full scale.<br>
</ul>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Results</h3></font>

     Transformations of trace metals were conducted using bench-scale drop-tube furnace (DTF)
equipment for both conventional combustion and gasification conditions.  Coal conversion
tests were performed in the pressurized DTF (PDTF) for Illinois No. 6 coal using furnace
conditions that ranged from 1000&#176; to 1500&#176;C, 50 to 150 psi, and 1.0 to 2.0
oxygen/carbon (O/C) ratio.  For comparison, the Illinois No. 6 coal was also tested in the PDTF
under highly oxidizing conditions. <p>

     The PDTF is a laboratory-scale entrained-flow tube furnace designed for the investigation of
pressurized combustion and gasification of coal.  Sampling was performed using a modified
version of EPA (Draft) Method 29.  The sampling method consisted of  using a multicyclone 
and final filter assembly, which was kept at the system pressure but under a lower temperature
of 150&#176;C.  Trace metal concentrations were measured for As, Cd, Cr, Pb, Ni, Se, and Hg by
collecting the entrained ash at the bottom of the PDTF using a multicyclone and impinger
sampling train and analyzing the particulate and liquids using atomic absorption spectroscopy
methods.  Average closure for Hg over twenty tests was 90% to 100%.  Noticeable impacts of
gas composition, expressed as O/C ratio, were observed on the partitioning and speciation of
Hg.  At lower O/C ratios or under more reducing conditions as would be encountered in a
gasification system, Hg appears to be driven to more volatile reduced forms.  Hg
concentrations in the submicron particulate or vapor-phase fraction of a sampling train are
greater at lower O/C ratios.  Speciation of Hg can be discerned indirectly by noting the
distribution of Hg concentrations in the impinger solutions used to capture vapor-phase Hg. 
The impinger system consists of hydrogen peroxide in the first impinger, which captures either
oxidized forms of Hg, such as Hg<sub>2</sub>O, or HgCl<sub>2</sub> and potassium
permanganate in the second
impinger, which captures reduced forms of Hg, such as elemental Hg.  Testing in the DTF
showed consistently more reduced forms of Hg being produced for lower O/C ratios.  The
greater amount of reduced Hg species would be more prevalent in the finer particulate or
vapor-phase fractions of the sampling train.<p>

     The transformation of As, Pb, Ni, Hg, and Se during combustion of Beulah lignite and the effects
of precombustion addition of kaolin, lime, and zeolite on the partitioning behavior of these same
metals were studied in the bench-scale atmospheric DTF (ADTF).  The ADTF is very similar in
construction and capabilities to the PDTF, except that for these tests, metal surfaces in the
furnace quench zone and multicyclone stages and filter assembly were Teflon-coated to
minimize sample contamination or reaction. The parent Beulah coal and coal-additive blends
were tested in the ADTF using conditions typical of pulverized coal-fired boilers.  Samples of
size-fractionated ash were collected using a multicyclone.  Trace elements present in the flue
gases were collected using EPA (Draft) Method 29.  As and Ni were almost completely
partitioned into the ash in all the ADTF tests.  In contrast, Hg was partitioned strongly into the
vapor phase.  Pb was partitioned into both the ash and vapor phase in the Beulah parent coal and
in the kaolin- and zeolite-coal blends.  Results for Pb in the lime-coal blend were ambiguous
because of poor mass balance closure.  Poor closure in mass balance results for Se indicated a
measurement problem, assuming that Se was not deposited on surfaces within the ADTF during
testing.  An investigation of Se sampling and measurement methods is required to avoid this
problem in future tests.  Ni was uniformly distributed among the different particle-size fractions,
suggesting that it did not vaporize and subsequently condense.  The vaporization-heterogeneous
condensation process would have resulted in the enrichment of Ni in the smallest size fraction
because of greater particle surface area per unit volume.  The smallest ash particle-size fraction
was significantly enriched in Pb, indicating control by a vaporization-condensation mechanism.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Combustion and Gasification System Development and
Testing</h3></font> 
     The construction of a conversion and environmental process simulator (CEPS) is near
completion.  The furnace stainless steel module shells have been assembled and installed into
the support structure.  Currently, refractory and the inner ceramic reaction tube are being cut
and fitted into the module shells.  Molds have been fabricated for molding castable refractory
sections of the furnace.  When completed, CEPS will enable the burning of liquid and/or
pulverized fuels at 40,000 Btu/hr.  The samples produced will be used to elucidate
transformation mechanisms and test various pollution control technologies.  An additional
system planned for development is a bed-burning reactor such as a stoker or a rotary kiln for
emulating waste-to-energy systems.<p>
<hr>
<b>CATM Directors:</b><ul plain>
<b>Steven A. Benson</b>/<a href=mailto:sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5177<br>
<b>John H. Pavlish</b>/<a href=mailto:jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5268<br></ul>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> October 1993 to September
1998<br>
<hr>
<a href="p00i.htm#Atmospheric">Return to Atmospheric
Emission Control</a> |
