<html>
<head>
<title>Control Technologies Center for Air Toxic Metals Program Area 3</title>
</head>
<body>
<body background = "../gif/drops1.jpg"><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h1>Control Technologies Center for Air Toxic Metals Program Area 3</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2> Background </h2>
<p>
     The Center for Air Toxic Metals (CATM) at the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center
(EERC) of the University of North Dakota (UND) emphasizes research, development,
demonstration, and commercialization of innovative environmental cleanup technologies
through partnerships between government, industry, and the EERC in the areas of  applied
science and engineering.  CATM was established by the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency (EPA) and is focused on minimizing the effects of air toxic metal pollutants on the
environment.  The Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAA) of 1990 require regulatory actions
addressing 189 substances, including air toxic metals.  In order to develop regulations, CATM
is working with industry and government to develop sufficient information on air toxic metals
to provide a scientific basis for preventing and controlling the emissions and evaluating the fate
and impacts of air toxic metals on plants and animals, including humans.  CATM-related
programs are focused on the development of methods to minimize the release of air toxic
metals via practical prevention and control methods based on scientific understanding and
principles.  To facilitate research efforts and dissemination of information, CATM is organized
into five integrated program areas:  Program Area 1 - Air Toxic Metals Transformation
Mechanisms, Program Area 2 - Analytical Methods Development, Program Area 3 - Control
Technologies, Program Area 4 - Modeling and Database, and Program Area 5 - Technology
Commercialization and Education.<p>
<p>
     Acid rain and the passage of legislation to reduce emissions of acid rain precursors continue to
be prominent issues in the United States, Canada, Europe, and Japan.  Emissions of fine
particles are of concern because these particles can be deposited in the lower respiratory
system through normal breathing.  The potential problem is further compounded because
hazardous trace elements, such as selenium and arsenic, are known to be concentrated on such
fine particles.  The CAAA address the issue of emissions of acid rain precursors, require the
investigation of air toxic emissions, and provide for possible expansion of visibility protection
measures.  Therefore, a current need exists to develop superior but economical methods to
control emissions of SO<sub>2</sub>, NO<sub>x</sub>, and air toxic trace elements.  The
best method to minimize
emissions is to improve collection of trace metal species via sorbent injection, minimize
reentrainment of fine particulates, or install high-efficiency fine-particle control devices.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     Program Area 3 is focused on pursuing and identifying opportunities for minimizing/controlling
trace element emissions in combustion and gasification systems, including prevention/minimization
of toxic element formation (e.g., fuel-to-energy conversion efficiency improvements, recycling);
capture by sorbents using precombustion, combustion, and postcombustion injection techniques in
conjunction with high-efficiency fine-particle control; and implementation of innovative
technologies.  The work in this area is closely tied to efforts in Program Area 1.  Specific goals
are as follows:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">As a means of control, encourage industry to implement
pollution
preventive practices and techniques<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">Identify and investigate ways to improve existing emission
reduction technologies relative to toxic metals<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">Develop new technologies that will minimize or revent toxic
metal emissions<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">Encourage waste reduction by developing innovative management
and utilization strategies for solid residue<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">Develop technologies that are environmentally safe<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">Develop technologies and techniques that are cost-effective to
implement<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif">Develop partnerships with industry to market new or improved
reduction technologies<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Control of air toxic metals emissions focused on the following technologies.<p>
<p>
<h3>Sorbent Injection</h3>
<p>
     A matrix of eight tests was executed to evaluate a number of commercially available sorbents
for their ability to remove elemental mercury and/or mercuric chloride from simulated flue gas
streams (utilities or incinerators).  Five different sorbents were evaluated:  1) American Norit
DARCO FGD, a steam-activated lignite carbon; 2) American Norit DARCO KB, a
chemical-activated hardwood;
3) American Norit PC 100, a chemical-activated bituminous coal; 4)
Barneby &amp; Sutcliffe Corporation CB, an iodized steam-activated coconut shell; and 5) Alcoa
Mersorb LH, a sulfur-impregnated steam-activated carbon.  An effectiveness ranking based on
total mercury adsorbed or removed was established.<p>
<p>
     Based on the limited testing performed, the flue gas components, O<sub>2</sub> and
SO<sub>2</sub>, each appeared to affect the performance of the activated carbons toward
elemental mercury removal.  Overall, both species tended to improve the mercury removal efficacy
for the DARCO KB, DARCO FGD and, most notably, Mersorb LH.  An exception was with the
DARCO PC 100 in which the presence of SO<SUB>2</SUB> significantly diminished the
removal efficiency.<p> 
<p>
     An attempt was made to assign a preliminary ranking to the activated carbons for the
adsorption of elemental mercury under the conditions of 0 to 4 vol% O<sub>2</sub>, 0 to 500
ppm SO<sub>2</sub>, and 100 &#181;g/m<sup>3</sup> Hg<sup>0</sup>.  The
ranking was based on the area under the mercury removal efficiency curve where a larger area
indicates higher adsorption capacity.  The Barneby &amp; Sutcliffe CB iodated activated carbon
appeared to be the consistently superior sorbent, while the American Norit Darco KB appeared to be
consistently the least effective.  However, because of the apparent effect of variables (notably
O<sub>2</sub> and SO<SUB>2</SUB>) on elemental mercury removal efficiency,
additional testing is needed
to elucidate the range of conditions in which the Alcoa Mersorb LH, Darco FGD, and Darco PC 100
may each have a decided advantage.<p>
<p>
<h3>Reentrainment of Fine Particulates</h3>
<p>
     Testing was conducted to determine the size distribution of ash reentrained from the
electrostatic precipitator (ESP) and baghouses during cleaning cycles since this may be a major
source of fine-particle emissions.  The ESP reentrainment tests were performed with the ESP
on the particulate test combustor (PTC) at the EERC.  The baghouse reentrainment tests were
performed with the three-bag pulse-jet baghouse on the PTC.  For the ESP, the concentration
of submicron particles in the entrained ash was lower than for the pulse-jet baghouse.  This
appears to have been caused by the increased cleaning energy of the pulse-jet system. 
However, the overall concentrations of particles downstream of the pulse-jet bags were lower
than the concentrations for the ESP.  As expected, pulsing pressure and operating pressure
appeared to have a noticeable effect on redispersion of particles within the baghouse.  As a
side note, the ashes were expected to redisperse into different distributions because they should
each have somewhat different cohesive properties.  However, there was little difference
between the injected and the redispersed ashes, which may be a limitation (or characteristic) of
the ash injection system.<p>
<p>
<h3>High-Efficiency Fine Particulate Collection</h3>
<p>

     To test various types of filter material, a bench-scale system was set up.  For the tests conducted,
the observed emission level achieved by the GORE-TEX&reg; felt with the GORE-TEX&reg;
membrane is over four orders of magnitude lower than for the woven fiberglass and two orders of
magnitude lower than for the Ryton felt. Review of the data indicated that several fabrics utilizing an
expanded polytetrafluoroethylene membrane appear to be capable of obtaining results similar to those
for the GORE-TEX&reg; product.<p>  
<p>
<h3>Management of Solid Residues</h3>
<p>
     The management, whether utilization or disposal options are considered, of solid residues is an
important issue that must be addressed.  The mobility and stability of trace metals were examined
for several coal-producing combustion by-products.  Several techniques were employed, some
with relative success, some requiring modification.  Work from several related projects was
combined to provide insight into the importance of trace elements in coal combustion by-products
(CCBs) and their disposal and utilization.  Additionally, work continued in the area of methods
development and standardization to provide more predictive capabilities for evaluating trace
element mobility when CCBs are placed in the environment.  Methods development continued to
identify specific properties of CCBs that may be used to better characterize and classify these
unique materials.
<p><hr>
<b>CATM Directors:</b><li>Steven A. Benson/<a href=mailto:sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
Phone: (701) 777-5177
<li>John H. Pavlish/<a href=mailto:jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
Phone: (701) 777-5268</b><br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
