<head>
<title>Coal Mineral Matter and Stack Emission
Opacity Relationship</title>
</head>
<body><center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"></center>
<center>
<h2> Coal Mineral Matter and Stack Emission Opacity Relationship </h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Background</h3></font>
     A utility plant equipped with an electrostatic precipitator (ESP) was exceeding the opacity
compliance limit of 20% when burning pulverized coal from a particular seam of its supply mine. 
In a preliminary investigation, the utility conducted test burns of samples from various coal
seams.  Measured opacity levels ranged from 9.5% to 24%.  The scattering of light by fine ash
particles was identified as the most likely cause of the opacity problem.<p>

     The concentration of fine ash particles emitted from a utility's stack is related primarily to coal
mineral matter characteristics.  The test burn coal samples were analyzed using energy dispersive
x-ray fluorescence spectrometry, automated scanning electron microscopy (SEM), and SEM
digital image analysis.  The test burn and coal analysis results were used to examine the
relationship between coal mineral matter characteristics and opacity.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Objective</h3></font>
     The objective of this investigation was to identify possible coal mineral matter sources of the fine
ash particles responsible for stack emission opacity.<p>



<font color="#990066"><h3>Results</h3></font> 
     ESPs require a specific range of ash resistivity, generally
10<sup>9</sup>-10<sup>10</sup> ohm-cm, to operate properly.  A change in this
parameter
can cause ESP collection efficiency to decline, especially for fine ash particles, which are the most
effective in scattering light.  The resistivity for each of the coal ashes was estimated using predictive
equations.  The predicted resistivities of the high-opacity coal ashes were greater by about
10<sup>0.5</sup> ohm-cm for a given temperature.  This relatively small change in ash
resistivity may have adversely affected ESP performance and contributed to the opacity problem. 
Variations in ash chemical compositions, most notably Fe<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>
content, accounted for the differences in calculated ash resistivities.<p>
   SEM-image analysis results indicated that the high-opacity coal samples contained a greater
proportion of kaolinite grains that were excluded from macerals.  Excluded kaolinite grains are
less likely to coalesce during combustion and can fragment to produce fine ash.  The relationship
between kaolinite fragmentation and opacity was originally proposed by the project sponsor. 
The results from this work, however, indicate that it is the amount of excluded kaolinite available
to fragment that is most important to consider as a source of fine ash.<p>
     The high-opacity coals were also found to be enriched in fine-grained (10 &#181;m or less)
mixed-clay minerals.  The Na, Mg, and Ca associated with these mixed-clay minerals may have
vaporized during combustion and subsequently condensed to form fine ash particles.  The
vaporization of fine-grained minerals is favored because they heat more rapidly, attain higher
temperatures, and have a shorter diffusion path to the particle surface.<p>
     The results of this investigation indicate that a combination of coal mineral matter characteristics
are responsible for enhancing fine ash production and, therefore, opacity.  A comparison of fine
ash and coal mineral compositions is required to verify the correlations noted in this
investigation.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Kevin C. Galbreath/<a href=mailto:kgalbreath@eerc.und.nodak.edu>kgalbreath@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5127<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b>TransAlta Utilities<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> September 1993 to March
1994<br>
<hr>
