<head>
<title>Review and Assessment of Results from
the Comprehensive Characterization of
Air Toxic Emissions from Coal-Fired
Power Plants</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src ="gifs/eerc_hd.gif">
<h2>Review and Assessment of Results from the Comprehensive Characterization of Air Toxic
Emissions from
Coal-Fired Power Plants </h2></center>
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Background</h2></font> <p>


     Significant concern exists over the impact of increasing energy consumption on ambient air
quality.  Acid rain and the passage of legislation to reduce emissions of acid rain precursors
continue to be prominent issues in the United States, Canada, Europe, and Japan.  Emissions
of fine particles are of concern because these particles can be deposited in the lower
respiratory system through normal breathing.  The potential problem is further compounded
because hazardous trace elements such as selenium and arsenic are known to be concentrated
on such fine particles.  Recent studies indicate that current levels of fine particles in the
atmosphere are causing up to 60,000 deaths per year and that the current ambient air quality
standard for PM10 may not adequately protect public health.  In addition to potentially causing
adverse health effects, fine particles, including secondary sulfates, are the primary cause of
visibility impairment in the atmosphere.  The Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAA) of 1990
address the issues of emissions of acid rain precursors, require investigation of air toxic
emissions, and provide for possible expansion of visibility protection measures.  Therefore, a
current need exists to develop superior but economical methods to control emissions of
SO<sub>2</sub>, NO<sub>x</sub>, fine particles, and air toxics.<p>
    To help meet the requirements of the CAAA, the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE)
sponsored a project entitled "Comprehensive Characterization of Air Toxic Emissions from
Coal-Fired Power Plants." Results from the investigation are intended to provide the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) with data to help decide whether regulation of air
toxic emissions from coal-fired power plants is necessary.  Draft reports which detail air toxic
emissions from eight power plants were completed, and the EERC served as an independent
reviewer of these reports.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives </h3></font>
     The objective of this project is to provide an independent review of reports produced from the
DOE Pittsburgh Energy Technology Center air toxic emissions investigation, evaluate the
scientific validity of the conclusions, identify significant correlations between emissions and
fuel or process parameters, compare the data with available results from Electric Power
Research Institute (EPRI) studies, and make recommendations for possible future studies.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Results </h3></font>
     Task 1 of this project consisted of the review of nine Phase I draft contractor field reports by
the EERC review team.  Comments were compiled for each report to serve as a guide for the
individual contractors to prepare their final reports.  Conference calls were held between the
EERC, DOE, and the respective contractors for each of these reports to discuss comments and
form a consensus as to required changes for the final contractor reports.  Task 1 activities
were completed in June 1994.<p>
    Task 2 required preparation of a report to DOE summarizing recommendations for improving
the quality of data to be collected during Phase II field tests.  The recommendations report was
based on review of the Phase I contractor draft reports and past EERC experience.  Specific
recommendations addressed 1) pre-field-sampling laboratory preparation and qualification, 2) a
data reporting and flagging system, 3) organic sampling and analysis, 4) inorganic sampling
and analysis, 5) radionuclides, 6) particulate and solid-vapor sampling and analysis, and 7) a
recommended format for reporting hazardous air pollutant data.  The report also summarized
recommendations made by individual contractors that were not site- or process-specific and
were considered to be of high priority by the EERC review team.  This report, entitled "Task
2 - Recommendations for Phase II Field Test," was completed in April 1995.<p>
     Task 3, currently ongoing, is focused on the preparation of a report summarizing the data
collected by the contractors at the eight Phase I field sites.  The report will also contain a
concise overview of the important findings from the Phase I effort.  A draft of the Phase I
summary report is scheduled to be completed by the end of May 1995, at which time it will be
submitted to DOE for review.<p>

     Task 4, currently ongoing, involves a comparison of the trace element emissions data from the
DOE Phase I data set with trace element emissions data that are available from EPRI-sponsored field
tests.  An
evaluation of correlations between emission factors and the coal,
process, and operating conditions will be completed, along with development of general
conclusions for the combined data set.  Completion of a draft report summarizing the results of
the Task 4 effort is scheduled for late May 1995, at which time the draft report will be
submitted to DOE for review.<p>

     In Task 5, currently ongoing, relevant DOE and EPRI data will be incorporated into the
database on air toxic metals that is part of the Center for Air Toxic Metals, which EPA
established at the EERC.  Upon completion, the database will supply well-organized
information on toxic metals to DOE, EPA, EPRI, and the general public.  Completion of the
database is scheduled for July 1995.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b> Stanley J. Miller/<a href=mailto:smiller@eerc.und.nodak.edu> smiller@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5210<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy  Morgantown
Energy Technology 
Center and Pittsburgh Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:  </b>March 1994 to March
1995<br>
