<html>
<head>
<title>Enhanced Air Toxics Control</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src ="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Enhanced Air Toxics Control </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Background </h3></font>
     The 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAA) address the issue of air toxic emissions by
requiring their investigation from coal combustion systems.  Fabric filters and electrostatic
precipitators (ESPs) are already capable of providing a sufficiently high level of particulate
control to meet the 0.03 lb/MMBtu total mass particulate emission standard.  However, fine
particulate removal efficiency deteriorates significantly in ESPs and somewhat in baghouses. 
Emissions of fine particles are of concern because these particles can be deposited in the lower
respiratory system through normal breathing.  The potential problem is further compounded
because hazardous trace elements such as selenium and arsenic are known to be concentrated
on such fine particles.  Control device removal efficiency is lowest for respirable particles, so
that a situation exists where the potentially most hazardous particles from coal combustion are
collected with the lowest removal efficiency.  Since most of the toxic metals present in coal
will be in particulate form, a high level of fine-particle control appears to be the best approach
to achieving a high level of air toxic control.  However, over 50% of mercury and a portion of
selenium emissions are in vapor form and are not typically collected in particulate control
devices.  If these vapor-phase metals could be retained in a particulate control device by the
use of a conditioning agent or sorbent, an effective method of controlling all metal air toxic
emissions would be available at a minimum impact on existing boiler systems.<p>

     The ability to remove mercury from power plant flue gas may become important because of
the CAAA requirement that the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) assess the
health risks associated with these emissions.  One approach for mercury removal, which may
be relatively simple to retrofit, is the injection of sorbents, such as activated carbon, upstream
of existing particulate control devices.  Activated carbon has been reported to capture mercury
when injected into flue gas upstream of a spray dryer baghouse system applied to waste
incinerators or coal-fired boilers.  However, the mercury capture ability of activated carbon
injected upstream of an ESP or baghouse operated at temperatures between 200&#176; and
400&#176;F is not well known.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives</h3></font>
     The overall objective of the proposed work is to evaluate the potential to remove trace metal
air toxic emissions from coal combustion in conventional particulate control devices.  A
specific goal of the work  is to determine the sorbent type, sorbent concentration, and process
conditions that result in effective mercury control.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Results </h3></font>

     The level of mercury in raw coal is very small, typically only 0.05 to 0.1 ppm, which results
in a trace mercury concentration at the stack of approximately 10 &#181;g/m<sup>3</sup> or
about 1 ppb.  Special sampling and analysis techniques are required to quantify these low-level
mercury concentrations under various test conditions.  However, the EERC has achieved excellent
agreement when comparing the actual measured mercury concentrations at the inlet to the baghouse
with expected concentrations based on the mercury in the coal.<p> 

<p>

     Simultaneous inlet and outlet mercury sampling was conducted according to EPA (Draft)
Method 29, also known as a multimetal sampling train method.  Method 29 does not claim to
speciate between oxidized and elemental mercury, but bench- and pilot-scale results indicate
that oxidized mercury will be trapped in the peroxide impingers and elemental mercury in the
permanganate impingers.  However, further research is being conducted at the EERC to
evaluate the mercury speciation ability of Method 29.  <p>
     Test variables included coal type, sorbent type, sorbent addition rate, collection media, and
temperature. The three coals tested to date include Powder River Basin subbituminous coals
from the Absaloka mine, a similar coal from the Belle Ayr mine (Comanche), and a
bituminous coal from the Pittsburgh No. 8 seam, Blacksville mine.  Since the level of mercury
in the coals ranged from 59 to 85 ppb and the coal feed rate to the combustor is about 60
lb/hr, the required sorbent add rate is only about 2-20 g/hr to achieve sorbent-to-mercury
ratios of 1000-10,000.  For all sorbent tests, the additive was injected into the flue gas duct
just upstream of the particulate collector, which was held at temperatures ranging from  200&#176;
to 400&#176;F.  Fabric type included Ryton and GORE-TEX&reg; membrane on GORE-TEX&reg;
Felt. The two primary carbon-based sorbents used in this investigation included a lignite-based
activated carbon, commercially available from American Norit Co., Inc., and an activated carbon
impregnated with an iodine compound obtained from Barnebey &amp; Sutcliffe Corp.  In addition to
the pilot-scale combustion tests, separate sorbent screening tests were completed with oxidized and
elemental forms of mercury using simulated flue gas.<p> 
    Preliminary conclusions are as follows:<p>


<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Inlet mercury speciation for the three coals was significantly
different and was highly dependent on the Method 29 filter temperature.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Iodine-impregnated activated carbon provided effective mercury
control at 300&#176; and 400&#176;F  with one subbituminous coal but was ineffective for a second
subbituminous coal.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Iodine-impregnated activated carbon was highly effective at
reducing the outlet elemental mercury concentration for all three coals; however, in some cases, the
elemental mercury is apparently converted to oxidized mercury and is not captured.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Lignite-based activated carbon provided some mercury control at
lower temperatures for all three coals but appeared to work best for the Comanche coal.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Mercury may interact with the Ryton fabric under some
conditions to affect mercury speciation and control effectiveness.<br>

<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  Bench-scale screening tests may not be good indicators of
sorbent
effectiveness unless flue gas conditions are adequately simulated.<br>
</ul>
<p>

     Future work planned for this project includes optimizing process conditions to achieve the
most economical control of mercury in an ESP or baghouse.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Stanley J. Miller/<a href=mailto:smiller@eerc.und.nodak.edu>smiller@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5210<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> <ul plain>Electric Power Research Institute <br>
     U.S. Department of Energy</ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  October 1992 to March 1996
<br>
