<DOCNO>WT24-B32-323</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000279-B018-185</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.eerc.und.nodak.edu:80/9395bien/p259.htm 134.129.141.26 19970113183434 text/html 7789
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:38:53 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 02-May-96 20:51:58 GMT
Content-length: 7599
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Mitigation of Air Toxics from Lignite
Generation Facilities</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Mitigation of Air Toxics from Lignite Generation Facilities</h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     Concerns over emissions of trace metals, considered air toxics, from coal-fired power plants
are increasing.  The Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAA) of 1990 list 189 substances as
potentially hazardous air pollutants.  Further, the CAAA established a schedule under which
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is required to establish maaximum
achievable control technology (MACT) standards for existing major sources of hazardous
pollutants.  A major source is any source which emits (or has the potential to emit) more than
10 tons per year of any one listed pollutant or 25 tons per year or more of any combination of
listed pollutants.  Coal combustion is thought to be an important source for eleven metals on
the list of 189 substances (antimony, arsenic, beryllium, cadmium, chromium, cobalt, lead,
manganese, mercury, nickel, and selenium).<p>

<p>

     Emission reduction strategies for trace elements in both conventional and advanced combustion
systems face the concurrent problems of 1) collection and removal of trace concentrations on a
large scale, 2) the costs associated with the removal, and 3) eventual disposal of the trace
species once collected.  Current control strategies are focusing on the use of sorbents as the
removal method.  The use of sorbents is an existing technology with many applications, and
handling, injection, and recovery methods are already available.  The primary concern is the
selection of the best, most cost-effective sorbent or sorbents for a specific purpose.  The
sorbents to be examined are either readily available materials where a large volume of low-cost,
disposable
material with modest sorption capacity is used or new, innovative materials
that require a small volume of more expensive material with high sorption capacity from which
the trace metals are recovered and the sorbent material reused.  In either case, cost injection
rate and effectiveness are critical issues that must be addressed.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Objectives</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The overall objective of this project is to determine the usefulness of sorbents in controlling
the emission of trace elements during the combustion of lignite coals.  The sorbents include
precombustion, combustion, and postcombustion injection materials, along with possible
gas-conditioning
agents.  The specific objectives of the project are as follows:<p>

<p>


<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To determine the concentrations of eleven trace elements from
six
representative North Dakota lignite coals and one Powder River Basin (PRB) coal<br>
<p>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif">  To determine the anticipated emissions from generation facilities
by simulating the combustion process using bench- and pilot-scale test equipment<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To investigate the current state-of-the-art sorbents as trace
element emission control technologies<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To test the most promising control sorbents<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To evaluate the effectiveness of the tested sorbents<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To suggest potential sorbent-based control technologies applicable
to full-scale utility power plants<br>
</ul><p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The air toxic control technologies that were investigated included precombustion, combustion,
and postcombustion sorbent injection, along with gas-conditioning agents.  In addition,
because the alkali and alkaline earth components (sodium, magnesium, calcium) in these coals
may adsorb many of the trace metals of concern, the ash constituents were also considered as
possible sorbents.  The potential for these technologies to provide mitigation of trace metal
emissions was reviewed, and the most promising techniques tested.<p>

<p>

     The most promising sorbents selected for mitigation of trace metal emissions were identified as
the precombustion sorbents zeolite, kaolinite, and lime and a postcombustion sorbent of
lignite-based activated carbon.  Bench- and pilot-scale testing of the sorbents and conditioning
agents were performed on Beulah, Falkirk, Freedom, and PRB coals to accumulate data on
effectiveness.<p>

<p>

     The three precombustion sorbents selected were tested in a bench-scale, laminar-flow, drop-tube
furnace (DTF) to determine their effectiveness in capturing the trace species.  Both
particulate and gas samples were obtained during the tests to determine their trace element
contents.  After completion of the DTF testing, the lime sorbent was selected for further
testing.  The selected precombustion sorbent (lime), postcombustion sorbent (activated
carbon), and gas-conditioning agent (SO<sub>3</sub>) were each separately tested in a
pilot-scale,
550,000-Btu/hr particulate test combustor (PTC) equipped with a baghouse.  The mitigation
tests were conducted with four of the seven previously analyzed coals.  These were the
Beulah, Falkirk, Freedom, and PRB coals.  Particulate and gas samples were collected and
analyzed using currently accepted EPA methods.<p>

<p>

     Results from the PTC tests show that mercury can be effectively controlled (captured) with the
use of activated carbon injected upstream of a baghouse for the conditions and coals tested.  In
some cases, the additional control (capture) of mercury was minimal.  In these cases, the level
of control without the use of any sorbents was quite high, above 80%.  Consequently, for
these tests, the addition of sorbents (lime or activated carbon ) showed little improvement.  In
all tests, the use of lime as a precombustion sorbent for mercury control proved to be
ineffective.  However, capture/collection of arsenic and selenium did improve in some cases. 
In short, based on the coals tested, activated carbon can be used to effectively control mercury
but does not improve collection of other toxic metals.  Lime, as a precombustion sorbent, is
not effective at controlling mercury emissions but showed some capability of improving
collection of other toxic metals (i.e., arsenic, selenium).
<hr>
<b>Project Managers: </b> <ul plain>Steven A. Benson/<a href=mailto:sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5177<br>
John H. Pavlish/<a href=mailto:jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jpavlish@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5268</ul>
<b>Sponsor: </b><ul plain>Basin Electric Power Cooperative<br>
     Cooperative Power<br>
     Electric Power Research Institute<br>
     Minnesota Power Company<br>
     Montana-Dakota Utilities Company<br>
     North Dakota Industrial Commission<br>
     U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</ul>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>January 1994 to August 1995<br>
