<html>
<head>
<title>Effective Sorbents for Trace Elements</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Effective Sorbents for Trace Elements </h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     Trace element emissions arise from coal combustion and gasification systems, waste
incineration, crematoriums, chlorine/alkali plants, and metallurgical operations.  The trace
species mercury, arsenic, and selenium are of concern because of their release as gases or
submicron fume and their potential toxicity to the ecosystem.  Sorbent technology is being
investigated and used to collect trace elements.  Sorbents consist of a large volume of
inexpensive, activated coal or char with modest sorption activity.  Alternatively, regenerable
sorbents with enhanced sorption capacity can be used from which trace metals can be
recovered.<p>

<p>

     Carbon sorbents have been used to trap mercury species with varying success because of
interfering reactions (e.g., with oxygen) and the nature of the sorbent. Insufficient data exist
for optimizing the effectiveness and for understanding the kinetics and mechanism of the
process of capture by carbon sorbents for different mercury species.  <p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Objectives</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The overall objective is to identify the conditions for effective capture of trace elements by
carbon sorbents and the controlling processes for trace element sorption in combustion and
gasification systems. Specific objectives entail determining the conditions controlling  capture
of mercury species by selected carbons in the presence of various flue gas components, such as
O<sub>2</sub>, CO, and SO<sub>2</sub>, and developing a preliminary understanding of
the kinetics and mechanism of mercury sorption.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     A fixed-bed reactor system with continuous Hg<sup>0</sup> analysis capabilities was
constructed and operated to evaluate commercial carbon sorbents for the removal of elemental
mercury from simulated flue gas containing N<sub>2</sub>, O<sub>2</sub>,
SO<sub>2</sub>, and HCl.  Sorbents included powdered forms of steam-activated lignite,
chemical-activated hardwood, chemical-activated bituminous coal, iodated steam-activated coconut
shell, and sulfur-impregnated steam-activated bituminous coal.  <p>

<p>

     Iodated activated carbon was a consistently superior sorbent regardless of the simulated flue
gas atmosphere, with over 99% mercury removal according to EPA Method 101A.  Chemical
activated hardwood was the least effective.  <p>

<p>

     Data indicated that increasing the O<sub>2</sub> concentration from 0 to 4 vol% reduced
the effectiveness of the steam-activated lignite, chemical-activated hardwood, and sulfur-impregnated
steam-activated bituminous coal.  Increasing the SO<sub>2</sub> concentration from 0 to 500
ppm, however,
appeared to have a more selective effect, increasing the mercury removal by the sulfur-impregnated
carbon
relative to the other carbons.  Increasing the HCl concentration from 0 to
50 ppm had the apparent effect of enhancing the mercury removal efficiency of the
sulfur-impregnated and
chemical-activated bituminous coals to a level comparable to the iodated
carbon.  Mercury removal by the chemical-activated bituminous coal exceeded 97% according
to EPA (Draft) Method 29.  Further, data indicated possible conversion of mercury to chloride
form(s).<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Brian C. Young/<a href=mailto:byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu>byoung@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5292<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown
Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> March 1994 to March 1995<br>
