<html>
<head>
<title>Trace Element Emissions</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2> Trace Element Emissions</h2> </center> 
<hr>



<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     Trace element emissions pose a potential problem to two emerging coal gasification electric
power generating systems:  integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC) and integrated
gasification fuel cell (IGFC).  The potential problems associated with trace elements are the
release of elements considered air toxics into the environment and the degradation of fuel cell
efficiency because of contamination with minor elements.  As a result of amendments to the
Clean Air Act, the control of nearly 200 additional air toxics or chemical contaminants is
required.  The trace elements being studied in this project are lead, mercury, nickel,
chromium, arsenic, selenium, and cadmium.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The objectives of this project are to identify and model important physical and chemical
transformation mechanisms of the trace elements during gasification as a function of coal
compositions (trace element abundance and association) and gasification conditions. 
Identification of the reactions and transformations coupled with the ability to accurately model
trace element behavior will provide essential information for the identification of the form of
the inorganic species.  This information will be used to identify the most effective control
technologies.  Emphasis is placed on providing a model that will benefit industry's use of coal
gasification processes.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     Progress concentrated in three areas during the first half of the project.  The first area
encompasses the analysis of coals, ashes, and chars for trace and bulk species.  Sample
preparation and analysis techniques have been continually enhanced as the project has
progressed.  Many of the analytical methods developed in this project will be used in support
of better techniques worldwide.<p>

<p>

     The second area has been the production of samples from bench-scale units and the
interpretation of their results.  A pressurized drop-tube furnace and an integrated bench-scale
gasifier are being used to produce samples similar to those of full-scale gasification processes. 
The samples generated are analyzed using advanced analytical methods and their results
summarized in tables and graphs.  The partitioning of the trace elements between the solid,
liquid, and vapor phases has been the major emphasis in this area.<p>

<p>

     The third area is the production of a model to predict the transformations of trace species
during gasification.  The model is based on a previous stochastic code, with enhancements in
the areas of thermodynamics and kinetics.  The model is intended for use by researchers,
operators, and manufacturers of gasification processes.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Steven A. Benson/<a href=mailto:sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>sbenson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5177<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b> U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  August 1992 to September 1995
<br>
<hr>
