</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Catalyst for Utilization of Methane in
Selective Catalytic Reduction of NO<sub>x</sub></title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Catalyst for Utilization of Methane in Selective Catalytic Reduction of
NO<sub>x</sub></h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

     The selective catalytic reduction (SCR) of NO<sub>x</sub> in flue gas or engine exhaust gas
with hydrocarbons as the reductant has great potential for less expense, less pollution, and easier
operation than SCR with ammonia.  Methane is the preferred reducing gas because of its low cost
and low toxicity.  Stable, low-cost catalysts for SCR with methane are required to demonstrate this
technology for controlling NO<sub>x</sub> emissions.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Objectives</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The overall objective of the proposed work is to demonstrate that catalysts consisting of metal
ion impregnated on a clay or pillared-clay support or on a highly stable composite carbon support
are effective for SCR of NO<sub>x</sub>.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The efficiency of the clay-supported nickel and cobalt catalyst for NO reduction with methane as
the reducing gas was poor.  Evidently, the only catalyst that can effect this reaction is that
reported by Li and Armor (Li, Y.; Armor, J.N.  <i>Applied Catal. B. Environment
<b></i>1993</b>, <i>2</i>, 239.), who claim a zeolite-supported cobalt catalyst will
activate methane for the NO reduction.<p>

<p>

     Results from the two-step experiments conducted at two temperatures are much more interesting. 
The carbonaceous material formed from methane dissociation at 400&#176;C not only reduced NO to
N<sub>2</sub>O at lower temperatures, but also prevented oxidation of NO to
NO<sub>2</sub>.  Unfortunately, the carbonaceous forms that reduce the NO are not available
for reactions at 400&#176;C in the presence of oxygen.  A two-step process employing this chemistry
would be difficult, because the catalyst would have to be cycled between the two temperatures.  Also
the desired reduction in nitrogen is not very efficient.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edwin S. Olson/<a href=mailto:eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>eolson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5155<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  March 1994 to March 1995<br>
<hr>
