<html>
<head>
<title>Evaluation of Owens-Corning Products
for Filtration Applications</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Evaluation of Owens-Corning Products for Filtration Applications </h2> </center> 
<hr>



<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The variables that determine the performance of a filter media can be divided into three
categories:  filter media properties, dust properties, and process conditions.  The main filter
media property that determines collection efficiency is pore size, which depends upon fiber
diameter and the filter media structure (e.g., type of weave or felted construction).  If the
average pore size in the filter is smaller than the median particle size, the filter itself will
achieve near 100% collection efficiency independent of dust properties and process conditions. 
Commercially available membrane-type fabric filters would fit into this category.  In such a
case, other parameters such as pressure drop primarily determine the amount of filtration area
required for a specific application.  However, for most cleanable filter media, it is not
practical or even desirable to achieve a pore size smaller than the dust being filtered.  A
compromise must be reached between achieving an acceptable pore size for good particulate
collection efficiency and constructing an economical, cleanable, and durable fabric.  Woven
glass fabrics with 100-200-&#181;m pores can achieve acceptably low particulate emissions for
some dusts at low air-to-cloth (A/C) ratios.  However, woven-glass fabrics are subject to high
emissions for some dusts and are not as durable as desired.  Needled felt fabrics (both glass
and synthetic fibers) generally provide better particulate collection efficiency, but have large
enough pores so that for some applications particulate collection efficiency is lower than
desired.  In addition, needled felt fabrics do not always achieve a sufficient bag life.  A goal
for the development of a superior filter media is to provide a durable fabric that can withstand
the harsh physical and chemical environment of many processes, while improving upon the
particulate collection capacity of existing woven or felted filter media.  This means that
significant optimization must occur to achieve the best balance among fabric pore size, fabric
weight, and durability for a variety of dust types and process conditions.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Objectives</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The overall objective of the project is to demonstrate that the filtration performance of fabric
samples manufactured using Owens-Corning (OC) products is as good as, if not better than,
commercially available filter media.  Specific goals for the bench-scale experiments include
demonstrating that fabric samples manufactured using OC products will achieve a minimum
overall mass emissions control level of 99.99%, demonstrating that fabric samples
manufactured using OC products will achieve a minimum emissions control level of 99.9% for
fine particles (&lt;5 microns), and developing insights concerning differential pressure
characteristics and the cleanability of the OC products relative to commercially available filter
media.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     Key issues to be addressed in the overall evaluation of OC fabric samples include mechanical
strength and durability, resistance to chemical attack, filtration characteristics, and fabric
cleanability.  The EERC has focused its effort on fabric filtration characteristics. Performance
data developed include total mass collection efficiency, fine-particle collection efficiency,
differential pressure data and fabric cleanability, and fabric durability for a range of fly ash
physical and chemical properties.  The results from this project are proprietary and, therefore,
cannot be included in this summary.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Greg F. Webe/<a href=mailto:gweber@eerc.und.nodak.edu>gweber@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5222<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  Owens-Corning<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> December 1994 to June 1995<br>
<hr>
