<html>
<head>
<title>Nitrous Oxide Emissions</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Nitrous Oxide Emissions</h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

     Because of growing public concern relating elevated carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>)
concentrations to changes in the global climate, other trace gases including methane
(CH<sub>4</sub>), chlorofluorocarbons, and nitrous oxide (N<sub>2</sub>O) have
become suspect as contributors to the greenhouse effect and ozone depletion.  N<sub>2</sub>O
is reportedly increasing in atmospheric concentrations at an estimated rate of 0.7 ppb per year and
was measured (1988) in the atmosphere at a concentration of 307 ppb.  Although the atmospheric
concentrations of N<sub>2</sub>O are low (1100 times less than CO<sub>2</sub>), the
relative strength of N<sub>2</sub>O as an infrared absorber is reportedly 200 times greater than
that of CO<sub>2</sub>.  In addition, N<sub>2</sub>O, being a stable compound, is
transported to the stratosphere where it is photochemically oxidized to NO (nitric oxide), the major
contributor to catalytic ozone depletion.  The association and/or contribution of
N<sub>2</sub>O to the greenhouse effect and ozone depletion has led to considerable interest in
determining the natural and anthropogenic pathways to its formation and destruction.  Typical
N<sub>2</sub>O measurements from fluidized-bed combustion (FBC) range from 50 to 200
ppm.  Therefore, contribution of N<sub>2</sub>O from FBCs will require attention in the
future, even though they may not be a major source of N<sub>2</sub>O.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

     <p>

     The purpose of this investigation was to determine the contribution of N<sub>2</sub>O to
the atmosphere from FBC of coal.  Additionally, goals were to establish a comprehensive engineering
model to assist in the prediction of N<sub>2</sub>O emissions based upon coal type and
operating and design considerations and to develop abatement techniques.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

     The effects of operational parameters and coal type on N<sub>2</sub>O emissions in a
1-MWth pilot-scale circulating FBC (CFBC) were examined.  Operational parameters included
combustor temperature, excess combustion air, limestone feed rate, and primary:secondary
combustion air split.  Seven coals ranging in rank from lignite to high-volatile A bituminous were
used to investigate coal- and fuel-related effects.  In addition, a petroleum coke derived from the
"fluid" coking process and another from the "delayed" coking process were used as CFBC fuels.  At
typical operating conditions (20% excess air, 1120 K), N<sub>2</sub>O emissions from lignite
coals ranged from 40-65 ppmv, while subbituminous and bituminous coals had emissions from 30-40
ppmv and 130-190 ppmv, respectively.  The delayed coke produced N<sub>2</sub>O emissions
similar to bituminous coals at 142 ppmv, while the fluid  coke yielded the highest overall
N<sub>2</sub>O emissions at 211 ppmv.  The impact of CFBC operational parameters on
N<sub>2</sub> O emissions follows theapproximate relationships:  temperature &gt; excess air,
air split &gt; sorbent feed.<p>

<p>

     Increasing combustion temperature was shown to decrease N<sub>2</sub>O emissions,
while increasing excess air was shown to increase N<sub>2</sub>O emissions.  Actual
measurements from pilot-scale data indicate that N<sub>2</sub>O emissions decreased at a rate
of 0.36 ppm/K for low-emitting fuels at low excess air conditions and at a rate of 2.0 ppm/K for
high-emitting coals under high excess air conditions.  The effect of limestone addition was shown to
be coal-dependent, with decreasing trends in N<sub>2</sub> O emissions observed. 
Primaryair-to-total air ratio has a minimal impact on N<sub>2</sub>O emissions but tends to
decrease emissions at higher temperatures, while the opposite trend occurs at lower
temperatures.<p>

<p>

     Although N<sub>2</sub>O emissions from FBCs as high as 460 ppm have been reported in
the literature, these have been for operating extremes.  Typical N<sub>2</sub>O emissions from
utility plants are in the 30- to 120-ppm range, with emissions from pilot plants being higher for
similar coals and operating conditions.  Data indicate that several techniques exist to keep the
N<sub>2</sub>O emissions at low levels, including operating at higher bed temperatures and
lower excess air levels.  Another control method is afterburning a gaseous fuel in the cyclone or
freeboard of the combustor.  Therefore, N<sub>2</sub>O emissions from FBC should not halt
the technology from moving forward. 
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Michael E. Collings/<a href=mailto:mcollings@eerc.und.nodak.edu>mcollings@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5211<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> July 1989 to September 1993<br>
<hr>
