<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency/American Plastics Council
Thermal Recycling of Plastics</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2> U.S. Environmental Protection Agency/American Plastics Council Thermal Recycling of
Plastics </h2>
</center> 
<hr>
<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>
     The purpose of this project is to investigate and optimize processes for waste plastics recycling
via thermal depolymerization to yield economically viable fuel and chemical feedstocks. 
Thermal depolymerization breaks down plastics under an inert atmosphere using catalysts and
heat.  The products of thermal depolymerization processes are a variety of organic materials,
the composition and yields of which are dependent on processing variables such as
temperature, bed material (catalysts, sorbents, inert materials), residence time, and feed
material composition.  The EERC has completed a scoping study for the American Plastics
Council (APC) in which the general depolymerization characteristics of several polymers were
investigated, including high-density polyethylene (HDPE), low-density polyethylene (LDPE),
linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP), polystyrene (PS), polyethylene
terephthalate (PET), polyvinyl chloride (PVC), nylon, polyurethane, and acrylonitrile
butadiene styrene (ABS).<p>

     Thermal depolymerization products, such as ethylene, propylene, butylenes (light olefins), and
terephthalic acid (TA), could be used as monomer feedstocks for production of recycled
consumer plastics.  Other organic liquids produced could be used as chemical feedstocks. 
Preliminary findings of the EERC depolymerization work have indicated that the most
practical alternative for the organic products not used for direct polymer production might be
as a feedstock to a petroleum refinery, where the variety of process entry points provides the
options needed for processing of such diverse materials (many depolymerization products
contain 300 or more components, ranging from light olefins and aliphatics to heavy aromatics
and waxes).  With the relatively high cost of curbside plastics collection and preparation for
recycling, the number of unit operations required for processing and separation needs to be
minimal, so that capital costs are kept low.  While some countries, including Japan and
Germany, have commercial depolymerization processes in place and others, including Great
Britain and the Netherlands, are well on their way, the process proposed here is different in
that it will deal with the higher levels of PET found in U.S. postconsumer plastics streams. 
Even with PET bottle sorting, PET levels are anticipated to be between 10% and 30%.  One
of the findings of the above-mentioned APC investigation is that the presence of PET in waste
plastics mixtures (at levels greater than about 5%) can cause severe operational difficulties. 
Another important finding is that when steam is present as a reactant, it is possible to
decompose PET to TA at higher temperatures than are normally used in a hydrolysis process. 
These two findings are relevant to the project in light of the current (and projected) high
demand for high-purity TA as a chemical feedstock.<p>

     Tests will be performed to investigate optimum reaction temperature, bed material composition
(calcium oxide will be added to the feed material to act as both a catalyst and a sorbent for
chlorine capture), gas residence time, reaction atmosphere, and waste plastics feed material
mix.  The feed material to be used in tests to optimize light (C<sub>2</sub> to
C<sub>4</sub>) olefin production will be the same as that used in the current APC program:  a
postconsumer (waste plastics) mix from the Minneapolis, Minnesota, area.  The feed material for
tests to optimize TA production will consist of the Minneapolis postconsumer mix to which virgin
PET will be added.  Compositional analysis of the postconsumer feed material will be performed by
Southwest Research Institute (SRI) of San Antonio, Texas.  SRI has already performed one analysis
of the Minneapolis postconsumer mix.<p>

     Testing will be performed using the EERC 1- to 4-lb/hr continuous fluid-bed reactor (CFBR),
which is rated for use at temperatures of up to 815&#176;C (1500&#176;F) and pressures of up to
170 psi.  The reactor consists of a 33-in.-high bed, having a nominal 3-in. inside diameter (ID).  The
freeboard section is 17 in. high, with a nominal 4-in. ID.  Any liquid used in the fluidization gas mix
is first preheated, then mixed with heated fluidization gas, and finally heated to reaction temperature
in a superheater.  Because plastics have a very low density, an inert bed material can be used to
facilitate adequate fluidization.  Waste plastics are fed into the reactor either through a dual-auger
arrangement or a modified ball valve "star feeder."  In the dual-auger arrangement, the first auger,
horizontally situated, meters out the feed material.  The metered feed drops to the second auger. 
This second auger, at a 30 angle from horizontal, delivers the feed material quickly into the hot
reactor.  The modified ball valve feed system involves a cup cut into a solid ball that drops a metered
amount of material onto an auger, which delivers the material quickly into the reactor.  Because
plastics soften and get sticky at a fairly low temperature, it is important to keep the feed at a low
temperature until it enters the reactor.<p>

     Spent (reacted) solids are collected from the reactor through a top-bed drain leg.  Material is
collected in a lock hopper-type pot.  Gas, volatiles, and fine solids leave the top of the reactor
and enter a 3-in.-ID cyclone where the fines are removed.  The gas stream enters one of the
two identical condensation trains (the system is configured to enable switching from one train
to the other to allow sampling and cleaning without shutting down the system).  A fixed bed,
which can be used for postreactor sorbent testing, is located upstream of one of the
condensation trains.  The fixed-bed cartridge is made of 3-in., Schedule 10, 304 stainless steel
pipe.  Two cartridges are available for use:  one 4 in. and one 8 in. long.  The cartridge and
lines leading to it are externally heated.  The two condensation trains consist of a water-cooled
indirect heat exchanger, followed by two glycol-cooled indirect heat exchangers.  The gas
stream that emerges from the condensation train is depressurized and metered and may be
sampled for on-line Fourier transform infrared spectrometry analysis.  Data collection and
process control are accomplished with a Genesis&copy; software package.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

     The two primary objectives of the project are 1) to identify processing conditions that provide
a maximum yield of "light olefins," a gaseous mixture consisting of ethylene
(C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub>), propylene (C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>6</sub>), and
five butylenes (1-butene, <i>cis</i>- and <i>trans</i>- 2-butene, isobutylene [all
C<sub>4</sub>H<sub>8</sub>], and butadiene [C<sub>4</sub>H<sub>6</sub>])
from a specific postconsumer plastics feed material and 2) to identify processing conditions that
provide a maximum yield of TA.<p>


<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>


     The EERC has completed the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Quality Assurance Plan
(Category IV) document and 14 of the 24 tests.  The olefin tests program has been completed,
with the remaining testing for terephthalic acid production.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  American Plastics Council<br>
     U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> October 1994 to October
1995<br>
<hr>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  American Plastics Council<br>
     U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> October 1994 to October
1995<br>
