</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Thermal Recycling of Plastics</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Thermal Recycling of Plastics </h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Plastics currently account for about 20% by volume of the materials entering a landfill. 
Landfilling and, to a lesser extent, incineration have been the traditional means of waste
disposal.  With ever more stringent regulations on material entering a landfill and the desire to
recycle more products, an effort is under way to reduce the volume of material disposed by
traditional means.  Although many products can be recycled directly back to their original
forms (e.g., paper, aluminum cans, high-density polyethylene [HDPE] bottles), others must be
recycled via alternative means to be economically viable.  The EERC is currently conducting a
program, sponsored by the American Plastics Council (APC), to examine the thermal
decomposition products resulting from the fluid-bed pyrolysis of polymers typically found in
postconsumer waste streams.  APC is a consortium of the 25 largest U.S. plastics producers. 
Thermal degradation of postconsumer plastics produces liquids and gases very similar to the
petroleum feedstock materials used in producing these plastics.  If located near a petroleum
refinery, the most cost-effective option might be to return the degradation products to the
refinery or olefin plant.  Not only would landfill volume be reduced, but the amount of
petroleum dedicated to polymer production would be decreased.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives are threefold:  to examine product yields (olefins, hydrocarbon liquids,
terephthalic acid) as a function of temperature, bed material, gas residence time, and feed
composition; to identify chlorine concentrations with varying processing conditions; and to
identify potentially troublesome products (e.g., organochlorides).<p>
<p>
<h2>Results </h2>
<p>
     The program has successfully demonstrated the conversion of plastics into liquids, gaseous
olefins, and terephthalic acid.  Results indicate that each of the products would be suitable for
entry into an olefin plant, refinery, or other chemical facility.  Materials tested included
polypropylene (PP), HDPE, low-density polyethylene (LDPE), linear low-density polyethylene
(LLDPE), polystyrene (PS), polyvinyl chloride (PVC), nylon, polyurethane, acrylonitrile
butadiene styrene (ABS), polyethylene terephthalate (PET), and several postconsumer plastics
with PET levels up to 20%.  Liquid yields ranged from 20% to  100%, and olefin yields
approached 50% at selected conditions.  Organochloride formation, which is a hindrance to
product acceptability, was found to be inhibited through the use of certain bed materials used as
chlorine sorbents.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> 
<li>American Plastics Council 
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>August 1992 to December 1995
<hr>
