<html>
<head>
<title>Feedstock Recycling of 3M Postindustrial
Products</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1> Feedstock Recycling of 3M Postindustrial Products</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Over the past several years, there has been a desire on the part of the public to recycle and/or
reuse more of the material currently being landfilled or incinerated.  Many communities have
initiated collection and recycling of some postconsumer materials, such as aluminum, glass,
paper, and selected types of plastics (mainly polyethylene terephthalate [PET] and high-density
polyethylene [HDPE]).  While the recycling emphasis has been on marketable postconsumer
material, some industrial manufacturers, such as the 3M company, have initiated efforts to
increase both recycling of industrial scrap and recovery and subsequent recycling of products
from consumers.  These products are materials that would not be eligible for traditional
recycling processes.  Much of the 3M scrap is polymer-based and may contain significant
levels of solids.  Because of the solids content and because many 3M products are
combinations of two or more types of plastics, traditional recycling methods are inappropriate. 
For example, about three-quarters by weight of magnetic tape is PET.  While technologies
exist to recycle PET (hydrolysis, methanolysis), no existing process can accept material with
high solids loading, with PET in combination with other types of plastics, or with other
organic material (e.g., mineral oils).<p>
<p>
     The EERC was given the opportunity to investigate the feasibility of recycling selected 3M
products by thermal degradation to hydrocarbon liquids and gases.  Materials examined
included magnetic tape pellets, Scotchpak<sup>TM</sup> pellets (with both high and low PET
content), pelletized polymer sheet material, a face mask skeleton scrap, and three types of reflective
tape.  Thermal depolymerization tests were performed in the EERC 1-4-lb/hr continuous
fluid-bed reactor (CFBR) system.  Eleven products were tested, with forty-two test points
attempted.  Results of the work indicate that several of the low-PET products can be
decomposed to yield a usable liquid, with hydrocarbon liquid yields ranging from 24% to 66%
over a temperature range of 475&#176; to 550&#176;C.  A high-Btu gas is also produced that could
potentially be used for process heat.  This option needs further investigation, since buildup of
trace contaminants in a recycle loop is a concern.  Conversion of high-PET materials focused
on terephthalic acid (TA) recovery, since TA may be worth substantially more than the oils
produced, possibly as much as 30% more.  An exact determination of product value cannot yet
be made, since it depends upon the level of purity attainable.  <p>
<p>
     Oils produced in the process can either be blended with boiler fuels and used in-house at 3M
or sold to a refinery for introduction to a higher-value unit, such as a cat cracker.<p>
<p>
     Products containing levels of PET greater than 10% were known to have limits on their
processing conditions prior to the investigation.  A goal of this program was to help outline
these boundaries.  Previous work had indicated that processing PET at temperatures above
about 600&#176;C resulted in coking and agglomeration in the bed.  Processing at almost all
temperatures without steam also resulted in a prohibitive amount of coking.  At the higher
temperatures, CO<sub>2</sub> is released from the ring structures, leaving behind a radical
site.  These radical sites stick together, forming a network of aromatic rings.   (Sharp, L.L.; Ness,
R.O., Jr.; Randall, J.C.; Aulich, T.A.  "Thermal Recycling of Plastics," report to American Plastics
Council; EERC publication, 1994.)  Previous attempts at lower temperatures
(450&#176;-550&#176;C) were unsuccessful; initially it was thought that this was due to insufficient
energy (low temperatures) to break down the other polymers present in the mixed plastics feed
used.(Sharp)<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     In this investigation, several tests were performed in a steam atmosphere in an attempt to
convert PET to TA by a reverse esterification reaction.  Using steam, PET in polymer
concentrations from 10% to 100% was successfully decomposed.  TA was produced, with
yields ranging from 1% to 110%.  Note that these are yields, not conversions, and that
starting PET concentrations ranged from 10% to 100%.  While some tests showed respectable
TA yields, it was determined that impracticably high steam-to-PET ratios were necessary for
the solids and gas residence times tested.  The highest TA yields observed were seen when a
high-PET Scotchpak<sup>TM</sup> was processed using a 10:1 water-to-PET ratio.  It is not
yet known
which process condition is responsible for this high yield.  Feed composition, residence time,
steam-to-PET ratio, bed material, or a combination of factors may be responsible for this
promising result.  Further testing is needed to investigate the possibility of lower steam ratios. 
Variations in solid and gas residence times may permit processing at reasonable steam flows.<p>
<p>
     Both high- and low-PET-content Scotchpak<sup>TM</sup> pellets were processed with
minimal difficulties.  The high-PET material, processed with an approximate 10:1 steam-to-PET
ratio, gave the highest TA yield of any product tested.  The low-PET Scotchpak<sup>TM</sup>,
processed with minimal steam (2:1 and lower), gave much lower TA yields.  In addition to the higher
steam ratios, gas residence time in the high-PET material tests was much shorter than in the low-PET
tests.<p>
<p>
     The white face mask material, composed mainly of polypropylene (PP) and PET, decomposed
easily, yielding a liquid similar in composition and boiling point distribution to diesel fuel. 
Liquid yields ranged from 31% to 39% over a temperature range of 500&#176; to
550&#176;C.<p>
<p>
     A product of 3M's Occupational Health &amp; Environmental Systems Division (OH&amp;ESD)
was tested at 500&#176; and 550&#176;C.  While the test at 500&#176;C was successful, resulting
in a liquid yield of 51%, the test at 550&#176;C was terminated because of reactor plugging.<p>
<p>
     Face mask material mixed with PP tape was tested at temperatures of 475&#176; and
500&#176;C and found to decompose readily, producing a liquid yield of between 40% and
49%.<p>
<p>
     Reflectolite<sup>TM</sup> contains a high amount of silica-based paper.  This product,
decomposed alone or when processed with other tapes at a level of 30%, showed agglomeration
tendencies.  It is recommended that this product be diluted prior to processing.  The limiting
composition is not precisely known, but is below 30%.  The two other tapes tested, High
Intensity<sup>TM</sup> and Diamondgrade<sup>TM</sup>, were easily decomposed,
producing liquid yields between 24% and 66% over a temperature range of 500&#176; to
550&#176;C.<p>
<p>
     One test was performed on a polymer sheet material known to contain fluorine.  One test only
was performed in order to determine the possibility of producing perfluoroisobutylene (PFIB),
a highly toxic substance.  Product gas was sampled and later analyzed by a 3M lab.  PFIB was
detected in significant quantities.  Testing with this material was terminated.<p>
<p>
     While several of the liquids produced had boiling point distributions heavier than might be
desired for use as a boiler fuel substitute, blending in some proportion may be acceptable
using currently known conditions.<p>
<p>
Based on a recent residence time investigation conducted at the EERC using postconsumer
plastics (not yet published), (This work consisted of a series of tests in the EERC 1-4-lb/hr CFBR. 
Most tests were conducted at 625&#176;C; various gas  residence times were completed.  The feed
material had the following approximate composition:  67% HDPE, 9% polyvinyl    chloride (PVC),
12% PET, 6% PP, 2% polystyrene (PS), and 4% other.) a slightly longer gas residence time will
yield a considerably lighter product liquid.  It is not yet known what effect a longer gas residence
time will have on PET coking or on TA conversion.  While the magnitude of the effects of both gas
and solids residence time on TA yield and PET coking is not yet fully understood, much progress has
been made since the initial tests in this (3M) work, in which bed coking and plugging were
severe.<p>
<p>
     The EERC began a program sponsored by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
and the American Plastics Council (APC) in October of 1994.  A goal of the investigation is to
examine TA recovery.  If the EPA-APC work indicates that reasonable TA yields can be
attained at practicable steam ratios, it will be recommended that development of a TA recovery
process by 3M continue, since TA recovery will most likely enhance process economics. 
While it can be stated that TA is a more valuable product than the hydrocarbon oils produced,
it is not known what degree of purity of TA is attainable or the costs associated with attaining
varying degrees of purity.  If TA recovery is pursued, a test plan should cover optimization of
TA yields and characterization of the hydrocarbon liquid coproducts.  A decision as to whether
high-PET streams will be processed along with low-PET streams will dictate specific program
goals.  If high-PET and low-PET-content products are to be processed separately, products
with low to moderate PET contents should be tested at several other gas residence times to
optimize liquid quality and yield, separate from TA optimization studies.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Robert O. Ness, Jr./<a href=mailto:rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rness@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5209<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>3M Company<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>December 1993 to  June 1994<br>
