<head>
<title>Development of an Airplane Deicing Concept</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Development of an Airplane Deicing Concept </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2
<p>
     Aircraft are deiced to prevent a buildup of ice that would compromise safe flight.  The most
commonly used deicing agent is an ethylene glycol-based formulation called a Type 1 deicer. 
In the past, no effort was made to collect the runoff from the spraying operations.  However,
environmental regulations have been tightened, necessitating a change in procedure to include
collection and processing of the deicer runoff.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The objective of this research program was to determine if spent Type 1 deicing fluid could be
recycled to produce either deicing fluid or polyester-grade ethylene glycol that could be used
in the production of new deicing fluid.<p>

<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     The research determined that spent Type 1 aircraft deicing fluid can be processed to produce
polyester-grade ethylene glycol suitable to be the basis for the production of Type 1 deicing
fluid.  The most effective recycling scheme tested consisted of physical separation of
suspended inorganic and organic debris followed by a series of mass transfer unit operations to
separate polyester-grade ethylene glycol from water and other organic liquids.  The success of
this research indicates that process scheme optimization and scaleup be performed, with the
resulting data used to determine the cost-effectiveness of this concept.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> John R. Rindt/<a href=mailto:jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5296<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>North Dakota Economic Development and Finance 
<li>Technology Transfer, Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>April 1994 to December 1995<br>
