<head>
<title>Treatment of Mixed Wastes</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Treatment of Mixed Wastes</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Mixed-waste sites make up the majority of contaminated sites, yet remediation techniques used
at such sites often target only the most prevalent contaminant.  A better understanding of the
most common types of contamination, current remediation techniques, and combinations of
techniques would provide insight into areas in which further research should be performed.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives of this work effort are to 1) perform a detailed literature search dealing with
common types of contamination and current techniques (and combinations of techniques) used
to treat mixed wastes and 2) assess each of the remediation techniques, combining them in
various ways appropriate to mixed-waste protocol.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     A comprehensive literature survey of common types of mixed-waste contamination as well as
current state-of-the-art treatments for mixed wastes has been completed.  The documents
identified by the survey are under review.  Data gathered during the survey are being
incorporated into two other remediation technology databases.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> John R. Rindt/<a href=mailto:jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5296<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>March 1994 to June 1995<br>
