<head>
<title>Aqueous-Phase Thermal Oxidation Wastewater Treatment</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Aqueous-Phase Thermal Oxidation Wastewater Treatment </h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Aqueous-phase waste streams pose a significant disposal problem.  These streams are made up
of by-product streams produced by industrial activity, process water, and contaminated
precipitation and have a volume totaling tens of millions of gallons per year.  Current
technologies used for aqueous stream cleanup include incineration, gravitational oil-water
separation, chemical stripping, activated carbon adsorption followed by desorption, and
microbial action.  Some of these technologies  cannot meet increasingly stringent release
requirements, and many are not economically viable.  Improved technologies capable of
dealing with this type of waste in an economic, environmentally acceptable manner are
needed.  Wet-air oxidation could be an appropriate technology if the high costs associated with
maintaining necessary reaction temperature and pressure could be reduced.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objective of this project is to shake down a novel wet-air oxidation apparatus that operates
in a manner that greatly reduces the high costs associated with maintenance of the required
reaction temperature and pressure.  <p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Fabrication of the apparatus is nearly complete, and shakedown testing will subsequently
follow.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> John R. Rindt/<a href=mailto:jrindty@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jrindt@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5296<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>March 1994 to June 1995 <br>
