<head>
<title>Coal Ash Resources Research Consortium</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Coal Ash Resources Research Consortium</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Coal by-products are produced in high volumes worldwide each year.  Disposal of these
materials is an important economic and environmental issue to electric power utilities and is
frequently a major deterrent to the advancement of certain clean coal technologies.  Disposal
costs have risen dramatically for conventional coal ash, and since many clean coal technologies
produce an even greater volume of by-product, these costs are expected to increase as well. 
The costs associated with disposal generally result from meeting regulatory requirements
applied to ensure environmentally sound disposal.  Coal ash utilization has long been
economically advantageous, but with the forecast for some stringent environmental regulations
and the increasing disposal costs, the ash utilization option is likely to become a more
economically viable alternative.  In order to meet the research and development needs of the
ash use industry, the Western Fly Ash Research, Development, and Data Center (WFARDDC)
was formed in 1985 to facilitate the promotion of coal ash utilization through scientific and
engineering research.  The WFARDDC was reorganized to become the Coal Ash Resources
Research Consortium (CARRC, pronounced cars).<p>
<p>
     CARRC is the core research group for coal ash utilization at the EERC.  CARRC is a
consortium of member organizations, scientists, and engineers dedicated to performing
research and developing techniques related to coal combustion by-products.  This research and
development program involves work spanning from ash generation through utilization or
disposal.  The strength of CARRC research lies in the expertise and experience of the research
scientists, engineers, and member organizations.  A multidisciplinary team approach is
emphasized in every aspect of the research effort, and member organizations provide valuable
direction, insight, and perspective to the overall research program.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The primary goal of CARRC is to work with industry to solve ash-related problems and promote
the environmentally safe, economic utilization and disposal of these highly complex materials. 
Secondary goals include the generation of scientific and engineering information regarding
regulations and specifications for coal combustion fly ash; the development of improved
characterization methods for coal by-products; the demonstration of new or improved coal ash
use applications; and technology commercialization.  Specific research objectives for 1994-1995
are summarized as follows:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Advance predictive capabilities for and demonstrate ash behavior
in utilization applications<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Promote high-volume use applications for coal ash<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Develop valid environmental test procedures for coal ash
applicable to utilization and disposal<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Develop a database of utilization applications requirements<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Investigate advanced technological utilization applications and
promote innovative ash use<br>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Promote product performance to evaluate products containing coal
ash<br>
</ul>
<p>
     These objectives are consistent with the primary goal of CARRC.  CARRC members are
encouraged to participate in defining specific yearly objectives and research tasks to achieve
these objectives.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2></font> <p>
<p>
     CARRC has developed the Coal Ash Properties Database for over 800 fly ash samples from
around the world.  This database includes physical, chemical, and mineralogical properties that
have proven valuable to researchers, users, producers, and marketers.  The database was made
available to CARRC members in a user-friendly, interactive database management system. <p>
<p>
     CARRC researchers have worked with local ash marketers and contractors in placing
high-volume fly ash concrete in commercial projects.  These projects are visually inspected on a
regular basis, and laboratory specimens are evaluated to determine strength and durability of the
various mix designs.  North Dakota lignite ash samples were characterized for performance and
environmental criteria.  Mix designs for a wide variety of road-building applications are under
development.<p>
<p>
     CARRC researchers have developed new characterization protocols for coal combustion
by-products including leaching procedures, application of computer-controlled scanning electron
microscopy, and heat of hydration.  Research has also focused on the hydration of coal
combustion products as these reactions play an important role in the behavior of these materials
in utilization applications.  CARRC participated in the development of new standards for coal
combustion by-product utilization through the American Society for Testing and Materials and in
regional and national coal combustion by-product promotional groups and activities.<p>
<hr> 
<b>Project Manager:</b> Debra F. Pflughoeft-Hassett/<a href=mailto:dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5261<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Brett Admixtures, Inc. 
<li>Cooperative Power Company 
<li>Nebraska Ash Company 
<li>Northern States Power Company 
<li>Otter Tail Power Company 
<li>U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>June 1992 to June 1995<br>
<hr>
