<html>
<head>
<title>Development of a Coal By-Product
Classification Protocol for Utilization</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Development of a Coal By-Product Classification Protocol for Utilization </h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     A major barrier to coal ash utilization is the lack of an effective classification system for coal
fly ash.  A large volume of fly ash is produced that does not meet current American Society
for Testing and Materials (ASTM) specifications for cement and concrete but could be used for
other applications.  In many cases, coal ash is required to meet ASTM specifications, even
when they are clearly inappropriate for the application (i.e., controlled low-strength material). 
The disposal of this fly ash creates environmental problems as well as economic considerations
for the utilities.  Because current disposal facilities are rapidly being filled, many utilities face
the development of new disposal facilities.  These new facilities are generally more stringently
regulated by state environmental agencies and will be much more costly for the utility. 
Furthermore, the current focus on reducing trace element emissions may cause an increase in
the trace elements in coal by-products such as fly ash, which may further impact disposal
requirements for the utility and cause greater environmental concern.<p>

<p>

     Creating a classification system for fly ash that facilitates the use of performance-based
specifications for use applications will broaden the utilization options for coal ash, resulting in
avoided disposal costs, and will provide opportunities for industry to develop new products
and expand the use of coal ash in existing products.  The inadequacy of the current
classification system is one of the major technical barriers to increased coal by-product
utilization.  This project is ideally suited to the EERC multidisciplinary approach and involved
personnel from several groups.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The goal of this project was to develop a classification system for fly ash based on parameters
that relate to performance specifications of engineering and construction applications.  The
new classification system will provide a means of evaluating the suitability of coal ash for use
in certain products that currently have no realistic standards or classifications.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     A flowchart to facilitate the identification of appropriate coal combustion fly ash materials for
use in structural fill applications was developed.  The first screening criterion for the materials
selection is the environmental or leaching characteristic of the material.  If the material is
environmentally suitable, physical and engineering properties, detailed in the ASTM standard
guideline for use of coal fly ash in structural fill, are determined.<p>

<p>

     Two samples of North Dakota lignite fly ash were evaluated using this procedure and found to
be good candidates for structural fill and other fill applications.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Debra F. Pflughoeft-Hassett/<a href=mailto:dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5261<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown
Energy Technology
Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  March 1994 to March 1995<br>
