<html>
<head>
<title>Development of an Ash Management
Program for Minnesota Power
Company's Clay Boswell Station</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Development of an Ash Management Program for Minnesota Power Company's Clay Boswell
Station
</h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     Coal residuals, like any other material, must be understood before they can be effectively
managed. 
To
fully assess coal combustion ash for its utilization potential, a thorough evaluation of its physical,
chemical,
and mineralogical characteristics is essential.  This evaluation will reveal what is in the material,
what form
it is in, how reactive it is in given situations, and how it will behave as a component in a product
setting.  <p>

<p>

     Until recently, virtually all utilization attempts were empirically, rather than scientifically, carried
out. 
This
resulted in no predictability or reliability and, consequently, little industrial enthusiasm to use ash.  A
well-designed research and development program in coal ash utilization is needed to match the
material
properties available with existing products to develop new products and markets.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Objectives</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     In recent years, a more scientific approach to ash utilization research has been developed at the
EERC. 
Significant progress has been made in understanding the chemistry and phase assemblages of these
highly
complex materials.  The understanding and interpretation of the inorganic transformations responsible
for
ash production during coal combustion have also been greatly improved in recent years.  The
research from
this project is an aggressive step towards integrating the transformations into a comprehensive ash
management plan, including the specific details relevant to the Clay Boswell power generation
facility. 
Several environmental and economic benefits are anticipated as a result of this project, including 1)
reduced
waste from coal combustion, 2) reduced ash disposal costs, and 3) production of a stable product in
addition
to electricity generation.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     Samples were collected to represent high-load, low-load, start-up, and shutdown conditions at
Minnesota
Power's Clay Boswell Station Unit No. 2.  These samples were thoroughly characterized and
represent the
coal ash quality as background samples.  A test burn at the Clay Boswell Station was done with
varying
plant loads and operational parameters in order to determine the impact of these parameters on ash
quality
and consistency.  Samples were collected during the test burn, characterized, and related to the plant
operational parameters that have an effect on ash quality.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Edward N. Steadman/<a href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5157<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> </ul plain>Minnesota Power Company<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology  Center</ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  October 1992 to September
1993<br>
