<head>
<title>Solidification and Stabilization of Wastes Using Coal Fly Ash</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Solidification and Stabilization of Wastes Using Coal Fly Ash</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Fly ash and fly ash with additives have been used to stabilize and solidify a wide variety of waste
materials.  A large number of laboratory-scale tests have been done using fly ash to stabilize
various wastes such as sludge, methanol, xylene, benzene, radioactive wastes, heavy metals, and
oils.  Because coal fly ash is often considered a waste material, its use is often overlooked or
questioned by remediation contractors and regulatory personnel.  However, several documented
sites exist in which fly ash was successfully used for the solidification and stabilization of
wastes.  The work requested by the American Coal Ash Association (ACAA) was focused on
providing useful information on site performance of fly ash as a solidification and stabilization
material for waste remediation sites.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The primary objective of this project was to assemble definitive information on the use of coal
fly ash and other coal conversion solid residues for the solidification and stabilization of
wastes.<p>
<h2> Results</h2>
<p>
     During the project, opportunities and needs related to fly ash and other residues for solidification
and stabilization of wastes were identified.  From the information compiled, a well-documented
article, "Solidification and Stabilization of Wastes Using Coal Fly Ash:  Current Status and
Direction," was prepared by the EERC for publication by the ACAA.  This document lists a
number of research projects as well as commercial applications of solidification and stabilization
of wastes using coal fly ash.  A list of the various wastes that have been successfully stabilized
using coal fly ash is given as well as the technical and regulatory issues concerning the use of
coal fly ash in the solidification/stabilization process.  Several case histories are cited as well as a
list of recommendations to Congress by the U.S. Department of Energy to increase the use of
coal fly ash.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edward N. Steadman/<a href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5157<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>American Coal Ash Association<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>December 1992 to May 1994<br>
