<head>
<title>Use of Coal By-Products for Removal and Solidification/Stabilization of Hazardous
Wastes</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Use of Coal By-Products for Removal and Solidification/Stabilization of Hazardous Wastes</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Increasing demand for carbon sorbents and catalytic supports has been stimulated by their
burgeoning use in controlling environmental pollution as well as optimizing the dispersion and
reducing the cost of catalysts.  Specialty carbons are being successfully used in numerous
applications such as selective pollutant sorption and high-temperature sorbents.  Currently,
brown coal coke and bituminous coal-based carbons are being used to adsorb sulfur dioxide,
hydrogen chloride, and mercury vapor as well as volatile organic compounds at power utilities
and waste incineration plants in Germany and Japan.  With the addition of ammonia to the flue
gas stream, NO<sub>x</sub> can also be controlled.  As the environmental regulations in the
United States become more stringent, the demand for adsorbent carbons will substantially increase
their application as sorbent materials in stacks at power utilities, cement factories, and waste
incineration plants, to give a few examples.<p>
<p>
     Low-rank coals (LRCs) are believed to be excellent precursors for sorbent carbons because of
their inherently high surface areas, which can be enhanced by thermal pretreatment.  Carbon
sorbents can also be made more selective in their application (e.g., for mercury species control)
by chemical treatment.  LRCs have a relatively higher oxygen content than high-rank coals do,
assisting in the development of optimum pore structure during activation.  In addition, LRCs are
available in plentiful supply and at low cost.<p>
<p>
     A second area of opportunity involves the use of coal ash.  It would be highly advantageous, both
for government and commercial sectors, to develop standard practices for the use of coal
conversion by-products in the development of solidification/stabilization (S/S) technologies for
the environmentally acceptable and economic disposal of mixed wastes.  The federal government
has a broad range of sites requiring remediation where S/S technologies using coal utilization
wastes may be the best available technology.  The use of coal combustion by-products and/or
ettringite formation has been found to have potential for the fixation and stabilization of
hazardous wastes.<p>
<p>
     Additional research is needed to understand the long-term performance potential of waste
stabilization using fly ash and clean coal technology by-products.  A better understanding of
mineral reactions involving metal hydroxides and substituted ettringites is a key part of
predicting the fixation and retention of hazardous trace metals over time using coal combustion
by-products.  In general, the chemistry of fly ash interactions with inorganic waste constituents
bears a close similarity to concrete chemistry, which can, therefore, be used to investigate
inorganic fixation.  Long-term stability is particularly difficult to define, and predictive modeling
must be used to project stability parameters.<p>

<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The objective of the project is twofold:  1) to produce and characterize test quantities of an
activated carbonaceous adsorbent and 2) to investigate the potential for application of coal
conversion by-products in waste stabilization settings with a focus on the potential for ettringites
and ettringitelike mineral forms for the fixation and retention of hazardous materials.<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Gascoyne lignite chars were prepared at 400&#176;C and subsequently steam-activated at
750&#176;C for 30 min.  The I<sub>2</sub> (iodine) numbers of the char and the activated
carbon were found to be 283 and 290, respectively.  The lack of improvement in surface area during
steam activation can be attributed to the mineral-catalyzed gasification, as with the leonardite chars. 
Thus several experiments with chemically cleaned lignite were preformed.  Nitric acid-washed
Gascoyne was prepared and carbonized at 400&#176;C.  The I<sub>2</sub> value was quite
low (183), probably because the pores collapsed to a greater extent during carbonization in the
absence of the calcium ions.  Steam activation of the char from the cleaned coal gave an
improvement in the I<sub>2</sub> value (283), but this value is still very low.  The char
produced from lignite cleaned with sulfurous acid had an I<sub>2</sub> number of 271.  Steam
activation of this char gave a carbon with I<sub>2</sub> = 317.  Although this value is low
compared with those of commercial carbons, it indicates that acid washing is essential for obtaining
usable carbons from LRCs.  A further demonstration of the mineral effect was obtained by washing
the 400&#176;C char from the uncleaned coal and then activating the cleaned char.  In this case, the I<sub>2</sub> number decreased for the 30-min activation, but increased substantially for the
60-min activation to 454.  Thus the kinetics of steam gasification in the absence of the calcium are
very slow, and a long activation time is required to develop the desired porosity.<p>
<p>
     Two samples of coal combustion by-products were selected for investigation in this project. 
These samples were submitted for laboratory testing, including bulk chemical analysis,
evaluation of mineralogy and phase association, physical and engineering properties, and
leaching studies.  As part of the leaching studies, an evaluation of the hydration reactions will
also be performed.  Several other regional coal ash samples are being evaluated for utilization
potential, and all relevant information available from this project will also be evaluated relative
to solidification/stabilization.  In addition to the stabilization of potentially hazardous trace
elements, such as boron and selenium, characterization results from all of these materials will be
evaluated for potential use for soil stabilization in roadbase, subbase, and slope protection.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edward N. Steadman/<a href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5157<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>June 1994 to September 1995<br>
