<head>
<title>Sulfate Resistance of Fly Ash Concrete</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2> Sulfate Resistance of Fly Ash Concrete </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The American Coal Ash Association (ACAA) has identified the issue of conflicting and
misrepresented information on sulfate resistance of fly ash concrete as one that may be highly
detrimental to the maintenance and expansion of the fly ash market for concrete.  The ACAA
determined that the initial step in addressing this issue is to summarize and evaluate available
technical information; the second step is to identify and prioritize research needs.  ACAA and
the U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center funded an effort at
the EERC to review key literature related to sulfate resistance of fly ash concrete and to
identify the research needs for technical support of the utilization of coal combustion fly ash in
concrete subject to a sulfate environment.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Objectives</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The primary objective of this project was to assemble definitive information on sulfate
resistance of fly ash concrete and develop a prioritized list of research needs for the coal by-product
industry
in this field.  The work consisted of a comprehensive review of literature
addressing the sulfate resistance of fly ash concrete. <p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The literature review and evaluation performed by the EERC for this effort indicate that the
common difficulties, such as the empirical nature of research, materials variability, variable
methodologies, limited documentation, and limited studies, described in coal ash research also
apply to research on sulfate resistance of fly ash concrete.  The literature review identified
specific cases of conflicting research conclusions by researchers from various backgrounds.<p>

<p>

     Research needs were identified both directly from the literature and from the review and
evaluation of the information available in the literature.  Research is needed in the following
key focus areas:<p>

<p>


<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Impact of fly ash on sulfate resistance of concrete<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Evaluation of fly ash for sulfate resistance potential<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Procedures for evaluation of sulfate resistance<br>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Mechanisms of sulfate attack on concrete<br>
</ul>
<p>

     It is also recommended that this effort be designed as a cooperative venture among several
research groups to provide ongoing peer review and maintain an unbiased viewpoint.  Direct
input from the coal ash industry is recommended to facilitate the performance of the best
possible project and documentation.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Edward N. Steadman/<a href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br><b>Phone: </b>(701) 777-5157<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b><ul plain>  American Coal Ash Association<br>
     U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology Center</ul>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> August 1992 to December
1993<br>
