<head>
<title>Testing of Radcon Formula #7 for
Resistance to Chloride Ion Penetration</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Testing of Radcon Formula #7 for Resistance to Chloride Ion Penetration  </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h3> Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The use of salts for combating ice formation on concrete surfaces is common practice in cold
regions of the United States.  The infiltration of chloride ions from these salts can cause severe
concrete degradation.  In the case of bridge spans, the chloride ions can attack the embedded, 
reinforced steel.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The objective of this project was to evaluate the product, Radcon Formula #7, for its potential
to resist chloride ion penetration.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     ASTM Test Method C672, "Scaling Resistance of Concrete Surfaces Exposed to Deicing
Chemicals," was used to evaluate Radcon Formula #7.  Concrete samples were fabricated, and
the finished surfaces were treated with the Radcon Formula #7.  These surfaces were then
exposed to a 3% sodium chloride solution.  After the prescribed exposure duration, cored
specimens were retained and evaluated for total chloride ion content.<p>

<p>

     The results indicated that Radcon product effectively reduced chloride ion penetration to the
specification levels prescribed by the American Concrete Institute and the North Dakota
Department of Transportation.  The use of the Radcon product will promote more construction
using concrete mixtures.  This, in turn, may promote the use of more coal by-products such as
fly ash.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Bruce A. Dockter/<a href=mailto:bdockter@eerc.und.nodak.edu>bdockter@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-4102<br>
<b>Sponsor: </b> Tech-Crete Inc.<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> June 1993 to February 1994<br>
<hr>
