<html>
<head>
<title>Use of Coal Ash in Ceramics</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2> Use of Coal Ash in Ceramics</h2> </center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Background</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     Previous empirical tests at the EERC have indicated that coal combustion by-products are a
viable starting material for the production of a variety of ceramic products, including brick,
tile, and high-flexural-strength ceramics.  The EERC has focused on high-temperature
properties of coal and has provided valuable insight into ash transformations, fouling, and
slagging for the utility industry.  The information generated in these past projects will be used
to develop material selection criteria and product manufacturing techniques based on scientific
and engineering characteristics of the ash.  Commercialization of the use of coal combustion
by-products in ceramics is more likely to become viable if a quality-assured product can be
made, and predictive materials selection is a key component of a quality-assured product.<p>

<p>
<font color="#990066"><h2>  <b>Objective</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     The objective of this project is to demonstrate the development and  production of a ceramic
material utilizing coal ash as a key component.  Chemical and high-temperature properties of
ash will be carefully determined, with the goal of identifying criteria for materials selection
and manufacturing options for ceramic production.  <p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h2> <b>Results</b> </h2></font> <p>

<p>

     A variety of coal fly ash samples have been selected from the Coal Ash Properties Database. 
A review of key chemistry parameters indicated that sodium and iron have an effect on the
behavior of ash subjected to high temperatures, and so the ash samples selected have a range
of sodium and iron concentrations.  Additional characterization techniques are being
performed on the selected ashes.  Preliminary mix designs for high-flexural-strength ceramics
have been developed, and laboratory specimens of ceramic will be prepared.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Debra F. Pflughoeft-Hassett/<a href=mailto:dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone: </b> (701) 777-5261 <br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  January 1995 to December 1995
<br>
<hr>
