<html>
<head>
<title>Use of Coal Ash in Recycled Plastics and
Composite Materials</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Use of Coal Ash in Recycled Plastics and Composite Materials </h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     Coal fly ash has been used as an inert filler in paints, plastics, and other manufactured
products.  Unfortunately, the properties of coal ash have not been considered to upgrade these
materials or to produce a unique material.  Coal ash exhibits a broad range of characteristics
that appear to have potential to be used beneficially in plastics and other composite materials. 
Baseline investigations of the use of coal ash in plastics, particularly recycled plastics, will use
information already being generated regarding the inorganic constituents in plastics and will
provide further information on the suitability of coal fly ash for use in recycled plastics and
other composite materials.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The goal of this research is to determine the potential for coal ash to serve as a functional filler
in plastics and other composite materials, with special emphasis on the interaction of coal ash
and recycled plastics in simple formulations designed to produce building or decorative tiles.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     Several samples of ash were considered for use in production of a plastic sample.  The ash types
selected for laboratory trials included a glassy, granular boiler slag, a pulverized coal fly ash, and
cenospheres.  Plastics that might be expected in postconsumer streams were reviewed.  Several
plastic types were selected for preliminary trials.  Polyester and acrylic were used to produce a
number of prototype tiles incorporating the various coal combustion by-products (CCBs) at
several different levels.  The tiles vary in appearance because of color and particle-size variation
in the CCBs.  The tiles are lighter than conventional ceramic tiles.  Performance criteria,
including flexural strength and resistance to abrasion, will be evaluated.  Testing the
compatibility of these tiles with adhesives and grout is also planned for future projects.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>Edward N. Steadman/<a href=mailto:esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu>esteadman@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5157<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>  U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown
Energy Technology
Center <br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b> March 1994 to March 1995<br>
<hr>
