<html>
<head>
<title>Ash Utilization in the State of North
Dakota</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Ash Utilization in the State of North Dakota</h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Background</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The use of coal combustion fly ash of appropriate quality to replace a portion of the portland
cement in concrete is one of the more established ash utilization options, such as in the
construction of the EERC laboratory addition.  Typically, 25% of the cement is replaced with
fly ash.  For this project, 70% of the cement was replaced with fly ash, and the performance
of the high-cement-replacement concrete was evaluated.  The use of controlled-density
flowable fill is also a high-volume use of fly ash that was demonstrated.  Finally, concerns
over the environmental acceptability of these materials were addressed.<p>

<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Objectives</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     The objectives of this project were:<p>

<p>


<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To demonstrate the use of high-fly-ash-replacement concrete for
the construction of several heavy-duty roads and parking lots at the Coal Creek Station near
Underwood, North Dakota.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To demonstrate the use of controlled-density flowable fill using
Coal Creek Station fly ash.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> To determine any environmental impacts on groundwater resulting
from the use of high-fly-ash-content concrete and fill.<br>
</ul>
<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>Results</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     Approximately 20,000 square yards of 8-in. concrete paving were placed at the Coal Creek
Station in 1988 and 1989.  The concrete mixture was innovative because Coal Creek fly ash
was used to replace 70% of the conventional portland cement.  The performance of the
high-fly-ash-replacement concrete was monitored, and the groundwater at the construction site was
sampled to evaluate the potential for trace element leaching from the concrete.  Cored
specimens and visual inspection have been performed, and results show strength and durability
similar to conventional concrete pavement.  High-volume fly ash concrete pavement competes
economically with asphalt pavement for placement with a longer life span.  The high-volume
fly ash concrete pavement remains in service today in heavy traffic areas at the plant site and
maintains excellent performance.  Laboratory and field results indicate no adverse impact from
leaching of the concrete.  Extensive laboratory testing was also performed to evaluate potential
environmental impact and engineering performance of controlled low-strength material
(CLSM) using 100% coal fly ash.  Following approval from the North Dakota State
Department of Health and Consolidated Laboratories, CLSM was placed in an abandoned
underground mine at Wilton, North Dakota.  The CLSM can be used for subsidence abatement
and is easily placed because of its excellent flowability.  Environmental monitoring of the
Wilton mine site indicated no detrimental impacts as a result of placement.  Environmental
monitoring will continue under another project.<p>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Project Managers:</b><ul plain> 
Debra F. Pflughoeft-Hassett/<a href=mailto:dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dphassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5261<br>
Raymond D. Butler/<a href=mailto:rbutler@eerc.und.nodak.edu>rbutler@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b>  (701) 777-5243<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> <ul plain> Cooperative Power Company<br>
     United Power Association (under  contract to Electric Power Research Institute)</ul>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  June 1988 to December
1994<br>
