<html>
<head>
<title>National Mine Land Reclamation Center: Research Program for the Western Region</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>National Mine Land Reclamation Center: Research Program for the Western Region</h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The National Mine Land Reclamation Center (NMLRC) was established in 1988 as three
regional centers--the Western Region center located at and administered by the EERC, with
research support provided by the North Dakota State University (NDSU) Land Reclamation
Research Center; the Midwest Region center at Southern Illinois University; and the Eastern
Region center at West Virginia University (WVU) and Pennsylvania State University.  This
program is sponsored by the U.S. Bureau of Mines, with WVU performing the overall
national program administration.  The NMLRC consortium brings together experienced
research teams that address regional and national reclamation issues with an interdisciplinary
approach.  The NMLRC Western Region at the EERC has more than two decades of research
experience in natural materials characterization, hydrogeology, and geochemistry of
environmental systems and process design and operation ranging from conceptual to
commercial in scale.<p>
<p>
     Reclamation of a landscape disturbed by surface coal mining involves addressing a number of
related issues, including degradation of groundwater quantity and quality, degradation of plant
growth potential, and instability of the reclaimed materials.  In order to determine the
environmental impacts due to surface mining, the total landscape must be evaluated, which
involves determining the relationships between surface morphology, physical and chemical
characteristics of the disturbed and reclaimed materials, and hydrogeology and geochemistry
of the saturated and unsaturated zones.  Reclamation design that is fundamentally sound,
appropriate, and effective in the long term must integrate and incorporate research on all of
these landscape components--surface and subsurface.  This applies to both abandoned mine
lands and current mining areas. <p>
<p>
     The Western Region center of the NMLRC conducts research on reclamation issues of
regional and national significance.  Overall, the Western Region program continues to
emphasize relationships between composition of materials, geochemistry, hydrogeology, soil
hydrology, and water quality problems at field sites in several western states, including North
Dakota, Montana, and Wyoming.  Understanding that reclamation is an inseparable part of
mining activities will result in programmatic planning and substantial economic benefit for all
participants in the mining process.<p>
<p>
     The projects in the Western Region program, participating research institutions, and location
of field research sites, respectively, are as follows:<p>
<p>
         <b> ND01:</b>     Surface and Root Zone Hydrology of Mined Lands--NDSU--Indian Head and
Velva mines, North Dakota<p>
<p>
          <b>ND02:</b>     Groundwater Movement and Chemical Evolution from the Root Zone to the Water
Table--EERC--Indian Head, Velva, and Fritz mines, North Dakota<p>
<p>
          <b>ND03:</b>     Stabilization of Underground Mine Voids by Filling with Coal Conversion Residual
Materials--EERC--Wilton mine, North Dakota<p>
<p>
          <b>ND04:</b>     Comparative Evaluation of Methods of Selenium Analysis for Determining
Potential
Environmental Problems--EERC--Cordero mine, Wyoming<p>
<p>
          <b>ND05:</b>     Physical and Geochemical Modeling of Waste Migration from
Mining-Contaminated
Floodplains, Phase I, Process Analysis--University of Montana, EERC, Resource Technology
Corporation--Silver Bow Creek, Montana<p>
<p>
          <b>ND06:</b>     Modeling Soil Water Status of Mine Land Profiles--NDSU--Indian Head and Velva
mines,
North Dakota<p>
<p>
          <b>ND07:</b>     Wetland Hydrology of Mine Lands--NDSU, EERC--several North Dakota
mines<p>
<p>
          <b>ND08:</b>     Diagenesis and Leaching Characteristics of Aged Coal Conversion Residues from
Mine
Disposal Settings--EERC--several North Dakota mines<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The overall objective of this program is to develop information and techniques for successful
long-term reclamation of abandoned mine lands and current mining areas, considering
differences in geology, hydrogeology, geochemistry, climate, and topography.  Previous
Western Region research projects focused on water occurrence and movement in the
landscape, mineral-water interactions, and geochemical evolution of subsurface water, and
more recent projects have included the investigation of generation, migration, fate, and
remediation of contaminants related to 1) coal ash disposal/utilization, 2) selenium in mine
spoils, and 3) metal mining wastes.<p>

<p>
<h2>Results</h2></font> 

<p>
<h3>Project ND01:  Surface and Root Zone Hydrology of
Mined Lands</h3>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Undisturbed soil profiles with permanent grass vegetation have
the highest capacity for infiltration, mostly through a network of macropores; spoil piles in
abandoned mine lands have the least capacity for infiltration, although desiccation cracks and pores
are abundant.  Well-vegetated topsoil and subsoils and depressional areas in abandoned mine lands
have equally high potential for infiltration.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Infiltration capacity of post-Surface Mining Conservation and
Reclamation Act (SMCRA) reclaimed soils on top of spoil material is higher than when these sodic
spoils are left alone.  Compared to undisturbed soil profiles, the hydraulic conductivity of reclaimed
soils is significantly lower because of a lack of macropore and micropore permeability caused by
spreading, layering, and compaction activities during reclamation.  Some premine soil profiles
severely compacted by traffic or overgrazing have lower conductivity than reclaimed profiles.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> There was a general lack of subsoil recharge during 1989-1992
due to low precipitation.  Only in depressional areas with nonspoil materials in abandoned mine land
profiles was there recharge to deeper soil depths.  Soil water storage and water levels on depressional
ponds at the Indian Head mine were depleted because of lack of precipitation and snowmelt runoff. 
During 1993, precipitation in the region was unusually abundant, making it necessary to continue
monitoring and evaluating the new data in contrast to drought conditions present during the preceding
few years.<br>
</ul><p>
<h3>Project ND02:  Groundwater Movement and Chemical
Evolution from the Root Zone to the Water Table</h3>
<p>
     Detailed assessment of principal hydro- and geochemical processes participating in pore and
groundwater chemistry evolution was carried out at three surface mine localities in North
Dakota--the Fritz, Indian Head, and Velva mines.  Extensive field and analytical work allowed
for generation of sufficient information on geology, hydrogeology, mineralogy, soil
characteristics, and pore and groundwater chemistry.  Geochemical model MINTEQA2 and
advanced statistical analysis coupled with traditional interpretive techniques were used to
determine site-specific environmental characteristics and to compare the differences between
study sites.<p>
<p>
     ND02 key project results finalized in the project report submitted to the U.S. Bureau of Mines
in 1995 are as follows:<p>
<p>
<ul palin>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Site-specific porewater and groundwater are typically of the same
chemical type.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Multivariate statistical analyses indicate that sulfate, magnesium,
calcium, gypsum saturation index, and sodium contribute the most to overall differences in
groundwater chemistry between study sites.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> SO<sub>4</sub> anion-enriched aqueous solutions in the
vadose zone enter the saturated zone and influence the quality of groundwater.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Soil paste extract pH and EC measurements performed on over
3700 samples document extremely acidic soils at the Fritz mine.  The number of samples with a pH
&lt;5.5 reaches 80%-90% of total samples from discrete depth near the top of the soil profile at the
Fritz mine.  Samples from Indian Head and Velva do not exceed the limit at all.  The percentage of
samples with an EC &gt;3 mS cm<sup>&#45;1</sup> is between 20%-40% at the Fritz mine
and below 20% for samples from Indian Head and Velva.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> The concentration of the sulfate anion in pore water and
groundwater reflects the presence of acid- generating minerals (pyrite) within the soil profile and
dramatically impacts pore water quality (lower pH, increased electrical conductivity).<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Pyrite was detected in soils at the Fritz mine by scanning electron
microscopy point count (SEMPC) and x-ray diffraction (XRD) analyses.  Pyrite was not detected in
soils from Indian Head and Velva.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Results of geochemical modeling indicate an increased tendency
for gypsum saturation within the vadose zone, particularly within the lands disturbed by mining
activity.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Project ND03:  Stabilization of Underground Mine
Voids by Filling with Coal Conversion Residual Materials</h3>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Emplacement of a formulated fly ash grout in a short stretch of
underground tunnel at the old Wilton mine to stabilize the subsidence hazard was completed and will
be followed by evaluation of the engineering and environmental performance of the grout, focusing
on strength, permeability, mineral diagenesis, and chemical behavior of the grout mixture in the
environment.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Project ND04:  Comparative Evaluation of Methods of
Selenium Analysis for Determining Potential Environmental Problems</h3>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Numerous overburden core samples from the Cordero mine near
Gillette, Wyoming, were screened for total selenium, and 18 were chemically analyzed and leached
using four different extraction procedures (to develop a comparative database of total selenium,
selenium species, relative of mobility, and potential for environmental problems).<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Data from ammonium bicarbonate-diethylenetriaminepentaacetic
acid (AB-DTPA), hot-water soluble, synthetic acid rain, and synthetic groundwater leaching
procedure (SGLP/leaching tests), indicated that the SGLP test was most relevant for simulating
natural conditions and provided flexibility for variable field situations. <br>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Project ND05:  Physical and Geochemical Modeling of
Waste Migration from Mining-Contaminated Floodplains, Phase I, Process Analysis
</h3>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Efforts at Silver Bow Creek by the University of Montana team
have resulted in establishing the general groundwater flow field using a network of monitoring
instruments in the soil and groundwater zones and also the patterns of metals contamination and
general groundwater quality relative to flow fields and concentrations of metals in site sediments. 
<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Laboratory simulation of EM on Silver Bow Creek site sediments
has been completed and parameters established for an initial field demonstration to test the technical
and economic feasibility of large-scale application.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Electrode arrays were installed at the Silver Bow Creek site,
followed by a program of monitoring and assessment to determine the viability of this technology to
remediate the toxic hazards. <br>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Project ND06:  Modeling Soil Water Status of Mine
Land Profiles</h3>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Field research conducted by the NDSU Land Reclamation
Research Center at the Indian Head and Velva mines in North Dakota under Project ND01 "Surface
and Root Zone Hydrology" has resulted in a database for estimating the amount of runoff, runon, and
evapotranspiration water available for plant growth and potential sites of groundwater recharge in
various topographic positions at these mines.<br>
</ul>
 <p>
<h3>Project ND07:  Wetland Hydrology of Mine Lands</h3></font> <p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Field monitoring is continuing at wetlands sites at the Coteau
mine, Falkirk mine, Indian Head mine, Velva mine, and several other wetlands in central North
Dakota, covering the comparative spectrum from reconstructed wetlands in reclaimed areas, to
wetlands in abandoned mines, to more natural and pristine wetlands in the glacial drift prairie.<br>
</ul><p>
<h3>Project ND08:  Diagenesis and Leaching Characteristics of
Aged Coal Conversion Solid Residues from Mine Disposal Environments</h3>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Coal conversion solid residue (CCSR) utilization is currently
very
limited so that disposal is usually the only alternative.  Resultant environmental concerns focus on the
interaction of CCSR leachate with surface water or groundwater.  There is a general lack of suitable
technical information on the physical, chemical, mineralogical, and leaching properties of CCSRs
that have aged for any significant periods of time.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> This research will generate data on the mineral diagenesis
(transformations) and leachability of CCSRs subjected to long-term environmental exposure over
decades.  Studies will be performed on a variety of disposed ash materials taken from undisturbed
cores from typical mine disposal settings.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Mineral transformations have been varied and dramatic.  Early
reactions with water transformed reactive mineral phases in raw materials to various cementitious and
hydrated phases.  Significant amounts of ettringite, thaumasite, tobermorite, and some Na-Al zeolite,
Na-Ca sulfate, calcite, and gypsum were identified.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> SGLP leachates had pH levels of 10-11 and a typical composition
of sodium and sulfate.  Resource Conservation and Recovery Act and other important metals in the
ash cores did not leach during lab tests.<br>
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> John A. Harju/<a href=mailto:jharju@eerc.und.nodak.edu>jharju@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5208<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Bureau of Mines under Subcontract to West Virginia University<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>July 1988 to June 1995  (renewable on an annual basis)
