<html>
<head>
<title>Analysis of Pollutant Organics from Contaminated Solids Using Off-Line
Supercritical Fluid Extraction and On-Line SFE/IR</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Analysis of Pollutant Organics from Contaminated Solids Using Off-Line Supercritical Fluid
Extraction and On-Line SFE/IR </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The remediation of U.S. Department of Energy sites requires rapid and accurate methods for
the determination of organic pollutants on soils and sediments.  Ideally, these methods should
be easily performed at the contaminated sites, with a minimum of laboratory support.  While
many field-portable instruments are available to analyze soil extracts, methods needed to
extract soil samples are generally not amenable to performance in the field.  Supercritical fluid
extraction (SFE) has been developed to the point where field-portable instruments can easily be
moved and yield excellent extraction efficiencies in relatively short times (usually less than 30
minutes).  In addition, coupling SFE with infrared spectrometry (IR) can yield rapid
determinations for many organic pollutants without the need to collect extracts for subsequent
analysis.  SFE/IR has the potential to provide a reliable and sensitive field-portable instrument
for surveying organic pollutants in soil samples without requiring any organic solvents to be
present on-site.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The objectives of this project are:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To develop and demonstrate the use of SFE under field conditions
for extracting organic pollutants from soil in preparation for analysis by conventional field-portable
analytical methods.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To develop and demonstrate the use of on-line SFE/IR under field
conditions for the rapid and solvent-free determination of organic pollutants. <br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Field demonstrations have been performed showing that commercially available SFE
instrumentation can  be operated easily and reliably in the field without the need for a
laboratory support vehicle.  Good quantitative agreement between field SFE and laboratory
extractions has been achieved for polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) from soil.  Over
30 soil samples can be extracted in a day using only a portable electrical generator.  A field
demonstration for the field determination of polychlorinated biphenyl (PCBs) is planned. 
Future work will also evaluate the use of enzyme-linked immunoassay (ELISA) combined with
SFE for the rapid field determination of PAHs and PCBs from contaminated soils.  Results of
field and laboratory work demonstrate that SFE can be used in the field to extract most
commonly measured organic pollutants for subsequent determination by any suitable
technique.<p>
<p>
     Laboratory work on the SFE/IR system has demonstrated robust operational characteristics
and good sensitivities (sub-ppm detection limits).  For example, SFE/IR analyses of total
petroleum hydrocarbons (TPHs) on contaminated soil can be performed in 15-30 minutes with
no organic solvent, and the quantitative results agree with conventional Soxhlet extraction,
which requires 4 hours of extraction with Freon-113 solvent.  Peer-reviewed publications
describing the results of this investigation are available upon request.  Discussions with a
leading instrument manufacturer are now being held for commercializing the SFE/IR interface.
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu> shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5256<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> 
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>
<li>September 1994 to September 1995
