<head>
<title>Selective Subcritical Water Extraction of Aromatic and Aliphatic Organic
Pollutants from Petroleum Industry Soils and Sludges</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Selective Subcritical Water Extraction of Aromatic and Aliphatic Organic Pollutants from
Petroleum Industry Soils and Sludges </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
     <p>
     Samples contaminated with petroleum industry wastes often contain complex mixtures of
aliphatic and aromatic hydrocarbons.  The analysis and remediation of such solids would be
facilitated by a selective extraction method that could extract the toxic components without the
need for organic solvents.  The EERC has previously demonstrated that subcritical (hot
pressurized) water is an efficient extraction solvent for nonpolar organics present in petroleum
wastes, such as polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs).<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
     <p>
     The use of subcritical water to selectively extract aromatic and aliphatic hydrocarbons from
petroleum waste solids will be developed.  Preliminary determinations of the solubility
behavior of liquid fuels in subcritical (hot pressurized) water will also be performed.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Subcritical water extraction conditions have been developed that allow quantitative removal of
aromatic hydrocarbons, ranging from BTEX (benzene, toluene, ethylbenzene, and xylene)
components to high-molecular-weight PAHs from a petroleum waste sludge.  Efficient
(&gt;98%) removal of polar organics such as phenols occurs with low-temperature (50&#176;C)
extractions.  BTEX organics extract efficiently at 100&#176;C, while PAHs are not extracted until
temperatures are increased to 150&#176;-250&#176;C.  At 250&#176;C, water is sufficiently
nonpolar to extract all regulated PAHs from sludge in 15 minutes, while few of the matrix hydrocarbons
(e.g., large alkanes) are extracted.  Peer-reviewed publications describing the results of this
investigation are available upon request.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu>shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5256<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>American Petroleum Institute <br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>August 1994 to August 1995<br>
