<head>
<title>Hot-Water Extraction of Organics, Metals, and Halogens from Coal and Contaminated Soils</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Hot-Water Extraction of Organics, Metals, and Halogens from Coal and Contaminated Soils
</h1></center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     The EERC has previously demonstrated that supercritical and subcritical (hot pressurized)
water can be used to extract sulfur from coal (including sulfate and pyrite) and nonpolar
organic pollutants from soils.  Depending on the temperature and pressure of the extractant
water, the solubilities of inorganic and organic pollutants vary by several orders of magnitude. 
However, the variations in solubility that occur and the potential for extracting a wide variety
of organic and inorganic pollutants are not well understood.  The reactivity of supercritical
water (i.e., it has both higher H<sup>+</sup> and OH<sup>&#45;</sup> concentrations
than water at ambient conditions) may also cause the release of pollutants from solid samples.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The potential for using supercritical (&gt;374&#176;C and &gt;220 atm) and hot pressurized
water (&lt;374&#176;C) to extract halogens and toxic metals from coal and contaminated soils will
be evaluated as well as the use of hot water to extract organic pollutants such as polychlorinated
biphenyls (PCBs).<p> 
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Preliminary results demonstrate that supercritical water is an efficient extraction solvent for
removing mercury from coal and from soil samples.  For example, when Illinois Basin coal is
extracted for 30 minutes with supercritical water (450&#176;C and 350 atm), &gt;85% of the
mercury is removed as well as ca. 70% of the coal sulfur.  However, over 70% of the carbon content
of the coal remains.  When soils contaminated with mercury were extracted for 30 minutes,
more than 99% of the mercury was removed, and more than 50% of the arsenic and selenium. 
At milder conditions (steam at 300&#176;C), PCBs are removed from contaminated soil in less than
5 minutes using liquid water at 250&#176;C and 50 atm.  These results indicate that both
supercritical and subcritical water should be useful for analytical- and remediation-scale
extractions of toxic metals and organics from coal and soil.  Future studies will determine the
ability to extract halogens and other toxic metals.  Peer-reviewed publications describing the
results of this investigation are available upon request.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> Steven B. Hawthorne/<a href=mailto:shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu>shawthorne@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5256<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li> January 1995 to December 1995<br>
