<html>
<head>
<title>Oil Spill Recovery Sorbent Evaluation</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Oil Spill Recovery Sorbent Evaluation</h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Petroleum product spills are detrimental to the environment in numerous ways.  Industrial
accidents involving spillage of crude oil or motor fuels are of increasing importance.  Recovery
of oil spilled on water or land with a minimum amount of labor is desirable.  Biomass-derived
sorbents have proven to be applicable to recovery of spilled crude oil or motor fuels which has
been spilled on water or land.  In addition, these same sorbents are being applied for collection of
other types of water contaminants, such as pesticides.  Biomass-derived sorbents are also
desirable since once used to absorb spillage, they may be used as a fuel.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
<p>
     The goal of this project was to evaluate the performance of a new biomass-derived sorbent
material for its applicability to recover crude oil from water or land.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     The candidate sorbent material was compared to two different commercially available sorbent
materials designed specifically for oil spill recovery.  All sorbents in the project were subjected
to testing in accordance with Canadian General Standards Board "Method for Testing Sorbents,"
CAN/CGSB-183.2-94. This test is designed to evaluate sorbents for the applications described
above.  Results of the work indicated that the proposed sorbent material did not perform as well
as commercially available sorbent materials.
<p><hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b>  Ames A. Grisanti/<a href=mailto:grisanti@badlands.nodak.edu>grisanti@badlands.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5158<br>
