<html>
<head>
<title>Spectroscopic Field Screening of Hazardous Waste and Toxic Spills</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Spectroscopic Field Screening of Hazardous Waste and Toxic Spills </h1> </center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
     <p>
     Field screening of petroleum product spills to determine the extent of soil contamination can
be time-consuming and expensive.  This project is investigating the applicability of coupling
Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy with cone penetrometry (FT-IR/CPT) as a means of
quickly and inexpensively characterizing the extent of soil contamination from petroleum
hydrocarbons.  Previously, researchers have demonstrated the ability of laser-induced
fluorescence spectroscopy-cone penetrometry (LIF-CPT) as a means to estimate the extent to
which a region of soil has been contaminated with petroleum hydrocarbons.  The LIF-CPT
technique is currently limited to detection of aromatic hydrocarbons. Aromatic hydrocarbons
are a small portion of a petroleum spill and represent the most volatile and mobile portion. 
The alkanes represent the vast majority of a typical petroleum spill and are more likely to
persist as residual contamination. Therefore, a rapid, cost-effective technique would more
likely approximate the total hydrocarbon mass that is present in the soil matrix.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
     <p>
     The feasibility of using FT-IR/CPT as a field screening technique will be determined through
laboratory investigation. The specific objectives of this work are the following:<p>
<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To design an accessory for use with FT-IR which interfaces the
spectrometer to a cone penetrometer.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To characterize the response of the FT-IR accessory to petroleum
hydrocarbons in a laboratory- simulated field environment.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> To determine the ability of the FT-IR/CPT instrument to measure
hydrocarbon contamination in soil by direct comparison with gas chromatography of hydrocarbons
extracted from the same soil.<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
     <p>
     Current project work is evaluating various stationary-phase materials for use in coating optical
fibers in order to provide the remote-sensing capability necessary for implementation of the
FT-IR/CPT.  The ideal stationary phase will be oleophilic and hydrophobic, allowing it to act
as a collection medium for soil contaminants.  Laboratory work has shown
polydimethylsiloxane to be useful as a reusable stationary phase for solid-phase
microextraction of volatile organic compounds.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> </b>Ames A. Grisanti/<a href=mailto:grisanti@badlands.nodak.edu>grisanti@badlands.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5158 <br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b>
<li>U.S. Department of Energy Morgantown Energy Technology  Center<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b> 
<li>January 1995 to December 1995<br>
<hr>
