<head>
<title>Development and Testing of Technologies for the Remediation of Mercury-Contaminated Soils</title>
</head>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<center>
<h1>Development and Testing of Technologies for the Remediation of Mercury-Contaminated
Soils </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Mercury manometers have been used for decades to measure natural gas flow at wellheads and
through gas pipelines.  As a result of the unintentional release of mercury from the
manometers, contamination of surrounding soils has occurred.  Under current regulations (the
Land Disposal Restrictions), only one identified technology, thermal treatment, is acceptable
for soils contaminated with higher levels of mercury, such as those common at natural gas
metering sites.  Concerns are that existing thermal treatment facilities designed to treat
mercury-contaminated soils do not have sufficient capacity to handle the potentially large
volumes of mercury-contaminated soils and that more economic alternatives should be
investigated.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The overall objective of this project is to select, develop, demonstrate, and evaluate alternative
treatment technologies for the remediation of mercury-contaminated soils.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Technology selection for development and testing was based on subcontractors' proposals
submitted in response to a Request for Proposals.  The selected technologies included a
prototype portable thermal treatment process, a bench-scale chemical leaching process, and a
prototype combination physical separation/chemical leaching process.<p>
<p>
     Each technology was evaluated using two different soil types:  a sandy soil from New Mexico
and a clayey soil from Ohio.  These soils, collected from contaminated natural gas metering
sites, were intended to represent dissimilar soil types and contamination conditions.  Soil
samples were mixed, split, and shipped to the three subcontractors for testing. 
Demonstrations of all three technologies were completed in late 1993.  The EERC's roles were
to witness and sample each demonstration, provide quality assurance/quality control oversight,
and summarize the results of each test in a final report entitled "Remediation of
Mercury-Contaminated Soils: 
Development and Testing of Technologies."<p>
<p>
     Thermal treatment was the most effective in removing mercury from the soils, based on both
percent total mercury removal and leachable mercury (by the toxicity characteristic leaching
procedure) after treatment.  However, both chemical leaching processes, when combined with
physical separation, were shown to be effective in reducing total and leachable mercury to
levels that would satisfy most regulatory requirements.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> David S. Charlton/<a href=mailto:dcharlton@eerc.und.nodak.edu>dcharlton@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5214<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> 
<li>Gas Research Institute 
<li>Union Gas Limited (Canada) 
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>November 1992 to December 1993<br>
