<head>
<title>Ettringite Formation as a Fixation Technology for Immobilizing Trace Elements</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Ettringite Formation as a Fixation Technology for Immobilizing Trace Element </h1>
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
     Operations involved in natural gas production, processing, and transport can result in solid
wastes or solutions containing arsenic, boron, chromium, molybdenum, selenium, or
vanadium.  These elements are typically in solution as oxyanions or other complex ions and
may be readily available for incorporation into hydrated mineral phases such as ettringite. 
Incorporation of these potentially hazardous trace elements into ettringite may be a means of
chemically fixing or stabilizing them in the environment.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objective</h2>
     Several key issues must be addressed to evaluate the potential effectiveness of ettringite
formation as a fixation technology for hazardous trace elements:<p>
<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Determination of the lower limit of concentration reduction of
thetrace elements<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Determination of the optimal formation conditions of
ettringite<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Determination of the structure of substituted ettringite<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Investigation of the release of fixed species from the ettringite
mineral under various conditions<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Investigation of the potential substitution of oxyanions into
previously formed existing ettringite<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Investigation of ettringite formation in commercially available
products and its applicability to natural gas industry wastes<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Evaluation of various materials as starting materials for ettringite
formation<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Investigation of the degradation products of ettringites under
thermal and chemical stress<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../misc/bull.gif"> Investigation of how water is bound in the ettringite structure and
the effect of dehydration<br>
</ul>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2></font> 
<p>
     Research on the use of ettringite as a fixation technology for immobilizing trace elements is
complete.  The research demonstrated that the formation of ettringite can be accompanied by a
reduction of solution concentrations of boron and selenium of up to two orders of magnitude. 
The process is economical and highly effective.  Enhanced ettringite formation is in the process
of being patented as a waste treatment technology.  The final report for this project has been
submitted for review by Gas Research Institute.  Numerous aspects of this project have been
related to the research, but not directly related to waste treatment.  Among these are the
development of advanced characterization techniques and understanding leading to the use of
ettringite in numerous areas such as mine land reclamation, use options for advanced coal
combustion process solid residues, and analytical chemistry and atomic spectroscopy.  A
continuous process for waste treatment has been demonstrated, and it has been determined that
the economics of this process are favorable for commercialization.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager:</b> David J. Hassett/<a href="mailto:dhassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu">dhassett@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:</b> (701) 777-5192<br>
<b>Informacion en espa&#241;ol:</b> Lucia Romuld/<a href=mailto:lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu>lromuld@eerc.und.nodak.edu</a><br>
<b>Phone:</b> 1-701-777-5223<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b>
<li>Gas Research Institute 
<li>U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>
<li>July 1990 to November 1993<br>
