<head>
<title>Fuel Quality Advisor</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Fuel Quality Advisor</h2> </center> 
<hr>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Background</h3></font>

     The ability to predict effectively the impacts of operational and fuel changes and fluctuations
within a utility boiler has long been the desire of many engineers.  The Fuel Quality Advisor
is a project to integrate a large portion of the work performed by the EERC and others into a
user-friendly computer program that can provide information on the effects of fuel quality on
design and performance of power systems.  The goal of this project is to aid utilities, fuel
processors, engineers, researchers, coal companies, and others to allow for efficient and
proper use of the volumes of complex results.  The project is initially focusing on integrating
current computer algorithms for conventional combustion ash transformations and deposition
along with new algorithms for coal handling, low-NO<sub>x</sub> ash transformations, and
entrained gasification ash transformations.  Limited work is also being done on identifying other
potential algorithms for the Fuel Quality Advisor, such as heat and mass transfer properties of
new and existing systems (computational fluid dynamics modeling), ash transformations and
deposition in fluidized-bed combustors, effectiveness of conventional particulate cleanup
processes and hot-gas cleanup loops, emissions of hazardous air pollutants from coal-fired
systems, and other processes related to the various aspects of coal utilization.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives </h3></font> 
     The overall objective of this program is to integrate the many complex correlations and
algorithms available into a single, or series of, computer program(s) to allow non-research-oriented
users to
benefit from their development.  By developing a standardized interface, both
current and future users will benefit from the universal operation of the program.  In addition,
the currently available algorithms for ash formation, ash deposition, and coal handleability will
be enhanced to be more reliable across a broader range of coals and operating conditions.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Results</h3></font>
     A Windows-based computer program is being developed which will utilize state-of-the-art
coal characterization data and operational information and produce a series of coal rankings for
common coal-related problems.  Indices for slagging, high-temperature fouling, low-temperature
fouling, and
coal handling are being included in the program.<p>
     The indices included in the program are based on engineering theory and enhanced with
bench-, pilot-, and full-scale information. To gain the necessary research information, tests are
being conducted in the EERC pressurized drop-tube furnace, conversion and environmental
process simulator, and coal handleability test loop.  Release of Version 1.0 of the Fuel Quality
Advisor will take place at the end of 1995.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>Thomas A. Erickson/<a href=mailto:terickson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>terickson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:  </b> (701) 777-5153<br>
<b>Sponsor:</b> U.S. Department of Energy<br>
<b>Duration of Project:</b>  January 1995 to December
1995<br>
<hr>

