<html>
<head>
<title>Computer Systems Used for Prediction of
Impacts of Changing Fuel Quality on
Power Systems</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h2>Computer Systems Used for Prediction of Impacts of Changing Fuel Quality on Power
Systems </h2>
</center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Background </h3></font>
     The effects of coal quality on utility boiler performance are difficult to predict using
conventional methods.  As a result of environmental concerns, more utilities are blending and
selecting coals that are not the design coals for their units.  This has led to a wide range of
problems, from grindability and moisture concerns to fly ash collection.<p>

     To help utilities predict the impacts of changing coal quality, the Electric Power Research
Institute (EPRI) and the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) have initiated a program called
Coal Quality Expert (CQE).  The program is undertaken to quantify coal quality impacts using
data generated in field-, pilot-, and laboratory-scale investigations.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives</h3></font>
     The overall objective of the program is to provide the utility industry with a personal
computer-based expert system to confidently and inexpensively evaluate the potential of
coal-cleaning,
blending, and switching options to reduce emissions while producing electricity at
the lowest cost.<p>

     The goals of the work being conducted by the EERC include the following:<p>

<ul plain>
<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Characterize coal, ashes, and deposits collected during field-,
pilot-, and bench-scale testing using state-of-the-art methods<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Use a bench-scale drop-tube furnace (DTF) to determine the
critical temperatures and conditions under which deposits form and develop strength<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Identify key characteristics in the coal and ashes responsible for
ash deposit formation in utility boilers<br>

<IMG SRC="GIFS/bl_dot.gif"> Use the results from the field-, pilot-, and bench-scale work to
develop a framework for fouling and slagging algorithms that will enhance CQE<br>
</ul>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Results</h3></font>

     Eight different coals were used in bench-, pilot-, and full-scale tests to determine the effects of
coal quality on boiler performance.  The coals and related ash and deposit samples were
characterized and the results used as input for algorithms to predict fouling and slagging
behavior.  The project is approximately three-quarters complete and will be concluded by the
fourth quarter of 1995.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>      <b>Task 1 - Coal Characterization Through
Computer-Controlled Scanning Electron Microscopy</b> </h3></font> <p>

     The eight coals were analyzed using computer-controlled scanning electron microscopy
(CCSEM) to determine composition, size distribution, and mineralogy.  The results helped to
elucidate the mechanisms involved in inorganic transformations of the coals and served as
input to the slagging and fouling algorithms.  The CCSEM results were also useful in
determining the effectiveness of coal-cleaning processes.<p>


<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>  Task 2 - Bench-Scale Ash Deposition:  Drop-Tube
Furnace Testing</b> </h3></font>  <p>



     The eight coals were tested in the optical DTF, which consists of a high-temperature furnace
equipped with optical access for observing the formation of deposit growth.  Deposits were
characterized using SEM point count (SEMPC), which yields bulk oxide chemistry.  Results
were similar to those obtained for the pilot- and full-scale tests (Tasks 3 and 4).  Data from
both CCSEM and SEMPC analyses were used as input for the fouling and slagging algorithms.<p>


<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>  Task 3 - Characterization of Samples from the ABB
Combustion Engineering Fireside Performance Test Facility</b></h3></font> <p>


     The eight coals were used in pilot-scale tests at ABB Combustion Engineering.  The resultant
fly ash and deposits were analyzed at the EERC using the same methods applied to the samples
produced through bench-scale testing (Task 2).<p>



<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>  Task 4 - Characterization of Field Test Samples</b>
</h3></font> <p> 


     Field testing was conducted to compare the results of the smaller-scale testing.  The three sites
used were the Public Service of Oklahoma Northeast Station, Mississippi Power Watson
Station, and Northern States Power Company King Station.  Samples of coal, entrained ash,
slagging and fouling deposits, and fly ash were analyzed using CCSEM and SEMPC methods
to verify the results of the pilot- and bench-scale testing.  The strengths and growth rates of
fouling and slagging deposits observed in the full-scale tests were similar to the results of the
smaller-scale tests.<p>


<font color="#990066"><h3> <b>  Task 5 - Development of Algorithms to Predict
Convective
Pass Fouling</b> </h3></font> <p>

<p>

     FOULER is a mechanistic model which predicts the coal ash deposition in a utility boiler. 
The model was placed into a C-based computer code that will be added into the CQE model
being developed by EPRI and DOE.  The CQE code is designed to explore a broad range of
economic and operational factors involved in the combustion of coal.<p>

<p>

     FOULER predicts both growth and removal of fouling deposits through the interaction of
several submodels:  deposit growth, strength development, thermal properties, deposit
removal, and sootblower effectiveness.  Inputs for the FOULER code include advanced coal
characterizations, boiler parameters, and operational conditions.  These submodels interact to
produce outputs, based on  time, for deposit mass, strength, resistivity, removal rates, and
sootblowing effectiveness.  The data generated from the program are used to predict the
resistance to heat transfer caused by the deposits.  The FOULER code has been constructed
and is currently being enhanced and integrated into the CQE program, with completion
expected by August 1995.<p>

<p>

     The EERC, in collaboration with PSI PowerServe, has developed and coded a computer
model, SLAGGO, that predict the effects of furnace slagging in a coal-fired boiler.  The
required inputs for the SLAGGO code include ash size and composition, boiler parameters,
and operational conditions.  These input values are provided by the PSI PowerServe mineral
matter transformation model and the CQE interface shell and heat-transfer modules,
respectively.  Using these input values, SLAGGO predicts both growth and removal of
slagging deposits through the interactions of the following submodels:  ash formation, deposit
growth, thermal properties, and deposit removal.  These submodels interact to produce
outputs, based on user-defined time intervals, of deposit mass, strength, and a cleanliness
factor.<p>
<hr>
<b>Project Manager: </b>Thomas A. Erickson/<a href=mailto:terickson@eerc.und.nodak.edu>terickson@eerc.und.nodak.edu </a> <br>
<b>Phone:  </b> (701) 777-5153<br>
<b>Sponsors:</b> <ul plain>Electric Power research Institute<br>
U.S. Department of Energy</ul>
<b>Duration of Project: </b>July 1990 to December 1995<br>
<hr>

