<html>
<head>
<title>Modeling and Database Applications
Center for Air Toxic Metals Program
Area 4</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/eerc_hd.gif">
<h2>Modeling and Database Applications Center for Air Toxic Metals Program Area 4  </h2>
</center> 
<hr>


<font color="#990066"><h3>Background </h3></font>
     The Center for Air Toxic Metals (CATM) at the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center
(EERC) of the University of North Dakota (UND) emphasizes research, development,
demonstration, and commercialization of innovative environmental cleanup technologies
through partnerships between government, industry, and the EERC in the areas of applied
science and engineering.  CATM was established by the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency (EPA) and is focused on minimizing the effects of air toxic metal pollutants on the
environment.  The Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 require regulatory actions addressing
189 substances, including air toxic metals.  In order to develop regulations, CATM is working
with industry and government to develop sufficient information on air toxic metals to provide a
scientific basis for preventing and controlling the emissions and evaluating the fate and impacts
of air toxic metals on plants and animals, including humans.  CATM-related programs are
focused on the development of methods to minimize the release of air toxic metals via practical
prevention and control methods based on scientific understanding and principles.  To facilitate
research efforts and dissemination of information, CATM is organized into five integrated
program areas:  Program Area 1 - Air Toxic Metals Transformation Mechanisms, Program
Area 2 - Analytical Methods Development, Program Area 3 - Control Technologies, Program
Area 4 - Modeling and Database, and Program Area 5 - Technology Commercialization and
Education.  Program Area 4 focuses on the development of advanced computer applications
that serve as tools for the understanding and mitigation of air toxic metals.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Objectives</h3></font>
     Modeling and Database Applications Program Area 4 focuses on three primary areas:  1) the
development of a database for the storage and retrieval of air toxic metal analytical,
engineering, and report information; 2) the development of models and algorithms
(nomograms) for predicting trace metal partitioning and the control and release of trace metals
from energy-producing systems; and 3) the creation of a user-friendly graphics package and
modem link for the database and the various trace metal models that are currently being
planned and/or developed.  Access to database information is available to government
agencies, academia, and industry through CATM.<p>

<font color="#990066"><h3>Results</h3></font>
     A first-generation, state-of-the-art database running on a Sun Sparc 10-51 workstation with a
database enhancement package has been created.  The first-level database utilizes three
different types of information:  analytical data, engineering information, and reporting
citations.  Data generated from the other program areas were used for implementation of the
first-level model.  This database will allow researchers, fuel buyers and sellers, system
designers, and managers to make educated decisions on the operation of energy- producing and
waste-incinerating facilities.  The database will allow users to compare information from
different systems and view information from specific systems.  A fully functional version of
the database will be operational at the end of 1996.<p>

     In addition to the development of the database, work was also conducted on developing an
interface for accessing the database and models at the EERC through outside computers. 
Tentative plans include both an Internet and modem link into the systems at the EERC.  An
interface has been designed for Internet access, and a modem link consisting of a dedicated
computer server that will handle all communication between the user and system is currently
under design.<p>

     Modeling activities to date have been conducted as enhancements to existing projects and
computer codes.  Modeling work was coordinated with a parallel project at the EERC "Trace
Element Emissions" (TEE), sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy.  The TEE project
is developing a computer program to predict the physical state and concentration of various
trace metals within a gasification system.  This project aided in the research of thermochemical
equilibrium programs and in the development of a user-friendly graphical interface.  The
development of a  submicron particle formation model was also initiated through the
cooperation of Flemming Frandsen, a visiting scientist from Denmark at the EERC.
<hr>
