<head>
<title>Resource Data Evaluation and Geographic Information System
Technologies</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="gifs/eerc_hd.gif"><br>
<h1>Resource Data Evaluation and Geographic Information System Technologies </h1>
</font> 
</center>
<hr>
<h2>Background</h2>
<p>
     Advances in computer hardware and software technology are reshaping approaches to data
acquisition, management, and analysis.  Data sharing and data availability have become an
important outcome of the increase in agencies and institutions striving for an integrated
approach to resolving the myriad of complex global concerns.  At the vanguard of integrative
technologies is an approach known as geographic information systems (GIS).  GIS is a
software technology that permits the input, manipulation, analysis, and display of
geographically referenced data.  GIS provides a set of tools to perform these functions by
integrating map information and associated attribute data.  The portrayal and analysis of such
information can occur at many levels of specificity.  The strength of GIS utility, however, is
its capability to integrate and portray the relationship between data typically left unassociated
because of the lack of a means to bring different types of information into one format and
method of analysis (e.g., the cost relationship between geology and urban sewer systems). 
With GIS technology and appropriate data management techniques, investigation, not
compilation and display, becomes the central research issue.<p>
<p>
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>
     The Resource Data Evaluation initiative consisted of two basic components that represent a
single objective to develop an understanding of the analysis capabilities across the spectrum of
program areas at the EERC in order to support data management needs as part of the decision-making
process.  These program areas include energy and environmental policy and planning,
mine planning and reclamation, energy resource occurrence, groundwater resource
occurrence, and waste management studies.  <p>
<p>
     Resource Data Integration research is developing an approach to fully integrate a
geographically based resource management system that will interpret the complex relationships
between capability, utilization, and reclamation.  The integration of resource data across the
large number of energy and environmental concerns requires specialized programming and
hardware specific to the information-intensive applications of multilayered attribute data
associated with GIS.  Commercially available GIS software is utilized with advanced
computing systems to analyze these relationships.  This research is focused on the
methodology and system requirements to undertake a sequence of pilot projects.  <p>
<p>
     Resource Data Correlation research is undertaken to apply GIS technologies by example to
determine programming and hardware requirements for a variety of data types.  Examples
include research areas in the Paleocene-age coal-bearing strata of the Williston Basin in North
Dakota and adjacent areas in Montana.  The objective of this project is to develop existing
EERC databases to integrate coal-related information with geologic information for the
specific purpose of summarizing the status of coal bed recognition and correlation in the
Williston Basin.  The resulting approach is specifically designed for earth resource evaluation
and characterization, with applications for groundwater and environmental concerns, by
providing the means of defining bed and other lithosome correlations in specific areas.<p>
<p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>
     Recent research in Resource Data Evaluation has begun to restructure the EERC geological
observation databases, using relational database management methodologies to develop a more
fully integrated approach to resource management and characterization.  This restructuring
permits the direct integration of digitized data derived from GIS activities with associated
attribute information.  The developing table or file organization is analogous to those
previously reported (Hartman, 1992, 1994a, b) using a flat-file database manager (Q&amp;A&reg;
by Symantec Corporation).  The major difference between flat-file and relational data
management philosophies is the ability of relational data managers to link tables in one-to-many
relationships. 
This capability, along with that of being able to directly link tables in
many-to-one or many-to-many relationships, significantly affects how data are organized into
subtables within and between databases.  In a relational data manager, queries represent a
method of data retrieval that permits the design of new combinative tables, based solely on
linkages, to which new data retrieval requests for information can be posed across multiple
tables.  The simplified database system example highlights selected database design features
using the relational management techniques incorporated by Microsoft Corporation into
Access&reg;. <p>
<p>
     The accompanying figure has, as its background, a portion of a surface geologic section
(M4772), which shows inclined lower Paleocene strata assigned to the Ludlow Formation,
exposed on the west side of the Cedar Creek Anticline in Dawson County, Montana.  These
rocks represent the lower portion of a sequence of coal-bearing strata comprising the Fort
Union Group in the Fort Union Coal Region of the Williston Basin.  The section includes two
fossiliferous horizons, Localities L6207 and L6207a, which are being used to paleontologically
date and correlate the section to other outcrop areas in the northern Great Plains.  The tables
(or files) noted on the accompanying figure illustrate a few of the most significant components
of a geological observation database system.  Surface and subsurface geologic observations are
included in an MNO database, which includes, among other tables, MNO (M-number) and
UNITS (section units) tables.  Paleontologic observations are maintained in an LNO database,
which includes LNO (L-number), SPPID (specimen identification), and other tables.  GIS
data, including unique machine numbers and digitized latitude and longitude values for L-numbers
and M-numbers, are included in a GIS table in a GIS database.  Other primary tables
include MAPS, for map data, MOLLES, for classification information on specimen
identifications, and BIB, for bibliographic references.  Any number of additional primary or
secondary tables could be added to manage project-specific information (e.g., analytical data
of a particular coal bed).  All of these tables were separate databases in Q&amp;A&reg;, variously
linked in many-to-one relationships through the construction of tabular reports (Report
Module).  In Access&reg;, these tables are linked through a query to effectively produce a
seamless master database.  <p>
<p>
     In addition, MNO and LNO relational and flat-file database or table designs differ radically in
their internal structure.  Using the table for paleontological observations as an example, the
main LNO table includes primarily location information, but summarizes other locality-specific data
noted below.  The main table (LNO) in the LNO database includes the following
cross-referenced fields:  LNO (locality number), REF (reference, e.g., author and year),
MNO (section number), UNIT (unit number within a section), STATE, and QUAD (U.S.
Geological Survey, 7.5-minute topographic quadrangle).  In addition, there are 12 fields
managing seven discrete reference categories (including other numbering systems); 11 record-keeping
fields (e.g., date and time last modified); 48 fields managing 12 discrete location
categories (e.g., country, state, elevation); and nine fields managing general stratigraphic
categories (e.g., Formation).  The LNO database includes secondary or subtables that manage
specific information categories.  Description subtables include Location, Stratigraphy, General
Comment, Fauna, and Identifications.  Subtables are also maintained for Reference Affiliation,
Discovery, Collection, and Horizons (i.e., referential data pertaining to locality stratigraphy).<p>
<p>
     The value of the database design described above is that it provides the user with the ability to
integrate stratigraphic, location, and identification data directly, with the opportunity to
display the results of questions posed to the database in a map format using GIS.  <p>
<p>
